{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"nietzscheWorks","displayName":"Nietzsche — Selected Works","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Common & Zimmern Translations, 1896-1910","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Modern Philosophy","audienceTags":["philosophy","critical-thinking"],"sortPriority":43,"itemCount":3905,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["work","section"],"groupingLabels":["Work","Section"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Nietzsche_Works.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-1","text":"“Zarathustra” is my brother’s most personal work; it is the history of\r his most individual experiences, of his friendships, ideals, raptures,\r bitterest disappointments and sorrows. Above it all, however, there\r soars, transfiguring it, the image of his greatest hopes and remotest\r aims. My brother had the figure of Zarathustra in his mind from his very\r earliest youth: he once told me that even as a child he had dreamt of\r him. At different periods in his life, he would call this haunter of his\r dreams by different names; “but in the end,” he declares in a note on\r the subject, “I had to do a PERSIAN the honour of identifying him with\r this creature of my fancy. Persians were the first to ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-2","text":"All Zarathustra’s views, as also his personality, were early conceptions\r of my brother’s mind. Whoever reads his posthumously published writings\r for the years 1869–82 with care, will constantly meet with passages\r suggestive of Zarathustra’s thoughts and doctrines. For instance, the\r ideal of the Superman is put forth quite clearly in all his writings\r during the years 1873–75; and in “We Philologists”, the following\r remarkable observations occur:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-3","text":"“How can one praise and glorify a nation as a whole?—Even among the\r Greeks, it was the INDIVIDUALS that counted.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-4","text":"“The Greeks are interesting and extremely important because they reared\r such a vast number of great individuals. How was this possible? The\r question is one which ought to be studied.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-5","text":"“I am interested only in the relations of a people to the rearing of\r the individual man, and among the Greeks the conditions were unusually\r favourable for the development of the individual; not by any means owing\r to the goodness of the people, but because of the struggles of their\r evil instincts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-6","text":"“WITH THE HELP OF FAVOURABLE MEASURES GREAT INDIVIDUALS MIGHT BE REARED\r WHO WOULD BE BOTH DIFFERENT FROM AND HIGHER THAN THOSE WHO HERETOFORE\r HAVE OWED THEIR EXISTENCE TO MERE CHANCE. Here we may still be hopeful:\r in the rearing of exceptional men.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-7","text":"The notion of rearing the Superman is only a new form of an ideal\r Nietzsche already had in his youth, that “THE OBJECT OF MANKIND SHOULD\r LIE IN ITS HIGHEST INDIVIDUALS” (or, as he writes in “Schopenhauer as\r Educator”: “Mankind ought constantly to be striving to produce great\r men—this and nothing else is its duty.”) But the ideals he most revered\r in those days are no longer held to be the highest types of men. No,\r around this future ideal of a coming humanity—the Superman—the poet\r spread the veil of becoming. Who can tell to what glorious heights man\r can still ascend? That is why, after having tested the worth of our\r noblest ideal—that of the Saviour, in the light of the new valuatio","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-8","text":"“Never yet hath there been a Superman. Naked have I seen both of them,\r the greatest and the smallest man:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-9","text":"All-too-similar are they still to each other. Verily even the greatest\r found I—all-too-human!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-10","text":"The phrase “the rearing of the Superman,” has very often been\r misunderstood. By the word “rearing,” in this case, is meant the act of\r modifying by means of new and higher values—values which, as laws and\r guides of conduct and opinion, are now to rule over mankind. In general\r the doctrine of the Superman can only be understood correctly in\r conjunction with other ideas of the author’s, such as:—the Order\r of Rank, the Will to Power, and the Transvaluation of all Values. He\r assumes that Christianity, as a product of the resentment of the botched\r and the weak, has put in ban all that is beautiful, strong, proud, and\r powerful, in fact all the qualities resulting from strength, and that,\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-11","text":"This type must not be regarded as a fanciful figure: it is not a\r nebulous hope which is to be realised at some indefinitely remote\r period, thousands of years hence; nor is it a new species (in the\r Darwinian sense) of which we can know nothing, and which it would\r therefore be somewhat absurd to strive after. But it is meant to be\r a possibility which men of the present could realise with all their\r spiritual and physical energies, provided they adopted the new values.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-12","text":"The author of “Zarathustra” never lost sight of that egregious example\r of a transvaluation of all values through Christianity, whereby the\r whole of the deified mode of life and thought of the Greeks, as well as\r strong Romedom, was almost annihilated or transvalued in a comparatively\r short time. Could not a rejuvenated Graeco-Roman system of valuing (once\r it had been refined and made more profound by the schooling which\r two thousand years of Christianity had provided) effect another such\r revolution within a calculable period of time, until that glorious type\r of manhood shall finally appear which is to be our new faith and hope,\r and in the creation of which Zarathustra exhorts us to p","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-13","text":"In his private notes on the subject the author uses the expression\r “Superman” (always in the singular, by-the-bye), as signifying “the most\r thoroughly well-constituted type,” as opposed to “modern man”; above\r all, however, he designates Zarathustra himself as an example of the\r Superman. In “Ecco Homo” he is careful to enlighten us concerning the\r precursors and prerequisites to the advent of this highest type, in\r referring to a certain passage in the “Gay Science”:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-14","text":"“In order to understand this type, we must first be quite clear in\r regard to the leading physiological condition on which it depends: this\r condition is what I call GREAT HEALTHINESS. I know not how to express my\r meaning more plainly or more personally than I have done already in\r one of the last chapters (Aphorism 382) of the fifth book of the ‘Gaya\r Scienza’.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-15","text":"“We, the new, the nameless, the hard-to-understand,”—it says\r there,—“we firstlings of a yet untried future—we require for a new end\r also a new means, namely, a new healthiness, stronger, sharper, tougher,\r bolder and merrier than all healthiness hitherto. He whose soul\r longeth to experience the whole range of hitherto recognised values\r and desirabilities, and to circumnavigate all the coasts of this ideal\r ‘Mediterranean Sea’, who, from the adventures of his most personal\r experience, wants to know how it feels to be a conqueror, and discoverer\r of the ideal—as likewise how it is with the artist, the saint, the\r legislator, the sage, the scholar, the devotee, the prophet, and the\r godly ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-16","text":"“How could we still be content with THE MAN OF THE PRESENT DAY\r after such outlooks, and with such a craving in our conscience and\r consciousness? Sad enough; but it is unavoidable that we should look\r on the worthiest aims and hopes of the man of the present-day with\r ill-concealed amusement, and perhaps should no longer look at them.\r Another ideal runs on before us, a strange, tempting ideal full of\r danger, to which we should not like to persuade any one, because we\r do not so readily acknowledge any one’s RIGHT THERETO: the ideal of\r a spirit who plays naively (that is to say involuntarily and from\r overflowing abundance and power) with everything that has hitherto\r been called holy, go","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-17","text":"Although the figure of Zarathustra and a large number of the leading\r thoughts in this work had appeared much earlier in the dreams and\r writings of the author, “Thus Spake Zarathustra” did not actually come\r into being until the month of August 1881 in Sils Maria; and it was the\r idea of the Eternal Recurrence of all things which finally induced my\r brother to set forth his new views in poetic language. In regard to his\r first conception of this idea, his autobiographical sketch, “Ecce Homo”,\r written in the autumn of 1888, contains the following passage:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-18","text":"“The fundamental idea of my work—namely, the Eternal Recurrence of\r all things—this highest of all possible formulae of a Yea-saying\r philosophy, first occurred to me in August 1881. I made a note of the\r thought on a sheet of paper, with the postscript: 6,000 feet beyond\r men and time! That day I happened to be wandering through the woods\r alongside of the lake of Silvaplana, and I halted beside a huge,\r pyramidal and towering rock not far from Surlei. It was then that the\r thought struck me. Looking back now, I find that exactly two months\r previous to this inspiration, I had had an omen of its coming in the\r form of a sudden and decisive alteration in my tastes—more particularly\r in music","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-12-19","text":"During the month of August 1881 my brother resolved to reveal the\r teaching of the Eternal Recurrence, in dithyrambic and psalmodic form,\r through the mouth of Zarathustra. Among the notes of this period, we\r found a page on which is written the first definite plan of “Thus Spake\r Zarathustra”:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-1","text":"“Zarathustra born on lake Urmi; left his home in his thirtieth year,\r went into the province of Aria, and, during ten years of solitude in the\r mountains, composed the Zend-Avesta.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-2","text":"“The sun of knowledge stands once more at midday; and the serpent\r of eternity lies coiled in its light—: It is YOUR time, ye midday\r brethren.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-3","text":"In that summer of 1881, my brother, after many years of steadily\r declining health, began at last to rally, and it is to this first gush\r of the recovery of his once splendid bodily condition that we owe not\r only “The Gay Science”, which in its mood may be regarded as a prelude\r to “Zarathustra”, but also “Zarathustra” itself. Just as he was\r beginning to recuperate his health, however, an unkind destiny brought\r him a number of most painful personal experiences. His friends caused\r him many disappointments, which were the more bitter to him, inasmuch as\r he regarded friendship as such a sacred institution; and for the first\r time in his life he realised the whole horror of that loneliness ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-4","text":"Whether my brother would ever have written “Thus Spake Zarathustra”\r  according to the first plan sketched in the summer of 1881, if he\r had not had the disappointments already referred to, is now an idle\r question; but perhaps where “Zarathustra” is concerned, we may also say\r with Master Eckhardt: “The fleetest beast to bear you to perfection is\r suffering.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-5","text":"My brother writes as follows about the origin of the first part of\r “Zarathustra”:—“In the winter of 1882–83, I was living on the charming\r little Gulf of Rapallo, not far from Genoa, and between Chiavari and\r Cape Porto Fino. My health was not very good; the winter was cold and\r exceptionally rainy; and the small inn in which I lived was so close\r to the water that at night my sleep would be disturbed if the sea were\r high. These circumstances were surely the very reverse of favourable;\r and yet in spite of it all, and as if in demonstration of my belief that\r everything decisive comes to life in spite of every obstacle, it was\r precisely during this winter and in the midst of these unfavou","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-6","text":"The first part of “Zarathustra” was written in about ten days—that is\r to say, from the beginning to about the middle of February 1883. “The\r last lines were written precisely in the hallowed hour when Richard\r Wagner gave up the ghost in Venice.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-7","text":"With the exception of the ten days occupied in composing the first part\r of this book, my brother often referred to this winter as the hardest\r and sickliest he had ever experienced. He did not, however, mean thereby\r that his former disorders were troubling him, but that he was suffering\r from a severe attack of influenza which he had caught in Santa\r Margherita, and which tormented him for several weeks after his arrival\r in Genoa. As a matter of fact, however, what he complained of most was\r his spiritual condition—that indescribable forsakenness—to which he\r gives such heartrending expression in “Zarathustra”. Even the reception\r which the first part met with at the hands of friends and ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-8","text":"We remained somewhat too long in Rome that spring, and what with the\r effect of the increasing heat and the discouraging circumstances already\r described, my brother resolved not to write any more, or in any case,\r not to proceed with “Zarathustra”, although I offered to relieve him\r of all trouble in connection with the proofs and the publisher. When,\r however, we returned to Switzerland towards the end of June, and he\r found himself once more in the familiar and exhilarating air of the\r mountains, all his joyous creative powers revived, and in a note to me\r announcing the dispatch of some manuscript, he wrote as follows: “I have\r engaged a place here for three months: forsooth, I am the gr","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-9","text":"The second part of “Zarathustra” was written between the 26th of June\r and the 6th July. “This summer, finding myself once more in the sacred\r place where the first thought of ‘Zarathustra’ flashed across my mind,\r I conceived the second part. Ten days sufficed. Neither for the second,\r the first, nor the third part, have I required a day longer.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-10","text":"He often used to speak of the ecstatic mood in which he wrote\r “Zarathustra”; how in his walks over hill and dale the ideas would crowd\r into his mind, and how he would note them down hastily in a note-book\r from which he would transcribe them on his return, sometimes working\r till midnight. He says in a letter to me: “You can have no idea of the\r vehemence of such composition,” and in “Ecce Homo” (autumn 1888) he\r describes as follows with passionate enthusiasm the incomparable mood in\r which he created Zarathustra:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-11","text":"“—Has any one at the end of the nineteenth century any distinct notion\r of what poets of a stronger age understood by the word inspiration? If\r not, I will describe it. If one had the smallest vestige of superstition\r in one, it would hardly be possible to set aside completely the idea\r that one is the mere incarnation, mouthpiece or medium of an almighty\r power. The idea of revelation in the sense that something becomes\r suddenly visible and audible with indescribable certainty and accuracy,\r which profoundly convulses and upsets one—describes simply the matter\r of fact. One hears—one does not seek; one takes—one does not ask\r who gives: a thought suddenly flashes up like lightning, it come","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-12","text":"In the autumn of 1883 my brother left the Engadine for Germany and\r stayed there a few weeks. In the following winter, after wandering\r somewhat erratically through Stresa, Genoa, and Spezia, he landed in\r Nice, where the climate so happily promoted his creative powers that\r he wrote the third part of “Zarathustra”. “In the winter, beneath the\r halcyon sky of Nice, which then looked down upon me for the first time\r in my life, I found the third ‘Zarathustra’—and came to the end of my\r task; the whole having occupied me scarcely a year. Many hidden corners\r and heights in the landscapes round about Nice are hallowed to me by\r unforgettable moments. That decisive chapter entitled ‘Old and New\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-13","text":"As we have seen, each of the three parts of “Zarathustra” was written,\r after a more or less short period of preparation, in about ten days.\r The composition of the fourth part alone was broken by occasional\r interruptions. The first notes relating to this part were written while\r he and I were staying together in Zurich in September 1884. In the\r following November, while staying at Mentone, he began to elaborate\r these notes, and after a long pause, finished the manuscript at Nice\r between the end of January and the middle of February 1885. My brother\r then called this part the fourth and last; but even before, and shortly\r after it had been privately printed, he wrote to me saying that he","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-14-14","text":"Already at the beginning of this history I hinted at the reasons which\r led my brother to select a Persian as the incarnation of his ideal of\r the majestic philosopher. His reasons, however, for choosing Zarathustra\r of all others to be his mouthpiece, he gives us in the following\r words:—“People have never asked me, as they should have done, what the\r name Zarathustra precisely means in my mouth, in the mouth of the first\r Immoralist; for what distinguishes that philosopher from all others\r in the past is the very fact that he was exactly the reverse of an\r immoralist. Zarathustra was the first to see in the struggle between\r good and evil the essential wheel in the working of things. The\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-1","text":"When Zarathustra was thirty years old, he left his home and the lake of\r his home, and went into the mountains. There he enjoyed his spirit and\r solitude, and for ten years did not weary of it. But at last his heart\r changed,—and rising one morning with the rosy dawn, he went before the\r sun, and spake thus unto it:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-2","text":"Thou great star! What would be thy happiness if thou hadst not those for\r whom thou shinest!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-3","text":"For ten years hast thou climbed hither unto my cave: thou wouldst have\r wearied of thy light and of the journey, had it not been for me, mine\r eagle, and my serpent.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-4","text":"But we awaited thee every morning, took from thee thine overflow and\r blessed thee for it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-5","text":"Lo! I am weary of my wisdom, like the bee that hath gathered too much\r honey; I need hands outstretched to take it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-6","text":"I would fain bestow and distribute, until the wise have once more become\r joyous in their folly, and the poor happy in their riches.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-7","text":"Therefore must I descend into the deep: as thou doest in the\r evening, when thou goest behind the sea, and givest light also to the\r nether-world, thou exuberant star!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-8","text":"Like thee must I GO DOWN, as men say, to whom I shall descend.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-9","text":"Bless me, then, thou tranquil eye, that canst behold even the greatest\r happiness without envy!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-10","text":"Bless the cup that is about to overflow, that the water may flow golden\r out of it, and carry everywhere the reflection of thy bliss!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-11","text":"Lo! This cup is again going to empty itself, and Zarathustra is again\r going to be a man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-12","text":"Zarathustra went down the mountain alone, no one meeting him. When he\r entered the forest, however, there suddenly stood before him an old man,\r who had left his holy cot to seek roots. And thus spake the old man to\r Zarathustra:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-13","text":"“No stranger to me is this wanderer: many years ago passed he by.\r Zarathustra he was called; but he hath altered.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-14","text":"Then thou carriedst thine ashes into the mountains: wilt thou now carry\r thy fire into the valleys? Fearest thou not the incendiary’s doom?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-15","text":"Yea, I recognise Zarathustra. Pure is his eye, and no loathing lurketh\r about his mouth. Goeth he not along like a dancer?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-16","text":"Altered is Zarathustra; a child hath Zarathustra become; an awakened one\r is Zarathustra: what wilt thou do in the land of the sleepers?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-17","text":"As in the sea hast thou lived in solitude, and it hath borne thee up.\r Alas, wilt thou now go ashore? Alas, wilt thou again drag thy body\r thyself?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-18","text":"“Why,” said the saint, “did I go into the forest and the desert? Was it\r not because I loved men far too well?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-19","text":"Now I love God: men, I do not love. Man is a thing too imperfect for me.\r Love to man would be fatal to me.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-20","text":"Zarathustra answered: “What spake I of love! I am bringing gifts unto\r men.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-21","text":"“Give them nothing,” said the saint. “Take rather part of their load,\r and carry it along with them—that will be most agreeable unto them: if\r only it be agreeable unto thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-22","text":"If, however, thou wilt give unto them, give them no more than an alms,\r and let them also beg for it!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-23","text":"“No,” replied Zarathustra, “I give no alms. I am not poor enough for\r that.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-24","text":"The saint laughed at Zarathustra, and spake thus: “Then see to it that\r they accept thy treasures! They are distrustful of anchorites, and do\r not believe that we come with gifts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-25","text":"The fall of our footsteps ringeth too hollow through their streets. And\r just as at night, when they are in bed and hear a man abroad long before\r sunrise, so they ask themselves concerning us: Where goeth the thief?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-26","text":"Go not to men, but stay in the forest! Go rather to the animals! Why not\r be like me—a bear amongst bears, a bird amongst birds?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-27","text":"“And what doeth the saint in the forest?” asked Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-28","text":"The saint answered: “I make hymns and sing them; and in making hymns I\r laugh and weep and mumble: thus do I praise God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-29","text":"With singing, weeping, laughing, and mumbling do I praise the God who is\r my God. But what dost thou bring us as a gift?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-30","text":"When Zarathustra had heard these words, he bowed to the saint and said:\r “What should I have to give thee! Let me rather hurry hence lest I take\r aught away from thee!”—And thus they parted from one another, the old\r man and Zarathustra, laughing like schoolboys.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-31","text":"When Zarathustra was alone, however, he said to his heart: “Could it be\r possible! This old saint in the forest hath not yet heard of it, that\r GOD IS DEAD!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-32","text":"When Zarathustra arrived at the nearest town which adjoineth the forest,\r he found many people assembled in the market-place; for it had been\r announced that a rope-dancer would give a performance. And Zarathustra\r spake thus unto the people:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-33","text":"I TEACH YOU THE SUPERMAN. Man is something that is to be surpassed. What\r have ye done to surpass man?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-34","text":"All beings hitherto have created something beyond themselves: and ye\r want to be the ebb of that great tide, and would rather go back to the\r beast than surpass man?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-35","text":"What is the ape to man? A laughing-stock, a thing of shame. And just the\r same shall man be to the Superman: a laughing-stock, a thing of shame.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-36","text":"Ye have made your way from the worm to man, and much within you is still\r worm. Once were ye apes, and even yet man is more of an ape than any of\r the apes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-37","text":"Even the wisest among you is only a disharmony and hybrid of plant and\r phantom. But do I bid you become phantoms or plants?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-38","text":"The Superman is the meaning of the earth. Let your will say: The\r Superman SHALL BE the meaning of the earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-39","text":"I conjure you, my brethren, REMAIN TRUE TO THE EARTH, and believe not\r those who speak unto you of superearthly hopes! Poisoners are they,\r whether they know it or not.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-40","text":"Despisers of life are they, decaying ones and poisoned ones themselves,\r of whom the earth is weary: so away with them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-41","text":"Once blasphemy against God was the greatest blasphemy; but God died,\r and therewith also those blasphemers. To blaspheme the earth is now the\r dreadfulest sin, and to rate the heart of the unknowable higher than the\r meaning of the earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-42","text":"Once the soul looked contemptuously on the body, and then that contempt\r was the supreme thing:—the soul wished the body meagre, ghastly, and\r famished. Thus it thought to escape from the body and the earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-43","text":"Oh, that soul was itself meagre, ghastly, and famished; and cruelty was\r the delight of that soul!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-44","text":"But ye, also, my brethren, tell me: What doth your body say about\r your soul? Is your soul not poverty and pollution and wretched\r self-complacency?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-45","text":"Verily, a polluted stream is man. One must be a sea, to receive a\r polluted stream without becoming impure.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-46","text":"Lo, I teach you the Superman: he is that sea; in him can your great\r contempt be submerged.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-47","text":"What is the greatest thing ye can experience? It is the hour of great\r contempt. The hour in which even your happiness becometh loathsome unto\r you, and so also your reason and virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-48","text":"The hour when ye say: “What good is my happiness! It is poverty and\r pollution and wretched self-complacency. But my happiness should justify\r existence itself!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-49","text":"The hour when ye say: “What good is my reason! Doth it long for\r knowledge as the lion for his food? It is poverty and pollution and\r wretched self-complacency!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-50","text":"The hour when ye say: “What good is my virtue! As yet it hath not made\r me passionate. How weary I am of my good and my bad! It is all poverty\r and pollution and wretched self-complacency!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-51","text":"The hour when ye say: “What good is my justice! I do not see that I am\r fervour and fuel. The just, however, are fervour and fuel!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-52","text":"The hour when ye say: “What good is my pity! Is not pity the cross on\r which he is nailed who loveth man? But my pity is not a crucifixion.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-53","text":"Have ye ever spoken thus? Have ye ever cried thus? Ah! would that I had\r heard you crying thus!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-54","text":"It is not your sin—it is your self-satisfaction that crieth unto\r heaven; your very sparingness in sin crieth unto heaven!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-55","text":"Where is the lightning to lick you with its tongue? Where is the frenzy\r with which ye should be inoculated?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-56","text":"Lo, I teach you the Superman: he is that lightning, he is that frenzy!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-57","text":"When Zarathustra had thus spoken, one of the people called out: “We have\r now heard enough of the rope-dancer; it is time now for us to see him!”\r  And all the people laughed at Zarathustra. But the rope-dancer, who\r thought the words applied to him, began his performance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-58","text":"Zarathustra, however, looked at the people and wondered. Then he spake\r thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-59","text":"Man is a rope stretched between the animal and the Superman—a rope over\r an abyss.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-60","text":"A dangerous crossing, a dangerous wayfaring, a dangerous looking-back, a\r dangerous trembling and halting.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-61","text":"What is great in man is that he is a bridge and not a goal: what is\r lovable in man is that he is an OVER-GOING and a DOWN-GOING.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-62","text":"I love those that know not how to live except as down-goers, for they\r are the over-goers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-63","text":"I love the great despisers, because they are the great adorers, and\r arrows of longing for the other shore.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-64","text":"I love those who do not first seek a reason beyond the stars for going\r down and being sacrifices, but sacrifice themselves to the earth, that\r the earth of the Superman may hereafter arrive.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-65","text":"I love him who liveth in order to know, and seeketh to know in\r order that the Superman may hereafter live. Thus seeketh he his own\r down-going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-66","text":"I love him who laboureth and inventeth, that he may build the house for\r the Superman, and prepare for him earth, animal, and plant: for thus\r seeketh he his own down-going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-67","text":"I love him who loveth his virtue: for virtue is the will to down-going,\r and an arrow of longing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-68","text":"I love him who reserveth no share of spirit for himself, but wanteth to\r be wholly the spirit of his virtue: thus walketh he as spirit over the\r bridge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-69","text":"I love him who maketh his virtue his inclination and destiny: thus, for\r the sake of his virtue, he is willing to live on, or live no more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-70","text":"I love him who desireth not too many virtues. One virtue is more of a\r virtue than two, because it is more of a knot for one’s destiny to cling\r to.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-71","text":"I love him whose soul is lavish, who wanteth no thanks and doth not give\r back: for he always bestoweth, and desireth not to keep for himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-72","text":"I love him who is ashamed when the dice fall in his favour, and who then\r asketh: “Am I a dishonest player?”—for he is willing to succumb.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-73","text":"I love him who scattereth golden words in advance of his deeds, and\r always doeth more than he promiseth: for he seeketh his own down-going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-74","text":"I love him who justifieth the future ones, and redeemeth the past ones:\r for he is willing to succumb through the present ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-75","text":"I love him who chasteneth his God, because he loveth his God: for he\r must succumb through the wrath of his God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-76","text":"I love him whose soul is deep even in the wounding, and may succumb\r through a small matter: thus goeth he willingly over the bridge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-77","text":"I love him whose soul is so overfull that he forgetteth himself, and all\r things are in him: thus all things become his down-going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-78","text":"I love him who is of a free spirit and a free heart: thus is his\r head only the bowels of his heart; his heart, however, causeth his\r down-going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-79","text":"I love all who are like heavy drops falling one by one out of the dark\r cloud that lowereth over man: they herald the coming of the lightning,\r and succumb as heralds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-80","text":"Lo, I am a herald of the lightning, and a heavy drop out of the cloud:\r the lightning, however, is the SUPERMAN.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-81","text":"When Zarathustra had spoken these words, he again looked at the people,\r and was silent. “There they stand,” said he to his heart; “there they\r laugh: they understand me not; I am not the mouth for these ears.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-82","text":"Must one first batter their ears, that they may learn to hear with their\r eyes? Must one clatter like kettledrums and penitential preachers? Or do\r they only believe the stammerer?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-83","text":"They have something whereof they are proud. What do they call it, that\r which maketh them proud? Culture, they call it; it distinguisheth them\r from the goatherds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-84","text":"They dislike, therefore, to hear of ‘contempt’ of themselves. So I will\r appeal to their pride.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-85","text":"I will speak unto them of the most contemptible thing: that, however, is\r THE LAST MAN!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-86","text":"It is time for man to fix his goal. It is time for man to plant the germ\r of his highest hope.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-87","text":"Still is his soil rich enough for it. But that soil will one day be\r poor and exhausted, and no lofty tree will any longer be able to grow\r thereon.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-88","text":"Alas! there cometh the time when man will no longer launch the arrow of\r his longing beyond man—and the string of his bow will have unlearned to\r whizz!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-89","text":"I tell you: one must still have chaos in one, to give birth to a dancing\r star. I tell you: ye have still chaos in you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-90","text":"Alas! There cometh the time when man will no longer give birth to any\r star. Alas! There cometh the time of the most despicable man, who can no\r longer despise himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-91","text":"“What is love? What is creation? What is longing? What is a star?”—so\r asketh the last man and blinketh.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-92","text":"The earth hath then become small, and on it there hoppeth the last man\r who maketh everything small. His species is ineradicable like that of\r the ground-flea; the last man liveth longest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-93","text":"“We have discovered happiness”—say the last men, and blink thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-94","text":"They have left the regions where it is hard to live; for they need\r warmth. One still loveth one’s neighbour and rubbeth against him; for\r one needeth warmth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-95","text":"Turning ill and being distrustful, they consider sinful: they walk\r warily. He is a fool who still stumbleth over stones or men!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-96","text":"A little poison now and then: that maketh pleasant dreams. And much\r poison at last for a pleasant death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-97","text":"One still worketh, for work is a pastime. But one is careful lest the\r pastime should hurt one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-98","text":"One no longer becometh poor or rich; both are too burdensome. Who still\r wanteth to rule? Who still wanteth to obey? Both are too burdensome.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-99","text":"No shepherd, and one herd! Every one wanteth the same; every one is\r equal: he who hath other sentiments goeth voluntarily into the madhouse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-100","text":"“Formerly all the world was insane,”—say the subtlest of them, and\r blink thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-101","text":"They are clever and know all that hath happened: so there is\r no end to their raillery. People still fall out, but are soon\r reconciled—otherwise it spoileth their stomachs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-102","text":"They have their little pleasures for the day, and their little pleasures\r for the night, but they have a regard for health.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-103","text":"“We have discovered happiness,”—say the last men, and blink thereby.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-104","text":"And here ended the first discourse of Zarathustra, which is also\r called “The Prologue”: for at this point the shouting and mirth of the\r multitude interrupted him. “Give us this last man, O Zarathustra,”—they\r called out—“make us into these last men! Then will we make thee a\r present of the Superman!” And all the people exulted and smacked their\r lips. Zarathustra, however, turned sad, and said to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-105","text":"Too long, perhaps, have I lived in the mountains; too much have I\r hearkened unto the brooks and trees: now do I speak unto them as unto\r the goatherds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-106","text":"Calm is my soul, and clear, like the mountains in the morning. But they\r think me cold, and a mocker with terrible jests.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-107","text":"And now do they look at me and laugh: and while they laugh they hate me\r too. There is ice in their laughter.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-108","text":"Then, however, something happened which made every mouth mute and every\r eye fixed. In the meantime, of course, the rope-dancer had commenced his\r performance: he had come out at a little door, and was going along the\r rope which was stretched between two towers, so that it hung above the\r market-place and the people. When he was just midway across, the little\r door opened once more, and a gaudily-dressed fellow like a buffoon\r sprang out, and went rapidly after the first one. “Go on, halt-foot,”\r  cried his frightful voice, “go on, lazy-bones, interloper,\r sallow-face!—lest I tickle thee with my heel! What dost thou here\r between the towers? In the tower is the place for thee, thou shouldst","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-109","text":"Zarathustra, however, remained standing, and just beside him fell the\r body, badly injured and disfigured, but not yet dead. After a while\r consciousness returned to the shattered man, and he saw Zarathustra\r kneeling beside him. “What art thou doing there?” said he at last, “I\r knew long ago that the devil would trip me up. Now he draggeth me to\r hell: wilt thou prevent him?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-110","text":"“On mine honour, my friend,” answered Zarathustra, “there is nothing of\r all that whereof thou speakest: there is no devil and no hell. Thy soul\r will be dead even sooner than thy body: fear, therefore, nothing any\r more!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-111","text":"The man looked up distrustfully. “If thou speakest the truth,” said he,\r “I lose nothing when I lose my life. I am not much more than an animal\r which hath been taught to dance by blows and scanty fare.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-112","text":"“Not at all,” said Zarathustra, “thou hast made danger thy calling;\r therein there is nothing contemptible. Now thou perishest by thy\r calling: therefore will I bury thee with mine own hands.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-113","text":"When Zarathustra had said this the dying one did not reply further; but\r he moved his hand as if he sought the hand of Zarathustra in gratitude.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-114","text":"Meanwhile the evening came on, and the market-place veiled itself in\r gloom. Then the people dispersed, for even curiosity and terror become\r fatigued. Zarathustra, however, still sat beside the dead man on the\r ground, absorbed in thought: so he forgot the time. But at last it\r became night, and a cold wind blew upon the lonely one. Then arose\r Zarathustra and said to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-115","text":"Verily, a fine catch of fish hath Zarathustra made to-day! It is not a\r man he hath caught, but a corpse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-116","text":"Sombre is human life, and as yet without meaning: a buffoon may be\r fateful to it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-117","text":"I want to teach men the sense of their existence, which is the Superman,\r the lightning out of the dark cloud—man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-118","text":"But still am I far from them, and my sense speaketh not unto their\r sense. To men I am still something between a fool and a corpse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-119","text":"Gloomy is the night, gloomy are the ways of Zarathustra. Come, thou cold\r and stiff companion! I carry thee to the place where I shall bury thee\r with mine own hands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-120","text":"When Zarathustra had said this to his heart, he put the corpse upon his\r shoulders and set out on his way. Yet had he not gone a hundred steps,\r when there stole a man up to him and whispered in his ear—and lo!\r he that spake was the buffoon from the tower. “Leave this town, O\r Zarathustra,” said he, “there are too many here who hate thee. The\r good and just hate thee, and call thee their enemy and despiser; the\r believers in the orthodox belief hate thee, and call thee a danger to\r the multitude. It was thy good fortune to be laughed at: and verily thou\r spakest like a buffoon. It was thy good fortune to associate with the\r dead dog; by so humiliating thyself thou hast saved thy life to-day","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-121","text":"At the gate of the town the grave-diggers met him: they shone their\r torch on his face, and, recognising Zarathustra, they sorely derided\r him. “Zarathustra is carrying away the dead dog: a fine thing that\r Zarathustra hath turned a grave-digger! For our hands are too cleanly\r for that roast. Will Zarathustra steal the bite from the devil? Well\r then, good luck to the repast! If only the devil is not a better thief\r than Zarathustra!—he will steal them both, he will eat them both!” And\r they laughed among themselves, and put their heads together.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-122","text":"Zarathustra made no answer thereto, but went on his way. When he had\r gone on for two hours, past forests and swamps, he had heard too much of\r the hungry howling of the wolves, and he himself became a-hungry. So he\r halted at a lonely house in which a light was burning.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-123","text":"“Hunger attacketh me,” said Zarathustra, “like a robber. Among forests\r and swamps my hunger attacketh me, and late in the night.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-124","text":"“Strange humours hath my hunger. Often it cometh to me only after a\r repast, and all day it hath failed to come: where hath it been?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-125","text":"And thereupon Zarathustra knocked at the door of the house. An old man\r appeared, who carried a light, and asked: “Who cometh unto me and my bad\r sleep?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-126","text":"“A living man and a dead one,” said Zarathustra. “Give me something to\r eat and drink, I forgot it during the day. He that feedeth the hungry\r refresheth his own soul, saith wisdom.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-127","text":"The old man withdrew, but came back immediately and offered Zarathustra\r bread and wine. “A bad country for the hungry,” said he; “that is why\r I live here. Animal and man come unto me, the anchorite. But bid thy\r companion eat and drink also, he is wearier than thou.” Zarathustra\r answered: “My companion is dead; I shall hardly be able to persuade him\r to eat.” “That doth not concern me,” said the old man sullenly; “he\r that knocketh at my door must take what I offer him. Eat, and fare ye\r well!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-128","text":"Thereafter Zarathustra again went on for two hours, trusting to the path\r and the light of the stars: for he was an experienced night-walker, and\r liked to look into the face of all that slept. When the morning dawned,\r however, Zarathustra found himself in a thick forest, and no path was\r any longer visible. He then put the dead man in a hollow tree at his\r head—for he wanted to protect him from the wolves—and laid himself\r down on the ground and moss. And immediately he fell asleep, tired in\r body, but with a tranquil soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-129","text":"Long slept Zarathustra; and not only the rosy dawn passed over his head,\r but also the morning. At last, however, his eyes opened, and amazedly he\r gazed into the forest and the stillness, amazedly he gazed into himself.\r Then he arose quickly, like a seafarer who all at once seeth the land;\r and he shouted for joy: for he saw a new truth. And he spake thus to his\r heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-130","text":"A light hath dawned upon me: I need companions—living ones; not dead\r companions and corpses, which I carry with me where I will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-131","text":"But I need living companions, who will follow me because they want to\r follow themselves—and to the place where I will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-132","text":"A light hath dawned upon me. Not to the people is Zarathustra to speak,\r but to companions! Zarathustra shall not be the herd’s herdsman and\r hound!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-133","text":"To allure many from the herd—for that purpose have I come. The people\r and the herd must be angry with me: a robber shall Zarathustra be called\r by the herdsmen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-134","text":"Herdsmen, I say, but they call themselves the good and just. Herdsmen, I\r say, but they call themselves the believers in the orthodox belief.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-135","text":"Behold the good and just! Whom do they hate most? Him who breaketh up\r their tables of values, the breaker, the law-breaker:—he, however, is\r the creator.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-136","text":"Behold the believers of all beliefs! Whom do they hate most? Him who\r breaketh up their tables of values, the breaker, the law-breaker—he,\r however, is the creator.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-137","text":"Companions, the creator seeketh, not corpses—and not herds or believers\r either. Fellow-creators the creator seeketh—those who grave new values\r on new tables.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-138","text":"Companions, the creator seeketh, and fellow-reapers: for everything is\r ripe for the harvest with him. But he lacketh the hundred sickles: so he\r plucketh the ears of corn and is vexed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-139","text":"Companions, the creator seeketh, and such as know how to whet their\r sickles. Destroyers, will they be called, and despisers of good and\r evil. But they are the reapers and rejoicers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-140","text":"Fellow-creators, Zarathustra seeketh; fellow-reapers and\r fellow-rejoicers, Zarathustra seeketh: what hath he to do with herds and\r herdsmen and corpses!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-141","text":"And thou, my first companion, rest in peace! Well have I buried thee in\r thy hollow tree; well have I hid thee from the wolves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-142","text":"But I part from thee; the time hath arrived. ‘Twixt rosy dawn and rosy\r dawn there came unto me a new truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-143","text":"I am not to be a herdsman, I am not to be a grave-digger. Not any more\r will I discourse unto the people; for the last time have I spoken unto\r the dead.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-144","text":"With the creators, the reapers, and the rejoicers will I associate: the\r rainbow will I show them, and all the stairs to the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-145","text":"To the lone-dwellers will I sing my song, and to the twain-dwellers;\r and unto him who hath still ears for the unheard, will I make the heart\r heavy with my happiness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-146","text":"I make for my goal, I follow my course; over the loitering and tardy\r will I leap. Thus let my on-going be their down-going!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-147","text":"This had Zarathustra said to his heart when the sun stood at noontide.\r Then he looked inquiringly aloft,—for he heard above him the sharp call\r of a bird. And behold! An eagle swept through the air in wide circles,\r and on it hung a serpent, not like a prey, but like a friend: for it\r kept itself coiled round the eagle’s neck.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-148","text":"“They are mine animals,” said Zarathustra, and rejoiced in his heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-149","text":"“The proudest animal under the sun, and the wisest animal under the\r sun,—they have come out to reconnoitre.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-150","text":"They want to know whether Zarathustra still liveth. Verily, do I still\r live?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-151","text":"More dangerous have I found it among men than among animals; in\r dangerous paths goeth Zarathustra. Let mine animals lead me!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-152","text":"When Zarathustra had said this, he remembered the words of the saint in\r the forest. Then he sighed and spake thus to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-153","text":"“Would that I were wiser! Would that I were wise from the very heart,\r like my serpent!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-154","text":"But I am asking the impossible. Therefore do I ask my pride to go always\r with my wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-18-155","text":"And if my wisdom should some day forsake me:—alas! it loveth to fly\r away!—may my pride then fly with my folly!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-1","text":"Three metamorphoses of the spirit do I designate to you: how the spirit\r becometh a camel, the camel a lion, and the lion at last a child.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-2","text":"Many heavy things are there for the spirit, the strong load-bearing\r spirit in which reverence dwelleth: for the heavy and the heaviest\r longeth its strength.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-3","text":"What is heavy? so asketh the load-bearing spirit; then kneeleth it down\r like the camel, and wanteth to be well laden.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-4","text":"What is the heaviest thing, ye heroes? asketh the load-bearing spirit,\r that I may take it upon me and rejoice in my strength.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-5","text":"Is it not this: To humiliate oneself in order to mortify one’s pride? To\r exhibit one’s folly in order to mock at one’s wisdom?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-6","text":"Or is it this: To desert our cause when it celebrateth its triumph? To\r ascend high mountains to tempt the tempter?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-7","text":"Or is it this: To feed on the acorns and grass of knowledge, and for the\r sake of truth to suffer hunger of soul?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-8","text":"Or is it this: To be sick and dismiss comforters, and make friends of\r the deaf, who never hear thy requests?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-9","text":"Or is it this: To go into foul water when it is the water of truth, and\r not disclaim cold frogs and hot toads?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-10","text":"Or is it this: To love those who despise us, and give one’s hand to the\r phantom when it is going to frighten us?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-11","text":"All these heaviest things the load-bearing spirit taketh upon itself:\r and like the camel, which, when laden, hasteneth into the wilderness, so\r hasteneth the spirit into its wilderness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-12","text":"But in the loneliest wilderness happeneth the second metamorphosis: here\r the spirit becometh a lion; freedom will it capture, and lordship in its\r own wilderness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-13","text":"Its last Lord it here seeketh: hostile will it be to him, and to its\r last God; for victory will it struggle with the great dragon.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-14","text":"What is the great dragon which the spirit is no longer inclined to call\r Lord and God? “Thou shalt,” is the great dragon called. But the spirit\r of the lion saith, “I will.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-15","text":"“Thou shalt,” lieth in its path, sparkling with gold—a scale-covered\r beast; and on every scale glittereth golden, “Thou shalt!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-16","text":"The values of a thousand years glitter on those scales, and\r thus speaketh the mightiest of all dragons: “All the values of\r things—glitter on me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-17","text":"All values have already been created, and all created values—do I\r represent. Verily, there shall be no ‘I will’ any more.” Thus speaketh\r the dragon.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-18","text":"My brethren, wherefore is there need of the lion in the spirit? Why\r sufficeth not the beast of burden, which renounceth and is reverent?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-19","text":"To create new values—that, even the lion cannot yet accomplish: but to\r create itself freedom for new creating—that can the might of the lion\r do.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-20","text":"To create itself freedom, and give a holy Nay even unto duty: for that,\r my brethren, there is need of the lion.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-21","text":"To assume the right to new values—that is the most formidable\r assumption for a load-bearing and reverent spirit. Verily, unto such a\r spirit it is preying, and the work of a beast of prey.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-22","text":"As its holiest, it once loved “Thou shalt”: now is it forced to find\r illusion and arbitrariness even in the holiest things, that it may\r capture freedom from its love: the lion is needed for this capture.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-23","text":"But tell me, my brethren, what the child can do, which even the lion\r could not do? Why hath the preying lion still to become a child?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-24","text":"Innocence is the child, and forgetfulness, a new beginning, a game, a\r self-rolling wheel, a first movement, a holy Yea.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-25","text":"Aye, for the game of creating, my brethren, there is needed a holy Yea\r unto life: ITS OWN will, willeth now the spirit; HIS OWN world winneth\r the world’s outcast.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":212},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-26","text":"Three metamorphoses of the spirit have I designated to you: how the\r spirit became a camel, the camel a lion, and the lion at last a child.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":213},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-20-27","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. And at that time he abode in the town which is\r called The Pied Cow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":214},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-1","text":"People commended unto Zarathustra a wise man, as one who could discourse\r well about sleep and virtue: greatly was he honoured and rewarded for\r it, and all the youths sat before his chair. To him went Zarathustra,\r and sat among the youths before his chair. And thus spake the wise man:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":215},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-2","text":"Respect and modesty in presence of sleep! That is the first thing! And\r to go out of the way of all who sleep badly and keep awake at night!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":216},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-3","text":"Modest is even the thief in presence of sleep: he always stealeth softly\r through the night. Immodest, however, is the night-watchman; immodestly\r he carrieth his horn.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":217},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-4","text":"No small art is it to sleep: it is necessary for that purpose to keep\r awake all day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":218},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-5","text":"Ten times a day must thou overcome thyself: that causeth wholesome\r weariness, and is poppy to the soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":219},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-6","text":"Ten times must thou reconcile again with thyself; for overcoming is\r bitterness, and badly sleep the unreconciled.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":220},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-7","text":"Ten truths must thou find during the day; otherwise wilt thou seek truth\r during the night, and thy soul will have been hungry.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":221},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-8","text":"Ten times must thou laugh during the day, and be cheerful; otherwise thy\r stomach, the father of affliction, will disturb thee in the night.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":222},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-9","text":"Few people know it, but one must have all the virtues in order to sleep\r well. Shall I bear false witness? Shall I commit adultery?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":223},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-10","text":"Shall I covet my neighbour’s maidservant? All that would ill accord with\r good sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":224},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-11","text":"And even if one have all the virtues, there is still one thing needful:\r to send the virtues themselves to sleep at the right time.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":225},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-12","text":"That they may not quarrel with one another, the good females! And about\r thee, thou unhappy one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":226},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-13","text":"Peace with God and thy neighbour: so desireth good sleep. And peace also\r with thy neighbour’s devil! Otherwise it will haunt thee in the night.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":227},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-14","text":"Honour to the government, and obedience, and also to the crooked\r government! So desireth good sleep. How can I help it, if power like to\r walk on crooked legs?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":228},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-15","text":"He who leadeth his sheep to the greenest pasture, shall always be for me\r the best shepherd: so doth it accord with good sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":229},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-16","text":"Many honours I want not, nor great treasures: they excite the spleen.\r But it is bad sleeping without a good name and a little treasure.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":230},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-17","text":"A small company is more welcome to me than a bad one: but they must come\r and go at the right time. So doth it accord with good sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":231},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-18","text":"Well, also, do the poor in spirit please me: they promote sleep. Blessed\r are they, especially if one always give in to them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":232},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-19","text":"Thus passeth the day unto the virtuous. When night cometh, then take I\r good care not to summon sleep. It disliketh to be summoned—sleep, the\r lord of the virtues!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":233},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-20","text":"But I think of what I have done and thought during the day. Thus\r ruminating, patient as a cow, I ask myself: What were thy ten\r overcomings?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":234},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-21","text":"And what were the ten reconciliations, and the ten truths, and the ten\r laughters with which my heart enjoyed itself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":235},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-22","text":"Thus pondering, and cradled by forty thoughts, it overtaketh me all at\r once—sleep, the unsummoned, the lord of the virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":236},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-23","text":"Sleep tappeth on mine eye, and it turneth heavy. Sleep toucheth my\r mouth, and it remaineth open.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":237},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-24","text":"Verily, on soft soles doth it come to me, the dearest of thieves, and\r stealeth from me my thoughts: stupid do I then stand, like this academic\r chair.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":238},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-25","text":"When Zarathustra heard the wise man thus speak, he laughed in his heart:\r for thereby had a light dawned upon him. And thus spake he to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":239},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-26","text":"A fool seemeth this wise man with his forty thoughts: but I believe he\r knoweth well how to sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":240},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-27","text":"Happy even is he who liveth near this wise man! Such sleep is\r contagious—even through a thick wall it is contagious.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":241},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-28","text":"A magic resideth even in his academic chair. And not in vain did the\r youths sit before the preacher of virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":242},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-29","text":"His wisdom is to keep awake in order to sleep well. And verily, if\r life had no sense, and had I to choose nonsense, this would be the\r desirablest nonsense for me also.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":243},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-30","text":"Now know I well what people sought formerly above all else when they\r sought teachers of virtue. Good sleep they sought for themselves, and\r poppy-head virtues to promote it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":244},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-31","text":"To all those belauded sages of the academic chairs, wisdom was sleep\r without dreams: they knew no higher significance of life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":245},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-32","text":"Even at present, to be sure, there are some like this preacher of\r virtue, and not always so honourable: but their time is past. And not\r much longer do they stand: there they already lie.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":246},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-21-33","text":"Blessed are those drowsy ones: for they shall soon nod to sleep.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":247},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-1","text":"Once on a time, Zarathustra also cast his fancy beyond man, like all\r backworldsmen. The work of a suffering and tortured God, did the world\r then seem to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":248},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-2","text":"The dream—and diction—of a God, did the world then seem to me;\r coloured vapours before the eyes of a divinely dissatisfied one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":249},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-3","text":"Good and evil, and joy and woe, and I and thou—coloured vapours did\r they seem to me before creative eyes. The creator wished to look away\r from himself,—thereupon he created the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":250},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-4","text":"Intoxicating joy is it for the sufferer to look away from his suffering\r and forget himself. Intoxicating joy and self-forgetting, did the world\r once seem to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":251},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-5","text":"This world, the eternally imperfect, an eternal contradiction’s image\r and imperfect image—an intoxicating joy to its imperfect creator:—thus\r did the world once seem to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":252},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-6","text":"Thus, once on a time, did I also cast my fancy beyond man, like all\r backworldsmen. Beyond man, forsooth?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":253},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-7","text":"Ah, ye brethren, that God whom I created was human work and human\r madness, like all the Gods!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":254},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-8","text":"A man was he, and only a poor fragment of a man and ego. Out of mine own\r ashes and glow it came unto me, that phantom. And verily, it came not\r unto me from the beyond!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":255},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-9","text":"What happened, my brethren? I surpassed myself, the suffering one; I\r carried mine own ashes to the mountain; a brighter flame I contrived for\r myself. And lo! Thereupon the phantom WITHDREW from me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":256},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-10","text":"To me the convalescent would it now be suffering and torment to believe\r in such phantoms: suffering would it now be to me, and humiliation. Thus\r speak I to backworldsmen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":257},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-11","text":"Suffering was it, and impotence—that created all backworlds; and\r the short madness of happiness, which only the greatest sufferer\r experienceth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":258},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-12","text":"Weariness, which seeketh to get to the ultimate with one leap, with\r a death-leap; a poor ignorant weariness, unwilling even to will any\r longer: that created all Gods and backworlds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":259},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-13","text":"Believe me, my brethren! It was the body which despaired of the body—it\r groped with the fingers of the infatuated spirit at the ultimate walls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":260},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-14","text":"Believe me, my brethren! It was the body which despaired of the\r earth—it heard the bowels of existence speaking unto it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":261},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-15","text":"And then it sought to get through the ultimate walls with its head—and\r not with its head only—into “the other world.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":262},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-16","text":"But that “other world” is well concealed from man, that dehumanised,\r inhuman world, which is a celestial naught; and the bowels of existence\r do not speak unto man, except as man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":263},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-17","text":"Verily, it is difficult to prove all being, and hard to make it speak.\r Tell me, ye brethren, is not the strangest of all things best proved?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":264},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-18","text":"Yea, this ego, with its contradiction and perplexity, speaketh most\r uprightly of its being—this creating, willing, evaluing ego, which is\r the measure and value of things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":265},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-19","text":"And this most upright existence, the ego—it speaketh of the body, and\r still implieth the body, even when it museth and raveth and fluttereth\r with broken wings.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":266},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-20","text":"Always more uprightly learneth it to speak, the ego; and the more it\r learneth, the more doth it find titles and honours for the body and the\r earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":267},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-21","text":"A new pride taught me mine ego, and that teach I unto men: no longer\r to thrust one’s head into the sand of celestial things, but to carry it\r freely, a terrestrial head, which giveth meaning to the earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":268},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-22","text":"A new will teach I unto men: to choose that path which man hath followed\r blindly, and to approve of it—and no longer to slink aside from it,\r like the sick and perishing!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":269},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-23","text":"The sick and perishing—it was they who despised the body and the earth,\r and invented the heavenly world, and the redeeming blood-drops; but even\r those sweet and sad poisons they borrowed from the body and the earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":270},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-24","text":"From their misery they sought escape, and the stars were too remote for\r them. Then they sighed: “O that there were heavenly paths by which to\r steal into another existence and into happiness!” Then they contrived\r for themselves their by-paths and bloody draughts!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":271},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-25","text":"Beyond the sphere of their body and this earth they now fancied\r themselves transported, these ungrateful ones. But to what did they owe\r the convulsion and rapture of their transport? To their body and this\r earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":272},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-26","text":"Gentle is Zarathustra to the sickly. Verily, he is not indignant\r at their modes of consolation and ingratitude. May they become\r convalescents and overcomers, and create higher bodies for themselves!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":273},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-27","text":"Neither is Zarathustra indignant at a convalescent who looketh tenderly\r on his delusions, and at midnight stealeth round the grave of his God;\r but sickness and a sick frame remain even in his tears.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":274},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-28","text":"Many sickly ones have there always been among those who muse, and\r languish for God; violently they hate the discerning ones, and the\r latest of virtues, which is uprightness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":275},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-29","text":"Backward they always gaze toward dark ages: then, indeed, were delusion\r and faith something different. Raving of the reason was likeness to God,\r and doubt was sin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":276},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-30","text":"Too well do I know those godlike ones: they insist on being believed in,\r and that doubt is sin. Too well, also, do I know what they themselves\r most believe in.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":277},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-31","text":"Verily, not in backworlds and redeeming blood-drops: but in the body\r do they also believe most; and their own body is for them the\r thing-in-itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":278},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-32","text":"But it is a sickly thing to them, and gladly would they get out of their\r skin. Therefore hearken they to the preachers of death, and themselves\r preach backworlds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":279},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-33","text":"Hearken rather, my brethren, to the voice of the healthy body; it is a\r more upright and pure voice.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":280},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-22-34","text":"More uprightly and purely speaketh the healthy body, perfect and\r square-built; and it speaketh of the meaning of the earth.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":281},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-1","text":"To the despisers of the body will I speak my word. I wish them neither\r to learn afresh, nor teach anew, but only to bid farewell to their own\r bodies,—and thus be dumb.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":282},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-2","text":"“Body am I, and soul”—so saith the child. And why should one not speak\r like children?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":283},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-3","text":"But the awakened one, the knowing one, saith: “Body am I entirely, and\r nothing more; and soul is only the name of something in the body.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":284},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-4","text":"The body is a big sagacity, a plurality with one sense, a war and a\r peace, a flock and a shepherd.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":285},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-5","text":"An instrument of thy body is also thy little sagacity, my brother, which\r thou callest “spirit”—a little instrument and plaything of thy big\r sagacity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":286},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-6","text":"“Ego,” sayest thou, and art proud of that word. But the greater\r thing—in which thou art unwilling to believe—is thy body with its big\r sagacity; it saith not “ego,” but doeth it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":287},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-7","text":"What the sense feeleth, what the spirit discerneth, hath never its end\r in itself. But sense and spirit would fain persuade thee that they are\r the end of all things: so vain are they.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":288},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-8","text":"Instruments and playthings are sense and spirit: behind them there\r is still the Self. The Self seeketh with the eyes of the senses, it\r hearkeneth also with the ears of the spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":289},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-9","text":"Ever hearkeneth the Self, and seeketh; it compareth, mastereth,\r conquereth, and destroyeth. It ruleth, and is also the ego’s ruler.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":290},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-10","text":"Behind thy thoughts and feelings, my brother, there is a mighty lord,\r an unknown sage—it is called Self; it dwelleth in thy body, it is thy\r body.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":291},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-11","text":"There is more sagacity in thy body than in thy best wisdom. And who then\r knoweth why thy body requireth just thy best wisdom?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":292},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-12","text":"Thy Self laugheth at thine ego, and its proud prancings. “What are these\r prancings and flights of thought unto me?” it saith to itself. “A by-way\r to my purpose. I am the leading-string of the ego, and the prompter of\r its notions.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":293},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-13","text":"The Self saith unto the ego: “Feel pain!” And thereupon it suffereth,\r and thinketh how it may put an end thereto—and for that very purpose it\r IS MEANT to think.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":294},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-14","text":"The Self saith unto the ego: “Feel pleasure!” Thereupon it rejoiceth,\r and thinketh how it may ofttimes rejoice—and for that very purpose it\r IS MEANT to think.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":295},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-15","text":"To the despisers of the body will I speak a word. That they despise is\r caused by their esteem. What is it that created esteeming and despising\r and worth and will?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":296},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-16","text":"The creating Self created for itself esteeming and despising, it created\r for itself joy and woe. The creating body created for itself spirit, as\r a hand to its will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":297},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-17","text":"Even in your folly and despising ye each serve your Self, ye despisers\r of the body. I tell you, your very Self wanteth to die, and turneth away\r from life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":298},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-18","text":"No longer can your Self do that which it desireth most:—create beyond\r itself. That is what it desireth most; that is all its fervour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":299},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-19","text":"But it is now too late to do so:—so your Self wisheth to succumb, ye\r despisers of the body.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":300},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-20","text":"To succumb—so wisheth your Self; and therefore have ye become despisers\r of the body. For ye can no longer create beyond yourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":301},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-21","text":"And therefore are ye now angry with life and with the earth. And\r unconscious envy is in the sidelong look of your contempt.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":302},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-23-22","text":"I go not your way, ye despisers of the body! Ye are no bridges for me to\r the Superman!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":303},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-1","text":"My brother, when thou hast a virtue, and it is thine own virtue, thou\r hast it in common with no one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":304},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-2","text":"To be sure, thou wouldst call it by name and caress it; thou wouldst\r pull its ears and amuse thyself with it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":305},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-3","text":"And lo! Then hast thou its name in common with the people, and hast\r become one of the people and the herd with thy virtue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":306},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-4","text":"Better for thee to say: “Ineffable is it, and nameless, that which is\r pain and sweetness to my soul, and also the hunger of my bowels.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":307},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-5","text":"Let thy virtue be too high for the familiarity of names, and if thou\r must speak of it, be not ashamed to stammer about it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":308},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-6","text":"Thus speak and stammer: “That is MY good, that do I love, thus doth it\r please me entirely, thus only do _I_ desire the good.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":309},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-7","text":"Not as the law of a God do I desire it, not as a human law or a human\r need do I desire it; it is not to be a guide-post for me to superearths\r and paradises.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":310},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-8","text":"An earthly virtue is it which I love: little prudence is therein, and\r the least everyday wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":311},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-9","text":"But that bird built its nest beside me: therefore, I love and cherish\r it—now sitteth it beside me on its golden eggs.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":312},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-10","text":"Once hadst thou passions and calledst them evil. But now hast thou only\r thy virtues: they grew out of thy passions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":313},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-11","text":"Thou implantedst thy highest aim into the heart of those passions: then\r became they thy virtues and joys.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":314},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-12","text":"And though thou wert of the race of the hot-tempered, or of the\r voluptuous, or of the fanatical, or the vindictive;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":315},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-13","text":"All thy passions in the end became virtues, and all thy devils angels.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":316},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-14","text":"Once hadst thou wild dogs in thy cellar: but they changed at last into\r birds and charming songstresses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":317},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-15","text":"Out of thy poisons brewedst thou balsam for thyself; thy cow,\r affliction, milkedst thou—now drinketh thou the sweet milk of her\r udder.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":318},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-16","text":"And nothing evil groweth in thee any longer, unless it be the evil that\r groweth out of the conflict of thy virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":319},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-17","text":"My brother, if thou be fortunate, then wilt thou have one virtue and no\r more: thus goest thou easier over the bridge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":320},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-18","text":"Illustrious is it to have many virtues, but a hard lot; and many a one\r hath gone into the wilderness and killed himself, because he was weary\r of being the battle and battlefield of virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":321},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-19","text":"My brother, are war and battle evil? Necessary, however, is the evil;\r necessary are the envy and the distrust and the back-biting among the\r virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":322},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-20","text":"Lo! how each of thy virtues is covetous of the highest place; it wanteth\r thy whole spirit to be ITS herald, it wanteth thy whole power, in wrath,\r hatred, and love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":323},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-21","text":"Jealous is every virtue of the others, and a dreadful thing is jealousy.\r Even virtues may succumb by jealousy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":324},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-22","text":"He whom the flame of jealousy encompasseth, turneth at last, like the\r scorpion, the poisoned sting against himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":325},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-23","text":"Ah! my brother, hast thou never seen a virtue backbite and stab itself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":326},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-24-24","text":"Man is something that hath to be surpassed: and therefore shalt thou\r love thy virtues,—for thou wilt succumb by them.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":327},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-1","text":"Ye do not mean to slay, ye judges and sacrificers, until the animal hath\r bowed its head? Lo! the pale criminal hath bowed his head: out of his\r eye speaketh the great contempt.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":328},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-2","text":"“Mine ego is something which is to be surpassed: mine ego is to me the\r great contempt of man”: so speaketh it out of that eye.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":329},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-3","text":"When he judged himself—that was his supreme moment; let not the exalted\r one relapse again into his low estate!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":330},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-4","text":"There is no salvation for him who thus suffereth from himself, unless it\r be speedy death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":331},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-5","text":"Your slaying, ye judges, shall be pity, and not revenge; and in that ye\r slay, see to it that ye yourselves justify life!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":332},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-6","text":"It is not enough that ye should reconcile with him whom ye slay. Let\r your sorrow be love to the Superman: thus will ye justify your own\r survival!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":333},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-7","text":"“Enemy” shall ye say but not “villain,” “invalid” shall ye say but not\r “wretch,” “fool” shall ye say but not “sinner.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":334},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-8","text":"And thou, red judge, if thou would say audibly all thou hast done in\r thought, then would every one cry: “Away with the nastiness and the\r virulent reptile!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":335},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-9","text":"But one thing is the thought, another thing is the deed, and another\r thing is the idea of the deed. The wheel of causality doth not roll\r between them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":336},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-10","text":"An idea made this pale man pale. Adequate was he for his deed when he\r did it, but the idea of it, he could not endure when it was done.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":337},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-11","text":"Evermore did he now see himself as the doer of one deed. Madness, I call\r this: the exception reversed itself to the rule in him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":338},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-12","text":"The streak of chalk bewitcheth the hen; the stroke he struck bewitched\r his weak reason. Madness AFTER the deed, I call this.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":339},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-13","text":"Hearken, ye judges! There is another madness besides, and it is BEFORE\r the deed. Ah! ye have not gone deep enough into this soul!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":340},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-14","text":"Thus speaketh the red judge: “Why did this criminal commit murder? He\r meant to rob.” I tell you, however, that his soul wanted blood, not\r booty: he thirsted for the happiness of the knife!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":341},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-15","text":"But his weak reason understood not this madness, and it persuaded him.\r “What matter about blood!” it said; “wishest thou not, at least, to make\r booty thereby? Or take revenge?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":342},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-16","text":"And he hearkened unto his weak reason: like lead lay its words upon\r him—thereupon he robbed when he murdered. He did not mean to be\r ashamed of his madness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":343},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-17","text":"And now once more lieth the lead of his guilt upon him, and once more is\r his weak reason so benumbed, so paralysed, and so dull.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":344},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-18","text":"Could he only shake his head, then would his burden roll off; but who\r shaketh that head?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":345},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-19","text":"What is this man? A mass of diseases that reach out into the world\r through the spirit; there they want to get their prey.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":346},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-20","text":"What is this man? A coil of wild serpents that are seldom at peace among\r themselves—so they go forth apart and seek prey in the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":347},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-21","text":"Look at that poor body! What it suffered and craved, the poor soul\r interpreted to itself—it interpreted it as murderous desire, and\r eagerness for the happiness of the knife.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":348},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-22","text":"Him who now turneth sick, the evil overtaketh which is now the evil: he\r seeketh to cause pain with that which causeth him pain. But there have\r been other ages, and another evil and good.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":349},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-23","text":"Once was doubt evil, and the will to Self. Then the invalid became a\r heretic or sorcerer; as heretic or sorcerer he suffered, and sought to\r cause suffering.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":350},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-24","text":"But this will not enter your ears; it hurteth your good people, ye tell\r me. But what doth it matter to me about your good people!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":351},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-25","text":"Many things in your good people cause me disgust, and verily, not their\r evil. I would that they had a madness by which they succumbed, like this\r pale criminal!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":352},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-26","text":"Verily, I would that their madness were called truth, or fidelity,\r or justice: but they have their virtue in order to live long, and in\r wretched self-complacency.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":353},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-25-27","text":"I am a railing alongside the torrent; whoever is able to grasp me may\r grasp me! Your crutch, however, I am not.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":354},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-1","text":"Of all that is written, I love only what a person hath written with his\r blood. Write with blood, and thou wilt find that blood is spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":355},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-2","text":"It is no easy task to understand unfamiliar blood; I hate the reading\r idlers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":356},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-3","text":"He who knoweth the reader, doeth nothing more for the reader. Another\r century of readers—and spirit itself will stink.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":357},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-4","text":"Every one being allowed to learn to read, ruineth in the long run not\r only writing but also thinking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":358},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-5","text":"Once spirit was God, then it became man, and now it even becometh\r populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":359},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-6","text":"He that writeth in blood and proverbs doth not want to be read, but\r learnt by heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":360},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-7","text":"In the mountains the shortest way is from peak to peak, but for that\r route thou must have long legs. Proverbs should be peaks, and those\r spoken to should be big and tall.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":361},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-8","text":"The atmosphere rare and pure, danger near and the spirit full of a\r joyful wickedness: thus are things well matched.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":362},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-9","text":"I want to have goblins about me, for I am courageous. The courage which\r scareth away ghosts, createth for itself goblins—it wanteth to laugh.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":363},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-10","text":"I no longer feel in common with you; the very cloud which I see\r beneath me, the blackness and heaviness at which I laugh—that is your\r thunder-cloud.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":364},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-11","text":"Ye look aloft when ye long for exaltation; and I look downward because I\r am exalted.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":365},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-12","text":"He who climbeth on the highest mountains, laugheth at all tragic plays\r and tragic realities.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":366},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-13","text":"Courageous, unconcerned, scornful, coercive—so wisdom wisheth us; she\r is a woman, and ever loveth only a warrior.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":367},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-14","text":"Ye tell me, “Life is hard to bear.” But for what purpose should ye have\r your pride in the morning and your resignation in the evening?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":368},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-15","text":"Life is hard to bear: but do not affect to be so delicate! We are all of\r us fine sumpter asses and assesses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":369},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-16","text":"What have we in common with the rose-bud, which trembleth because a drop\r of dew hath formed upon it?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":370},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-17","text":"It is true we love life; not because we are wont to live, but because we\r are wont to love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":371},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-18","text":"There is always some madness in love. But there is always, also, some\r method in madness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":372},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-19","text":"And to me also, who appreciate life, the butterflies, and soap-bubbles,\r and whatever is like them amongst us, seem most to enjoy happiness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":373},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-20","text":"To see these light, foolish, pretty, lively little sprites flit\r about—that moveth Zarathustra to tears and songs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":374},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-21","text":"I should only believe in a God that would know how to dance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":375},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-22","text":"And when I saw my devil, I found him serious, thorough, profound,\r solemn: he was the spirit of gravity—through him all things fall.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":376},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-23","text":"Not by wrath, but by laughter, do we slay. Come, let us slay the spirit\r of gravity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":377},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-24","text":"I learned to walk; since then have I let myself run. I learned to fly;\r since then I do not need pushing in order to move from a spot.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":378},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-26-25","text":"Now am I light, now do I fly; now do I see myself under myself. Now\r there danceth a God in me.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":379},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-1","text":"Zarathustra’s eye had perceived that a certain youth avoided him. And as\r he walked alone one evening over the hills surrounding the town called\r “The Pied Cow,” behold, there found he the youth sitting leaning against\r a tree, and gazing with wearied look into the valley. Zarathustra\r thereupon laid hold of the tree beside which the youth sat, and spake\r thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":380},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-2","text":"“If I wished to shake this tree with my hands, I should not be able to\r do so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":381},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-3","text":"But the wind, which we see not, troubleth and bendeth it as it listeth.\r We are sorest bent and troubled by invisible hands.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":382},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-4","text":"Thereupon the youth arose disconcerted, and said: “I hear Zarathustra,\r and just now was I thinking of him!” Zarathustra answered:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":383},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-5","text":"“Why art thou frightened on that account?—But it is the same with man\r as with the tree.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":384},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-6","text":"The more he seeketh to rise into the height and light, the more\r vigorously do his roots struggle earthward, downward, into the dark and\r deep—into the evil.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":385},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-7","text":"“Yea, into the evil!” cried the youth. “How is it possible that thou\r hast discovered my soul?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":386},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-8","text":"Zarathustra smiled, and said: “Many a soul one will never discover,\r unless one first invent it.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":387},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-9","text":"“Thou saidst the truth, Zarathustra. I trust myself no longer since I\r sought to rise into the height, and nobody trusteth me any longer; how\r doth that happen?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":388},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-10","text":"I change too quickly: my to-day refuteth my yesterday. I often overleap\r the steps when I clamber; for so doing, none of the steps pardons me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":389},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-11","text":"When aloft, I find myself always alone. No one speaketh unto me; the\r frost of solitude maketh me tremble. What do I seek on the height?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":390},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-12","text":"My contempt and my longing increase together; the higher I clamber, the\r more do I despise him who clambereth. What doth he seek on the height?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":391},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-13","text":"How ashamed I am of my clambering and stumbling! How I mock at my\r violent panting! How I hate him who flieth! How tired I am on the\r height!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":392},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-14","text":"Here the youth was silent. And Zarathustra contemplated the tree beside\r which they stood, and spake thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":393},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-15","text":"“This tree standeth lonely here on the hills; it hath grown up high\r above man and beast.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":394},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-16","text":"And if it wanted to speak, it would have none who could understand it:\r so high hath it grown.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":395},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-17","text":"Now it waiteth and waiteth,—for what doth it wait? It dwelleth too\r close to the seat of the clouds; it waiteth perhaps for the first\r lightning?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":396},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-18","text":"When Zarathustra had said this, the youth called out with violent\r gestures: “Yea, Zarathustra, thou speakest the truth. My destruction\r I longed for, when I desired to be on the height, and thou art the\r lightning for which I waited! Lo! what have I been since thou hast\r appeared amongst us? It is mine envy of thee that hath destroyed\r me!”—Thus spake the youth, and wept bitterly. Zarathustra, however, put\r his arm about him, and led the youth away with him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":397},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-19","text":"And when they had walked a while together, Zarathustra began to speak\r thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":398},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-20","text":"It rendeth my heart. Better than thy words express it, thine eyes tell\r me all thy danger.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":399},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-21","text":"As yet thou art not free; thou still SEEKEST freedom. Too unslept hath\r thy seeking made thee, and too wakeful.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":400},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-22","text":"On the open height wouldst thou be; for the stars thirsteth thy soul.\r But thy bad impulses also thirst for freedom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":401},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-23","text":"Thy wild dogs want liberty; they bark for joy in their cellar when thy\r spirit endeavoureth to open all prison doors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":402},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-24","text":"Still art thou a prisoner—it seemeth to me—who deviseth liberty\r for himself: ah! sharp becometh the soul of such prisoners, but also\r deceitful and wicked.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":403},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-25","text":"To purify himself, is still necessary for the freedman of the spirit.\r Much of the prison and the mould still remaineth in him: pure hath his\r eye still to become.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":404},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-26","text":"Yea, I know thy danger. But by my love and hope I conjure thee: cast not\r thy love and hope away!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":405},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-27","text":"Noble thou feelest thyself still, and noble others also feel thee still,\r though they bear thee a grudge and cast evil looks. Know this, that to\r everybody a noble one standeth in the way.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":406},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-28","text":"Also to the good, a noble one standeth in the way: and even when they\r call him a good man, they want thereby to put him aside.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":407},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-29","text":"The new, would the noble man create, and a new virtue. The old, wanteth\r the good man, and that the old should be conserved.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":408},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-30","text":"But it is not the danger of the noble man to turn a good man, but lest\r he should become a blusterer, a scoffer, or a destroyer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":409},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-31","text":"Ah! I have known noble ones who lost their highest hope. And then they\r disparaged all high hopes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":410},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-32","text":"Then lived they shamelessly in temporary pleasures, and beyond the day\r had hardly an aim.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":411},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-33","text":"“Spirit is also voluptuousness,”—said they. Then broke the wings of\r their spirit; and now it creepeth about, and defileth where it gnaweth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":412},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-34","text":"Once they thought of becoming heroes; but sensualists are they now. A\r trouble and a terror is the hero to them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":413},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-27-35","text":"But by my love and hope I conjure thee: cast not away the hero in thy\r soul! Maintain holy thy highest hope!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":414},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-1","text":"There are preachers of death: and the earth is full of those to whom\r desistance from life must be preached.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":415},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-2","text":"Full is the earth of the superfluous; marred is life by the\r many-too-many. May they be decoyed out of this life by the “life\r eternal”!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":416},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-3","text":"“The yellow ones”: so are called the preachers of death, or “the black\r ones.” But I will show them unto you in other colours besides.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":417},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-4","text":"There are the terrible ones who carry about in themselves the beast of\r prey, and have no choice except lusts or self-laceration. And even their\r lusts are self-laceration.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":418},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-5","text":"They have not yet become men, those terrible ones: may they preach\r desistance from life, and pass away themselves!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":419},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-6","text":"There are the spiritually consumptive ones: hardly are they born when\r they begin to die, and long for doctrines of lassitude and renunciation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":420},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-7","text":"They would fain be dead, and we should approve of their wish! Let\r us beware of awakening those dead ones, and of damaging those living\r coffins!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":421},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-8","text":"They meet an invalid, or an old man, or a corpse—and immediately they\r say: “Life is refuted!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":422},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-9","text":"But they only are refuted, and their eye, which seeth only one aspect of\r existence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":423},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-10","text":"Shrouded in thick melancholy, and eager for the little casualties that\r bring death: thus do they wait, and clench their teeth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":424},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-11","text":"Or else, they grasp at sweetmeats, and mock at their childishness\r thereby: they cling to their straw of life, and mock at their still\r clinging to it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":425},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-12","text":"Their wisdom speaketh thus: “A fool, he who remaineth alive; but so far\r are we fools! And that is the foolishest thing in life!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":426},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-13","text":"“Life is only suffering”: so say others, and lie not. Then see to it\r that YE cease! See to it that the life ceaseth which is only suffering!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":427},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-14","text":"And let this be the teaching of your virtue: “Thou shalt slay thyself!\r Thou shalt steal away from thyself!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":428},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-15","text":"“Lust is sin,”—so say some who preach death—“let us go apart and beget\r no children!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":429},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-16","text":"“Giving birth is troublesome,”—say others—“why still give birth? One\r beareth only the unfortunate!” And they also are preachers of death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":430},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-17","text":"“Pity is necessary,”—so saith a third party. “Take what I have! Take\r what I am! So much less doth life bind me!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":431},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-18","text":"Were they consistently pitiful, then would they make their neighbours\r sick of life. To be wicked—that would be their true goodness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":432},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-19","text":"But they want to be rid of life; what care they if they bind others\r still faster with their chains and gifts!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":433},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-20","text":"And ye also, to whom life is rough labour and disquiet, are ye not very\r tired of life? Are ye not very ripe for the sermon of death?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":434},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-21","text":"All ye to whom rough labour is dear, and the rapid, new, and strange—ye\r put up with yourselves badly; your diligence is flight, and the will to\r self-forgetfulness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":435},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-22","text":"If ye believed more in life, then would ye devote yourselves less to the\r momentary. But for waiting, ye have not enough of capacity in you—nor\r even for idling!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":436},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-23","text":"Everywhere resoundeth the voices of those who preach death; and the\r earth is full of those to whom death hath to be preached.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":437},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-28-24","text":"Or “life eternal”; it is all the same to me—if only they pass away\r quickly!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":438},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-1","text":"By our best enemies we do not want to be spared, nor by those either\r whom we love from the very heart. So let me tell you the truth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":439},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-2","text":"My brethren in war! I love you from the very heart. I am, and was ever,\r your counterpart. And I am also your best enemy. So let me tell you the\r truth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":440},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-3","text":"I know the hatred and envy of your hearts. Ye are not great enough not\r to know of hatred and envy. Then be great enough not to be ashamed of\r them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":441},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-4","text":"And if ye cannot be saints of knowledge, then, I pray you, be at least\r its warriors. They are the companions and forerunners of such saintship.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":442},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-5","text":"I see many soldiers; could I but see many warriors! “Uniform” one\r calleth what they wear; may it not be uniform what they therewith hide!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":443},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-6","text":"Ye shall be those whose eyes ever seek for an enemy—for YOUR enemy. And\r with some of you there is hatred at first sight.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":444},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-7","text":"Your enemy shall ye seek; your war shall ye wage, and for the sake of\r your thoughts! And if your thoughts succumb, your uprightness shall\r still shout triumph thereby!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":445},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-8","text":"Ye shall love peace as a means to new wars—and the short peace more\r than the long.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":446},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-9","text":"You I advise not to work, but to fight. You I advise not to peace, but\r to victory. Let your work be a fight, let your peace be a victory!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":447},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-10","text":"One can only be silent and sit peacefully when one hath arrow and bow;\r otherwise one prateth and quarrelleth. Let your peace be a victory!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":448},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-11","text":"Ye say it is the good cause which halloweth even war? I say unto you: it\r is the good war which halloweth every cause.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":449},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-12","text":"War and courage have done more great things than charity. Not your\r sympathy, but your bravery hath hitherto saved the victims.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":450},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-13","text":"“What is good?” ye ask. To be brave is good. Let the little girls say:\r “To be good is what is pretty, and at the same time touching.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":451},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-14","text":"They call you heartless: but your heart is true, and I love the\r bashfulness of your good-will. Ye are ashamed of your flow, and others\r are ashamed of their ebb.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":452},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-15","text":"Ye are ugly? Well then, my brethren, take the sublime about you, the\r mantle of the ugly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":453},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-16","text":"And when your soul becometh great, then doth it become haughty, and in\r your sublimity there is wickedness. I know you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":454},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-17","text":"In wickedness the haughty man and the weakling meet. But they\r misunderstand one another. I know you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":455},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-18","text":"Ye shall only have enemies to be hated, but not enemies to be despised.\r Ye must be proud of your enemies; then, the successes of your enemies\r are also your successes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":456},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-19","text":"Resistance—that is the distinction of the slave. Let your distinction\r be obedience. Let your commanding itself be obeying!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":457},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-20","text":"To the good warrior soundeth “thou shalt” pleasanter than “I will.” And\r all that is dear unto you, ye shall first have it commanded unto you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":458},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-21","text":"Let your love to life be love to your highest hope; and let your highest\r hope be the highest thought of life!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":459},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-22","text":"Your highest thought, however, ye shall have it commanded unto you by\r me—and it is this: man is something that is to be surpassed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":460},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-23","text":"So live your life of obedience and of war! What matter about long life!\r What warrior wisheth to be spared!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":461},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-29-24","text":"I spare you not, I love you from my very heart, my brethren in war!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":462},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-1","text":"Somewhere there are still peoples and herds, but not with us, my\r brethren: here there are states.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":463},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-2","text":"A state? What is that? Well! open now your ears unto me, for now will I\r say unto you my word concerning the death of peoples.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":464},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-3","text":"A state, is called the coldest of all cold monsters. Coldly lieth\r it also; and this lie creepeth from its mouth: “I, the state, am the\r people.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":465},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-4","text":"It is a lie! Creators were they who created peoples, and hung a faith\r and a love over them: thus they served life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":466},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-5","text":"Destroyers, are they who lay snares for many, and call it the state:\r they hang a sword and a hundred cravings over them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":467},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-6","text":"Where there is still a people, there the state is not understood, but\r hated as the evil eye, and as sin against laws and customs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":468},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-7","text":"This sign I give unto you: every people speaketh its language of good\r and evil: this its neighbour understandeth not. Its language hath it\r devised for itself in laws and customs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":469},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-8","text":"But the state lieth in all languages of good and evil; and whatever it\r saith it lieth; and whatever it hath it hath stolen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":470},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-9","text":"False is everything in it; with stolen teeth it biteth, the biting one.\r False are even its bowels.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":471},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-10","text":"Confusion of language of good and evil; this sign I give unto you as\r the sign of the state. Verily, the will to death, indicateth this sign!\r Verily, it beckoneth unto the preachers of death!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":472},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-11","text":"Many too many are born: for the superfluous ones was the state devised!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":473},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-12","text":"See just how it enticeth them to it, the many-too-many! How it\r swalloweth and cheweth and recheweth them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":474},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-13","text":"“On earth there is nothing greater than I: it is I who am the regulating\r finger of God”—thus roareth the monster. And not only the long-eared\r and short-sighted fall upon their knees!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":475},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-14","text":"Ah! even in your ears, ye great souls, it whispereth its gloomy lies!\r Ah! it findeth out the rich hearts which willingly lavish themselves!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":476},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-15","text":"Yea, it findeth you out too, ye conquerors of the old God! Weary ye\r became of the conflict, and now your weariness serveth the new idol!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":477},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-16","text":"Heroes and honourable ones, it would fain set up around it, the new\r idol! Gladly it basketh in the sunshine of good consciences,—the cold\r monster!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":478},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-17","text":"Everything will it give YOU, if YE worship it, the new idol: thus it\r purchaseth the lustre of your virtue, and the glance of your proud eyes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":479},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-18","text":"It seeketh to allure by means of you, the many-too-many! Yea, a hellish\r artifice hath here been devised, a death-horse jingling with the\r trappings of divine honours!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":480},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-19","text":"Yea, a dying for many hath here been devised, which glorifieth itself as\r life: verily, a hearty service unto all preachers of death!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":481},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-20","text":"The state, I call it, where all are poison-drinkers, the good and the\r bad: the state, where all lose themselves, the good and the bad: the\r state, where the slow suicide of all—is called “life.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":482},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-21","text":"Just see these superfluous ones! They steal the works of the inventors\r and the treasures of the wise. Culture, they call their theft—and\r everything becometh sickness and trouble unto them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":483},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-22","text":"Just see these superfluous ones! Sick are they always; they vomit their\r bile and call it a newspaper. They devour one another, and cannot even\r digest themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":484},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-23","text":"Just see these superfluous ones! Wealth they acquire and become poorer\r thereby. Power they seek for, and above all, the lever of power, much\r money—these impotent ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":485},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-24","text":"See them clamber, these nimble apes! They clamber over one another, and\r thus scuffle into the mud and the abyss.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":486},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-25","text":"Towards the throne they all strive: it is their madness—as if happiness\r sat on the throne! Ofttimes sitteth filth on the throne.—and ofttimes\r also the throne on filth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":487},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-26","text":"Madmen they all seem to me, and clambering apes, and too eager. Badly\r smelleth their idol to me, the cold monster: badly they all smell to me,\r these idolaters.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":488},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-27","text":"My brethren, will ye suffocate in the fumes of their maws and appetites!\r Better break the windows and jump into the open air!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":489},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-28","text":"Do go out of the way of the bad odour! Withdraw from the idolatry of the\r superfluous!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":490},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-29","text":"Do go out of the way of the bad odour! Withdraw from the steam of these\r human sacrifices!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":491},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-30","text":"Open still remaineth the earth for great souls. Empty are still many\r sites for lone ones and twain ones, around which floateth the odour of\r tranquil seas.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":492},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-31","text":"Open still remaineth a free life for great souls. Verily, he who\r possesseth little is so much the less possessed: blessed be moderate\r poverty!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":493},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-32","text":"There, where the state ceaseth—there only commenceth the man who is not\r superfluous: there commenceth the song of the necessary ones, the single\r and irreplaceable melody.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":494},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-30-33","text":"There, where the state CEASETH—pray look thither, my brethren! Do ye\r not see it, the rainbow and the bridges of the Superman?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":495},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-1","text":"Flee, my friend, into thy solitude! I see thee deafened with the noise\r of the great men, and stung all over with the stings of the little ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":496},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-2","text":"Admirably do forest and rock know how to be silent with thee. Resemble\r again the tree which thou lovest, the broad-branched one—silently and\r attentively it o’erhangeth the sea.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":497},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-3","text":"Where solitude endeth, there beginneth the market-place; and where the\r market-place beginneth, there beginneth also the noise of the great\r actors, and the buzzing of the poison-flies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":498},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-4","text":"In the world even the best things are worthless without those who\r represent them: those representers, the people call great men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":499},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-5","text":"Little do the people understand what is great—that is to say, the\r creating agency. But they have a taste for all representers and actors\r of great things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":500},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-6","text":"Around the devisers of new values revolveth the world:—invisibly it\r revolveth. But around the actors revolve the people and the glory: such\r is the course of things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":501},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-7","text":"Spirit, hath the actor, but little conscience of the spirit. He\r believeth always in that wherewith he maketh believe most strongly—in\r HIMSELF!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":502},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-8","text":"To-morrow he hath a new belief, and the day after, one still newer. Sharp\r perceptions hath he, like the people, and changeable humours.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":503},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-9","text":"To upset—that meaneth with him to prove. To drive mad—that meaneth\r with him to convince. And blood is counted by him as the best of all\r arguments.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":504},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-10","text":"A truth which only glideth into fine ears, he calleth falsehood and\r trumpery. Verily, he believeth only in Gods that make a great noise in\r the world!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":505},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-11","text":"Full of clattering buffoons is the market-place,—and the people glory\r in their great men! These are for them the masters of the hour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":506},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-12","text":"But the hour presseth them; so they press thee. And also from thee\r they want Yea or Nay. Alas! thou wouldst set thy chair betwixt For and\r Against?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":507},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-13","text":"On account of those absolute and impatient ones, be not jealous, thou\r lover of truth! Never yet did truth cling to the arm of an absolute one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":508},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-14","text":"On account of those abrupt ones, return into thy security: only in the\r market-place is one assailed by Yea? or Nay?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":509},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-15","text":"Slow is the experience of all deep fountains: long have they to wait\r until they know WHAT hath fallen into their depths.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":510},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-16","text":"Away from the market-place and from fame taketh place all that is great:\r away from the market-place and from fame have ever dwelt the devisers of\r new values.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":511},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-17","text":"Flee, my friend, into thy solitude: I see thee stung all over by the\r poisonous flies. Flee thither, where a rough, strong breeze bloweth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":512},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-18","text":"Flee into thy solitude! Thou hast lived too closely to the small and the\r pitiable. Flee from their invisible vengeance! Towards thee they have\r nothing but vengeance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":513},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-19","text":"Raise no longer an arm against them! Innumerable are they, and it is not\r thy lot to be a fly-flap.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":514},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-20","text":"Innumerable are the small and pitiable ones; and of many a proud\r structure, rain-drops and weeds have been the ruin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":515},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-21","text":"Thou art not stone; but already hast thou become hollow by the numerous\r drops. Thou wilt yet break and burst by the numerous drops.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":516},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-22","text":"Exhausted I see thee, by poisonous flies; bleeding I see thee, and torn\r at a hundred spots; and thy pride will not even upbraid.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":517},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-23","text":"Blood they would have from thee in all innocence; blood their bloodless\r souls crave for—and they sting, therefore, in all innocence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":518},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-24","text":"But thou, profound one, thou sufferest too profoundly even from small\r wounds; and ere thou hadst recovered, the same poison-worm crawled over\r thy hand.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":519},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-25","text":"Too proud art thou to kill these sweet-tooths. But take care lest it be\r thy fate to suffer all their poisonous injustice!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":520},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-26","text":"They buzz around thee also with their praise: obtrusiveness, is their\r praise. They want to be close to thy skin and thy blood.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":521},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-27","text":"They flatter thee, as one flattereth a God or devil; they whimper before\r thee, as before a God or devil. What doth it come to! Flatterers are\r they, and whimperers, and nothing more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":522},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-28","text":"Often, also, do they show themselves to thee as amiable ones. But that\r hath ever been the prudence of the cowardly. Yea! the cowardly are wise!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":523},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-29","text":"They think much about thee with their circumscribed souls—thou art\r always suspected by them! Whatever is much thought about is at last\r thought suspicious.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":524},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-30","text":"They punish thee for all thy virtues. They pardon thee in their inmost\r hearts only—for thine errors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":525},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-31","text":"Because thou art gentle and of upright character, thou sayest:\r “Blameless are they for their small existence.” But their circumscribed\r souls think: “Blamable is all great existence.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":526},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-32","text":"Even when thou art gentle towards them, they still feel themselves\r despised by thee; and they repay thy beneficence with secret\r maleficence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":527},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-33","text":"Thy silent pride is always counter to their taste; they rejoice if once\r thou be humble enough to be frivolous.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":528},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-34","text":"What we recognise in a man, we also irritate in him. Therefore be on\r your guard against the small ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":529},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-35","text":"In thy presence they feel themselves small, and their baseness gleameth\r and gloweth against thee in invisible vengeance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":530},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-36","text":"Sawest thou not how often they became dumb when thou approachedst them,\r and how their energy left them like the smoke of an extinguishing fire?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":531},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-37","text":"Yea, my friend, the bad conscience art thou of thy neighbours; for they\r are unworthy of thee. Therefore they hate thee, and would fain suck thy\r blood.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":532},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-38","text":"Thy neighbours will always be poisonous flies; what is great in\r thee—that itself must make them more poisonous, and always more\r fly-like.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":533},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-31-39","text":"Flee, my friend, into thy solitude—and thither, where a rough strong\r breeze bloweth. It is not thy lot to be a fly-flap.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":534},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-1","text":"I love the forest. It is bad to live in cities: there, there are too\r many of the lustful.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":535},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-2","text":"Is it not better to fall into the hands of a murderer, than into the\r dreams of a lustful woman?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":536},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-3","text":"And just look at these men: their eye saith it—they know nothing better\r on earth than to lie with a woman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":537},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-4","text":"Filth is at the bottom of their souls; and alas! if their filth hath\r still spirit in it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":538},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-5","text":"Would that ye were perfect—at least as animals! But to animals\r belongeth innocence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":539},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-6","text":"Do I counsel you to slay your instincts? I counsel you to innocence in\r your instincts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":540},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-7","text":"Do I counsel you to chastity? Chastity is a virtue with some, but with\r many almost a vice.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":541},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-8","text":"These are continent, to be sure: but doggish lust looketh enviously out\r of all that they do.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":542},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-9","text":"Even into the heights of their virtue and into their cold spirit doth\r this creature follow them, with its discord.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":543},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-10","text":"And how nicely can doggish lust beg for a piece of spirit, when a piece\r of flesh is denied it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":544},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-11","text":"Ye love tragedies and all that breaketh the heart? But I am distrustful\r of your doggish lust.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":545},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-12","text":"Ye have too cruel eyes, and ye look wantonly towards the sufferers.\r Hath not your lust just disguised itself and taken the name of\r fellow-suffering?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":546},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-13","text":"And also this parable give I unto you: Not a few who meant to cast out\r their devil, went thereby into the swine themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":547},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-14","text":"To whom chastity is difficult, it is to be dissuaded: lest it become the\r road to hell—to filth and lust of soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":548},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-15","text":"Do I speak of filthy things? That is not the worst thing for me to do.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":549},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-16","text":"Not when the truth is filthy, but when it is shallow, doth the\r discerning one go unwillingly into its waters.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":550},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-17","text":"Verily, there are chaste ones from their very nature; they are gentler\r of heart, and laugh better and oftener than you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":551},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-18","text":"Is chastity not folly? But the folly came unto us, and not we unto it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":552},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-32-19","text":"We offered that guest harbour and heart: now it dwelleth with us—let it\r stay as long as it will!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":553},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-1","text":"“One, is always too many about me”—thinketh the anchorite. “Always once\r one—that maketh two in the long run!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":554},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-2","text":"I and me are always too earnestly in conversation: how could it be\r endured, if there were not a friend?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":555},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-3","text":"The friend of the anchorite is always the third one: the third one is\r the cork which preventeth the conversation of the two sinking into the\r depth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":556},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-4","text":"Ah! there are too many depths for all anchorites. Therefore, do they\r long so much for a friend, and for his elevation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":557},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-5","text":"Our faith in others betrayeth wherein we would fain have faith in\r ourselves. Our longing for a friend is our betrayer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":558},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-6","text":"And often with our love we want merely to overleap envy. And often we\r attack and make ourselves enemies, to conceal that we are vulnerable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":559},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-7","text":"“Be at least mine enemy!”—thus speaketh the true reverence, which doth\r not venture to solicit friendship.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":560},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-8","text":"If one would have a friend, then must one also be willing to wage war\r for him: and in order to wage war, one must be CAPABLE of being an\r enemy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":561},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-9","text":"One ought still to honour the enemy in one’s friend. Canst thou go nigh\r unto thy friend, and not go over to him?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":562},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-10","text":"In one’s friend one shall have one’s best enemy. Thou shalt be closest\r unto him with thy heart when thou withstandest him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":563},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-11","text":"Thou wouldst wear no raiment before thy friend? It is in honour of thy\r friend that thou showest thyself to him as thou art? But he wisheth thee\r to the devil on that account!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":564},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-12","text":"He who maketh no secret of himself shocketh: so much reason have ye\r to fear nakedness! Aye, if ye were Gods, ye could then be ashamed of\r clothing!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":565},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-13","text":"Thou canst not adorn thyself fine enough for thy friend; for thou shalt\r be unto him an arrow and a longing for the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":566},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-14","text":"Sawest thou ever thy friend asleep—to know how he looketh? What is\r usually the countenance of thy friend? It is thine own countenance, in a\r coarse and imperfect mirror.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":567},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-15","text":"Sawest thou ever thy friend asleep? Wert thou not dismayed at thy friend\r looking so? O my friend, man is something that hath to be surpassed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":568},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-16","text":"In divining and keeping silence shall the friend be a master: not\r everything must thou wish to see. Thy dream shall disclose unto thee\r what thy friend doeth when awake.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":569},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-17","text":"Let thy pity be a divining: to know first if thy friend wanteth pity.\r Perhaps he loveth in thee the unmoved eye, and the look of eternity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":570},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-18","text":"Let thy pity for thy friend be hid under a hard shell; thou shalt bite\r out a tooth upon it. Thus will it have delicacy and sweetness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":571},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-19","text":"Art thou pure air and solitude and bread and medicine to thy friend?\r Many a one cannot loosen his own fetters, but is nevertheless his\r friend’s emancipator.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":572},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-20","text":"Art thou a slave? Then thou canst not be a friend. Art thou a tyrant?\r Then thou canst not have friends.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":573},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-21","text":"Far too long hath there been a slave and a tyrant concealed in woman.\r On that account woman is not yet capable of friendship: she knoweth only\r love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":574},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-22","text":"In woman’s love there is injustice and blindness to all she doth not\r love. And even in woman’s conscious love, there is still always surprise\r and lightning and night, along with the light.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":575},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-23","text":"As yet woman is not capable of friendship: women are still cats, and\r birds. Or at the best, cows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":576},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-24","text":"As yet woman is not capable of friendship. But tell me, ye men, who of\r you are capable of friendship?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":577},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-33-25","text":"Oh! your poverty, ye men, and your sordidness of soul! As much as ye\r give to your friend, will I give even to my foe, and will not have\r become poorer thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":578},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-1","text":"Many lands saw Zarathustra, and many peoples: thus he discovered the\r good and bad of many peoples. No greater power did Zarathustra find on\r earth than good and bad.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":579},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-2","text":"No people could live without first valuing; if a people will maintain\r itself, however, it must not value as its neighbour valueth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":580},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-3","text":"Much that passed for good with one people was regarded with scorn and\r contempt by another: thus I found it. Much found I here called bad,\r which was there decked with purple honours.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":581},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-4","text":"Never did the one neighbour understand the other: ever did his soul\r marvel at his neighbour’s delusion and wickedness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":582},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-5","text":"A table of excellencies hangeth over every people. Lo! it is the table\r of their triumphs; lo! it is the voice of their Will to Power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":583},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-6","text":"It is laudable, what they think hard; what is indispensable and hard\r they call good; and what relieveth in the direst distress, the unique\r and hardest of all,—they extol as holy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":584},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-7","text":"Whatever maketh them rule and conquer and shine, to the dismay and envy\r of their neighbours, they regard as the high and foremost thing, the\r test and the meaning of all else.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":585},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-8","text":"Verily, my brother, if thou knewest but a people’s need, its land,\r its sky, and its neighbour, then wouldst thou divine the law of its\r surmountings, and why it climbeth up that ladder to its hope.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":586},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-9","text":"“Always shalt thou be the foremost and prominent above others: no one\r shall thy jealous soul love, except a friend”—that made the soul of a\r Greek thrill: thereby went he his way to greatness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":587},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-10","text":"“To speak truth, and be skilful with bow and arrow”—so seemed it alike\r pleasing and hard to the people from whom cometh my name—the name which\r is alike pleasing and hard to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":588},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-11","text":"“To honour father and mother, and from the root of the soul to do their\r will”—this table of surmounting hung another people over them, and\r became powerful and permanent thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":589},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-12","text":"“To have fidelity, and for the sake of fidelity to risk honour and\r blood, even in evil and dangerous courses”—teaching itself so, another\r people mastered itself, and thus mastering itself, became pregnant and\r heavy with great hopes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":590},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-13","text":"Verily, men have given unto themselves all their good and bad. Verily,\r they took it not, they found it not, it came not unto them as a voice\r from heaven.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":591},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-14","text":"Values did man only assign to things in order to maintain himself—he\r created only the significance of things, a human significance!\r Therefore, calleth he himself “man,” that is, the valuator.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":592},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-15","text":"Valuing is creating: hear it, ye creating ones! Valuation itself is the\r treasure and jewel of the valued things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":593},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-16","text":"Through valuation only is there value; and without valuation the nut of\r existence would be hollow. Hear it, ye creating ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":594},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-17","text":"Change of values—that is, change of the creating ones. Always doth he\r destroy who hath to be a creator.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":595},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-18","text":"Creating ones were first of all peoples, and only in late times\r individuals; verily, the individual himself is still the latest\r creation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":596},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-19","text":"Peoples once hung over them tables of the good. Love which would rule\r and love which would obey, created for themselves such tables.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":597},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-20","text":"Older is the pleasure in the herd than the pleasure in the ego: and as\r long as the good conscience is for the herd, the bad conscience only\r saith: ego.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":598},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-21","text":"Verily, the crafty ego, the loveless one, that seeketh its advantage in\r the advantage of many—it is not the origin of the herd, but its ruin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":599},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-22","text":"Loving ones, was it always, and creating ones, that created good and\r bad. Fire of love gloweth in the names of all the virtues, and fire of\r wrath.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":600},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-23","text":"Many lands saw Zarathustra, and many peoples: no greater power did\r Zarathustra find on earth than the creations of the loving ones—“good”\r  and “bad” are they called.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":601},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-24","text":"Verily, a prodigy is this power of praising and blaming. Tell me, ye\r brethren, who will master it for me? Who will put a fetter upon the\r thousand necks of this animal?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":602},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-25","text":"A thousand goals have there been hitherto, for a thousand peoples have\r there been. Only the fetter for the thousand necks is still lacking;\r there is lacking the one goal. As yet humanity hath not a goal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":603},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-34-26","text":"But pray tell me, my brethren, if the goal of humanity be still lacking,\r is there not also still lacking—humanity itself?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":604},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-1","text":"Ye crowd around your neighbour, and have fine words for it. But I say\r unto you: your neighbour-love is your bad love of yourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":605},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-2","text":"Ye flee unto your neighbour from yourselves, and would fain make a\r virtue thereof: but I fathom your “unselfishness.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":606},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-3","text":"The THOU is older than the _I_; the THOU hath been consecrated, but not\r yet the _I_: so man presseth nigh unto his neighbour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":607},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-4","text":"Do I advise you to neighbour-love? Rather do I advise you to\r neighbour-flight and to furthest love!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":608},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-5","text":"Higher than love to your neighbour is love to the furthest and future\r ones; higher still than love to men, is love to things and phantoms.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":609},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-6","text":"The phantom that runneth on before thee, my brother, is fairer than\r thou; why dost thou not give unto it thy flesh and thy bones? But thou\r fearest, and runnest unto thy neighbour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":610},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-7","text":"Ye cannot endure it with yourselves, and do not love yourselves\r sufficiently: so ye seek to mislead your neighbour into love, and would\r fain gild yourselves with his error.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":611},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-8","text":"Would that ye could not endure it with any kind of near ones, or their\r neighbours; then would ye have to create your friend and his overflowing\r heart out of yourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":612},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-9","text":"Ye call in a witness when ye want to speak well of yourselves; and\r when ye have misled him to think well of you, ye also think well of\r yourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":613},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-10","text":"Not only doth he lie, who speaketh contrary to his knowledge, but more\r so, he who speaketh contrary to his ignorance. And thus speak ye\r of yourselves in your intercourse, and belie your neighbour with\r yourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":614},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-11","text":"Thus saith the fool: “Association with men spoileth the character,\r especially when one hath none.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":615},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-12","text":"The one goeth to his neighbour because he seeketh himself, and the other\r because he would fain lose himself. Your bad love to yourselves maketh\r solitude a prison to you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":616},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-13","text":"The furthest ones are they who pay for your love to the near ones; and\r when there are but five of you together, a sixth must always die.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":617},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-14","text":"I love not your festivals either: too many actors found I there, and\r even the spectators often behaved like actors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":618},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-15","text":"Not the neighbour do I teach you, but the friend. Let the friend be the\r festival of the earth to you, and a foretaste of the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":619},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-16","text":"I teach you the friend and his overflowing heart. But one must know how\r to be a sponge, if one would be loved by overflowing hearts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":620},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-17","text":"I teach you the friend in whom the world standeth complete, a capsule\r of the good,—the creating friend, who hath always a complete world to\r bestow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":621},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-18","text":"And as the world unrolled itself for him, so rolleth it together again\r for him in rings, as the growth of good through evil, as the growth of\r purpose out of chance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":622},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-19","text":"Let the future and the furthest be the motive of thy to-day; in thy\r friend shalt thou love the Superman as thy motive.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":623},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-35-20","text":"My brethren, I advise you not to neighbour-love—I advise you to\r furthest love!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":624},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-1","text":"Wouldst thou go into isolation, my brother? Wouldst thou seek the way\r unto thyself? Tarry yet a little and hearken unto me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":625},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-2","text":"“He who seeketh may easily get lost himself. All isolation is wrong”: so\r say the herd. And long didst thou belong to the herd.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":626},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-3","text":"The voice of the herd will still echo in thee. And when thou sayest,\r “I have no longer a conscience in common with you,” then will it be a\r plaint and a pain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":627},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-4","text":"Lo, that pain itself did the same conscience produce; and the last gleam\r of that conscience still gloweth on thine affliction.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":628},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-5","text":"But thou wouldst go the way of thine affliction, which is the way unto\r thyself? Then show me thine authority and thy strength to do so!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":629},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-6","text":"Art thou a new strength and a new authority? A first motion? A\r self-rolling wheel? Canst thou also compel stars to revolve around thee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":630},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-7","text":"Alas! there is so much lusting for loftiness! There are so many\r convulsions of the ambitions! Show me that thou art not a lusting and\r ambitious one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":631},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-8","text":"Alas! there are so many great thoughts that do nothing more than the\r bellows: they inflate, and make emptier than ever.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":632},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-9","text":"Free, dost thou call thyself? Thy ruling thought would I hear of, and\r not that thou hast escaped from a yoke.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":633},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-10","text":"Art thou one ENTITLED to escape from a yoke? Many a one hath cast away\r his final worth when he hath cast away his servitude.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":634},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-11","text":"Free from what? What doth that matter to Zarathustra! Clearly, however,\r shall thine eye show unto me: free FOR WHAT?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":635},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-12","text":"Canst thou give unto thyself thy bad and thy good, and set up thy will\r as a law over thee? Canst thou be judge for thyself, and avenger of thy\r law?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":636},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-13","text":"Terrible is aloneness with the judge and avenger of one’s own law.\r Thus is a star projected into desert space, and into the icy breath of\r aloneness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":637},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-14","text":"To-day sufferest thou still from the multitude, thou individual; to-day\r hast thou still thy courage unabated, and thy hopes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":638},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-15","text":"But one day will the solitude weary thee; one day will thy pride yield,\r and thy courage quail. Thou wilt one day cry: “I am alone!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":639},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-16","text":"One day wilt thou see no longer thy loftiness, and see too closely thy\r lowliness; thy sublimity itself will frighten thee as a phantom. Thou\r wilt one day cry: “All is false!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":640},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-17","text":"There are feelings which seek to slay the lonesome one; if they do not\r succeed, then must they themselves die! But art thou capable of it—to\r be a murderer?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":641},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-18","text":"Hast thou ever known, my brother, the word “disdain”? And the anguish of\r thy justice in being just to those that disdain thee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":642},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-19","text":"Thou forcest many to think differently about thee; that, charge they\r heavily to thine account. Thou camest nigh unto them, and yet wentest\r past: for that they never forgive thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":643},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-20","text":"Thou goest beyond them: but the higher thou risest, the smaller doth the\r eye of envy see thee. Most of all, however, is the flying one hated.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":644},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-21","text":"“How could ye be just unto me!”—must thou say—“I choose your injustice\r as my allotted portion.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":645},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-22","text":"Injustice and filth cast they at the lonesome one: but, my brother, if\r thou wouldst be a star, thou must shine for them none the less on that\r account!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":646},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-23","text":"And be on thy guard against the good and just! They would fain crucify\r those who devise their own virtue—they hate the lonesome ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":647},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-24","text":"Be on thy guard, also, against holy simplicity! All is unholy to it that\r is not simple; fain, likewise, would it play with the fire—of the fagot\r and stake.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":648},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-25","text":"And be on thy guard, also, against the assaults of thy love! Too readily\r doth the recluse reach his hand to any one who meeteth him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":649},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-26","text":"To many a one mayest thou not give thy hand, but only thy paw; and I\r wish thy paw also to have claws.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":650},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-27","text":"But the worst enemy thou canst meet, wilt thou thyself always be; thou\r waylayest thyself in caverns and forests.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":651},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-28","text":"Thou lonesome one, thou goest the way to thyself! And past thyself and\r thy seven devils leadeth thy way!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":652},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-29","text":"A heretic wilt thou be to thyself, and a wizard and a soothsayer, and a\r fool, and a doubter, and a reprobate, and a villain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":653},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-30","text":"Ready must thou be to burn thyself in thine own flame; how couldst thou\r become new if thou have not first become ashes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":654},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-31","text":"Thou lonesome one, thou goest the way of the creating one: a God wilt\r thou create for thyself out of thy seven devils!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":655},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-32","text":"Thou lonesome one, thou goest the way of the loving one: thou lovest\r thyself, and on that account despisest thou thyself, as only the loving\r ones despise.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":656},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-33","text":"To create, desireth the loving one, because he despiseth! What knoweth\r he of love who hath not been obliged to despise just what he loved!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":657},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-34","text":"With thy love, go into thine isolation, my brother, and with thy\r creating; and late only will justice limp after thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":658},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-36-35","text":"With my tears, go into thine isolation, my brother. I love him who\r seeketh to create beyond himself, and thus succumbeth.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":659},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-1","text":"“Why stealest thou along so furtively in the twilight, Zarathustra? And\r what hidest thou so carefully under thy mantle?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":660},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-2","text":"Is it a treasure that hath been given thee? Or a child that hath been\r born thee? Or goest thou thyself on a thief’s errand, thou friend of the\r evil?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":661},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-3","text":"Verily, my brother, said Zarathustra, it is a treasure that hath been\r given me: it is a little truth which I carry.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":662},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-4","text":"But it is naughty, like a young child; and if I hold not its mouth, it\r screameth too loudly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":663},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-5","text":"As I went on my way alone to-day, at the hour when the sun declineth,\r there met me an old woman, and she spake thus unto my soul:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":664},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-6","text":"“Much hath Zarathustra spoken also to us women, but never spake he unto\r us concerning woman.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":665},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-7","text":"And I answered her: “Concerning woman, one should only talk unto men.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":666},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-8","text":"“Talk also unto me of woman,” said she; “I am old enough to forget it\r presently.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":667},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-9","text":"Everything in woman is a riddle, and everything in woman hath one\r solution—it is called pregnancy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":668},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-10","text":"Man is for woman a means: the purpose is always the child. But what is\r woman for man?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":669},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-11","text":"Two different things wanteth the true man: danger and diversion.\r Therefore wanteth he woman, as the most dangerous plaything.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":670},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-12","text":"Man shall be trained for war, and woman for the recreation of the\r warrior: all else is folly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":671},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-13","text":"Too sweet fruits—these the warrior liketh not. Therefore liketh he\r woman;—bitter is even the sweetest woman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":672},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-14","text":"Better than man doth woman understand children, but man is more childish\r than woman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":673},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-15","text":"In the true man there is a child hidden: it wanteth to play. Up then, ye\r women, and discover the child in man!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":674},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-16","text":"A plaything let woman be, pure and fine like the precious stone,\r illumined with the virtues of a world not yet come.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":675},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-17","text":"Let the beam of a star shine in your love! Let your hope say: “May I\r bear the Superman!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":676},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-18","text":"In your love let there be valour! With your love shall ye assail him who\r inspireth you with fear!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":677},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-19","text":"In your love be your honour! Little doth woman understand otherwise\r about honour. But let this be your honour: always to love more than ye\r are loved, and never be the second.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":678},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-20","text":"Let man fear woman when she loveth: then maketh she every sacrifice, and\r everything else she regardeth as worthless.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":679},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-21","text":"Let man fear woman when she hateth: for man in his innermost soul is\r merely evil; woman, however, is mean.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":680},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-22","text":"Whom hateth woman most?—Thus spake the iron to the loadstone: “I hate\r thee most, because thou attractest, but art too weak to draw unto thee.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":681},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-23","text":"The happiness of man is, “I will.” The happiness of woman is, “He will.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":682},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-24","text":"“Lo! now hath the world become perfect!”—thus thinketh every woman when\r she obeyeth with all her love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":683},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-25","text":"Obey, must the woman, and find a depth for her surface. Surface, is\r woman’s soul, a mobile, stormy film on shallow water.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":684},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-26","text":"Man’s soul, however, is deep, its current gusheth in subterranean\r caverns: woman surmiseth its force, but comprehendeth it not.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":685},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-27","text":"Then answered me the old woman: “Many fine things hath Zarathustra said,\r especially for those who are young enough for them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":686},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-28","text":"Strange! Zarathustra knoweth little about woman, and yet he is right\r about them! Doth this happen, because with women nothing is impossible?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":687},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-29","text":"And now accept a little truth by way of thanks! I am old enough for it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":688},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-30","text":"Swaddle it up and hold its mouth: otherwise it will scream too loudly,\r the little truth.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":689},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-37-31","text":"“Give me, woman, thy little truth!” said I. And thus spake the old\r woman:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":690},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-1","text":"One day had Zarathustra fallen asleep under a fig-tree, owing to the\r heat, with his arms over his face. And there came an adder and bit him\r in the neck, so that Zarathustra screamed with pain. When he had\r taken his arm from his face he looked at the serpent; and then did it\r recognise the eyes of Zarathustra, wriggled awkwardly, and tried to get\r away. “Not at all,” said Zarathustra, “as yet hast thou not received\r my thanks! Thou hast awakened me in time; my journey is yet long.”\r  “Thy journey is short,” said the adder sadly; “my poison is fatal.”\r  Zarathustra smiled. “When did ever a dragon die of a serpent’s\r poison?”—said he. “But take thy poison back! Thou art not rich enough\r to p","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":691},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-2","text":"When Zarathustra once told this to his disciples they asked him:\r “And what, O Zarathustra, is the moral of thy story?” And Zarathustra\r answered them thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":692},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-3","text":"The destroyer of morality, the good and just call me: my story is\r immoral.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":693},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-4","text":"When, however, ye have an enemy, then return him not good for evil: for\r that would abash him. But prove that he hath done something good to you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":694},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-5","text":"And rather be angry than abash any one! And when ye are cursed, it\r pleaseth me not that ye should then desire to bless. Rather curse a\r little also!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":695},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-6","text":"And should a great injustice befall you, then do quickly five small ones\r besides. Hideous to behold is he on whom injustice presseth alone.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":696},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-7","text":"Did ye ever know this? Shared injustice is half justice. And he who can\r bear it, shall take the injustice upon himself!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":697},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-8","text":"A small revenge is humaner than no revenge at all. And if the punishment\r be not also a right and an honour to the transgressor, I do not like\r your punishing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":698},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-9","text":"Nobler is it to own oneself in the wrong than to establish one’s right,\r especially if one be in the right. Only, one must be rich enough to do\r so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":699},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-10","text":"I do not like your cold justice; out of the eye of your judges there\r always glanceth the executioner and his cold steel.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":700},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-11","text":"Tell me: where find we justice, which is love with seeing eyes?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":701},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-12","text":"Devise me, then, the love which not only beareth all punishment, but\r also all guilt!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":702},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-13","text":"Devise me, then, the justice which acquitteth every one except the\r judge!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":703},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-14","text":"And would ye hear this likewise? To him who seeketh to be just from the\r heart, even the lie becometh philanthropy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":704},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-15","text":"But how could I be just from the heart! How can I give every one his\r own! Let this be enough for me: I give unto every one mine own.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":705},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-16","text":"Finally, my brethren, guard against doing wrong to any anchorite. How\r could an anchorite forget! How could he requite!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":706},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-17","text":"Like a deep well is an anchorite. Easy is it to throw in a stone: if\r it should sink to the bottom, however, tell me, who will bring it out\r again?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":707},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-38-18","text":"Guard against injuring the anchorite! If ye have done so, however, well\r then, kill him also!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":708},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-1","text":"I have a question for thee alone, my brother: like a sounding-lead, cast\r I this question into thy soul, that I may know its depth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":709},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-2","text":"Thou art young, and desirest child and marriage. But I ask thee: Art\r thou a man ENTITLED to desire a child?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":710},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-3","text":"Art thou the victorious one, the self-conqueror, the ruler of thy\r passions, the master of thy virtues? Thus do I ask thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":711},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-4","text":"Or doth the animal speak in thy wish, and necessity? Or isolation? Or\r discord in thee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":712},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-5","text":"I would have thy victory and freedom long for a child. Living monuments\r shalt thou build to thy victory and emancipation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":713},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-6","text":"Beyond thyself shalt thou build. But first of all must thou be built\r thyself, rectangular in body and soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":714},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-7","text":"Not only onward shalt thou propagate thyself, but upward! For that\r purpose may the garden of marriage help thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":715},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-8","text":"A higher body shalt thou create, a first movement, a spontaneously\r rolling wheel—a creating one shalt thou create.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":716},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-9","text":"Marriage: so call I the will of the twain to create the one that is\r more than those who created it. The reverence for one another, as those\r exercising such a will, call I marriage.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":717},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-10","text":"Let this be the significance and the truth of thy marriage. But that\r which the many-too-many call marriage, those superfluous ones—ah, what\r shall I call it?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":718},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-11","text":"Ah, the poverty of soul in the twain! Ah, the filth of soul in the\r twain! Ah, the pitiable self-complacency in the twain!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":719},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-12","text":"Marriage they call it all; and they say their marriages are made in\r heaven.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":720},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-13","text":"Well, I do not like it, that heaven of the superfluous! No, I do not\r like them, those animals tangled in the heavenly toils!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":721},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-14","text":"Far from me also be the God who limpeth thither to bless what he hath\r not matched!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":722},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-15","text":"Laugh not at such marriages! What child hath not had reason to weep over\r its parents?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":723},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-16","text":"Worthy did this man seem, and ripe for the meaning of the earth: but\r when I saw his wife, the earth seemed to me a home for madcaps.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":724},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-17","text":"Yea, I would that the earth shook with convulsions when a saint and a\r goose mate with one another.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":725},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-18","text":"This one went forth in quest of truth as a hero, and at last got for\r himself a small decked-up lie: his marriage he calleth it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":726},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-19","text":"That one was reserved in intercourse and chose choicely. But one time he\r spoilt his company for all time: his marriage he calleth it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":727},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-20","text":"Another sought a handmaid with the virtues of an angel. But all at once\r he became the handmaid of a woman, and now would he need also to become\r an angel.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":728},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-21","text":"Careful, have I found all buyers, and all of them have astute eyes. But\r even the astutest of them buyeth his wife in a sack.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":729},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-22","text":"Many short follies—that is called love by you. And your marriage\r putteth an end to many short follies, with one long stupidity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":730},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-23","text":"Your love to woman, and woman’s love to man—ah, would that it were\r sympathy for suffering and veiled deities! But generally two animals\r alight on one another.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":731},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-24","text":"But even your best love is only an enraptured simile and a painful\r ardour. It is a torch to light you to loftier paths.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":732},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-25","text":"Beyond yourselves shall ye love some day! Then LEARN first of all to\r love. And on that account ye had to drink the bitter cup of your love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":733},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-26","text":"Bitterness is in the cup even of the best love: thus doth it cause\r longing for the Superman; thus doth it cause thirst in thee, the\r creating one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":734},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-39-27","text":"Thirst in the creating one, arrow and longing for the Superman: tell me,\r my brother, is this thy will to marriage?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":735},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-1","text":"Many die too late, and some die too early. Yet strange soundeth the\r precept: “Die at the right time!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":736},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-2","text":"To be sure, he who never liveth at the right time, how could he ever die\r at the right time? Would that he might never be born!—Thus do I advise\r the superfluous ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":737},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-3","text":"But even the superfluous ones make much ado about their death, and even\r the hollowest nut wanteth to be cracked.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":738},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-4","text":"Every one regardeth dying as a great matter: but as yet death is not\r a festival. Not yet have people learned to inaugurate the finest\r festivals.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":739},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-5","text":"The consummating death I show unto you, which becometh a stimulus and\r promise to the living.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":740},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-6","text":"His death, dieth the consummating one triumphantly, surrounded by hoping\r and promising ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":741},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-7","text":"Thus should one learn to die; and there should be no festival at which\r such a dying one doth not consecrate the oaths of the living!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":742},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-8","text":"Thus to die is best; the next best, however, is to die in battle, and\r sacrifice a great soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":743},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-9","text":"But to the fighter equally hateful as to the victor, is your grinning\r death which stealeth nigh like a thief,—and yet cometh as master.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":744},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-10","text":"My death, praise I unto you, the voluntary death, which cometh unto me\r because _I_ want it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":745},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-11","text":"And when shall I want it?—He that hath a goal and an heir, wanteth\r death at the right time for the goal and the heir.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":746},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-12","text":"And out of reverence for the goal and the heir, he will hang up no more\r withered wreaths in the sanctuary of life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":747},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-13","text":"Verily, not the rope-makers will I resemble: they lengthen out their\r cord, and thereby go ever backward.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":748},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-14","text":"Many a one, also, waxeth too old for his truths and triumphs; a\r toothless mouth hath no longer the right to every truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":749},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-15","text":"And whoever wanteth to have fame, must take leave of honour betimes, and\r practise the difficult art of—going at the right time.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":750},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-16","text":"One must discontinue being feasted upon when one tasteth best: that is\r known by those who want to be long loved.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":751},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-17","text":"Sour apples are there, no doubt, whose lot is to wait until the last\r day of autumn: and at the same time they become ripe, yellow, and\r shrivelled.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":752},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-18","text":"In some ageth the heart first, and in others the spirit. And some are\r hoary in youth, but the late young keep long young.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":753},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-19","text":"To many men life is a failure; a poison-worm gnaweth at their heart.\r Then let them see to it that their dying is all the more a success.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":754},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-20","text":"Many never become sweet; they rot even in the summer. It is cowardice\r that holdeth them fast to their branches.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":755},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-21","text":"Far too many live, and far too long hang they on their branches. Would\r that a storm came and shook all this rottenness and worm-eatenness from\r the tree!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":756},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-22","text":"Would that there came preachers of SPEEDY death! Those would be the\r appropriate storms and agitators of the trees of life! But I hear only\r slow death preached, and patience with all that is “earthly.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":757},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-23","text":"Ah! ye preach patience with what is earthly? This earthly is it that\r hath too much patience with you, ye blasphemers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":758},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-24","text":"Verily, too early died that Hebrew whom the preachers of slow death\r honour: and to many hath it proved a calamity that he died too early.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":759},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-25","text":"As yet had he known only tears, and the melancholy of the Hebrews,\r together with the hatred of the good and just—the Hebrew Jesus: then\r was he seized with the longing for death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":760},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-26","text":"Had he but remained in the wilderness, and far from the good and just!\r Then, perhaps, would he have learned to live, and love the earth—and\r laughter also!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":761},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-27","text":"Believe it, my brethren! He died too early; he himself would have\r disavowed his doctrine had he attained to my age! Noble enough was he to\r disavow!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":762},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-28","text":"But he was still immature. Immaturely loveth the youth, and immaturely\r also hateth he man and earth. Confined and awkward are still his soul\r and the wings of his spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":763},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-29","text":"But in man there is more of the child than in the youth, and less of\r melancholy: better understandeth he about life and death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":764},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-30","text":"Free for death, and free in death; a holy Naysayer, when there is no\r longer time for Yea: thus understandeth he about death and life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":765},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-31","text":"That your dying may not be a reproach to man and the earth, my friends:\r that do I solicit from the honey of your soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":766},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-32","text":"In your dying shall your spirit and your virtue still shine like an\r evening after-glow around the earth: otherwise your dying hath been\r unsatisfactory.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":767},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-33","text":"Thus will I die myself, that ye friends may love the earth more for my\r sake; and earth will I again become, to have rest in her that bore me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":768},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-34","text":"Verily, a goal had Zarathustra; he threw his ball. Now be ye friends the\r heirs of my goal; to you throw I the golden ball.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":769},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-40-35","text":"Best of all, do I see you, my friends, throw the golden ball! And so\r tarry I still a little while on the earth—pardon me for it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":770},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-1","text":"When Zarathustra had taken leave of the town to which his heart was\r attached, the name of which is “The Pied Cow,” there followed him many\r people who called themselves his disciples, and kept him company. Thus\r came they to a crossroad. Then Zarathustra told them that he now wanted\r to go alone; for he was fond of going alone. His disciples, however,\r presented him at his departure with a staff, on the golden handle of\r which a serpent twined round the sun. Zarathustra rejoiced on account\r of the staff, and supported himself thereon; then spake he thus to his\r disciples:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":771},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-2","text":"Tell me, pray: how came gold to the highest value? Because it is\r uncommon, and unprofiting, and beaming, and soft in lustre; it always\r bestoweth itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":772},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-3","text":"Only as image of the highest virtue came gold to the highest value.\r Goldlike, beameth the glance of the bestower. Gold-lustre maketh peace\r between moon and sun.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":773},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-4","text":"Uncommon is the highest virtue, and unprofiting, beaming is it, and soft\r of lustre: a bestowing virtue is the highest virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":774},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-5","text":"Verily, I divine you well, my disciples: ye strive like me for the\r bestowing virtue. What should ye have in common with cats and wolves?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":775},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-6","text":"It is your thirst to become sacrifices and gifts yourselves: and\r therefore have ye the thirst to accumulate all riches in your soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":776},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-7","text":"Insatiably striveth your soul for treasures and jewels, because your\r virtue is insatiable in desiring to bestow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":777},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-8","text":"Ye constrain all things to flow towards you and into you, so that they\r shall flow back again out of your fountain as the gifts of your love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":778},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-9","text":"Verily, an appropriator of all values must such bestowing love become;\r but healthy and holy, call I this selfishness.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":779},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-10","text":"Another selfishness is there, an all-too-poor and hungry kind, which\r would always steal—the selfishness of the sick, the sickly selfishness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":780},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-11","text":"With the eye of the thief it looketh upon all that is lustrous; with the\r craving of hunger it measureth him who hath abundance; and ever doth it\r prowl round the tables of bestowers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":781},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-12","text":"Sickness speaketh in such craving, and invisible degeneration; of a\r sickly body, speaketh the larcenous craving of this selfishness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":782},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-13","text":"Tell me, my brother, what do we think bad, and worst of all? Is it not\r DEGENERATION?—And we always suspect degeneration when the bestowing\r soul is lacking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":783},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-14","text":"Upward goeth our course from genera on to super-genera. But a horror to\r us is the degenerating sense, which saith: “All for myself.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":784},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-15","text":"Upward soareth our sense: thus is it a simile of our body, a simile of\r an elevation. Such similes of elevations are the names of the virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":785},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-16","text":"Thus goeth the body through history, a becomer and fighter. And the\r spirit—what is it to the body? Its fights’ and victories’ herald, its\r companion and echo.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":786},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-17","text":"Similes, are all names of good and evil; they do not speak out, they\r only hint. A fool who seeketh knowledge from them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":787},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-18","text":"Give heed, my brethren, to every hour when your spirit would speak in\r similes: there is the origin of your virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":788},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-19","text":"Elevated is then your body, and raised up; with its delight, enraptureth\r it the spirit; so that it becometh creator, and valuer, and lover, and\r everything’s benefactor.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":789},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-20","text":"When your heart overfloweth broad and full like the river, a blessing\r and a danger to the lowlanders: there is the origin of your virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":790},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-21","text":"When ye are exalted above praise and blame, and your will would command\r all things, as a loving one’s will: there is the origin of your virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":791},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-22","text":"When ye despise pleasant things, and the effeminate couch, and cannot\r couch far enough from the effeminate: there is the origin of your\r virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":792},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-23","text":"When ye are willers of one will, and when that change of every need is\r needful to you: there is the origin of your virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":793},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-24","text":"Verily, a new good and evil is it! Verily, a new deep murmuring, and the\r voice of a new fountain!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":794},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-25","text":"Power is it, this new virtue; a ruling thought is it, and around it a\r subtle soul: a golden sun, with the serpent of knowledge around it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":795},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-26","text":"Here paused Zarathustra awhile, and looked lovingly on his disciples.\r Then he continued to speak thus—and his voice had changed:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":796},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-27","text":"Remain true to the earth, my brethren, with the power of your virtue!\r Let your bestowing love and your knowledge be devoted to be the meaning\r of the earth! Thus do I pray and conjure you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":797},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-28","text":"Let it not fly away from the earthly and beat against eternal walls with\r its wings! Ah, there hath always been so much flown-away virtue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":798},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-29","text":"Lead, like me, the flown-away virtue back to the earth—yea, back\r to body and life: that it may give to the earth its meaning, a human\r meaning!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":799},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-30","text":"A hundred times hitherto hath spirit as well as virtue flown away\r and blundered. Alas! in our body dwelleth still all this delusion and\r blundering: body and will hath it there become.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":800},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-31","text":"A hundred times hitherto hath spirit as well as virtue attempted and\r erred. Yea, an attempt hath man been. Alas, much ignorance and error\r hath become embodied in us!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":801},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-32","text":"Not only the rationality of millenniums—also their madness, breaketh\r out in us. Dangerous is it to be an heir.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":802},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-33","text":"Still fight we step by step with the giant Chance, and over all mankind\r hath hitherto ruled nonsense, the lack-of-sense.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":803},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-34","text":"Let your spirit and your virtue be devoted to the sense of the earth,\r my brethren: let the value of everything be determined anew by you!\r Therefore shall ye be fighters! Therefore shall ye be creators!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":804},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-35","text":"Intelligently doth the body purify itself; attempting with intelligence\r it exalteth itself; to the discerners all impulses sanctify themselves;\r to the exalted the soul becometh joyful.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":805},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-36","text":"Physician, heal thyself: then wilt thou also heal thy patient. Let it be\r his best cure to see with his eyes him who maketh himself whole.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":806},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-37","text":"A thousand paths are there which have never yet been trodden; a thousand\r salubrities and hidden islands of life. Unexhausted and undiscovered is\r still man and man’s world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":807},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-38","text":"Awake and hearken, ye lonesome ones! From the future come winds with\r stealthy pinions, and to fine ears good tidings are proclaimed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":808},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-39","text":"Ye lonesome ones of to-day, ye seceding ones, ye shall one day be a\r people: out of you who have chosen yourselves, shall a chosen people\r arise:—and out of it the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":809},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-40","text":"Verily, a place of healing shall the earth become! And already is a new\r odour diffused around it, a salvation-bringing odour—and a new hope!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":810},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-41","text":"When Zarathustra had spoken these words, he paused, like one who had not\r said his last word; and long did he balance the staff doubtfully in his\r hand. At last he spake thus—and his voice had changed:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":811},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-42","text":"I now go alone, my disciples! Ye also now go away, and alone! So will I\r have it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":812},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-43","text":"Verily, I advise you: depart from me, and guard yourselves against\r Zarathustra! And better still: be ashamed of him! Perhaps he hath\r deceived you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":813},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-44","text":"The man of knowledge must be able not only to love his enemies, but also\r to hate his friends.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":814},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-45","text":"One requiteth a teacher badly if one remain merely a scholar. And why\r will ye not pluck at my wreath?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":815},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-46","text":"Ye venerate me; but what if your veneration should some day collapse?\r Take heed lest a statue crush you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":816},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-47","text":"Ye say, ye believe in Zarathustra? But of what account is Zarathustra!\r Ye are my believers: but of what account are all believers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":817},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-48","text":"Ye had not yet sought yourselves: then did ye find me. So do all\r believers; therefore all belief is of so little account.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":818},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-49","text":"Now do I bid you lose me and find yourselves; and only when ye have all\r denied me, will I return unto you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":819},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-50","text":"Verily, with other eyes, my brethren, shall I then seek my lost ones;\r with another love shall I then love you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":820},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-51","text":"And once again shall ye have become friends unto me, and children of one\r hope: then will I be with you for the third time, to celebrate the great\r noontide with you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":821},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-52","text":"And it is the great noontide, when man is in the middle of his course\r between animal and Superman, and celebrateth his advance to the evening\r as his highest hope: for it is the advance to a new morning.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":822},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-53","text":"At such time will the down-goer bless himself, that he should be an\r over-goer; and the sun of his knowledge will be at noontide.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":823},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-41-54","text":"“DEAD ARE ALL THE GODS: NOW DO WE DESIRE THE SUPERMAN TO LIVE.”—Let\r this be our final will at the great noontide!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":824},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-42-1","text":"“—and only when ye have all denied me, will I return unto you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":825},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-42-2","text":"Verily, with other eyes, my brethren, shall I then seek my lost ones;\r with another love shall I then love you.”—ZARATHUSTRA, I., “The\r Bestowing Virtue.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":826},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-1","text":"After this Zarathustra returned again into the mountains to the solitude\r of his cave, and withdrew himself from men, waiting like a sower who\r hath scattered his seed. His soul, however, became impatient and full of\r longing for those whom he loved: because he had still much to give them.\r For this is hardest of all: to close the open hand out of love, and keep\r modest as a giver.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":827},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-2","text":"Thus passed with the lonesome one months and years; his wisdom meanwhile\r increased, and caused him pain by its abundance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":828},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-3","text":"One morning, however, he awoke ere the rosy dawn, and having meditated\r long on his couch, at last spake thus to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":829},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-4","text":"Why did I startle in my dream, so that I awoke? Did not a child come to\r me, carrying a mirror?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":830},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-5","text":"“O Zarathustra”—said the child unto me—“look at thyself in the\r mirror!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":831},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-6","text":"But when I looked into the mirror, I shrieked, and my heart throbbed:\r for not myself did I see therein, but a devil’s grimace and derision.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":832},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-7","text":"Verily, all too well do I understand the dream’s portent and monition:\r my DOCTRINE is in danger; tares want to be called wheat!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":833},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-8","text":"Mine enemies have grown powerful and have disfigured the likeness of\r my doctrine, so that my dearest ones have to blush for the gifts that I\r gave them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":834},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-9","text":"Lost are my friends; the hour hath come for me to seek my lost ones!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":835},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-10","text":"With these words Zarathustra started up, not however like a person in\r anguish seeking relief, but rather like a seer and a singer whom the\r spirit inspireth. With amazement did his eagle and serpent gaze upon\r him: for a coming bliss overspread his countenance like the rosy dawn.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":836},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-11","text":"What hath happened unto me, mine animals?—said Zarathustra. Am I not\r transformed? Hath not bliss come unto me like a whirlwind?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":837},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-12","text":"Foolish is my happiness, and foolish things will it speak: it is still\r too young—so have patience with it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":838},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-13","text":"Wounded am I by my happiness: all sufferers shall be physicians unto me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":839},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-14","text":"To my friends can I again go down, and also to mine enemies! Zarathustra\r can again speak and bestow, and show his best love to his loved ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":840},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-15","text":"My impatient love overfloweth in streams,—down towards sunrise and\r sunset. Out of silent mountains and storms of affliction, rusheth my\r soul into the valleys.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":841},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-16","text":"Too long have I longed and looked into the distance. Too long hath\r solitude possessed me: thus have I unlearned to keep silence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":842},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-17","text":"Utterance have I become altogether, and the brawling of a brook from\r high rocks: downward into the valleys will I hurl my speech.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":843},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-18","text":"And let the stream of my love sweep into unfrequented channels! How\r should a stream not finally find its way to the sea!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":844},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-19","text":"Forsooth, there is a lake in me, sequestered and self-sufficing; but the\r stream of my love beareth this along with it, down—to the sea!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":845},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-20","text":"New paths do I tread, a new speech cometh unto me; tired have I become—\r like all creators—of the old tongues. No longer will my spirit walk on\r worn-out soles.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":846},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-21","text":"Too slowly runneth all speaking for me:—into thy chariot, O storm, do I\r leap! And even thee will I whip with my spite!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":847},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-22","text":"Like a cry and an huzza will I traverse wide seas, till I find the Happy\r Isles where my friends sojourn;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":848},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-23","text":"And mine enemies amongst them! How I now love every one unto whom I may\r but speak! Even mine enemies pertain to my bliss.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":849},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-24","text":"And when I want to mount my wildest horse, then doth my spear always\r help me up best: it is my foot’s ever ready servant:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":850},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-25","text":"The spear which I hurl at mine enemies! How grateful am I to mine\r enemies that I may at last hurl it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":851},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-26","text":"Too great hath been the tension of my cloud: ‘twixt laughters of\r lightnings will I cast hail-showers into the depths.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":852},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-27","text":"Violently will my breast then heave; violently will it blow its storm\r over the mountains: thus cometh its assuagement.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":853},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-28","text":"Verily, like a storm cometh my happiness, and my freedom! But mine\r enemies shall think that THE EVIL ONE roareth over their heads.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":854},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-29","text":"Yea, ye also, my friends, will be alarmed by my wild wisdom; and perhaps\r ye will flee therefrom, along with mine enemies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":855},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-30","text":"Ah, that I knew how to lure you back with shepherds’ flutes! Ah, that\r my lioness wisdom would learn to roar softly! And much have we already\r learned with one another!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":856},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-31","text":"My wild wisdom became pregnant on the lonesome mountains; on the rough\r stones did she bear the youngest of her young.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":857},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-32","text":"Now runneth she foolishly in the arid wilderness, and seeketh and\r seeketh the soft sward—mine old, wild wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":858},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-43-33","text":"On the soft sward of your hearts, my friends!—on your love, would she\r fain couch her dearest one!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":859},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-1","text":"The figs fall from the trees, they are good and sweet; and in falling\r the red skins of them break. A north wind am I to ripe figs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":860},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-2","text":"Thus, like figs, do these doctrines fall for you, my friends: imbibe\r now their juice and their sweet substance! It is autumn all around, and\r clear sky, and afternoon.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":861},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-3","text":"Lo, what fulness is around us! And out of the midst of superabundance,\r it is delightful to look out upon distant seas.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":862},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-4","text":"Once did people say God, when they looked out upon distant seas; now,\r however, have I taught you to say, Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":863},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-5","text":"God is a conjecture: but I do not wish your conjecturing to reach beyond\r your creating will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":864},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-6","text":"Could ye CREATE a God?—Then, I pray you, be silent about all Gods! But\r ye could well create the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":865},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-7","text":"Not perhaps ye yourselves, my brethren! But into fathers and forefathers\r of the Superman could ye transform yourselves: and let that be your best\r creating!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":866},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-8","text":"God is a conjecture: but I should like your conjecturing restricted to\r the conceivable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":867},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-9","text":"Could ye CONCEIVE a God?—But let this mean Will to Truth unto you,\r that everything be transformed into the humanly conceivable, the humanly\r visible, the humanly sensible! Your own discernment shall ye follow out\r to the end!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":868},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-10","text":"And what ye have called the world shall but be created by you: your\r reason, your likeness, your will, your love, shall it itself become! And\r verily, for your bliss, ye discerning ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":869},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-11","text":"And how would ye endure life without that hope, ye discerning ones?\r Neither in the inconceivable could ye have been born, nor in the\r irrational.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":870},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-12","text":"But that I may reveal my heart entirely unto you, my friends: IF there\r were gods, how could I endure it to be no God! THEREFORE there are no\r Gods.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":871},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-13","text":"Yea, I have drawn the conclusion; now, however, doth it draw me.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":872},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-14","text":"God is a conjecture: but who could drink all the bitterness of this\r conjecture without dying? Shall his faith be taken from the creating\r one, and from the eagle his flights into eagle-heights?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":873},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-15","text":"God is a thought—it maketh all the straight crooked, and all that\r standeth reel. What? Time would be gone, and all the perishable would be\r but a lie?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":874},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-16","text":"To think this is giddiness and vertigo to human limbs, and even vomiting\r to the stomach: verily, the reeling sickness do I call it, to conjecture\r such a thing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":875},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-17","text":"Evil do I call it and misanthropic: all that teaching about the one, and\r the plenum, and the unmoved, and the sufficient, and the imperishable!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":876},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-18","text":"All the imperishable—that’s but a simile, and the poets lie too much.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":877},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-19","text":"But of time and of becoming shall the best similes speak: a praise shall\r they be, and a justification of all perishableness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":878},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-20","text":"Creating—that is the great salvation from suffering, and life’s\r alleviation. But for the creator to appear, suffering itself is needed,\r and much transformation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":879},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-21","text":"Yea, much bitter dying must there be in your life, ye creators! Thus are\r ye advocates and justifiers of all perishableness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":880},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-22","text":"For the creator himself to be the new-born child, he must also\r be willing to be the child-bearer, and endure the pangs of the\r child-bearer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":881},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-23","text":"Verily, through a hundred souls went I my way, and through a hundred\r cradles and birth-throes. Many a farewell have I taken; I know the\r heart-breaking last hours.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":882},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-24","text":"But so willeth it my creating Will, my fate. Or, to tell you it more\r candidly: just such a fate—willeth my Will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":883},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-25","text":"All FEELING suffereth in me, and is in prison: but my WILLING ever\r cometh to me as mine emancipator and comforter.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":884},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-26","text":"Willing emancipateth: that is the true doctrine of will and\r emancipation—so teacheth you Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":885},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-27","text":"No longer willing, and no longer valuing, and no longer creating! Ah,\r that that great debility may ever be far from me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":886},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-28","text":"And also in discerning do I feel only my will’s procreating and evolving\r delight; and if there be innocence in my knowledge, it is because there\r is will to procreation in it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":887},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-29","text":"Away from God and Gods did this will allure me; what would there be to\r create if there were—Gods!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":888},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-30","text":"But to man doth it ever impel me anew, my fervent creative will; thus\r impelleth it the hammer to the stone.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":889},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-31","text":"Ah, ye men, within the stone slumbereth an image for me, the image of my\r visions! Ah, that it should slumber in the hardest, ugliest stone!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":890},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-32","text":"Now rageth my hammer ruthlessly against its prison. From the stone fly\r the fragments: what’s that to me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":891},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-33","text":"I will complete it: for a shadow came unto me—the stillest and lightest\r of all things once came unto me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":892},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-44-34","text":"The beauty of the Superman came unto me as a shadow. Ah, my brethren! Of\r what account now are—the Gods to me!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":893},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-1","text":"My friends, there hath arisen a satire on your friend: “Behold\r Zarathustra! Walketh he not amongst us as if amongst animals?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":894},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-2","text":"But it is better said in this wise: “The discerning one walketh amongst\r men AS amongst animals.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":895},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-3","text":"Man himself is to the discerning one: the animal with red cheeks.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":896},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-4","text":"How hath that happened unto him? Is it not because he hath had to be\r ashamed too oft?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":897},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-5","text":"O my friends! Thus speaketh the discerning one: shame, shame,\r shame—that is the history of man!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":898},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-6","text":"And on that account doth the noble one enjoin upon himself not to abash:\r bashfulness doth he enjoin on himself in presence of all sufferers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":899},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-7","text":"Verily, I like them not, the merciful ones, whose bliss is in their\r pity: too destitute are they of bashfulness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":900},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-8","text":"If I must be pitiful, I dislike to be called so; and if I be so, it is\r preferably at a distance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":901},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-9","text":"Preferably also do I shroud my head, and flee, before being recognised:\r and thus do I bid you do, my friends!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":902},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-10","text":"May my destiny ever lead unafflicted ones like you across my path, and\r those with whom I MAY have hope and repast and honey in common!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":903},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-11","text":"Verily, I have done this and that for the afflicted: but something\r better did I always seem to do when I had learned to enjoy myself\r better.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":904},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-12","text":"Since humanity came into being, man hath enjoyed himself too little:\r that alone, my brethren, is our original sin!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":905},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-13","text":"And when we learn better to enjoy ourselves, then do we unlearn best to\r give pain unto others, and to contrive pain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":906},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-14","text":"Therefore do I wash the hand that hath helped the sufferer; therefore do\r I wipe also my soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":907},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-15","text":"For in seeing the sufferer suffering—thereof was I ashamed on account\r of his shame; and in helping him, sorely did I wound his pride.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":908},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-16","text":"Great obligations do not make grateful, but revengeful; and when a small\r kindness is not forgotten, it becometh a gnawing worm.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":909},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-17","text":"“Be shy in accepting! Distinguish by accepting!”—thus do I advise those\r who have naught to bestow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":910},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-18","text":"I, however, am a bestower: willingly do I bestow as friend to friends.\r Strangers, however, and the poor, may pluck for themselves the fruit\r from my tree: thus doth it cause less shame.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":911},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-19","text":"Beggars, however, one should entirely do away with! Verily, it annoyeth\r one to give unto them, and it annoyeth one not to give unto them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":912},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-20","text":"And likewise sinners and bad consciences! Believe me, my friends: the\r sting of conscience teacheth one to sting.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":913},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-21","text":"The worst things, however, are the petty thoughts. Verily, better to\r have done evilly than to have thought pettily!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":914},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-22","text":"To be sure, ye say: “The delight in petty evils spareth one many a great\r evil deed.” But here one should not wish to be sparing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":915},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-23","text":"Like a boil is the evil deed: it itcheth and irritateth and breaketh\r forth—it speaketh honourably.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":916},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-24","text":"“Behold, I am disease,” saith the evil deed: that is its honourableness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":917},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-25","text":"But like infection is the petty thought: it creepeth and hideth, and\r wanteth to be nowhere—until the whole body is decayed and withered by\r the petty infection.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":918},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-26","text":"To him however, who is possessed of a devil, I would whisper this word\r in the ear: “Better for thee to rear up thy devil! Even for thee there\r is still a path to greatness!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":919},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-27","text":"Ah, my brethren! One knoweth a little too much about every one! And many\r a one becometh transparent to us, but still we can by no means penetrate\r him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":920},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-28","text":"It is difficult to live among men because silence is so difficult.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":921},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-29","text":"And not to him who is offensive to us are we most unfair, but to him who\r doth not concern us at all.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":922},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-30","text":"If, however, thou hast a suffering friend, then be a resting-place for\r his suffering; like a hard bed, however, a camp-bed: thus wilt thou\r serve him best.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":923},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-31","text":"And if a friend doeth thee wrong, then say: “I forgive thee what thou\r hast done unto me; that thou hast done it unto THYSELF, however—how\r could I forgive that!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":924},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-32","text":"Thus speaketh all great love: it surpasseth even forgiveness and pity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":925},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-33","text":"One should hold fast one’s heart; for when one letteth it go, how\r quickly doth one’s head run away!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":926},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-34","text":"Ah, where in the world have there been greater follies than with the\r pitiful? And what in the world hath caused more suffering than the\r follies of the pitiful?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":927},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-35","text":"Woe unto all loving ones who have not an elevation which is above their\r pity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":928},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-36","text":"Thus spake the devil unto me, once on a time: “Even God hath his hell:\r it is his love for man.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":929},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-37","text":"And lately, did I hear him say these words: “God is dead: of his pity\r for man hath God died.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":930},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-38","text":"So be ye warned against pity: FROM THENCE there yet cometh unto men a\r heavy cloud! Verily, I understand weather-signs!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":931},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-39","text":"But attend also to this word: All great love is above all its pity: for\r it seeketh—to create what is loved!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":932},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-45-40","text":"“Myself do I offer unto my love, AND MY NEIGHBOUR AS MYSELF”—such is\r the language of all creators.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":933},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-1","text":"And one day Zarathustra made a sign to his disciples, and spake these\r words unto them:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":934},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-2","text":"“Here are priests: but although they are mine enemies, pass them quietly\r and with sleeping swords!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":935},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-3","text":"Even among them there are heroes; many of them have suffered too much—:\r so they want to make others suffer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":936},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-4","text":"Bad enemies are they: nothing is more revengeful than their meekness.\r And readily doth he soil himself who toucheth them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":937},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-5","text":"But my blood is related to theirs; and I want withal to see my blood\r honoured in theirs.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":938},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-6","text":"And when they had passed, a pain attacked Zarathustra; but not long had\r he struggled with the pain, when he began to speak thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":939},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-7","text":"It moveth my heart for those priests. They also go against my taste; but\r that is the smallest matter unto me, since I am among men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":940},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-8","text":"But I suffer and have suffered with them: prisoners are they unto me,\r and stigmatised ones. He whom they call Saviour put them in fetters:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":941},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-9","text":"In fetters of false values and fatuous words! Oh, that some one would\r save them from their Saviour!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":942},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-10","text":"On an isle they once thought they had landed, when the sea tossed them\r about; but behold, it was a slumbering monster!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":943},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-11","text":"False values and fatuous words: these are the worst monsters for\r mortals—long slumbereth and waiteth the fate that is in them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":944},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-12","text":"But at last it cometh and awaketh and devoureth and engulfeth whatever\r hath built tabernacles upon it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":945},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-13","text":"Oh, just look at those tabernacles which those priests have built\r themselves! Churches, they call their sweet-smelling caves!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":946},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-14","text":"Oh, that falsified light, that mustified air! Where the soul—may not\r fly aloft to its height!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":947},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-15","text":"But so enjoineth their belief: “On your knees, up the stair, ye\r sinners!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":948},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-16","text":"Verily, rather would I see a shameless one than the distorted eyes of\r their shame and devotion!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":949},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-17","text":"Who created for themselves such caves and penitence-stairs? Was it not\r those who sought to conceal themselves, and were ashamed under the clear\r sky?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":950},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-18","text":"And only when the clear sky looketh again through ruined roofs, and down\r upon grass and red poppies on ruined walls—will I again turn my heart\r to the seats of this God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":951},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-19","text":"They called God that which opposed and afflicted them: and verily, there\r was much hero-spirit in their worship!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":952},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-20","text":"And they knew not how to love their God otherwise than by nailing men to\r the cross!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":953},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-21","text":"As corpses they thought to live; in black draped they their corpses;\r even in their talk do I still feel the evil flavour of charnel-houses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":954},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-22","text":"And he who liveth nigh unto them liveth nigh unto black pools, wherein\r the toad singeth his song with sweet gravity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":955},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-23","text":"Better songs would they have to sing, for me to believe in their\r Saviour: more like saved ones would his disciples have to appear unto\r me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":956},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-24","text":"Naked, would I like to see them: for beauty alone should preach\r penitence. But whom would that disguised affliction convince!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":957},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-25","text":"Verily, their Saviours themselves came not from freedom and freedom’s\r seventh heaven! Verily, they themselves never trod the carpets of\r knowledge!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":958},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-26","text":"Of defects did the spirit of those Saviours consist; but into every\r defect had they put their illusion, their stop-gap, which they called\r God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":959},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-27","text":"In their pity was their spirit drowned; and when they swelled and\r o’erswelled with pity, there always floated to the surface a great\r folly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":960},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-28","text":"Eagerly and with shouts drove they their flock over their foot-bridge;\r as if there were but one foot-bridge to the future! Verily, those\r shepherds also were still of the flock!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":961},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-29","text":"Small spirits and spacious souls had those shepherds: but, my brethren,\r what small domains have even the most spacious souls hitherto been!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":962},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-30","text":"Characters of blood did they write on the way they went, and their folly\r taught that truth is proved by blood.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":963},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-31","text":"But blood is the very worst witness to truth; blood tainteth the purest\r teaching, and turneth it into delusion and hatred of heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":964},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-32","text":"And when a person goeth through fire for his teaching—what doth that\r prove! It is more, verily, when out of one’s own burning cometh one’s\r own teaching!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":965},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-33","text":"Sultry heart and cold head; where these meet, there ariseth the\r blusterer, the “Saviour.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":966},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-34","text":"Greater ones, verily, have there been, and higher-born ones, than those\r whom the people call Saviours, those rapturous blusterers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":967},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-35","text":"And by still greater ones than any of the Saviours must ye be saved, my\r brethren, if ye would find the way to freedom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":968},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-36","text":"Never yet hath there been a Superman. Naked have I seen both of them,\r the greatest man and the smallest man:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":969},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-46-37","text":"All-too-similar are they still to each other. Verily, even the greatest\r found I—all-too-human!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":970},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-1","text":"With thunder and heavenly fireworks must one speak to indolent and\r somnolent senses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":971},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-2","text":"But beauty’s voice speaketh gently: it appealeth only to the most\r awakened souls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":972},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-3","text":"Gently vibrated and laughed unto me to-day my buckler; it was beauty’s\r holy laughing and thrilling.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":973},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-4","text":"At you, ye virtuous ones, laughed my beauty to-day. And thus came its\r voice unto me: “They want—to be paid besides!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":974},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-5","text":"Ye want to be paid besides, ye virtuous ones! Ye want reward for virtue,\r and heaven for earth, and eternity for your to-day?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":975},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-6","text":"And now ye upbraid me for teaching that there is no reward-giver,\r nor paymaster? And verily, I do not even teach that virtue is its own\r reward.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":976},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-7","text":"Ah! this is my sorrow: into the basis of things have reward and\r punishment been insinuated—and now even into the basis of your souls,\r ye virtuous ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":977},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-8","text":"But like the snout of the boar shall my word grub up the basis of your\r souls; a ploughshare will I be called by you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":978},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-9","text":"All the secrets of your heart shall be brought to light; and when ye\r lie in the sun, grubbed up and broken, then will also your falsehood be\r separated from your truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":979},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-10","text":"For this is your truth: ye are TOO PURE for the filth of the words:\r vengeance, punishment, recompense, retribution.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":980},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-11","text":"Ye love your virtue as a mother loveth her child; but when did one hear\r of a mother wanting to be paid for her love?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":981},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-12","text":"It is your dearest Self, your virtue. The ring’s thirst is in you: to\r reach itself again struggleth every ring, and turneth itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":982},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-13","text":"And like the star that goeth out, so is every work of your virtue: ever\r is its light on its way and travelling—and when will it cease to be on\r its way?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":983},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-14","text":"Thus is the light of your virtue still on its way, even when its work\r is done. Be it forgotten and dead, still its ray of light liveth and\r travelleth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":984},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-15","text":"That your virtue is your Self, and not an outward thing, a skin, or\r a cloak: that is the truth from the basis of your souls, ye virtuous\r ones!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":985},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-16","text":"But sure enough there are those to whom virtue meaneth writhing under\r the lash: and ye have hearkened too much unto their crying!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":986},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-17","text":"And others are there who call virtue the slothfulness of their vices;\r and when once their hatred and jealousy relax the limbs, their “justice”\r  becometh lively and rubbeth its sleepy eyes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":987},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-18","text":"And others are there who are drawn downwards: their devils draw them.\r But the more they sink, the more ardently gloweth their eye, and the\r longing for their God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":988},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-19","text":"Ah! their crying also hath reached your ears, ye virtuous ones: “What I\r am NOT, that, that is God to me, and virtue!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":989},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-20","text":"And others are there who go along heavily and creakingly, like carts\r taking stones downhill: they talk much of dignity and virtue—their drag\r they call virtue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":990},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-21","text":"And others are there who are like eight-day clocks when wound up; they\r tick, and want people to call ticking—virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":991},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-22","text":"Verily, in those have I mine amusement: wherever I find such clocks I\r shall wind them up with my mockery, and they shall even whirr thereby!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":992},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-23","text":"And others are proud of their modicum of righteousness, and for the sake\r of it do violence to all things: so that the world is drowned in their\r unrighteousness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":993},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-24","text":"Ah! how ineptly cometh the word “virtue” out of their mouth! And when\r they say: “I am just,” it always soundeth like: “I am just—revenged!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":994},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-25","text":"With their virtues they want to scratch out the eyes of their enemies;\r and they elevate themselves only that they may lower others.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":995},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-26","text":"And again there are those who sit in their swamp, and speak thus from\r among the bulrushes: “Virtue—that is to sit quietly in the swamp.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":996},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-27","text":"We bite no one, and go out of the way of him who would bite; and in all\r matters we have the opinion that is given us.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":997},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-28","text":"And again there are those who love attitudes, and think that virtue is a\r sort of attitude.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":998},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-29","text":"Their knees continually adore, and their hands are eulogies of virtue,\r but their heart knoweth naught thereof.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":999},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-30","text":"And again there are those who regard it as virtue to say: “Virtue\r is necessary”; but after all they believe only that policemen are\r necessary.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1000},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-31","text":"And many a one who cannot see men’s loftiness, calleth it virtue to see\r their baseness far too well: thus calleth he his evil eye virtue.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1001},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-32","text":"And some want to be edified and raised up, and call it virtue: and\r others want to be cast down,—and likewise call it virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1002},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-33","text":"And thus do almost all think that they participate in virtue; and at\r least every one claimeth to be an authority on “good” and “evil.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1003},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-34","text":"But Zarathustra came not to say unto all those liars and fools: “What do\r YE know of virtue! What COULD ye know of virtue!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1004},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-35","text":"But that ye, my friends, might become weary of the old words which ye\r have learned from the fools and liars:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1005},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-36","text":"That ye might become weary of the words “reward,” “retribution,”\r  “punishment,” “righteous vengeance.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1006},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-37","text":"That ye might become weary of saying: “That an action is good is because\r it is unselfish.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1007},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-38","text":"Ah! my friends! That YOUR very Self be in your action, as the mother is\r in the child: let that be YOUR formula of virtue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1008},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-39","text":"Verily, I have taken from you a hundred formulae and your virtue’s\r favourite playthings; and now ye upbraid me, as children upbraid.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1009},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-40","text":"They played by the sea—then came there a wave and swept their\r playthings into the deep: and now do they cry.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1010},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-41","text":"But the same wave shall bring them new playthings, and spread before\r them new speckled shells!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1011},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-47-42","text":"Thus will they be comforted; and like them shall ye also, my friends,\r have your comforting—and new speckled shells!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":1012},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-1","text":"Life is a well of delight; but where the rabble also drink, there all\r fountains are poisoned.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1013},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-2","text":"To everything cleanly am I well disposed; but I hate to see the grinning\r mouths and the thirst of the unclean.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1014},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-3","text":"They cast their eye down into the fountain: and now glanceth up to me\r their odious smile out of the fountain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1015},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-4","text":"The holy water have they poisoned with their lustfulness; and when they\r called their filthy dreams delight, then poisoned they also the words.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1016},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-5","text":"Indignant becometh the flame when they put their damp hearts to the\r fire; the spirit itself bubbleth and smoketh when the rabble approach\r the fire.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1017},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-6","text":"Mawkish and over-mellow becometh the fruit in their hands: unsteady, and\r withered at the top, doth their look make the fruit-tree.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1018},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-7","text":"And many a one who hath turned away from life, hath only turned away\r from the rabble: he hated to share with them fountain, flame, and fruit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1019},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-8","text":"And many a one who hath gone into the wilderness and suffered thirst\r with beasts of prey, disliked only to sit at the cistern with filthy\r camel-drivers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1020},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-9","text":"And many a one who hath come along as a destroyer, and as a hailstorm\r to all cornfields, wanted merely to put his foot into the jaws of the\r rabble, and thus stop their throat.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1021},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-10","text":"And it is not the mouthful which hath most choked me, to know that life\r itself requireth enmity and death and torture-crosses:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1022},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-11","text":"But I asked once, and suffocated almost with my question: What? is the\r rabble also NECESSARY for life?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1023},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-12","text":"Are poisoned fountains necessary, and stinking fires, and filthy dreams,\r and maggots in the bread of life?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1024},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-13","text":"Not my hatred, but my loathing, gnawed hungrily at my life! Ah, ofttimes\r became I weary of spirit, when I found even the rabble spiritual!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1025},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-14","text":"And on the rulers turned I my back, when I saw what they now call\r ruling: to traffic and bargain for power—with the rabble!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1026},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-15","text":"Amongst peoples of a strange language did I dwell, with stopped ears: so\r that the language of their trafficking might remain strange unto me, and\r their bargaining for power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1027},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-16","text":"And holding my nose, I went morosely through all yesterdays and to-days:\r verily, badly smell all yesterdays and to-days of the scribbling rabble!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1028},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-17","text":"Like a cripple become deaf, and blind, and dumb—thus have I lived long;\r that I might not live with the power-rabble, the scribe-rabble, and the\r pleasure-rabble.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1029},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-18","text":"Toilsomely did my spirit mount stairs, and cautiously; alms of delight\r were its refreshment; on the staff did life creep along with the blind\r one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1030},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-19","text":"What hath happened unto me? How have I freed myself from loathing?\r Who hath rejuvenated mine eye? How have I flown to the height where no\r rabble any longer sit at the wells?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1031},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-20","text":"Did my loathing itself create for me wings and fountain-divining powers?\r Verily, to the loftiest height had I to fly, to find again the well of\r delight!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1032},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-21","text":"Oh, I have found it, my brethren! Here on the loftiest height bubbleth\r up for me the well of delight! And there is a life at whose waters none\r of the rabble drink with me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1033},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-22","text":"Almost too violently dost thou flow for me, thou fountain of delight!\r And often emptiest thou the goblet again, in wanting to fill it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1034},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-23","text":"And yet must I learn to approach thee more modestly: far too violently\r doth my heart still flow towards thee:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1035},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-24","text":"My heart on which my summer burneth, my short, hot, melancholy,\r over-happy summer: how my summer heart longeth for thy coolness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1036},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-25","text":"Past, the lingering distress of my spring! Past, the wickedness of my\r snowflakes in June! Summer have I become entirely, and summer-noontide!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1037},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-26","text":"A summer on the loftiest height, with cold fountains and blissful\r stillness: oh, come, my friends, that the stillness may become more\r blissful!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1038},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-27","text":"For this is OUR height and our home: too high and steep do we here dwell\r for all uncleanly ones and their thirst.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1039},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-28","text":"Cast but your pure eyes into the well of my delight, my friends! How\r could it become turbid thereby! It shall laugh back to you with ITS\r purity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1040},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-29","text":"On the tree of the future build we our nest; eagles shall bring us lone\r ones food in their beaks!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1041},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-30","text":"Verily, no food of which the impure could be fellow-partakers! Fire,\r would they think they devoured, and burn their mouths!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1042},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-31","text":"Verily, no abodes do we here keep ready for the impure! An ice-cave to\r their bodies would our happiness be, and to their spirits!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1043},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-32","text":"And as strong winds will we live above them, neighbours to the eagles,\r neighbours to the snow, neighbours to the sun: thus live the strong\r winds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1044},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-33","text":"And like a wind will I one day blow amongst them, and with my spirit,\r take the breath from their spirit: thus willeth my future.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1045},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-48-34","text":"Verily, a strong wind is Zarathustra to all low places; and this counsel\r counselleth he to his enemies, and to whatever spitteth and speweth:\r “Take care not to spit AGAINST the wind!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":1046},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-1","text":"Lo, this is the tarantula’s den! Wouldst thou see the tarantula itself?\r Here hangeth its web: touch this, so that it may tremble.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1047},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-2","text":"There cometh the tarantula willingly: Welcome, tarantula! Black on thy\r back is thy triangle and symbol; and I know also what is in thy soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1048},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-3","text":"Revenge is in thy soul: wherever thou bitest, there ariseth black scab;\r with revenge, thy poison maketh the soul giddy!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1049},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-4","text":"Thus do I speak unto you in parable, ye who make the soul giddy,\r ye preachers of EQUALITY! Tarantulas are ye unto me, and secretly\r revengeful ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1050},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-5","text":"But I will soon bring your hiding-places to the light: therefore do I\r laugh in your face my laughter of the height.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1051},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-6","text":"Therefore do I tear at your web, that your rage may lure you out of your\r den of lies, and that your revenge may leap forth from behind your word\r “justice.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1052},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-7","text":"Because, FOR MAN TO BE REDEEMED FROM REVENGE—that is for me the bridge\r to the highest hope, and a rainbow after long storms.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1053},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-8","text":"Otherwise, however, would the tarantulas have it. “Let it be\r very justice for the world to become full of the storms of our\r vengeance”—thus do they talk to one another.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1054},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-9","text":"“Vengeance will we use, and insult, against all who are not like\r us”—thus do the tarantula-hearts pledge themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1055},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-10","text":"“And ‘Will to Equality’—that itself shall henceforth be the name of\r virtue; and against all that hath power will we raise an outcry!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1056},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-11","text":"Ye preachers of equality, the tyrant-frenzy of impotence crieth thus in\r you for “equality”: your most secret tyrant-longings disguise themselves\r thus in virtue-words!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1057},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-12","text":"Fretted conceit and suppressed envy—perhaps your fathers’ conceit and\r envy: in you break they forth as flame and frenzy of vengeance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1058},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-13","text":"What the father hath hid cometh out in the son; and oft have I found in\r the son the father’s revealed secret.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1059},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-14","text":"Inspired ones they resemble: but it is not the heart that inspireth\r them—but vengeance. And when they become subtle and cold, it is not\r spirit, but envy, that maketh them so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1060},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-15","text":"Their jealousy leadeth them also into thinkers’ paths; and this is the\r sign of their jealousy—they always go too far: so that their fatigue\r hath at last to go to sleep on the snow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1061},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-16","text":"In all their lamentations soundeth vengeance, in all their eulogies is\r maleficence; and being judge seemeth to them bliss.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1062},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-17","text":"But thus do I counsel you, my friends: distrust all in whom the impulse\r to punish is powerful!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1063},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-18","text":"They are people of bad race and lineage; out of their countenances peer\r the hangman and the sleuth-hound.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1064},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-19","text":"Distrust all those who talk much of their justice! Verily, in their\r souls not only honey is lacking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1065},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-20","text":"And when they call themselves “the good and just,” forget not, that for\r them to be Pharisees, nothing is lacking but—power!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1066},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-21","text":"My friends, I will not be mixed up and confounded with others.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1067},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-22","text":"There are those who preach my doctrine of life, and are at the same time\r preachers of equality, and tarantulas.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1068},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-23","text":"That they speak in favour of life, though they sit in their den, these\r poison-spiders, and withdrawn from life—is because they would thereby\r do injury.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1069},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-24","text":"To those would they thereby do injury who have power at present: for\r with those the preaching of death is still most at home.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1070},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-25","text":"Were it otherwise, then would the tarantulas teach otherwise: and they\r themselves were formerly the best world-maligners and heretic-burners.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1071},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-26","text":"With these preachers of equality will I not be mixed up and confounded.\r For thus speaketh justice UNTO ME: “Men are not equal.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1072},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-27","text":"And neither shall they become so! What would be my love to the Superman,\r if I spake otherwise?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1073},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-28","text":"On a thousand bridges and piers shall they throng to the future, and\r always shall there be more war and inequality among them: thus doth my\r great love make me speak!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1074},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-29","text":"Inventors of figures and phantoms shall they be in their hostilities;\r and with those figures and phantoms shall they yet fight with each other\r the supreme fight!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1075},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-30","text":"Good and evil, and rich and poor, and high and low, and all names of\r values: weapons shall they be, and sounding signs, that life must again\r and again surpass itself!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1076},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-31","text":"Aloft will it build itself with columns and stairs—life itself: into\r remote distances would it gaze, and out towards blissful beauties—\r THEREFORE doth it require elevation!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1077},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-32","text":"And because it requireth elevation, therefore doth it require steps, and\r variance of steps and climbers! To rise striveth life, and in rising to\r surpass itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1078},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-33","text":"And just behold, my friends! Here where the tarantula’s den is, riseth\r aloft an ancient temple’s ruins—just behold it with enlightened eyes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1079},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-34","text":"Verily, he who here towered aloft his thoughts in stone, knew as well as\r the wisest ones about the secret of life!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1080},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-35","text":"That there is struggle and inequality even in beauty, and war for power\r and supremacy: that doth he here teach us in the plainest parable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1081},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-36","text":"How divinely do vault and arch here contrast in the struggle: how with\r light and shade they strive against each other, the divinely striving\r ones.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1082},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-37","text":"Thus, steadfast and beautiful, let us also be enemies, my friends!\r Divinely will we strive AGAINST one another!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1083},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-38","text":"Alas! There hath the tarantula bit me myself, mine old enemy! Divinely\r steadfast and beautiful, it hath bit me on the finger!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1084},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-39","text":"“Punishment must there be, and justice”—so thinketh it: “not\r gratuitously shall he here sing songs in honour of enmity!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1085},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-40","text":"Yea, it hath revenged itself! And alas! now will it make my soul also\r dizzy with revenge!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1086},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-41","text":"That I may NOT turn dizzy, however, bind me fast, my friends, to this\r pillar! Rather will I be a pillar-saint than a whirl of vengeance!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1087},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-49-42","text":"Verily, no cyclone or whirlwind is Zarathustra: and if he be a dancer,\r he is not at all a tarantula-dancer!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":1088},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-1","text":"The people have ye served and the people’s superstition—NOT the\r truth!—all ye famous wise ones! And just on that account did they pay\r you reverence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1089},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-2","text":"And on that account also did they tolerate your unbelief, because it\r was a pleasantry and a by-path for the people. Thus doth the master give\r free scope to his slaves, and even enjoyeth their presumptuousness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1090},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-3","text":"But he who is hated by the people, as the wolf by the dogs—is the free\r spirit, the enemy of fetters, the non-adorer, the dweller in the woods.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1091},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-4","text":"To hunt him out of his lair—that was always called “sense of right” by\r the people: on him do they still hound their sharpest-toothed dogs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1092},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-5","text":"“For there the truth is, where the people are! Woe, woe to the seeking\r ones!”—thus hath it echoed through all time.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1093},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-6","text":"Your people would ye justify in their reverence: that called ye “Will to\r Truth,” ye famous wise ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1094},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-7","text":"And your heart hath always said to itself: “From the people have I come:\r from thence came to me also the voice of God.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1095},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-8","text":"Stiff-necked and artful, like the ass, have ye always been, as the\r advocates of the people.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1096},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-9","text":"And many a powerful one who wanted to run well with the people, hath\r harnessed in front of his horses—a donkey, a famous wise man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1097},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-10","text":"And now, ye famous wise ones, I would have you finally throw off\r entirely the skin of the lion!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1098},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-11","text":"The skin of the beast of prey, the speckled skin, and the dishevelled\r locks of the investigator, the searcher, and the conqueror!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1099},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-12","text":"Ah! for me to learn to believe in your “conscientiousness,” ye would\r first have to break your venerating will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1100},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-13","text":"Conscientious—so call I him who goeth into God-forsaken wildernesses,\r and hath broken his venerating heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1101},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-14","text":"In the yellow sands and burnt by the sun, he doubtless peereth thirstily\r at the isles rich in fountains, where life reposeth under shady trees.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1102},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-15","text":"But his thirst doth not persuade him to become like those comfortable\r ones: for where there are oases, there are also idols.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1103},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-16","text":"Hungry, fierce, lonesome, God-forsaken: so doth the lion-will wish\r itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1104},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-17","text":"Free from the happiness of slaves, redeemed from Deities and adorations,\r fearless and fear-inspiring, grand and lonesome: so is the will of the\r conscientious.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1105},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-18","text":"In the wilderness have ever dwelt the conscientious, the free spirits,\r as lords of the wilderness; but in the cities dwell the well-foddered,\r famous wise ones—the draught-beasts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1106},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-19","text":"Not that I on that account upbraid them: but serving ones do they\r remain, and harnessed ones, even though they glitter in golden harness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1107},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-20","text":"And often have they been good servants and worthy of their hire. For\r thus saith virtue: “If thou must be a servant, seek him unto whom thy\r service is most useful!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1108},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-21","text":"The spirit and virtue of thy master shall advance by thou being his\r servant: thus wilt thou thyself advance with his spirit and virtue!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1109},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-22","text":"And verily, ye famous wise ones, ye servants of the people! Ye\r yourselves have advanced with the people’s spirit and virtue—and the\r people by you! To your honour do I say it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1110},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-23","text":"But the people ye remain for me, even with your virtues, the people with\r purblind eyes—the people who know not what SPIRIT is!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1111},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-24","text":"Spirit is life which itself cutteth into life: by its own torture doth\r it increase its own knowledge,—did ye know that before?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1112},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-25","text":"And the spirit’s happiness is this: to be anointed and consecrated with\r tears as a sacrificial victim,—did ye know that before?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1113},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-26","text":"And the blindness of the blind one, and his seeking and groping, shall\r yet testify to the power of the sun into which he hath gazed,—did ye\r know that before?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1114},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-27","text":"And with mountains shall the discerning one learn to BUILD! It is\r a small thing for the spirit to remove mountains,—did ye know that\r before?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1115},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-28","text":"Ye know only the sparks of the spirit: but ye do not see the anvil which\r it is, and the cruelty of its hammer!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1116},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-29","text":"Verily, ye know not the spirit’s pride! But still less could ye endure\r the spirit’s humility, should it ever want to speak!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1117},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-30","text":"And never yet could ye cast your spirit into a pit of snow: ye are not\r hot enough for that! Thus are ye unaware, also, of the delight of its\r coldness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1118},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-31","text":"In all respects, however, ye make too familiar with the spirit; and out\r of wisdom have ye often made an almshouse and a hospital for bad poets.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1119},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-32","text":"Ye are not eagles: thus have ye never experienced the happiness of the\r alarm of the spirit. And he who is not a bird should not camp above\r abysses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1120},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-33","text":"Ye seem to me lukewarm ones: but coldly floweth all deep knowledge.\r Ice-cold are the innermost wells of the spirit: a refreshment to hot\r hands and handlers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1121},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-34","text":"Respectable do ye there stand, and stiff, and with straight backs, ye\r famous wise ones!—no strong wind or will impelleth you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1122},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-35","text":"Have ye ne’er seen a sail crossing the sea, rounded and inflated, and\r trembling with the violence of the wind?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1123},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-36","text":"Like the sail trembling with the violence of the spirit, doth my wisdom\r cross the sea—my wild wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1124},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-50-37","text":"But ye servants of the people, ye famous wise ones—how COULD ye go with\r me!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":1125},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-1","text":"‘Tis night: now do all gushing fountains speak louder. And my soul also\r is a gushing fountain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1126},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-2","text":"‘Tis night: now only do all songs of the loving ones awake. And my soul\r also is the song of a loving one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1127},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-3","text":"Something unappeased, unappeasable, is within me; it longeth to find\r expression. A craving for love is within me, which speaketh itself the\r language of love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1128},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-4","text":"Light am I: ah, that I were night! But it is my lonesomeness to be\r begirt with light!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1129},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-5","text":"Ah, that I were dark and nightly! How would I suck at the breasts of\r light!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1130},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-6","text":"And you yourselves would I bless, ye twinkling starlets and glow-worms\r aloft!—and would rejoice in the gifts of your light.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1131},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-7","text":"But I live in mine own light, I drink again into myself the flames that\r break forth from me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1132},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-8","text":"I know not the happiness of the receiver; and oft have I dreamt that\r stealing must be more blessed than receiving.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1133},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-9","text":"It is my poverty that my hand never ceaseth bestowing; it is mine envy\r that I see waiting eyes and the brightened nights of longing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1134},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-10","text":"Oh, the misery of all bestowers! Oh, the darkening of my sun! Oh, the\r craving to crave! Oh, the violent hunger in satiety!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1135},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-11","text":"They take from me: but do I yet touch their soul? There is a gap ‘twixt\r giving and receiving; and the smallest gap hath finally to be bridged\r over.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1136},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-12","text":"A hunger ariseth out of my beauty: I should like to injure those I\r illumine; I should like to rob those I have gifted:—thus do I hunger\r for wickedness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1137},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-13","text":"Withdrawing my hand when another hand already stretcheth out to it;\r hesitating like the cascade, which hesitateth even in its leap:—thus do\r I hunger for wickedness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1138},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-14","text":"Such revenge doth mine abundance think of: such mischief welleth out of\r my lonesomeness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1139},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-15","text":"My happiness in bestowing died in bestowing; my virtue became weary of\r itself by its abundance!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1140},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-16","text":"He who ever bestoweth is in danger of losing his shame; to him who ever\r dispenseth, the hand and heart become callous by very dispensing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1141},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-17","text":"Mine eye no longer overfloweth for the shame of suppliants; my hand hath\r become too hard for the trembling of filled hands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1142},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-18","text":"Whence have gone the tears of mine eye, and the down of my heart? Oh,\r the lonesomeness of all bestowers! Oh, the silence of all shining ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1143},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-19","text":"Many suns circle in desert space: to all that is dark do they speak with\r their light—but to me they are silent.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1144},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-20","text":"Oh, this is the hostility of light to the shining one: unpityingly doth\r it pursue its course.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1145},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-21","text":"Unfair to the shining one in its innermost heart, cold to the\r suns:—thus travelleth every sun.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1146},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-22","text":"Like a storm do the suns pursue their courses: that is their travelling.\r Their inexorable will do they follow: that is their coldness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1147},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-23","text":"Oh, ye only is it, ye dark, nightly ones, that extract warmth from the\r shining ones! Oh, ye only drink milk and refreshment from the light’s\r udders!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1148},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-24","text":"Ah, there is ice around me; my hand burneth with the iciness! Ah, there\r is thirst in me; it panteth after your thirst!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1149},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-25","text":"‘Tis night: alas, that I have to be light! And thirst for the nightly!\r And lonesomeness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1150},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-26","text":"‘Tis night: now doth my longing break forth in me as a fountain,—for\r speech do I long.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1151},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-27","text":"‘Tis night: now do all gushing fountains speak louder. And my soul also\r is a gushing fountain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1152},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-51-28","text":"‘Tis night: now do all songs of loving ones awake. And my soul also is\r the song of a loving one.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":1153},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-1","text":"One evening went Zarathustra and his disciples through the forest; and\r when he sought for a well, lo, he lighted upon a green meadow peacefully\r surrounded with trees and bushes, where maidens were dancing together.\r As soon as the maidens recognised Zarathustra, they ceased dancing;\r Zarathustra, however, approached them with friendly mien and spake these\r words:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1154},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-2","text":"Cease not your dancing, ye lovely maidens! No game-spoiler hath come to\r you with evil eye, no enemy of maidens.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1155},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-3","text":"God’s advocate am I with the devil: he, however, is the spirit of\r gravity. How could I, ye light-footed ones, be hostile to divine dances?\r Or to maidens’ feet with fine ankles?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1156},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-4","text":"To be sure, I am a forest, and a night of dark trees: but he who is not\r afraid of my darkness, will find banks full of roses under my cypresses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1157},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-5","text":"And even the little God may he find, who is dearest to maidens: beside\r the well lieth he quietly, with closed eyes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1158},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-6","text":"Verily, in broad daylight did he fall asleep, the sluggard! Had he\r perhaps chased butterflies too much?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1159},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-7","text":"Upbraid me not, ye beautiful dancers, when I chasten the little God\r somewhat! He will cry, certainly, and weep—but he is laughable even\r when weeping!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1160},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-8","text":"And with tears in his eyes shall he ask you for a dance; and I myself\r will sing a song to his dance:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1161},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-9","text":"A dance-song and satire on the spirit of gravity my supremest,\r powerfulest devil, who is said to be “lord of the world.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1162},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-10","text":"And this is the song that Zarathustra sang when Cupid and the maidens\r danced together:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1163},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-11","text":"Of late did I gaze into thine eye, O Life! And into the unfathomable did\r I there seem to sink.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1164},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-12","text":"But thou pulledst me out with a golden angle; derisively didst thou\r laugh when I called thee unfathomable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1165},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-13","text":"“Such is the language of all fish,” saidst thou; “what THEY do not\r fathom is unfathomable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1166},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-14","text":"But changeable am I only, and wild, and altogether a woman, and no\r virtuous one:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1167},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-15","text":"Though I be called by you men the ‘profound one,’ or the ‘faithful one,’\r ‘the eternal one,’ ‘the mysterious one.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1168},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-16","text":"But ye men endow us always with your own virtues—alas, ye virtuous\r ones!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1169},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-17","text":"Thus did she laugh, the unbelievable one; but never do I believe her and\r her laughter, when she speaketh evil of herself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1170},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-18","text":"And when I talked face to face with my wild Wisdom, she said to me\r angrily: “Thou willest, thou cravest, thou lovest; on that account alone\r dost thou PRAISE Life!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1171},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-19","text":"Then had I almost answered indignantly and told the truth to the angry\r one; and one cannot answer more indignantly than when one “telleth the\r truth” to one’s Wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1172},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-20","text":"For thus do things stand with us three. In my heart do I love only\r Life—and verily, most when I hate her!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1173},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-21","text":"But that I am fond of Wisdom, and often too fond, is because she\r remindeth me very strongly of Life!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1174},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-22","text":"She hath her eye, her laugh, and even her golden angle-rod: am I\r responsible for it that both are so alike?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1175},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-23","text":"And when once Life asked me: “Who is she then, this Wisdom?”—then said\r I eagerly: “Ah, yes! Wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1176},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-24","text":"One thirsteth for her and is not satisfied, one looketh through veils,\r one graspeth through nets.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1177},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-25","text":"Is she beautiful? What do I know! But the oldest carps are still lured\r by her.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1178},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-26","text":"Changeable is she, and wayward; often have I seen her bite her lip, and\r pass the comb against the grain of her hair.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1179},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-27","text":"Perhaps she is wicked and false, and altogether a woman; but when she\r speaketh ill of herself, just then doth she seduce most.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1180},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-28","text":"When I had said this unto Life, then laughed she maliciously, and shut\r her eyes. “Of whom dost thou speak?” said she. “Perhaps of me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1181},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-29","text":"And if thou wert right—is it proper to say THAT in such wise to my\r face! But now, pray, speak also of thy Wisdom!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1182},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-30","text":"Ah, and now hast thou again opened thine eyes, O beloved Life! And into\r the unfathomable have I again seemed to sink.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1183},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-31","text":"Thus sang Zarathustra. But when the dance was over and the maidens had\r departed, he became sad.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1184},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-32","text":"“The sun hath been long set,” said he at last, “the meadow is damp, and\r from the forest cometh coolness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1185},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-33","text":"An unknown presence is about me, and gazeth thoughtfully. What! Thou\r livest still, Zarathustra?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1186},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-34","text":"Why? Wherefore? Whereby? Whither? Where? How? Is it not folly still to\r live?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1187},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-35","text":"Ah, my friends; the evening is it which thus interrogateth in me.\r Forgive me my sadness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1188},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-52-36","text":"Evening hath come on: forgive me that evening hath come on!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":1189},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-1","text":"“Yonder is the grave-island, the silent isle; yonder also are the graves\r of my youth. Thither will I carry an evergreen wreath of life.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1190},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-2","text":"Oh, ye sights and scenes of my youth! Oh, all ye gleams of love, ye\r divine fleeting gleams! How could ye perish so soon for me! I think of\r you to-day as my dead ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1191},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-3","text":"From you, my dearest dead ones, cometh unto me a sweet savour,\r heart-opening and melting. Verily, it convulseth and openeth the heart\r of the lone seafarer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1192},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-4","text":"Still am I the richest and most to be envied—I, the lonesomest one!\r For I HAVE POSSESSED you, and ye possess me still. Tell me: to whom hath\r there ever fallen such rosy apples from the tree as have fallen unto me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1193},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-5","text":"Still am I your love’s heir and heritage, blooming to your memory with\r many-hued, wild-growing virtues, O ye dearest ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1194},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-6","text":"Ah, we were made to remain nigh unto each other, ye kindly strange\r marvels; and not like timid birds did ye come to me and my longing—nay,\r but as trusting ones to a trusting one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1195},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-7","text":"Yea, made for faithfulness, like me, and for fond eternities, must I now\r name you by your faithlessness, ye divine glances and fleeting gleams:\r no other name have I yet learnt.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1196},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-8","text":"Verily, too early did ye die for me, ye fugitives. Yet did ye not flee\r from me, nor did I flee from you: innocent are we to each other in our\r faithlessness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1197},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-9","text":"To kill ME, did they strangle you, ye singing birds of my hopes! Yea, at\r you, ye dearest ones, did malice ever shoot its arrows—to hit my heart!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1198},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-10","text":"And they hit it! Because ye were always my dearest, my possession and my\r possessedness: ON THAT ACCOUNT had ye to die young, and far too early!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1199},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-11","text":"At my most vulnerable point did they shoot the arrow—namely, at you,\r whose skin is like down—or more like the smile that dieth at a glance!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1200},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-12","text":"But this word will I say unto mine enemies: What is all manslaughter in\r comparison with what ye have done unto me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1201},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-13","text":"Worse evil did ye do unto me than all manslaughter; the irretrievable\r did ye take from me:—thus do I speak unto you, mine enemies!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1202},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-14","text":"Slew ye not my youth’s visions and dearest marvels! My playmates took ye\r from me, the blessed spirits! To their memory do I deposit this wreath\r and this curse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1203},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-15","text":"This curse upon you, mine enemies! Have ye not made mine eternal short,\r as a tone dieth away in a cold night! Scarcely, as the twinkle of divine\r eyes, did it come to me—as a fleeting gleam!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1204},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-16","text":"Thus spake once in a happy hour my purity: “Divine shall everything be\r unto me.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1205},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-17","text":"Then did ye haunt me with foul phantoms; ah, whither hath that happy\r hour now fled!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1206},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-18","text":"“All days shall be holy unto me”—so spake once the wisdom of my youth:\r verily, the language of a joyous wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1207},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-19","text":"But then did ye enemies steal my nights, and sold them to sleepless\r torture: ah, whither hath that joyous wisdom now fled?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1208},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-20","text":"Once did I long for happy auspices: then did ye lead an owl-monster\r across my path, an adverse sign. Ah, whither did my tender longing then\r flee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1209},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-21","text":"All loathing did I once vow to renounce: then did ye change my nigh ones\r and nearest ones into ulcerations. Ah, whither did my noblest vow then\r flee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1210},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-22","text":"As a blind one did I once walk in blessed ways: then did ye cast\r filth on the blind one’s course: and now is he disgusted with the old\r footpath.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1211},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-23","text":"And when I performed my hardest task, and celebrated the triumph of\r my victories, then did ye make those who loved me call out that I then\r grieved them most.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1212},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-24","text":"Verily, it was always your doing: ye embittered to me my best honey, and\r the diligence of my best bees.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1213},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-25","text":"To my charity have ye ever sent the most impudent beggars; around my\r sympathy have ye ever crowded the incurably shameless. Thus have ye\r wounded the faith of my virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1214},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-26","text":"And when I offered my holiest as a sacrifice, immediately did your\r “piety” put its fatter gifts beside it: so that my holiest suffocated in\r the fumes of your fat.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1215},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-27","text":"And once did I want to dance as I had never yet danced: beyond all\r heavens did I want to dance. Then did ye seduce my favourite minstrel.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1216},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-28","text":"And now hath he struck up an awful, melancholy air; alas, he tooted as a\r mournful horn to mine ear!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1217},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-29","text":"Murderous minstrel, instrument of evil, most innocent instrument!\r Already did I stand prepared for the best dance: then didst thou slay my\r rapture with thy tones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1218},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-30","text":"Only in the dance do I know how to speak the parable of the highest\r things:—and now hath my grandest parable remained unspoken in my limbs!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1219},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-31","text":"Unspoken and unrealised hath my highest hope remained! And there have\r perished for me all the visions and consolations of my youth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1220},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-32","text":"How did I ever bear it? How did I survive and surmount such wounds? How\r did my soul rise again out of those sepulchres?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1221},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-33","text":"Yea, something invulnerable, unburiable is with me, something that would\r rend rocks asunder: it is called MY WILL. Silently doth it proceed, and\r unchanged throughout the years.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1222},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-34","text":"Its course will it go upon my feet, mine old Will; hard of heart is its\r nature and invulnerable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1223},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-35","text":"Invulnerable am I only in my heel. Ever livest thou there, and art like\r thyself, thou most patient one! Ever hast thou burst all shackles of the\r tomb!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1224},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-36","text":"In thee still liveth also the unrealisedness of my youth; and as life\r and youth sittest thou here hopeful on the yellow ruins of graves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1225},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-53-37","text":"Yea, thou art still for me the demolisher of all graves: Hail to thee,\r my Will! And only where there are graves are there resurrections.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":1226},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-1","text":"“Will to Truth” do ye call it, ye wisest ones, that which impelleth you\r and maketh you ardent?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1227},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-2","text":"Will for the thinkableness of all being: thus do _I_ call your will!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1228},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-3","text":"All being would ye MAKE thinkable: for ye doubt with good reason whether\r it be already thinkable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1229},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-4","text":"But it shall accommodate and bend itself to you! So willeth your will.\r Smooth shall it become and subject to the spirit, as its mirror and\r reflection.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1230},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-5","text":"That is your entire will, ye wisest ones, as a Will to Power; and even\r when ye speak of good and evil, and of estimates of value.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1231},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-6","text":"Ye would still create a world before which ye can bow the knee: such is\r your ultimate hope and ecstasy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1232},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-7","text":"The ignorant, to be sure, the people—they are like a river on which a\r boat floateth along: and in the boat sit the estimates of value, solemn\r and disguised.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1233},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-8","text":"Your will and your valuations have ye put on the river of becoming; it\r betrayeth unto me an old Will to Power, what is believed by the people\r as good and evil.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1234},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-9","text":"It was ye, ye wisest ones, who put such guests in this boat, and gave\r them pomp and proud names—ye and your ruling Will!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1235},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-10","text":"Onward the river now carrieth your boat: it MUST carry it. A small\r matter if the rough wave foameth and angrily resisteth its keel!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1236},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-11","text":"It is not the river that is your danger and the end of your good and\r evil, ye wisest ones: but that Will itself, the Will to Power—the\r unexhausted, procreating life-will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1237},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-12","text":"But that ye may understand my gospel of good and evil, for that purpose\r will I tell you my gospel of life, and of the nature of all living\r things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1238},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-13","text":"The living thing did I follow; I walked in the broadest and narrowest\r paths to learn its nature.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1239},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-14","text":"With a hundred-faced mirror did I catch its glance when its mouth was\r shut, so that its eye might speak unto me. And its eye spake unto me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1240},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-15","text":"But wherever I found living things, there heard I also the language of\r obedience. All living things are obeying things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1241},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-16","text":"And this heard I secondly: Whatever cannot obey itself, is commanded.\r Such is the nature of living things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1242},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-17","text":"This, however, is the third thing which I heard—namely, that commanding\r is more difficult than obeying. And not only because the commander\r beareth the burden of all obeyers, and because this burden readily\r crusheth him:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1243},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-18","text":"An attempt and a risk seemed all commanding unto me; and whenever it\r commandeth, the living thing risketh itself thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1244},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-19","text":"Yea, even when it commandeth itself, then also must it atone for its\r commanding. Of its own law must it become the judge and avenger and\r victim.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1245},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-20","text":"How doth this happen! so did I ask myself. What persuadeth the living\r thing to obey, and command, and even be obedient in commanding?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1246},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-21","text":"Hearken now unto my word, ye wisest ones! Test it seriously, whether\r I have crept into the heart of life itself, and into the roots of its\r heart!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1247},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-22","text":"Wherever I found a living thing, there found I Will to Power; and even\r in the will of the servant found I the will to be master.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1248},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-23","text":"That to the stronger the weaker shall serve—thereto persuadeth he his\r will who would be master over a still weaker one. That delight alone he\r is unwilling to forego.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1249},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-24","text":"And as the lesser surrendereth himself to the greater that he may have\r delight and power over the least of all, so doth even the greatest\r surrender himself, and staketh—life, for the sake of power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1250},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-25","text":"It is the surrender of the greatest to run risk and danger, and play\r dice for death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1251},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-26","text":"And where there is sacrifice and service and love-glances, there also\r is the will to be master. By by-ways doth the weaker then slink into\r the fortress, and into the heart of the mightier one—and there stealeth\r power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1252},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-27","text":"And this secret spake Life herself unto me. “Behold,” said she, “I am\r that WHICH MUST EVER SURPASS ITSELF.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1253},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-28","text":"To be sure, ye call it will to procreation, or impulse towards a goal,\r towards the higher, remoter, more manifold: but all that is one and the\r same secret.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1254},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-29","text":"Rather would I succumb than disown this one thing; and verily, where\r there is succumbing and leaf-falling, lo, there doth Life sacrifice\r itself—for power!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1255},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-30","text":"That I have to be struggle, and becoming, and purpose, and\r cross-purpose—ah, he who divineth my will, divineth well also on what\r CROOKED paths it hath to tread!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1256},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-31","text":"Whatever I create, and however much I love it,—soon must I be adverse\r to it, and to my love: so willeth my will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1257},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-32","text":"And even thou, discerning one, art only a path and footstep of my will:\r verily, my Will to Power walketh even on the feet of thy Will to Truth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1258},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-33","text":"He certainly did not hit the truth who shot at it the formula: ‘Will to\r existence’: that will—doth not exist!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1259},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-34","text":"For what is not, cannot will; that, however, which is in existence—how\r could it still strive for existence!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1260},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-35","text":"Only where there is life, is there also will: not, however, Will to\r Life, but—so teach I thee—Will to Power!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1261},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-36","text":"Much is reckoned higher than life itself by the living one; but out of\r the very reckoning speaketh—the Will to Power!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1262},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-37","text":"Thus did Life once teach me: and thereby, ye wisest ones, do I solve you\r the riddle of your hearts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1263},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-38","text":"Verily, I say unto you: good and evil which would be everlasting—it\r doth not exist! Of its own accord must it ever surpass itself anew.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1264},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-39","text":"With your values and formulae of good and evil, ye exercise power,\r ye valuing ones: and that is your secret love, and the sparkling,\r trembling, and overflowing of your souls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1265},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-40","text":"But a stronger power groweth out of your values, and a new surpassing:\r by it breaketh egg and egg-shell.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1266},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-41","text":"And he who hath to be a creator in good and evil—verily, he hath first\r to be a destroyer, and break values in pieces.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1267},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-42","text":"Thus doth the greatest evil pertain to the greatest good: that, however,\r is the creating good.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1268},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-43","text":"Let us SPEAK thereof, ye wisest ones, even though it be bad. To be\r silent is worse; all suppressed truths become poisonous.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1269},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-54-44","text":"And let everything break up which—can break up by our truths! Many a\r house is still to be built!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":1270},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-1","text":"Calm is the bottom of my sea: who would guess that it hideth droll\r monsters!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1271},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-2","text":"Unmoved is my depth: but it sparkleth with swimming enigmas and\r laughters.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1272},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-3","text":"A sublime one saw I to-day, a solemn one, a penitent of the spirit: Oh,\r how my soul laughed at his ugliness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1273},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-4","text":"With upraised breast, and like those who draw in their breath: thus did\r he stand, the sublime one, and in silence:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1274},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-5","text":"O’erhung with ugly truths, the spoil of his hunting, and rich in torn\r raiment; many thorns also hung on him—but I saw no rose.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1275},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-6","text":"Not yet had he learned laughing and beauty. Gloomy did this hunter\r return from the forest of knowledge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1276},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-7","text":"From the fight with wild beasts returned he home: but even yet a wild\r beast gazeth out of his seriousness—an unconquered wild beast!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1277},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-8","text":"As a tiger doth he ever stand, on the point of springing; but I do not\r like those strained souls; ungracious is my taste towards all those\r self-engrossed ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1278},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-9","text":"And ye tell me, friends, that there is to be no dispute about taste and\r tasting? But all life is a dispute about taste and tasting!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1279},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-10","text":"Taste: that is weight at the same time, and scales and weigher; and alas\r for every living thing that would live without dispute about weight and\r scales and weigher!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1280},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-11","text":"Should he become weary of his sublimeness, this sublime one, then only\r will his beauty begin—and then only will I taste him and find him\r savoury.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1281},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-12","text":"And only when he turneth away from himself will he o’erleap his own\r shadow—and verily! into HIS sun.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1282},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-13","text":"Far too long did he sit in the shade; the cheeks of the penitent of the\r spirit became pale; he almost starved on his expectations.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1283},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-14","text":"Contempt is still in his eye, and loathing hideth in his mouth. To be\r sure, he now resteth, but he hath not yet taken rest in the sunshine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1284},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-15","text":"As the ox ought he to do; and his happiness should smell of the earth,\r and not of contempt for the earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1285},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-16","text":"As a white ox would I like to see him, which, snorting and lowing,\r walketh before the ploughshare: and his lowing should also laud all\r that is earthly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1286},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-17","text":"Dark is still his countenance; the shadow of his hand danceth upon it.\r O’ershadowed is still the sense of his eye.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1287},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-18","text":"His deed itself is still the shadow upon him: his doing obscureth the\r doer. Not yet hath he overcome his deed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1288},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-19","text":"To be sure, I love in him the shoulders of the ox: but now do I want to\r see also the eye of the angel.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1289},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-20","text":"Also his hero-will hath he still to unlearn: an exalted one shall he\r be, and not only a sublime one:—the ether itself should raise him, the\r will-less one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1290},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-21","text":"He hath subdued monsters, he hath solved enigmas. But he should also\r redeem his monsters and enigmas; into heavenly children should he\r transform them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1291},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-22","text":"As yet hath his knowledge not learned to smile, and to be without\r jealousy; as yet hath his gushing passion not become calm in beauty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1292},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-23","text":"Verily, not in satiety shall his longing cease and disappear, but in\r beauty! Gracefulness belongeth to the munificence of the magnanimous.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1293},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-24","text":"His arm across his head: thus should the hero repose; thus should he\r also surmount his repose.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1294},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-25","text":"But precisely to the hero is BEAUTY the hardest thing of all.\r Unattainable is beauty by all ardent wills.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1295},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-26","text":"A little more, a little less: precisely this is much here, it is the\r most here.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1296},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-27","text":"To stand with relaxed muscles and with unharnessed will: that is the\r hardest for all of you, ye sublime ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1297},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-28","text":"When power becometh gracious and descendeth into the visible—I call\r such condescension, beauty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1298},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-29","text":"And from no one do I want beauty so much as from thee, thou powerful\r one: let thy goodness be thy last self-conquest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1299},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-30","text":"All evil do I accredit to thee: therefore do I desire of thee the good.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1300},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-31","text":"Verily, I have often laughed at the weaklings, who think themselves good\r because they have crippled paws!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1301},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-32","text":"The virtue of the pillar shalt thou strive after: more beautiful doth\r it ever become, and more graceful—but internally harder and more\r sustaining—the higher it riseth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1302},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-33","text":"Yea, thou sublime one, one day shalt thou also be beautiful, and hold up\r the mirror to thine own beauty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1303},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-34","text":"Then will thy soul thrill with divine desires; and there will be\r adoration even in thy vanity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1304},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-55-35","text":"For this is the secret of the soul: when the hero hath abandoned it,\r then only approacheth it in dreams—the superhero.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":1305},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-1","text":"And when I looked around me, lo! there time was my sole contemporary.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1306},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-2","text":"Then did I fly backwards, homewards—and always faster. Thus did I come\r unto you, ye present-day men, and into the land of culture.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1307},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-3","text":"For the first time brought I an eye to see you, and good desire: verily,\r with longing in my heart did I come.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1308},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-4","text":"But how did it turn out with me? Although so alarmed—I had yet to\r laugh! Never did mine eye see anything so motley-coloured!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1309},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-5","text":"I laughed and laughed, while my foot still trembled, and my heart as\r well. “Here forsooth, is the home of all the paintpots,”—said I.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1310},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-6","text":"With fifty patches painted on faces and limbs—so sat ye there to mine\r astonishment, ye present-day men!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1311},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-7","text":"And with fifty mirrors around you, which flattered your play of colours,\r and repeated it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1312},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-8","text":"Verily, ye could wear no better masks, ye present-day men, than your own\r faces! Who could—RECOGNISE you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1313},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-9","text":"Written all over with the characters of the past, and these characters\r also pencilled over with new characters—thus have ye concealed\r yourselves well from all decipherers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1314},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-10","text":"And though one be a trier of the reins, who still believeth that ye have\r reins! Out of colours ye seem to be baked, and out of glued scraps.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1315},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-11","text":"All times and peoples gaze divers-coloured out of your veils; all\r customs and beliefs speak divers-coloured out of your gestures.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1316},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-12","text":"He who would strip you of veils and wrappers, and paints and gestures,\r would just have enough left to scare the crows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1317},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-13","text":"Verily, I myself am the scared crow that once saw you naked, and without\r paint; and I flew away when the skeleton ogled at me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1318},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-14","text":"Rather would I be a day-labourer in the nether-world, and among the\r shades of the bygone!—Fatter and fuller than ye, are forsooth the\r nether-worldlings!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1319},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-15","text":"This, yea this, is bitterness to my bowels, that I can neither endure\r you naked nor clothed, ye present-day men!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1320},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-16","text":"All that is unhomelike in the future, and whatever maketh strayed birds\r shiver, is verily more homelike and familiar than your “reality.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1321},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-17","text":"For thus speak ye: “Real are we wholly, and without faith and\r superstition”: thus do ye plume yourselves—alas! even without plumes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1322},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-18","text":"Indeed, how would ye be ABLE to believe, ye divers-coloured ones!—ye\r who are pictures of all that hath ever been believed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1323},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-19","text":"Perambulating refutations are ye, of belief itself, and a dislocation of\r all thought. UNTRUSTWORTHY ONES: thus do _I_ call you, ye real ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1324},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-20","text":"All periods prate against one another in your spirits; and the dreams\r and pratings of all periods were even realer than your awakeness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1325},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-21","text":"Unfruitful are ye: THEREFORE do ye lack belief. But he who had to\r create, had always his presaging dreams and astral premonitions—and\r believed in believing!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1326},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-22","text":"Half-open doors are ye, at which grave-diggers wait. And this is YOUR\r reality: “Everything deserveth to perish.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1327},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-23","text":"Alas, how ye stand there before me, ye unfruitful ones; how lean your\r ribs! And many of you surely have had knowledge thereof.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1328},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-24","text":"Many a one hath said: “There hath surely a God filched something from\r me secretly whilst I slept? Verily, enough to make a girl for himself\r therefrom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1329},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-25","text":"“Amazing is the poverty of my ribs!” thus hath spoken many a present-day\r man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1330},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-26","text":"Yea, ye are laughable unto me, ye present-day men! And especially when\r ye marvel at yourselves!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1331},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-27","text":"And woe unto me if I could not laugh at your marvelling, and had to\r swallow all that is repugnant in your platters!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1332},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-28","text":"As it is, however, I will make lighter of you, since I have to carry\r _what is heavy;_ and what matter if beetles and May-bugs also alight on\r my load!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1333},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-29","text":"Verily, it shall not on that account become heavier to me! And not from\r you, ye present-day men, shall my great weariness arise.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1334},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-30","text":"Ah, whither shall I now ascend with my longing! From all mountains do I\r look out for fatherlands and motherlands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1335},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-31","text":"But a home have I found nowhere: unsettled am I in all cities, and\r decamping at all gates.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1336},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-32","text":"Alien to me, and a mockery, are the present-day men, to whom of late my\r heart impelled me; and exiled am I from fatherlands and motherlands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1337},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-33","text":"Thus do I love only my CHILDREN’S LAND, the undiscovered in the remotest\r sea: for it do I bid my sails search and search.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1338},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-56-34","text":"Unto my children will I make amends for being the child of my fathers:\r and unto all the future—for THIS present-day!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":1339},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-1","text":"When yester-eve the moon arose, then did I fancy it about to bear a sun:\r so broad and teeming did it lie on the horizon.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1340},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-2","text":"But it was a liar with its pregnancy; and sooner will I believe in the\r man in the moon than in the woman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1341},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-3","text":"To be sure, little of a man is he also, that timid night-reveller.\r Verily, with a bad conscience doth he stalk over the roofs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1342},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-4","text":"For he is covetous and jealous, the monk in the moon; covetous of the\r earth, and all the joys of lovers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1343},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-5","text":"Nay, I like him not, that tom-cat on the roofs! Hateful unto me are all\r that slink around half-closed windows!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1344},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-6","text":"Piously and silently doth he stalk along on the star-carpets:—but I\r like no light-treading human feet, on which not even a spur jingleth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1345},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-7","text":"Every honest one’s step speaketh; the cat however, stealeth along over\r the ground. Lo! cat-like doth the moon come along, and dishonestly.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1346},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-8","text":"This parable speak I unto you sentimental dissemblers, unto you, the\r “pure discerners!” You do _I_ call—covetous ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1347},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-9","text":"Also ye love the earth, and the earthly: I have divined you well!—but\r shame is in your love, and a bad conscience—ye are like the moon!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1348},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-10","text":"To despise the earthly hath your spirit been persuaded, but not your\r bowels: these, however, are the strongest in you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1349},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-11","text":"And now is your spirit ashamed to be at the service of your bowels, and\r goeth by-ways and lying ways to escape its own shame.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1350},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-12","text":"“That would be the highest thing for me”—so saith your lying spirit\r unto itself—“to gaze upon life without desire, and not like the dog,\r with hanging-out tongue:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1351},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-13","text":"To be happy in gazing: with dead will, free from the grip and greed\r of selfishness—cold and ashy-grey all over, but with intoxicated\r moon-eyes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1352},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-14","text":"That would be the dearest thing to me”—thus doth the seduced one seduce\r himself,—“to love the earth as the moon loveth it, and with the eye\r only to feel its beauty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1353},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-15","text":"And this do I call IMMACULATE perception of all things: to want nothing\r else from them, but to be allowed to lie before them as a mirror with a\r hundred facets.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1354},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-16","text":"Oh, ye sentimental dissemblers, ye covetous ones! Ye lack innocence in\r your desire: and now do ye defame desiring on that account!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1355},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-17","text":"Verily, not as creators, as procreators, or as jubilators do ye love the\r earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1356},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-18","text":"Where is innocence? Where there is will to procreation. And he who\r seeketh to create beyond himself, hath for me the purest will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1357},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-19","text":"Where is beauty? Where I MUST WILL with my whole Will; where I will love\r and perish, that an image may not remain merely an image.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1358},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-20","text":"Loving and perishing: these have rhymed from eternity. Will to love:\r that is to be ready also for death. Thus do I speak unto you cowards!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1359},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-21","text":"But now doth your emasculated ogling profess to be “contemplation!”\r  And that which can be examined with cowardly eyes is to be christened\r “beautiful!” Oh, ye violators of noble names!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1360},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-22","text":"But it shall be your curse, ye immaculate ones, ye pure discerners, that\r ye shall never bring forth, even though ye lie broad and teeming on the\r horizon!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1361},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-23","text":"Verily, ye fill your mouth with noble words: and we are to believe that\r your heart overfloweth, ye cozeners?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1362},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-24","text":"But MY words are poor, contemptible, stammering words: gladly do I pick\r up what falleth from the table at your repasts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1363},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-25","text":"Yet still can I say therewith the truth—to dissemblers! Yea, my\r fish-bones, shells, and prickly leaves shall—tickle the noses of\r dissemblers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1364},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-26","text":"Bad air is always about you and your repasts: your lascivious thoughts,\r your lies, and secrets are indeed in the air!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1365},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-27","text":"Dare only to believe in yourselves—in yourselves and in your inward\r parts! He who doth not believe in himself always lieth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1366},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-28","text":"A God’s mask have ye hung in front of you, ye “pure ones”: into a God’s\r mask hath your execrable coiling snake crawled.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1367},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-29","text":"Verily ye deceive, ye “contemplative ones!” Even Zarathustra was once\r the dupe of your godlike exterior; he did not divine the serpent’s coil\r with which it was stuffed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1368},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-30","text":"A God’s soul, I once thought I saw playing in your games, ye pure\r discerners! No better arts did I once dream of than your arts!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1369},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-31","text":"Serpents’ filth and evil odour, the distance concealed from me: and that\r a lizard’s craft prowled thereabouts lasciviously.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1370},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-32","text":"But I came NIGH unto you: then came to me the day,—and now cometh it to\r you,—at an end is the moon’s love affair!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1371},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-33","text":"See there! Surprised and pale doth it stand—before the rosy dawn!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1372},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-34","text":"For already she cometh, the glowing one,—HER love to the earth cometh!\r Innocence and creative desire, is all solar love!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1373},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-35","text":"See there, how she cometh impatiently over the sea! Do ye not feel the\r thirst and the hot breath of her love?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1374},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-36","text":"At the sea would she suck, and drink its depths to her height: now\r riseth the desire of the sea with its thousand breasts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1375},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-37","text":"Kissed and sucked WOULD it be by the thirst of the sun; vapour WOULD it\r become, and height, and path of light, and light itself!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1376},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-57-38","text":"And this meaneth TO ME knowledge: all that is deep shall ascend—to my\r height!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":1377},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-1","text":"When I lay asleep, then did a sheep eat at the ivy-wreath on my\r head,—it ate, and said thereby: “Zarathustra is no longer a scholar.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1378},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-2","text":"It said this, and went away clumsily and proudly. A child told it to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1379},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-3","text":"I like to lie here where the children play, beside the ruined wall,\r among thistles and red poppies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1380},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-4","text":"A scholar am I still to the children, and also to the thistles and red\r poppies. Innocent are they, even in their wickedness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1381},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-5","text":"But to the sheep I am no longer a scholar: so willeth my lot—blessings\r upon it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1382},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-6","text":"For this is the truth: I have departed from the house of the scholars,\r and the door have I also slammed behind me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1383},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-7","text":"Too long did my soul sit hungry at their table: not like them have I got\r the knack of investigating, as the knack of nut-cracking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1384},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-8","text":"Freedom do I love, and the air over fresh soil; rather would I sleep on\r ox-skins than on their honours and dignities.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1385},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-9","text":"I am too hot and scorched with mine own thought: often is it ready to\r take away my breath. Then have I to go into the open air, and away from\r all dusty rooms.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1386},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-10","text":"But they sit cool in the cool shade: they want in everything to be\r merely spectators, and they avoid sitting where the sun burneth on the\r steps.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1387},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-11","text":"Like those who stand in the street and gape at the passers-by: thus do\r they also wait, and gape at the thoughts which others have thought.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1388},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-12","text":"Should one lay hold of them, then do they raise a dust like flour-sacks,\r and involuntarily: but who would divine that their dust came from corn,\r and from the yellow delight of the summer fields?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1389},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-13","text":"When they give themselves out as wise, then do their petty sayings and\r truths chill me: in their wisdom there is often an odour as if it came\r from the swamp; and verily, I have even heard the frog croak in it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1390},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-14","text":"Clever are they—they have dexterous fingers: what doth MY simplicity\r pretend to beside their multiplicity! All threading and knitting and\r weaving do their fingers understand: thus do they make the hose of the\r spirit!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1391},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-15","text":"Good clockworks are they: only be careful to wind them up properly!\r Then do they indicate the hour without mistake, and make a modest noise\r thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1392},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-16","text":"Like millstones do they work, and like pestles: throw only seed-corn\r unto them!—they know well how to grind corn small, and make white dust\r out of it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1393},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-17","text":"They keep a sharp eye on one another, and do not trust each other the\r best. Ingenious in little artifices, they wait for those whose knowledge\r walketh on lame feet,—like spiders do they wait.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1394},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-18","text":"I saw them always prepare their poison with precaution; and always did\r they put glass gloves on their fingers in doing so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1395},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-19","text":"They also know how to play with false dice; and so eagerly did I find\r them playing, that they perspired thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1396},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-20","text":"We are alien to each other, and their virtues are even more repugnant to\r my taste than their falsehoods and false dice.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1397},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-21","text":"And when I lived with them, then did I live above them. Therefore did\r they take a dislike to me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1398},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-22","text":"They want to hear nothing of any one walking above their heads; and so\r they put wood and earth and rubbish betwixt me and their heads.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1399},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-23","text":"Thus did they deafen the sound of my tread: and least have I hitherto\r been heard by the most learned.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1400},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-24","text":"All mankind’s faults and weaknesses did they put betwixt themselves and\r me:—they call it “false ceiling” in their houses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1401},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-25","text":"But nevertheless I walk with my thoughts ABOVE their heads; and even\r should I walk on mine own errors, still would I be above them and their\r heads.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1402},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-58-26","text":"For men are NOT equal: so speaketh justice. And what I will, THEY may\r not will!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":1403},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-1","text":"“Since I have known the body better”—said Zarathustra to one of his\r disciples—“the spirit hath only been to me symbolically spirit; and all\r the ‘imperishable’—that is also but a simile.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1404},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-2","text":"“So have I heard thee say once before,” answered the disciple, “and then\r thou addedst: ‘But the poets lie too much.’ Why didst thou say that the\r poets lie too much?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1405},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-3","text":"“Why?” said Zarathustra. “Thou askest why? I do not belong to those who\r may be asked after their Why.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1406},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-4","text":"Is my experience but of yesterday? It is long ago that I experienced the\r reasons for mine opinions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1407},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-5","text":"Should I not have to be a cask of memory, if I also wanted to have my\r reasons with me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1408},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-6","text":"It is already too much for me even to retain mine opinions; and many a\r bird flieth away.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1409},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-7","text":"And sometimes, also, do I find a fugitive creature in my dovecote, which\r is alien to me, and trembleth when I lay my hand upon it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1410},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-8","text":"But what did Zarathustra once say unto thee? That the poets lie too\r much?—But Zarathustra also is a poet.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1411},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-9","text":"Believest thou that he there spake the truth? Why dost thou believe it?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1412},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-10","text":"The disciple answered: “I believe in Zarathustra.” But Zarathustra shook\r his head and smiled.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1413},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-11","text":"Belief doth not sanctify me, said he, least of all the belief in myself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1414},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-12","text":"But granting that some one did say in all seriousness that the poets lie\r too much: he was right—WE do lie too much.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1415},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-13","text":"We also know too little, and are bad learners: so we are obliged to lie.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1416},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-14","text":"And which of us poets hath not adulterated his wine? Many a poisonous\r hotchpotch hath evolved in our cellars: many an indescribable thing hath\r there been done.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1417},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-15","text":"And because we know little, therefore are we pleased from the heart with\r the poor in spirit, especially when they are young women!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1418},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-16","text":"And even of those things are we desirous, which old women tell one\r another in the evening. This do we call the eternally feminine in us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1419},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-17","text":"And as if there were a special secret access to knowledge, which CHOKETH\r UP for those who learn anything, so do we believe in the people and in\r their “wisdom.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1420},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-18","text":"This, however, do all poets believe: that whoever pricketh up his ears\r when lying in the grass or on lonely slopes, learneth something of the\r things that are betwixt heaven and earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1421},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-19","text":"And if there come unto them tender emotions, then do the poets always\r think that nature herself is in love with them:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1422},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-20","text":"And that she stealeth to their ear to whisper secrets into it, and\r amorous flatteries: of this do they plume and pride themselves, before\r all mortals!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1423},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-21","text":"Ah, there are so many things betwixt heaven and earth of which only the\r poets have dreamed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1424},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-22","text":"And especially ABOVE the heavens: for all Gods are poet-symbolisations,\r poet-sophistications!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1425},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-23","text":"Verily, ever are we drawn aloft—that is, to the realm of the clouds:\r on these do we set our gaudy puppets, and then call them Gods and\r Supermen:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1426},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-24","text":"Are not they light enough for those chairs!—all these Gods and\r Supermen?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1427},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-25","text":"Ah, how I am weary of all the inadequate that is insisted on as actual!\r Ah, how I am weary of the poets!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1428},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-26","text":"When Zarathustra so spake, his disciple resented it, but was silent. And\r Zarathustra also was silent; and his eye directed itself inwardly, as if\r it gazed into the far distance. At last he sighed and drew breath.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1429},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-27","text":"I am of to-day and heretofore, said he thereupon; but something is in me\r that is of the morrow, and the day following, and the hereafter.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1430},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-28","text":"I became weary of the poets, of the old and of the new: superficial are\r they all unto me, and shallow seas.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1431},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-29","text":"They did not think sufficiently into the depth; therefore their feeling\r did not reach to the bottom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1432},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-30","text":"Some sensation of voluptuousness and some sensation of tedium: these\r have as yet been their best contemplation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1433},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-31","text":"Ghost-breathing and ghost-whisking, seemeth to me all the\r jingle-jangling of their harps; what have they known hitherto of the\r fervour of tones!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1434},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-32","text":"They are also not pure enough for me: they all muddle their water that\r it may seem deep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1435},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-33","text":"And fain would they thereby prove themselves reconcilers: but mediaries\r and mixers are they unto me, and half-and-half, and impure!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1436},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-34","text":"Ah, I cast indeed my net into their sea, and meant to catch good fish;\r but always did I draw up the head of some ancient God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1437},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-35","text":"Thus did the sea give a stone to the hungry one. And they themselves may\r well originate from the sea.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1438},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-36","text":"Certainly, one findeth pearls in them: thereby they are the more like\r hard molluscs. And instead of a soul, I have often found in them salt\r slime.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1439},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-37","text":"They have learned from the sea also its vanity: is not the sea the\r peacock of peacocks?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1440},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-38","text":"Even before the ugliest of all buffaloes doth it spread out its tail;\r never doth it tire of its lace-fan of silver and silk.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1441},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-39","text":"Disdainfully doth the buffalo glance thereat, nigh to the sand with its\r soul, nigher still to the thicket, nighest, however, to the swamp.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1442},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-40","text":"What is beauty and sea and peacock-splendour to it! This parable I speak\r unto the poets.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1443},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-41","text":"Verily, their spirit itself is the peacock of peacocks, and a sea of\r vanity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1444},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-42","text":"Spectators, seeketh the spirit of the poet—should they even be\r buffaloes!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1445},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-43","text":"But of this spirit became I weary; and I see the time coming when it\r will become weary of itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1446},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-44","text":"Yea, changed have I seen the poets, and their glance turned towards\r themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1447},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-59-45","text":"Penitents of the spirit have I seen appearing; they grew out of the\r poets.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":1448},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-1","text":"There is an isle in the sea—not far from the Happy Isles of\r Zarathustra—on which a volcano ever smoketh; of which isle the people,\r and especially the old women amongst them, say that it is placed as a\r rock before the gate of the nether-world; but that through the volcano\r itself the narrow way leadeth downwards which conducteth to this gate.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1449},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-2","text":"Now about the time that Zarathustra sojourned on the Happy Isles, it\r happened that a ship anchored at the isle on which standeth the smoking\r mountain, and the crew went ashore to shoot rabbits. About the noontide\r hour, however, when the captain and his men were together again, they\r saw suddenly a man coming towards them through the air, and a voice said\r distinctly: “It is time! It is the highest time!” But when the figure\r was nearest to them (it flew past quickly, however, like a shadow, in\r the direction of the volcano), then did they recognise with the greatest\r surprise that it was Zarathustra; for they had all seen him before\r except the captain himself, and they loved him as the p","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1450},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-3","text":"“Behold!” said the old helmsman, “there goeth Zarathustra to hell!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1451},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-4","text":"About the same time that these sailors landed on the fire-isle, there\r was a rumour that Zarathustra had disappeared; and when his friends were\r asked about it, they said that he had gone on board a ship by night,\r without saying whither he was going.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1452},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-5","text":"Thus there arose some uneasiness. After three days, however, there came\r the story of the ship’s crew in addition to this uneasiness—and\r then did all the people say that the devil had taken Zarathustra. His\r disciples laughed, sure enough, at this talk; and one of them said even:\r “Sooner would I believe that Zarathustra hath taken the devil.” But at\r the bottom of their hearts they were all full of anxiety and longing: so\r their joy was great when on the fifth day Zarathustra appeared amongst\r them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1453},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-6","text":"And this is the account of Zarathustra’s interview with the fire-dog:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1454},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-7","text":"The earth, said he, hath a skin; and this skin hath diseases. One of\r these diseases, for example, is called “man.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1455},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-8","text":"And another of these diseases is called “the fire-dog”: concerning HIM\r men have greatly deceived themselves, and let themselves be deceived.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1456},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-9","text":"To fathom this mystery did I go o’er the sea; and I have seen the truth\r naked, verily! barefooted up to the neck.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1457},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-10","text":"Now do I know how it is concerning the fire-dog; and likewise concerning\r all the spouting and subversive devils, of which not only old women are\r afraid.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1458},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-11","text":"“Up with thee, fire-dog, out of thy depth!” cried I, “and confess how\r deep that depth is! Whence cometh that which thou snortest up?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1459},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-12","text":"Thou drinkest copiously at the sea: that doth thine embittered eloquence\r betray! In sooth, for a dog of the depth, thou takest thy nourishment\r too much from the surface!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1460},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-13","text":"At the most, I regard thee as the ventriloquist of the earth: and ever,\r when I have heard subversive and spouting devils speak, I have found\r them like thee: embittered, mendacious, and shallow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1461},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-14","text":"Ye understand how to roar and obscure with ashes! Ye are the best\r braggarts, and have sufficiently learned the art of making dregs boil.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1462},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-15","text":"Where ye are, there must always be dregs at hand, and much that is\r spongy, hollow, and compressed: it wanteth to have freedom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1463},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-16","text":"‘Freedom’ ye all roar most eagerly: but I have unlearned the belief in\r ‘great events,’ when there is much roaring and smoke about them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1464},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-17","text":"And believe me, friend Hullabaloo! The greatest events—are not our\r noisiest, but our stillest hours.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1465},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-18","text":"Not around the inventors of new noise, but around the inventors of new\r values, doth the world revolve; INAUDIBLY it revolveth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1466},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-19","text":"And just own to it! Little had ever taken place when thy noise and smoke\r passed away. What, if a city did become a mummy, and a statue lay in the\r mud!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1467},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-20","text":"And this do I say also to the o’erthrowers of statues: It is certainly\r the greatest folly to throw salt into the sea, and statues into the mud.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1468},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-21","text":"In the mud of your contempt lay the statue: but it is just its law, that\r out of contempt, its life and living beauty grow again!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1469},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-22","text":"With diviner features doth it now arise, seducing by its suffering; and\r verily! it will yet thank you for o’erthrowing it, ye subverters!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1470},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-23","text":"This counsel, however, do I counsel to kings and churches, and to all\r that is weak with age or virtue—let yourselves be o’erthrown! That ye\r may again come to life, and that virtue—may come to you!—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1471},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-24","text":"Thus spake I before the fire-dog: then did he interrupt me sullenly, and\r asked: “Church? What is that?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1472},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-25","text":"“Church?” answered I, “that is a kind of state, and indeed the most\r mendacious. But remain quiet, thou dissembling dog! Thou surely knowest\r thine own species best!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1473},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-26","text":"Like thyself the state is a dissembling dog; like thee doth it like\r to speak with smoke and roaring—to make believe, like thee, that it\r speaketh out of the heart of things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1474},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-27","text":"For it seeketh by all means to be the most important creature on earth,\r the state; and people think it so.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1475},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-28","text":"When I had said this, the fire-dog acted as if mad with envy. “What!”\r  cried he, “the most important creature on earth? And people think it\r so?” And so much vapour and terrible voices came out of his throat, that\r I thought he would choke with vexation and envy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1476},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-29","text":"At last he became calmer and his panting subsided; as soon, however, as\r he was quiet, I said laughingly:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1477},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-30","text":"And that I may also maintain the right, hear the story of another\r fire-dog; he speaketh actually out of the heart of the earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1478},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-31","text":"Gold doth his breath exhale, and golden rain: so doth his heart desire.\r What are ashes and smoke and hot dregs to him!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1479},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-32","text":"Laughter flitteth from him like a variegated cloud; adverse is he to thy\r gargling and spewing and grips in the bowels!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1480},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-33","text":"The gold, however, and the laughter—these doth he take out of the heart\r of the earth: for, that thou mayst know it,—THE HEART OF THE EARTH IS\r OF GOLD.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1481},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-34","text":"When the fire-dog heard this, he could no longer endure to listen to me.\r Abashed did he draw in his tail, said “bow-wow!” in a cowed voice, and\r crept down into his cave.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1482},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-35","text":"Thus told Zarathustra. His disciples, however, hardly listened to him:\r so great was their eagerness to tell him about the sailors, the rabbits,\r and the flying man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1483},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-36","text":"“What am I to think of it!” said Zarathustra. “Am I indeed a ghost?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1484},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-37","text":"But it may have been my shadow. Ye have surely heard something of the\r Wanderer and his Shadow?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1485},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-38","text":"One thing, however, is certain: I must keep a tighter hold of it;\r otherwise it will spoil my reputation.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1486},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-39","text":"And once more Zarathustra shook his head and wondered. “What am I to\r think of it!” said he once more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1487},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-60-40","text":"“Why did the ghost cry: ‘It is time! It is the highest time!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":1488},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-1","text":"“—And I saw a great sadness come over mankind. The best turned weary of\r their works.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1489},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-2","text":"A doctrine appeared, a faith ran beside it: ‘All is empty, all is alike,\r all hath been!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1490},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-3","text":"And from all hills there re-echoed: ‘All is empty, all is alike, all\r hath been!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1491},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-4","text":"To be sure we have harvested: but why have all our fruits become rotten\r and brown? What was it fell last night from the evil moon?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1492},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-5","text":"In vain was all our labour, poison hath our wine become, the evil eye\r hath singed yellow our fields and hearts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1493},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-6","text":"Arid have we all become; and fire falling upon us, then do we turn dust\r like ashes:—yea, the fire itself have we made aweary.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1494},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-7","text":"All our fountains have dried up, even the sea hath receded. All the\r ground trieth to gape, but the depth will not swallow!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1495},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-8","text":"‘Alas! where is there still a sea in which one could be drowned?’ so\r soundeth our plaint—across shallow swamps.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1496},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-9","text":"Verily, even for dying have we become too weary; now do we keep awake\r and live on—in sepulchres.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1497},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-10","text":"Thus did Zarathustra hear a soothsayer speak; and the foreboding touched\r his heart and transformed him. Sorrowfully did he go about and wearily;\r and he became like unto those of whom the soothsayer had spoken.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1498},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-11","text":"Verily, said he unto his disciples, a little while, and there cometh the\r long twilight. Alas, how shall I preserve my light through it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1499},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-12","text":"That it may not smother in this sorrowfulness! To remoter worlds shall\r it be a light, and also to remotest nights!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1500},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-13","text":"Thus did Zarathustra go about grieved in his heart, and for three days\r he did not take any meat or drink: he had no rest, and lost his speech.\r At last it came to pass that he fell into a deep sleep. His disciples,\r however, sat around him in long night-watches, and waited anxiously to\r see if he would awake, and speak again, and recover from his affliction.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1501},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-14","text":"And this is the discourse that Zarathustra spake when he awoke; his\r voice, however, came unto his disciples as from afar:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1502},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-15","text":"Hear, I pray you, the dream that I dreamed, my friends, and help me to\r divine its meaning!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1503},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-16","text":"A riddle is it still unto me, this dream; the meaning is hidden in it\r and encaged, and doth not yet fly above it on free pinions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1504},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-17","text":"All life had I renounced, so I dreamed. Night-watchman and\r grave-guardian had I become, aloft, in the lone mountain-fortress of\r Death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1505},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-18","text":"There did I guard his coffins: full stood the musty vaults of those\r trophies of victory. Out of glass coffins did vanquished life gaze upon\r me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1506},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-19","text":"The odour of dust-covered eternities did I breathe: sultry and\r dust-covered lay my soul. And who could have aired his soul there!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1507},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-20","text":"Brightness of midnight was ever around me; lonesomeness cowered beside\r her; and as a third, death-rattle stillness, the worst of my female\r friends.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1508},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-21","text":"Keys did I carry, the rustiest of all keys; and I knew how to open with\r them the most creaking of all gates.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1509},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-22","text":"Like a bitterly angry croaking ran the sound through the long corridors\r when the leaves of the gate opened: ungraciously did this bird cry,\r unwillingly was it awakened.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1510},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-23","text":"But more frightful even, and more heart-strangling was it, when it again\r became silent and still all around, and I alone sat in that malignant\r silence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1511},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-24","text":"Thus did time pass with me, and slip by, if time there still was: what\r do I know thereof! But at last there happened that which awoke me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1512},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-25","text":"Thrice did there peal peals at the gate like thunders, thrice did the\r vaults resound and howl again: then did I go to the gate.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1513},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-26","text":"Alpa! cried I, who carrieth his ashes unto the mountain? Alpa! Alpa! who\r carrieth his ashes unto the mountain?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1514},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-27","text":"And I pressed the key, and pulled at the gate, and exerted myself. But\r not a finger’s-breadth was it yet open:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1515},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-28","text":"Then did a roaring wind tear the folds apart: whistling, whizzing, and\r piercing, it threw unto me a black coffin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1516},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-29","text":"And in the roaring, and whistling, and whizzing the coffin burst up, and\r spouted out a thousand peals of laughter.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1517},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-30","text":"And a thousand caricatures of children, angels, owls, fools, and\r child-sized butterflies laughed and mocked, and roared at me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1518},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-31","text":"Fearfully was I terrified thereby: it prostrated me. And I cried with\r horror as I ne’er cried before.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1519},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-32","text":"Thus did Zarathustra relate his dream, and then was silent: for as yet\r he knew not the interpretation thereof. But the disciple whom he loved\r most arose quickly, seized Zarathustra’s hand, and said:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1520},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-33","text":"“Thy life itself interpreteth unto us this dream, O Zarathustra!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1521},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-34","text":"Art thou not thyself the wind with shrill whistling, which bursteth open\r the gates of the fortress of Death?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1522},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-35","text":"Art thou not thyself the coffin full of many-hued malices and\r angel-caricatures of life?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1523},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-36","text":"Verily, like a thousand peals of children’s laughter cometh\r Zarathustra into all sepulchres, laughing at those night-watchmen and\r grave-guardians, and whoever else rattleth with sinister keys.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1524},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-37","text":"With thy laughter wilt thou frighten and prostrate them: fainting and\r recovering will demonstrate thy power over them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1525},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-38","text":"And when the long twilight cometh and the mortal weariness, even then\r wilt thou not disappear from our firmament, thou advocate of life!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1526},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-39","text":"New stars hast thou made us see, and new nocturnal glories: verily,\r laughter itself hast thou spread out over us like a many-hued canopy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1527},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-40","text":"Now will children’s laughter ever from coffins flow; now will a strong\r wind ever come victoriously unto all mortal weariness: of this thou art\r thyself the pledge and the prophet!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1528},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-41","text":"Verily, THEY THEMSELVES DIDST THOU DREAM, thine enemies: that was thy\r sorest dream.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1529},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-42","text":"But as thou awokest from them and camest to thyself, so shall they\r awaken from themselves—and come unto thee!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1530},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-43","text":"Thus spake the disciple; and all the others then thronged around\r Zarathustra, grasped him by the hands, and tried to persuade him to\r leave his bed and his sadness, and return unto them. Zarathustra,\r however, sat upright on his couch, with an absent look. Like one\r returning from long foreign sojourn did he look on his disciples, and\r examined their features; but still he knew them not. When, however, they\r raised him, and set him upon his feet, behold, all on a sudden his eye\r changed; he understood everything that had happened, stroked his beard,\r and said with a strong voice:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1531},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-44","text":"“Well! this hath just its time; but see to it, my disciples, that we\r have a good repast; and without delay! Thus do I mean to make amends for\r bad dreams!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1532},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-45","text":"The soothsayer, however, shall eat and drink at my side: and verily, I\r will yet show him a sea in which he can drown himself!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1533},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-61-46","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. Then did he gaze long into the face of the\r disciple who had been the dream-interpreter, and shook his head.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":1534},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-1","text":"When Zarathustra went one day over the great bridge, then did the\r cripples and beggars surround him, and a hunchback spake thus unto him:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1535},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-2","text":"“Behold, Zarathustra! Even the people learn from thee, and acquire faith\r in thy teaching: but for them to believe fully in thee, one thing is\r still needful—thou must first of all convince us cripples! Here hast\r thou now a fine selection, and verily, an opportunity with more than one\r forelock! The blind canst thou heal, and make the lame run; and from\r him who hath too much behind, couldst thou well, also, take away a\r little;—that, I think, would be the right method to make the cripples\r believe in Zarathustra!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1536},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-3","text":"Zarathustra, however, answered thus unto him who so spake: When one\r taketh his hump from the hunchback, then doth one take from him his\r spirit—so do the people teach. And when one giveth the blind man eyes,\r then doth he see too many bad things on the earth: so that he curseth\r him who healed him. He, however, who maketh the lame man run, inflicteth\r upon him the greatest injury; for hardly can he run, when his vices\r run away with him—so do the people teach concerning cripples. And why\r should not Zarathustra also learn from the people, when the people learn\r from Zarathustra?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1537},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-4","text":"It is, however, the smallest thing unto me since I have been amongst\r men, to see one person lacking an eye, another an ear, and a third a\r leg, and that others have lost the tongue, or the nose, or the head.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1538},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-5","text":"I see and have seen worse things, and divers things so hideous, that I\r should neither like to speak of all matters, nor even keep silent about\r some of them: namely, men who lack everything, except that they have\r too much of one thing—men who are nothing more than a big eye, or a big\r mouth, or a big belly, or something else big,—reversed cripples, I call\r such men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1539},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-6","text":"And when I came out of my solitude, and for the first time passed over\r this bridge, then I could not trust mine eyes, but looked again and\r again, and said at last: “That is an ear! An ear as big as a man!” I\r looked still more attentively—and actually there did move under the ear\r something that was pitiably small and poor and slim. And in truth this\r immense ear was perched on a small thin stalk—the stalk, however, was a\r man! A person putting a glass to his eyes, could even recognise further\r a small envious countenance, and also that a bloated soullet dangled at\r the stalk. The people told me, however, that the big ear was not only a\r man, but a great man, a genius. But I never believed","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1540},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-7","text":"When Zarathustra had spoken thus unto the hunchback, and unto those of\r whom the hunchback was the mouthpiece and advocate, then did he turn to\r his disciples in profound dejection, and said:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1541},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-8","text":"Verily, my friends, I walk amongst men as amongst the fragments and\r limbs of human beings!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1542},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-9","text":"This is the terrible thing to mine eye, that I find man broken up, and\r scattered about, as on a battle- and butcher-ground.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1543},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-10","text":"And when mine eye fleeth from the present to the bygone, it findeth ever\r the same: fragments and limbs and fearful chances—but no men!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1544},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-11","text":"The present and the bygone upon earth—ah! my friends—that is MY most\r unbearable trouble; and I should not know how to live, if I were not a\r seer of what is to come.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1545},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-12","text":"A seer, a purposer, a creator, a future itself, and a bridge to the\r future—and alas! also as it were a cripple on this bridge: all that is\r Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1546},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-13","text":"And ye also asked yourselves often: “Who is Zarathustra to us? What\r shall he be called by us?” And like me, did ye give yourselves questions\r for answers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1547},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-14","text":"Is he a promiser? Or a fulfiller? A conqueror? Or an inheritor? A\r harvest? Or a ploughshare? A physician? Or a healed one?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1548},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-15","text":"Is he a poet? Or a genuine one? An emancipator? Or a subjugator? A good\r one? Or an evil one?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1549},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-16","text":"I walk amongst men as the fragments of the future: that future which I\r contemplate.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1550},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-17","text":"And it is all my poetisation and aspiration to compose and collect into\r unity what is fragment and riddle and fearful chance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1551},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-18","text":"And how could I endure to be a man, if man were not also the composer,\r and riddle-reader, and redeemer of chance!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1552},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-19","text":"To redeem what is past, and to transform every “It was” into “Thus would\r I have it!”—that only do I call redemption!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1553},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-20","text":"Will—so is the emancipator and joy-bringer called: thus have I taught\r you, my friends! But now learn this likewise: the Will itself is still a\r prisoner.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1554},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-21","text":"Willing emancipateth: but what is that called which still putteth the\r emancipator in chains?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1555},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-22","text":"“It was”: thus is the Will’s teeth-gnashing and lonesomest tribulation\r called. Impotent towards what hath been done—it is a malicious\r spectator of all that is past.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1556},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-23","text":"Not backward can the Will will; that it cannot break time and time’s\r desire—that is the Will’s lonesomest tribulation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1557},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-24","text":"Willing emancipateth: what doth Willing itself devise in order to get\r free from its tribulation and mock at its prison?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1558},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-25","text":"Ah, a fool becometh every prisoner! Foolishly delivereth itself also the\r imprisoned Will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1559},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-26","text":"That time doth not run backward—that is its animosity: “That which\r was”: so is the stone which it cannot roll called.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1560},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-27","text":"And thus doth it roll stones out of animosity and ill-humour, and taketh\r revenge on whatever doth not, like it, feel rage and ill-humour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1561},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-28","text":"Thus did the Will, the emancipator, become a torturer; and on all\r that is capable of suffering it taketh revenge, because it cannot go\r backward.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1562},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-29","text":"This, yea, this alone is REVENGE itself: the Will’s antipathy to time,\r and its “It was.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1563},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-30","text":"Verily, a great folly dwelleth in our Will; and it became a curse unto\r all humanity, that this folly acquired spirit!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1564},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-31","text":"THE SPIRIT OF REVENGE: my friends, that hath hitherto been man’s best\r contemplation; and where there was suffering, it was claimed there was\r always penalty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1565},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-32","text":"“Penalty,” so calleth itself revenge. With a lying word it feigneth a\r good conscience.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1566},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-33","text":"And because in the willer himself there is suffering, because he cannot\r will backwards—thus was Willing itself, and all life, claimed—to be\r penalty!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1567},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-34","text":"And then did cloud after cloud roll over the spirit, until at last\r madness preached: “Everything perisheth, therefore everything deserveth\r to perish!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1568},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-35","text":"“And this itself is justice, the law of time—that he must devour his\r children:” thus did madness preach.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1569},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-36","text":"“Morally are things ordered according to justice and penalty. Oh, where\r is there deliverance from the flux of things and from the ‘existence’ of\r penalty?” Thus did madness preach.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1570},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-37","text":"“Can there be deliverance when there is eternal justice? Alas,\r unrollable is the stone, ‘It was’: eternal must also be all penalties!”\r  Thus did madness preach.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1571},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-38","text":"“No deed can be annihilated: how could it be undone by the penalty!\r This, this is what is eternal in the ‘existence’ of penalty, that\r existence also must be eternally recurring deed and guilt!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1572},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-39","text":"Unless the Will should at last deliver itself, and Willing become\r non-Willing—:” but ye know, my brethren, this fabulous song of madness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1573},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-40","text":"Away from those fabulous songs did I lead you when I taught you: “The\r Will is a creator.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1574},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-41","text":"All “It was” is a fragment, a riddle, a fearful chance—until the\r creating Will saith thereto: “But thus would I have it.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1575},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-42","text":"Until the creating Will saith thereto: “But thus do I will it! Thus\r shall I will it!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1576},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-43","text":"But did it ever speak thus? And when doth this take place? Hath the Will\r been unharnessed from its own folly?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1577},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-44","text":"Hath the Will become its own deliverer and joy-bringer? Hath it\r unlearned the spirit of revenge and all teeth-gnashing?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1578},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-45","text":"And who hath taught it reconciliation with time, and something higher\r than all reconciliation?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1579},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-46","text":"Something higher than all reconciliation must the Will will which is the\r Will to Power—: but how doth that take place? Who hath taught it also\r to will backwards?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1580},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-47","text":"—But at this point in his discourse it chanced that Zarathustra\r suddenly paused, and looked like a person in the greatest alarm. With\r terror in his eyes did he gaze on his disciples; his glances pierced as\r with arrows their thoughts and arrear-thoughts. But after a brief space\r he again laughed, and said soothedly:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1581},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-48","text":"“It is difficult to live amongst men, because silence is so difficult—\r especially for a babbler.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1582},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-49","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. The hunchback, however, had listened to the\r conversation and had covered his face during the time; but when he heard\r Zarathustra laugh, he looked up with curiosity, and said slowly:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1583},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-50","text":"“But why doth Zarathustra speak otherwise unto us than unto his\r disciples?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1584},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-51","text":"Zarathustra answered: “What is there to be wondered at! With hunchbacks\r one may well speak in a hunchbacked way!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1585},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-52","text":"“Very good,” said the hunchback; “and with pupils one may well tell\r tales out of school.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1586},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-62-53","text":"But why doth Zarathustra speak otherwise unto his pupils—than unto\r himself?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":1587},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-1","text":"The declivity, where the gaze shooteth DOWNWARDS, and the hand graspeth\r UPWARDS. There doth the heart become giddy through its double will.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1588},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-2","text":"This, this is MY declivity and my danger, that my gaze shooteth towards\r the summit, and my hand would fain clutch and lean—on the depth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1589},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-3","text":"To man clingeth my will; with chains do I bind myself to man, because\r I am pulled upwards to the Superman: for thither doth mine other will\r tend.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1590},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-4","text":"And THEREFORE do I live blindly among men, as if I knew them not: that\r my hand may not entirely lose belief in firmness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1591},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-5","text":"I know not you men: this gloom and consolation is often spread around\r me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1592},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-6","text":"I sit at the gateway for every rogue, and ask: Who wisheth to deceive\r me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1593},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-7","text":"This is my first manly prudence, that I allow myself to be deceived, so\r as not to be on my guard against deceivers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1594},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-8","text":"Ah, if I were on my guard against man, how could man be an anchor to my\r ball! Too easily would I be pulled upwards and away!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1595},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-9","text":"This providence is over my fate, that I have to be without foresight.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1596},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-10","text":"And he who would not languish amongst men, must learn to drink out of\r all glasses; and he who would keep clean amongst men, must know how to\r wash himself even with dirty water.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1597},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-11","text":"And thus spake I often to myself for consolation: “Courage! Cheer up!\r old heart! An unhappiness hath failed to befall thee: enjoy that as\r thy—happiness!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1598},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-12","text":"This, however, is mine other manly prudence: I am more forbearing to the\r VAIN than to the proud.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1599},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-13","text":"Is not wounded vanity the mother of all tragedies? Where, however, pride\r is wounded, there groweth up something better than pride.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1600},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-14","text":"That life may be fair to behold, its game must be well played; for that\r purpose, however, it needeth good actors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1601},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-15","text":"Good actors have I found all the vain ones: they play, and wish people\r to be fond of beholding them—all their spirit is in this wish.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1602},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-16","text":"They represent themselves, they invent themselves; in their\r neighbourhood I like to look upon life—it cureth of melancholy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1603},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-17","text":"Therefore am I forbearing to the vain, because they are the physicians\r of my melancholy, and keep me attached to man as to a drama.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1604},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-18","text":"And further, who conceiveth the full depth of the modesty of the vain\r man! I am favourable to him, and sympathetic on account of his modesty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1605},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-19","text":"From you would he learn his belief in himself; he feedeth upon your\r glances, he eateth praise out of your hands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1606},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-20","text":"Your lies doth he even believe when you lie favourably about him: for in\r its depths sigheth his heart: “What am _I_?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1607},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-21","text":"And if that be the true virtue which is unconscious of itself—well, the\r vain man is unconscious of his modesty!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1608},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-22","text":"This is, however, my third manly prudence: I am not put out of conceit\r with the WICKED by your timorousness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1609},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-23","text":"I am happy to see the marvels the warm sun hatcheth: tigers and palms\r and rattle-snakes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1610},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-24","text":"Also amongst men there is a beautiful brood of the warm sun, and much\r that is marvellous in the wicked.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1611},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-25","text":"In truth, as your wisest did not seem to me so very wise, so found I\r also human wickedness below the fame of it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1612},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-26","text":"And oft did I ask with a shake of the head: Why still rattle, ye\r rattle-snakes?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1613},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-27","text":"Verily, there is still a future even for evil! And the warmest south is\r still undiscovered by man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1614},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-28","text":"How many things are now called the worst wickedness, which are only\r twelve feet broad and three months long! Some day, however, will greater\r dragons come into the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1615},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-29","text":"For that the Superman may not lack his dragon, the superdragon that\r is worthy of him, there must still much warm sun glow on moist virgin\r forests!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1616},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-30","text":"Out of your wild cats must tigers have evolved, and out of your\r poison-toads, crocodiles: for the good hunter shall have a good hunt!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1617},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-31","text":"And verily, ye good and just! In you there is much to be laughed at, and\r especially your fear of what hath hitherto been called “the devil!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1618},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-32","text":"So alien are ye in your souls to what is great, that to you the Superman\r would be FRIGHTFUL in his goodness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1619},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-33","text":"And ye wise and knowing ones, ye would flee from the solar-glow of the\r wisdom in which the Superman joyfully batheth his nakedness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1620},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-34","text":"Ye highest men who have come within my ken! this is my doubt of you, and\r my secret laughter: I suspect ye would call my Superman—a devil!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1621},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-35","text":"Ah, I became tired of those highest and best ones: from their “height”\r  did I long to be up, out, and away to the Superman!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1622},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-36","text":"A horror came over me when I saw those best ones naked: then there grew\r for me the pinions to soar away into distant futures.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1623},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-37","text":"Into more distant futures, into more southern souths than ever artist\r dreamed of: thither, where Gods are ashamed of all clothes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1624},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-38","text":"But disguised do I want to see YOU, ye neighbours and fellowmen, and\r well-attired and vain and estimable, as “the good and just;”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1625},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-63-39","text":"And disguised will I myself sit amongst you—that I may MISTAKE you and\r myself: for that is my last manly prudence.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":1626},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-1","text":"What hath happened unto me, my friends? Ye see me troubled, driven\r forth, unwillingly obedient, ready to go—alas, to go away from YOU!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1627},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-2","text":"Yea, once more must Zarathustra retire to his solitude: but unjoyously\r this time doth the bear go back to his cave!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1628},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-3","text":"What hath happened unto me? Who ordereth this?—Ah, mine angry mistress\r wisheth it so; she spake unto me. Have I ever named her name to you?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1629},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-4","text":"Yesterday towards evening there spake unto me MY STILLEST HOUR: that is\r the name of my terrible mistress.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1630},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-5","text":"And thus did it happen—for everything must I tell you, that your heart\r may not harden against the suddenly departing one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1631},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-6","text":"To the very toes he is terrified, because the ground giveth way under\r him, and the dream beginneth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1632},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-7","text":"This do I speak unto you in parable. Yesterday at the stillest hour did\r the ground give way under me: the dream began.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1633},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-8","text":"The hour-hand moved on, the timepiece of my life drew breath—never did\r I hear such stillness around me, so that my heart was terrified.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1634},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-9","text":"Then was there spoken unto me without voice: “THOU KNOWEST IT,\r ZARATHUSTRA?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1635},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-10","text":"And I cried in terror at this whispering, and the blood left my face:\r but I was silent.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1636},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-11","text":"Then was there once more spoken unto me without voice: “Thou knowest it,\r Zarathustra, but thou dost not speak it!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1637},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-12","text":"And at last I answered, like one defiant: “Yea, I know it, but I will\r not speak it!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1638},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-13","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “Thou WILT not,\r Zarathustra? Is this true? Conceal thyself not behind thy defiance!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1639},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-14","text":"And I wept and trembled like a child, and said: “Ah, I would indeed, but\r how can I do it! Exempt me only from this! It is beyond my power!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1640},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-15","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “What matter about\r thyself, Zarathustra! Speak thy word, and succumb!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1641},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-16","text":"And I answered: “Ah, is it MY word? Who am _I_? I await the worthier\r one; I am not worthy even to succumb by it.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1642},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-17","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “What matter about\r thyself? Thou art not yet humble enough for me. Humility hath the\r hardest skin.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1643},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-18","text":"And I answered: “What hath not the skin of my humility endured! At the\r foot of my height do I dwell: how high are my summits, no one hath yet\r told me. But well do I know my valleys.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1644},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-19","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “O Zarathustra, he\r who hath to remove mountains removeth also valleys and plains.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1645},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-20","text":"And I answered: “As yet hath my word not removed mountains, and what I\r have spoken hath not reached man. I went, indeed, unto men, but not yet\r have I attained unto them.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1646},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-21","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “What knowest thou\r THEREOF! The dew falleth on the grass when the night is most silent.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1647},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-22","text":"And I answered: “They mocked me when I found and walked in mine own\r path; and certainly did my feet then tremble.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1648},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-23","text":"And thus did they speak unto me: Thou forgottest the path before, now\r dost thou also forget how to walk!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1649},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-24","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “What matter about\r their mockery! Thou art one who hast unlearned to obey: now shalt thou\r command!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1650},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-25","text":"Knowest thou not who is most needed by all? He who commandeth great\r things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1651},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-26","text":"To execute great things is difficult: but the more difficult task is to\r command great things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1652},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-27","text":"This is thy most unpardonable obstinacy: thou hast the power, and thou\r wilt not rule.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1653},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-28","text":"And I answered: “I lack the lion’s voice for all commanding.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1654},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-29","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me as a whispering: “It is the stillest\r words which bring the storm. Thoughts that come with doves’ footsteps\r guide the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1655},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-30","text":"O Zarathustra, thou shalt go as a shadow of that which is to come: thus\r wilt thou command, and in commanding go foremost.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1656},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-31","text":"Then was there again spoken unto me without voice: “Thou must yet become\r a child, and be without shame.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1657},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-32","text":"The pride of youth is still upon thee; late hast thou become young: but\r he who would become a child must surmount even his youth.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1658},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-33","text":"And I considered a long while, and trembled. At last, however, did I say\r what I had said at first. “I will not.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1659},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-34","text":"Then did a laughing take place all around me. Alas, how that laughing\r lacerated my bowels and cut into my heart!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1660},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-35","text":"And there was spoken unto me for the last time: “O Zarathustra, thy\r fruits are ripe, but thou art not ripe for thy fruits!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1661},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-36","text":"So must thou go again into solitude: for thou shalt yet become\r mellow.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1662},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-37","text":"And again was there a laughing, and it fled: then did it become still\r around me, as with a double stillness. I lay, however, on the ground,\r and the sweat flowed from my limbs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1663},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-38","text":"—Now have ye heard all, and why I have to return into my solitude.\r Nothing have I kept hidden from you, my friends.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1664},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-39","text":"But even this have ye heard from me, WHO is still the most reserved of\r men—and will be so!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1665},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-40","text":"Ah, my friends! I should have something more to say unto you! I should\r have something more to give unto you! Why do I not give it? Am I then a\r niggard?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1666},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-64-41","text":"When, however, Zarathustra had spoken these words, the violence of his\r pain, and a sense of the nearness of his departure from his friends came\r over him, so that he wept aloud; and no one knew how to console him. In\r the night, however, he went away alone and left his friends.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":1667},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-65-1","text":"“Ye look aloft when ye long for exaltation, and I look downward because\r I am exalted.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":1668},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-65-2","text":"“He who climbeth on the highest mountains, laugheth at all tragic plays\r and tragic realities.”—ZARATHUSTRA, I., “Reading and Writing.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":1669},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-1","text":"Then, when it was about midnight, Zarathustra went his way over the\r ridge of the isle, that he might arrive early in the morning at the\r other coast; because there he meant to embark. For there was a good\r roadstead there, in which foreign ships also liked to anchor: those\r ships took many people with them, who wished to cross over from the\r Happy Isles. So when Zarathustra thus ascended the mountain, he thought\r on the way of his many solitary wanderings from youth onwards, and how\r many mountains and ridges and summits he had already climbed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1670},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-2","text":"I am a wanderer and mountain-climber, said he to his heart, I love not\r the plains, and it seemeth I cannot long sit still.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1671},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-3","text":"And whatever may still overtake me as fate and experience—a wandering\r will be therein, and a mountain-climbing: in the end one experienceth\r only oneself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1672},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-4","text":"The time is now past when accidents could befall me; and what COULD now\r fall to my lot which would not already be mine own!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1673},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-5","text":"It returneth only, it cometh home to me at last—mine own Self, and\r such of it as hath been long abroad, and scattered among things and\r accidents.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1674},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-6","text":"And one thing more do I know: I stand now before my last summit, and\r before that which hath been longest reserved for me. Ah, my hardest path\r must I ascend! Ah, I have begun my lonesomest wandering!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1675},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-7","text":"He, however, who is of my nature doth not avoid such an hour: the hour\r that saith unto him: Now only dost thou go the way to thy greatness!\r Summit and abyss—these are now comprised together!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1676},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-8","text":"Thou goest the way to thy greatness: now hath it become thy last refuge,\r what was hitherto thy last danger!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1677},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-9","text":"Thou goest the way to thy greatness: it must now be thy best courage\r that there is no longer any path behind thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1678},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-10","text":"Thou goest the way to thy greatness: here shall no one steal after thee!\r Thy foot itself hath effaced the path behind thee, and over it standeth\r written: Impossibility.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1679},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-11","text":"And if all ladders henceforth fail thee, then must thou learn to mount\r upon thine own head: how couldst thou mount upward otherwise?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1680},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-12","text":"Upon thine own head, and beyond thine own heart! Now must the gentlest\r in thee become the hardest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1681},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-13","text":"He who hath always much-indulged himself, sickeneth at last by his\r much-indulgence. Praises on what maketh hardy! I do not praise the land\r where butter and honey—flow!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1682},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-14","text":"To learn TO LOOK AWAY FROM oneself, is necessary in order to see MANY\r THINGS:—this hardiness is needed by every mountain-climber.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1683},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-15","text":"He, however, who is obtrusive with his eyes as a discerner, how can he\r ever see more of anything than its foreground!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1684},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-16","text":"But thou, O Zarathustra, wouldst view the ground of everything, and its\r background: thus must thou mount even above thyself—up, upwards, until\r thou hast even thy stars UNDER thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1685},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-17","text":"Yea! To look down upon myself, and even upon my stars: that only would I\r call my SUMMIT, that hath remained for me as my LAST summit!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1686},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-18","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra to himself while ascending, comforting his heart\r with harsh maxims: for he was sore at heart as he had never been before.\r And when he had reached the top of the mountain-ridge, behold, there\r lay the other sea spread out before him: and he stood still and was\r long silent. The night, however, was cold at this height, and clear and\r starry.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1687},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-19","text":"I recognise my destiny, said he at last, sadly. Well! I am ready. Now\r hath my last lonesomeness begun.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1688},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-20","text":"Ah, this sombre, sad sea, below me! Ah, this sombre nocturnal vexation!\r Ah, fate and sea! To you must I now GO DOWN!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1689},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-21","text":"Before my highest mountain do I stand, and before my longest wandering:\r therefore must I first go deeper down than I ever ascended:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1690},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-22","text":"—Deeper down into pain than I ever ascended, even into its darkest\r flood! So willeth my fate. Well! I am ready.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1691},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-23","text":"Whence come the highest mountains? so did I once ask. Then did I learn\r that they come out of the sea.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1692},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-24","text":"That testimony is inscribed on their stones, and on the walls of their\r summits. Out of the deepest must the highest come to its height.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1693},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-25","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra on the ridge of the mountain where it was cold:\r when, however, he came into the vicinity of the sea, and at last stood\r alone amongst the cliffs, then had he become weary on his way, and\r eagerer than ever before.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1694},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-26","text":"Everything as yet sleepeth, said he; even the sea sleepeth. Drowsily and\r strangely doth its eye gaze upon me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1695},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-27","text":"But it breatheth warmly—I feel it. And I feel also that it dreameth. It\r tosseth about dreamily on hard pillows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1696},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-28","text":"Hark! Hark! How it groaneth with evil recollections! Or evil\r expectations?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1697},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-29","text":"Ah, I am sad along with thee, thou dusky monster, and angry with myself\r even for thy sake.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1698},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-30","text":"Ah, that my hand hath not strength enough! Gladly, indeed, would I free\r thee from evil dreams!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1699},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-31","text":"And while Zarathustra thus spake, he laughed at himself with melancholy\r and bitterness. What! Zarathustra, said he, wilt thou even sing\r consolation to the sea?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1700},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-32","text":"Ah, thou amiable fool, Zarathustra, thou too-blindly confiding one! But\r thus hast thou ever been: ever hast thou approached confidently all that\r is terrible.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1701},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-33","text":"Every monster wouldst thou caress. A whiff of warm breath, a little soft\r tuft on its paw—: and immediately wert thou ready to love and lure it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1702},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-34","text":"LOVE is the danger of the lonesomest one, love to anything, IF IT ONLY\r LIVE! Laughable, verily, is my folly and my modesty in love!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1703},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-66-35","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and laughed thereby a second time. Then,\r however, he thought of his abandoned friends—and as if he had done them\r a wrong with his thoughts, he upbraided himself because of his thoughts.\r And forthwith it came to pass that the laugher wept—with anger and\r longing wept Zarathustra bitterly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":1704},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-1","text":"When it got abroad among the sailors that Zarathustra was on board the\r ship—for a man who came from the Happy Isles had gone on board along\r with him,—there was great curiosity and expectation. But Zarathustra\r kept silent for two days, and was cold and deaf with sadness; so that he\r neither answered looks nor questions. On the evening of the second day,\r however, he again opened his ears, though he still kept silent: for\r there were many curious and dangerous things to be heard on board the\r ship, which came from afar, and was to go still further. Zarathustra,\r however, was fond of all those who make distant voyages, and dislike to\r live without danger. And behold! when listening, his own ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1705},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-2","text":"To you, the daring venturers and adventurers, and whoever hath embarked\r with cunning sails upon frightful seas,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1706},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-3","text":"To you the enigma-intoxicated, the twilight-enjoyers, whose souls are\r allured by flutes to every treacherous gulf:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1707},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-4","text":"—For ye dislike to grope at a thread with cowardly hand; and where ye\r can DIVINE, there do ye hate to CALCULATE—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1708},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-5","text":"To you only do I tell the enigma that I SAW—the vision of the\r lonesomest one.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1709},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-6","text":"Gloomily walked I lately in corpse-coloured twilight—gloomily and\r sternly, with compressed lips. Not only one sun had set for me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1710},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-7","text":"A path which ascended daringly among boulders, an evil, lonesome path,\r which neither herb nor shrub any longer cheered, a mountain-path,\r crunched under the daring of my foot.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1711},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-8","text":"Mutely marching over the scornful clinking of pebbles, trampling the\r stone that let it slip: thus did my foot force its way upwards.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1712},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-9","text":"Upwards:—in spite of the spirit that drew it downwards, towards the\r abyss, the spirit of gravity, my devil and arch-enemy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1713},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-10","text":"Upwards:—although it sat upon me, half-dwarf, half-mole; paralysed,\r paralysing; dripping lead in mine ear, and thoughts like drops of lead\r into my brain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1714},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-11","text":"“O Zarathustra,” it whispered scornfully, syllable by syllable, “thou\r stone of wisdom! Thou threwest thyself high, but every thrown stone\r must—fall!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1715},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-12","text":"O Zarathustra, thou stone of wisdom, thou sling-stone, thou\r star-destroyer! Thyself threwest thou so high,—but every thrown\r stone—must fall!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1716},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-13","text":"Condemned of thyself, and to thine own stoning: O Zarathustra, far\r indeed threwest thou thy stone—but upon THYSELF will it recoil!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1717},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-14","text":"Then was the dwarf silent; and it lasted long. The silence, however,\r oppressed me; and to be thus in pairs, one is verily lonesomer than when\r alone!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1718},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-15","text":"I ascended, I ascended, I dreamt, I thought,—but everything oppressed\r me. A sick one did I resemble, whom bad torture wearieth, and a worse\r dream reawakeneth out of his first sleep.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1719},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-16","text":"But there is something in me which I call courage: it hath hitherto\r slain for me every dejection. This courage at last bade me stand still\r and say: “Dwarf! Thou! Or I!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1720},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-17","text":"For courage is the best slayer,—courage which ATTACKETH: for in every\r attack there is sound of triumph.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1721},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-18","text":"Man, however, is the most courageous animal: thereby hath he overcome\r every animal. With sound of triumph hath he overcome every pain; human\r pain, however, is the sorest pain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1722},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-19","text":"Courage slayeth also giddiness at abysses: and where doth man not stand\r at abysses! Is not seeing itself—seeing abysses?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1723},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-20","text":"Courage is the best slayer: courage slayeth also fellow-suffering.\r Fellow-suffering, however, is the deepest abyss: as deeply as man\r looketh into life, so deeply also doth he look into suffering.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1724},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-21","text":"Courage, however, is the best slayer, courage which attacketh: it\r slayeth even death itself; for it saith: “WAS THAT life? Well! Once\r more!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1725},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-22","text":"In such speech, however, there is much sound of triumph. He who hath\r ears to hear, let him hear.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1726},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-23","text":"“Halt, dwarf!” said I. “Either I—or thou! I, however, am the stronger\r of the two:—thou knowest not mine abysmal thought! IT—couldst thou not\r endure!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1727},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-24","text":"Then happened that which made me lighter: for the dwarf sprang from my\r shoulder, the prying sprite! And it squatted on a stone in front of me.\r There was however a gateway just where we halted.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1728},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-25","text":"“Look at this gateway! Dwarf!” I continued, “it hath two faces. Two\r roads come together here: these hath no one yet gone to the end of.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1729},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-26","text":"This long lane backwards: it continueth for an eternity. And that long\r lane forward—that is another eternity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1730},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-27","text":"They are antithetical to one another, these roads; they directly abut on\r one another:—and it is here, at this gateway, that they come together.\r The name of the gateway is inscribed above: ‘This Moment.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1731},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-28","text":"But should one follow them further—and ever further and further\r on, thinkest thou, dwarf, that these roads would be eternally\r antithetical?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1732},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-29","text":"“Everything straight lieth,” murmured the dwarf, contemptuously. “All\r truth is crooked; time itself is a circle.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1733},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-30","text":"“Thou spirit of gravity!” said I wrathfully, “do not take it too\r lightly! Or I shall let thee squat where thou squattest, Haltfoot,—and\r I carried thee HIGH!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1734},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-31","text":"“Observe,” continued I, “This Moment! From the gateway, This Moment,\r there runneth a long eternal lane BACKWARDS: behind us lieth an\r eternity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1735},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-32","text":"Must not whatever CAN run its course of all things, have already run\r along that lane? Must not whatever CAN happen of all things have already\r happened, resulted, and gone by?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1736},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-33","text":"And if everything have already existed, what thinkest thou, dwarf, of\r This Moment? Must not this gateway also—have already existed?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1737},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-34","text":"And are not all things closely bound together in such wise that This\r Moment draweth all coming things after it? CONSEQUENTLY—itself also?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1738},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-35","text":"For whatever CAN run its course of all things, also in this long lane\r OUTWARD—MUST it once more run!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1739},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-36","text":"And this slow spider which creepeth in the moonlight, and this moonlight\r itself, and thou and I in this gateway whispering together, whispering\r of eternal things—must we not all have already existed?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1740},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-37","text":"—And must we not return and run in that other lane out before us, that\r long weird lane—must we not eternally return?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1741},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-38","text":"Thus did I speak, and always more softly: for I was afraid of mine own\r thoughts, and arrear-thoughts. Then, suddenly did I hear a dog HOWL near\r me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1742},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-39","text":"Had I ever heard a dog howl thus? My thoughts ran back. Yes! When I was\r a child, in my most distant childhood:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1743},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-40","text":"—Then did I hear a dog howl thus. And saw it also, with hair bristling,\r its head upwards, trembling in the stillest midnight, when even dogs\r believe in ghosts:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1744},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-41","text":"—So that it excited my commiseration. For just then went the full moon,\r silent as death, over the house; just then did it stand still, a glowing\r globe—at rest on the flat roof, as if on some one’s property:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1745},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-42","text":"Thereby had the dog been terrified: for dogs believe in thieves and\r ghosts. And when I again heard such howling, then did it excite my\r commiseration once more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1746},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-43","text":"Where was now the dwarf? And the gateway? And the spider? And all the\r whispering? Had I dreamt? Had I awakened? ‘Twixt rugged rocks did I\r suddenly stand alone, dreary in the dreariest moonlight.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1747},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-44","text":"BUT THERE LAY A MAN! And there! The dog leaping, bristling, whining—now\r did it see me coming—then did it howl again, then did it CRY:—had I\r ever heard a dog cry so for help?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1748},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-45","text":"And verily, what I saw, the like had I never seen. A young shepherd did\r I see, writhing, choking, quivering, with distorted countenance, and\r with a heavy black serpent hanging out of his mouth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1749},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-46","text":"Had I ever seen so much loathing and pale horror on one countenance?\r He had perhaps gone to sleep? Then had the serpent crawled into his\r throat—there had it bitten itself fast.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1750},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-47","text":"My hand pulled at the serpent, and pulled:—in vain! I failed to pull\r the serpent out of his throat. Then there cried out of me: “Bite! Bite!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1751},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-48","text":"Its head off! Bite!”—so cried it out of me; my horror, my hatred, my\r loathing, my pity, all my good and my bad cried with one voice out of\r me.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1752},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-49","text":"Ye daring ones around me! Ye venturers and adventurers, and whoever\r of you have embarked with cunning sails on unexplored seas! Ye\r enigma-enjoyers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1753},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-50","text":"Solve unto me the enigma that I then beheld, interpret unto me the\r vision of the lonesomest one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1754},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-51","text":"For it was a vision and a foresight:—WHAT did I then behold in parable?\r And WHO is it that must come some day?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1755},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-52","text":"WHO is the shepherd into whose throat the serpent thus crawled? WHO is\r the man into whose throat all the heaviest and blackest will thus crawl?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1756},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-53","text":"—The shepherd however bit as my cry had admonished him; he bit with a\r strong bite! Far away did he spit the head of the serpent—: and sprang\r up.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1757},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-54","text":"No longer shepherd, no longer man—a transfigured being, a\r light-surrounded being, that LAUGHED! Never on earth laughed a man as HE\r laughed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1758},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-55","text":"O my brethren, I heard a laughter which was no human laughter,—and now\r gnaweth a thirst at me, a longing that is never allayed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1759},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-67-56","text":"My longing for that laughter gnaweth at me: oh, how can I still endure\r to live! And how could I endure to die at present!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":1760},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-1","text":"With such enigmas and bitterness in his heart did Zarathustra sail o’er\r the sea. When, however, he was four day-journeys from the Happy\r Isles and from his friends, then had he surmounted all his pain—:\r triumphantly and with firm foot did he again accept his fate. And then\r talked Zarathustra in this wise to his exulting conscience:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1761},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-2","text":"Alone am I again, and like to be so, alone with the pure heaven, and the\r open sea; and again is the afternoon around me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1762},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-3","text":"On an afternoon did I find my friends for the first time; on an\r afternoon, also, did I find them a second time:—at the hour when all\r light becometh stiller.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1763},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-4","text":"For whatever happiness is still on its way ‘twixt heaven and earth, now\r seeketh for lodging a luminous soul: WITH HAPPINESS hath all light now\r become stiller.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1764},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-5","text":"O afternoon of my life! Once did my happiness also descend to the valley\r that it might seek a lodging: then did it find those open hospitable\r souls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1765},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-6","text":"O afternoon of my life! What did I not surrender that I might have\r one thing: this living plantation of my thoughts, and this dawn of my\r highest hope!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1766},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-7","text":"Companions did the creating one once seek, and children of HIS hope: and\r lo, it turned out that he could not find them, except he himself should\r first create them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1767},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-8","text":"Thus am I in the midst of my work, to my children going, and from\r them returning: for the sake of his children must Zarathustra perfect\r himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1768},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-9","text":"For in one’s heart one loveth only one’s child and one’s work; and where\r there is great love to oneself, then is it the sign of pregnancy: so\r have I found it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1769},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-10","text":"Still are my children verdant in their first spring, standing nigh one\r another, and shaken in common by the winds, the trees of my garden and\r of my best soil.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1770},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-11","text":"And verily, where such trees stand beside one another, there ARE Happy\r Isles!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1771},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-12","text":"But one day will I take them up, and put each by itself alone: that it\r may learn lonesomeness and defiance and prudence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1772},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-13","text":"Gnarled and crooked and with flexible hardness shall it then stand by\r the sea, a living lighthouse of unconquerable life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1773},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-14","text":"Yonder where the storms rush down into the sea, and the snout of the\r mountain drinketh water, shall each on a time have his day and night\r watches, for HIS testing and recognition.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1774},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-15","text":"Recognised and tested shall each be, to see if he be of my type and\r lineage:—if he be master of a long will, silent even when he speaketh,\r and giving in such wise that he TAKETH in giving:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1775},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-16","text":"—So that he may one day become my companion, a fellow-creator and\r fellow-enjoyer with Zarathustra:—such a one as writeth my will on my\r tables, for the fuller perfection of all things.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1776},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-17","text":"And for his sake and for those like him, must I perfect MYSELF:\r therefore do I now avoid my happiness, and present myself to every\r misfortune—for MY final testing and recognition.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1777},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-18","text":"And verily, it were time that I went away; and the wanderer’s shadow and\r the longest tedium and the stillest hour—have all said unto me: “It is\r the highest time!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1778},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-19","text":"The word blew to me through the keyhole and said “Come!” The door sprang\r subtlely open unto me, and said “Go!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1779},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-20","text":"But I lay enchained to my love for my children: desire spread this\r snare for me—the desire for love—that I should become the prey of my\r children, and lose myself in them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1780},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-21","text":"Desiring—that is now for me to have lost myself. I POSSESS YOU, MY\r CHILDREN! In this possessing shall everything be assurance and nothing\r desire.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1781},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-22","text":"But brooding lay the sun of my love upon me, in his own juice stewed\r Zarathustra,—then did shadows and doubts fly past me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1782},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-23","text":"For frost and winter I now longed: “Oh, that frost and winter would\r again make me crack and crunch!” sighed I:—then arose icy mist out of\r me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1783},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-24","text":"My past burst its tomb, many pains buried alive woke up—: fully slept\r had they merely, concealed in corpse-clothes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1784},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-25","text":"So called everything unto me in signs: “It is time!” But I—heard not,\r until at last mine abyss moved, and my thought bit me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1785},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-26","text":"Ah, abysmal thought, which art MY thought! When shall I find strength to\r hear thee burrowing, and no longer tremble?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1786},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-27","text":"To my very throat throbbeth my heart when I hear thee burrowing! Thy\r muteness even is like to strangle me, thou abysmal mute one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1787},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-28","text":"As yet have I never ventured to call thee UP; it hath been enough that\r I—have carried thee about with me! As yet have I not been strong\r enough for my final lion-wantonness and playfulness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1788},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-29","text":"Sufficiently formidable unto me hath thy weight ever been: but one day\r shall I yet find the strength and the lion’s voice which will call thee\r up!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1789},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-30","text":"When I shall have surmounted myself therein, then will I surmount myself\r also in that which is greater; and a VICTORY shall be the seal of my\r perfection!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1790},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-31","text":"Meanwhile do I sail along on uncertain seas; chance flattereth me,\r smooth-tongued chance; forward and backward do I gaze—, still see I no\r end.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1791},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-32","text":"As yet hath the hour of my final struggle not come to me—or doth it\r come to me perhaps just now? Verily, with insidious beauty do sea and\r life gaze upon me round about:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1792},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-33","text":"O afternoon of my life! O happiness before eventide! O haven upon high\r seas! O peace in uncertainty! How I distrust all of you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1793},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-34","text":"Verily, distrustful am I of your insidious beauty! Like the lover am I,\r who distrusteth too sleek smiling.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1794},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-35","text":"As he pusheth the best-beloved before him—tender even in severity, the\r jealous one—, so do I push this blissful hour before me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1795},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-36","text":"Away with thee, thou blissful hour! With thee hath there come to me an\r involuntary bliss! Ready for my severest pain do I here stand:—at the\r wrong time hast thou come!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1796},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-37","text":"Away with thee, thou blissful hour! Rather harbour there—with my\r children! Hasten! and bless them before eventide with MY happiness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1797},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-38","text":"There, already approacheth eventide: the sun sinketh. Away—my\r happiness!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1798},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-68-39","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. And he waited for his misfortune the whole\r night; but he waited in vain. The night remained clear and calm, and\r happiness itself came nigher and nigher unto him. Towards morning,\r however, Zarathustra laughed to his heart, and said mockingly:\r “Happiness runneth after me. That is because I do not run after women.\r Happiness, however, is a woman.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":1799},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-1","text":"O heaven above me, thou pure, thou deep heaven! Thou abyss of light!\r Gazing on thee, I tremble with divine desires.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1800},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-2","text":"Up to thy height to toss myself—that is MY depth! In thy purity to hide\r myself—that is MINE innocence!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1801},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-3","text":"The God veileth his beauty: thus hidest thou thy stars. Thou speakest\r not: THUS proclaimest thou thy wisdom unto me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1802},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-4","text":"Mute o’er the raging sea hast thou risen for me to-day; thy love and thy\r modesty make a revelation unto my raging soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1803},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-5","text":"In that thou camest unto me beautiful, veiled in thy beauty, in that\r thou spakest unto me mutely, obvious in thy wisdom:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1804},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-6","text":"Oh, how could I fail to divine all the modesty of thy soul! BEFORE the\r sun didst thou come unto me—the lonesomest one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1805},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-7","text":"We have been friends from the beginning: to us are grief, gruesomeness,\r and ground common; even the sun is common to us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1806},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-8","text":"We do not speak to each other, because we know too much—: we keep\r silent to each other, we smile our knowledge to each other.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1807},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-9","text":"Art thou not the light of my fire? Hast thou not the sister-soul of mine\r insight?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1808},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-10","text":"Together did we learn everything; together did we learn to ascend beyond\r ourselves to ourselves, and to smile uncloudedly:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1809},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-11","text":"—Uncloudedly to smile down out of luminous eyes and out of miles of\r distance, when under us constraint and purpose and guilt steam like\r rain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1810},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-12","text":"And wandered I alone, for WHAT did my soul hunger by night and in\r labyrinthine paths? And climbed I mountains, WHOM did I ever seek, if\r not thee, upon mountains?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1811},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-13","text":"And all my wandering and mountain-climbing: a necessity was it merely,\r and a makeshift of the unhandy one:—to FLY only, wanteth mine entire\r will, to fly into THEE!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1812},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-14","text":"And what have I hated more than passing clouds, and whatever tainteth\r thee? And mine own hatred have I even hated, because it tainted thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1813},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-15","text":"The passing clouds I detest—those stealthy cats of prey: they take\r from thee and me what is common to us—the vast unbounded Yea- and\r Amen-saying.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1814},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-16","text":"These mediators and mixers we detest—the passing clouds: those\r half-and-half ones, that have neither learned to bless nor to curse from\r the heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1815},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-17","text":"Rather will I sit in a tub under a closed heaven, rather will I sit in\r the abyss without heaven, than see thee, thou luminous heaven, tainted\r with passing clouds!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1816},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-18","text":"And oft have I longed to pin them fast with the jagged gold-wires of\r lightning, that I might, like the thunder, beat the drum upon their\r kettle-bellies:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1817},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-19","text":"—An angry drummer, because they rob me of thy Yea and Amen!—thou\r heaven above me, thou pure, thou luminous heaven! Thou abyss of\r light!—because they rob thee of MY Yea and Amen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1818},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-20","text":"For rather will I have noise and thunders and tempest-blasts, than this\r discreet, doubting cat-repose; and also amongst men do I hate most\r of all the soft-treaders, and half-and-half ones, and the doubting,\r hesitating, passing clouds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1819},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-21","text":"And “he who cannot bless shall LEARN to curse!”—this clear teaching\r dropt unto me from the clear heaven; this star standeth in my heaven\r even in dark nights.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1820},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-22","text":"I, however, am a blesser and a Yea-sayer, if thou be but around me, thou\r pure, thou luminous heaven! Thou abyss of light!—into all abysses do I\r then carry my beneficent Yea-saying.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1821},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-23","text":"A blesser have I become and a Yea-sayer: and therefore strove I long and\r was a striver, that I might one day get my hands free for blessing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1822},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-24","text":"This, however, is my blessing: to stand above everything as its own\r heaven, its round roof, its azure bell and eternal security: and blessed\r is he who thus blesseth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1823},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-25","text":"For all things are baptized at the font of eternity, and beyond good and\r evil; good and evil themselves, however, are but fugitive shadows and\r damp afflictions and passing clouds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1824},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-26","text":"Verily, it is a blessing and not a blasphemy when I teach that “above\r all things there standeth the heaven of chance, the heaven of innocence,\r the heaven of hazard, the heaven of wantonness.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1825},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-27","text":"“Of Hazard”—that is the oldest nobility in the world; that gave I back\r to all things; I emancipated them from bondage under purpose.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1826},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-28","text":"This freedom and celestial serenity did I put like an azure bell above\r all things, when I taught that over them and through them, no “eternal\r Will”—willeth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1827},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-29","text":"This wantonness and folly did I put in place of that Will, when I taught\r that “In everything there is one thing impossible—rationality!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1828},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-30","text":"A LITTLE reason, to be sure, a germ of wisdom scattered from star to\r star—this leaven is mixed in all things: for the sake of folly, wisdom\r is mixed in all things!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1829},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-31","text":"A little wisdom is indeed possible; but this blessed security have I\r found in all things, that they prefer—_to dance_ on the feet of chance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1830},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-32","text":"O heaven above me! thou pure, thou lofty heaven! This is now thy purity\r unto me, that there is no eternal reason-spider and reason-cobweb:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1831},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-33","text":"—That thou art to me a dancing-floor for divine chances, that thou art\r to me a table of the Gods, for divine dice and dice-players!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1832},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-34","text":"But thou blushest? Have I spoken unspeakable things? Have I abused, when\r I meant to bless thee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1833},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-35","text":"Or is it the shame of being two of us that maketh thee blush!—Dost thou\r bid me go and be silent, because now—DAY cometh?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1834},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-36","text":"The world is deep:—and deeper than e’er the day could read. Not\r everything may be uttered in presence of day. But day cometh: so let us\r part!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1835},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-69-37","text":"O heaven above me, thou modest one! thou glowing one! O thou, my\r happiness before sunrise! The day cometh: so let us part!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":1836},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-1","text":"When Zarathustra was again on the continent, he did not go straightway\r to his mountains and his cave, but made many wanderings and\r questionings, and ascertained this and that; so that he said of himself\r jestingly: “Lo, a river that floweth back unto its source in many\r windings!” For he wanted to learn what had taken place AMONG MEN during\r the interval: whether they had become greater or smaller. And once, when\r he saw a row of new houses, he marvelled, and said:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1837},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-2","text":"“What do these houses mean? Verily, no great soul put them up as its\r simile!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1838},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-3","text":"Did perhaps a silly child take them out of its toy-box? Would that\r another child put them again into the box!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1839},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-4","text":"And these rooms and chambers—can MEN go out and in there? They seem to\r be made for silk dolls; or for dainty-eaters, who perhaps let others eat\r with them.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1840},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-5","text":"And Zarathustra stood still and meditated. At last he said sorrowfully:\r “There hath EVERYTHING become smaller!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1841},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-6","text":"Everywhere do I see lower doorways: he who is of MY type can still go\r therethrough, but—he must stoop!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1842},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-7","text":"Oh, when shall I arrive again at my home, where I shall no longer have\r to stoop—shall no longer have to stoop BEFORE THE SMALL ONES!”—And\r Zarathustra sighed, and gazed into the distance.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1843},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-8","text":"The same day, however, he gave his discourse on the bedwarfing virtue.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1844},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-9","text":"I pass through this people and keep mine eyes open: they do not forgive\r me for not envying their virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1845},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-10","text":"They bite at me, because I say unto them that for small people, small\r virtues are necessary—and because it is hard for me to understand that\r small people are NECESSARY!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1846},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-11","text":"Here am I still like a cock in a strange farm-yard, at which even the\r hens peck: but on that account I am not unfriendly to the hens.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1847},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-12","text":"I am courteous towards them, as towards all small annoyances; to be\r prickly towards what is small, seemeth to me wisdom for hedgehogs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1848},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-13","text":"They all speak of me when they sit around their fire in the\r evening—they speak of me, but no one thinketh—of me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1849},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-14","text":"This is the new stillness which I have experienced: their noise around\r me spreadeth a mantle over my thoughts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1850},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-15","text":"They shout to one another: “What is this gloomy cloud about to do to us?\r Let us see that it doth not bring a plague upon us!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1851},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-16","text":"And recently did a woman seize upon her child that was coming unto\r me: “Take the children away,” cried she, “such eyes scorch children’s\r souls.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1852},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-17","text":"They cough when I speak: they think coughing an objection to strong\r winds—they divine nothing of the boisterousness of my happiness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1853},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-18","text":"“We have not yet time for Zarathustra”—so they object; but what matter\r about a time that “hath no time” for Zarathustra?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1854},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-19","text":"And if they should altogether praise me, how could I go to sleep on\r THEIR praise? A girdle of spines is their praise unto me: it scratcheth\r me even when I take it off.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1855},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-20","text":"And this also did I learn among them: the praiser doeth as if he gave\r back; in truth, however, he wanteth more to be given him!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1856},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-21","text":"Ask my foot if their lauding and luring strains please it! Verily,\r to such measure and ticktack, it liketh neither to dance nor to stand\r still.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1857},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-22","text":"To small virtues would they fain lure and laud me; to the ticktack of\r small happiness would they fain persuade my foot.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1858},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-23","text":"I pass through this people and keep mine eyes open; they have become\r SMALLER, and ever become smaller:—THE REASON THEREOF IS THEIR DOCTRINE\r OF HAPPINESS AND VIRTUE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1859},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-24","text":"For they are moderate also in virtue,—because they want comfort. With\r comfort, however, moderate virtue only is compatible.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1860},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-25","text":"To be sure, they also learn in their way to stride on and stride\r forward: that, I call their HOBBLING.—Thereby they become a hindrance\r to all who are in haste.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1861},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-26","text":"And many of them go forward, and look backwards thereby, with stiffened\r necks: those do I like to run up against.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1862},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-27","text":"Foot and eye shall not lie, nor give the lie to each other. But there is\r much lying among small people.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1863},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-28","text":"Some of them WILL, but most of them are WILLED. Some of them are\r genuine, but most of them are bad actors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1864},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-29","text":"There are actors without knowing it amongst them, and actors without\r intending it—, the genuine ones are always rare, especially the genuine\r actors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1865},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-30","text":"Of man there is little here: therefore do their women masculinise\r themselves. For only he who is man enough, will—SAVE THE WOMAN in\r woman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1866},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-31","text":"And this hypocrisy found I worst amongst them, that even those who\r command feign the virtues of those who serve.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1867},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-32","text":"“I serve, thou servest, we serve”—so chanteth here even the hypocrisy\r of the rulers—and alas! if the first lord be ONLY the first servant!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1868},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-33","text":"Ah, even upon their hypocrisy did mine eyes’ curiosity alight; and well\r did I divine all their fly-happiness, and their buzzing around sunny\r window-panes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1869},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-34","text":"So much kindness, so much weakness do I see. So much justice and pity,\r so much weakness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1870},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-35","text":"Round, fair, and considerate are they to one another, as grains of sand\r are round, fair, and considerate to grains of sand.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1871},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-36","text":"Modestly to embrace a small happiness—that do they call “submission”!\r and at the same time they peer modestly after a new small happiness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1872},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-37","text":"In their hearts they want simply one thing most of all: that no one hurt\r them. Thus do they anticipate every one’s wishes and do well unto every\r one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1873},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-38","text":"And when they chance to speak harshly, those small people, then do _I_\r hear therein only their hoarseness—every draught of air maketh them\r hoarse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1874},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-39","text":"Shrewd indeed are they, their virtues have shrewd fingers. But they lack\r fists: their fingers do not know how to creep behind fists.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1875},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-40","text":"Virtue for them is what maketh modest and tame: therewith have they made\r the wolf a dog, and man himself man’s best domestic animal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1876},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-41","text":"“We set our chair in the MIDST”—so saith their smirking unto me—“and\r as far from dying gladiators as from satisfied swine.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1877},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-42","text":"That, however, is—MEDIOCRITY, though it be called moderation.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1878},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-43","text":"I pass through this people and let fall many words: but they know\r neither how to take nor how to retain them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1879},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-44","text":"They wonder why I came not to revile venery and vice; and verily, I came\r not to warn against pickpockets either!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1880},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-45","text":"They wonder why I am not ready to abet and whet their wisdom: as if they\r had not yet enough of wiseacres, whose voices grate on mine ear like\r slate-pencils!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1881},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-46","text":"And when I call out: “Curse all the cowardly devils in you, that\r would fain whimper and fold the hands and adore”—then do they shout:\r “Zarathustra is godless.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1882},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-47","text":"And especially do their teachers of submission shout this;—but\r precisely in their ears do I love to cry: “Yea! I AM Zarathustra, the\r godless!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1883},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-48","text":"Those teachers of submission! Wherever there is aught puny, or sickly,\r or scabby, there do they creep like lice; and only my disgust preventeth\r me from cracking them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1884},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-49","text":"Well! This is my sermon for THEIR ears: I am Zarathustra the godless,\r who saith: “Who is more godless than I, that I may enjoy his teaching?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1885},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-50","text":"I am Zarathustra the godless: where do I find mine equal? And all\r those are mine equals who give unto themselves their Will, and divest\r themselves of all submission.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1886},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-51","text":"I am Zarathustra the godless! I cook every chance in MY pot. And only\r when it hath been quite cooked do I welcome it as MY food.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1887},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-52","text":"And verily, many a chance came imperiously unto me: but still more\r imperiously did my WILL speak unto it,—then did it lie imploringly upon\r its knees—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1888},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-53","text":"—Imploring that it might find home and heart with me, and saying\r flatteringly: “See, O Zarathustra, how friend only cometh unto\r friend!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1889},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-54","text":"But why talk I, when no one hath MINE ears! And so will I shout it out\r unto all the winds:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1890},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-55","text":"Ye ever become smaller, ye small people! Ye crumble away, ye comfortable\r ones! Ye will yet perish—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1891},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-56","text":"—By your many small virtues, by your many small omissions, and by your\r many small submissions!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1892},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-57","text":"Too tender, too yielding: so is your soil! But for a tree to become\r GREAT, it seeketh to twine hard roots around hard rocks!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1893},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-58","text":"Also what ye omit weaveth at the web of all the human future; even your\r naught is a cobweb, and a spider that liveth on the blood of the future.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1894},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-59","text":"And when ye take, then is it like stealing, ye small virtuous ones;\r but even among knaves HONOUR saith that “one shall only steal when one\r cannot rob.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1895},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-60","text":"“It giveth itself”—that is also a doctrine of submission. But I say\r unto you, ye comfortable ones, that IT TAKETH TO ITSELF, and will ever\r take more and more from you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1896},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-61","text":"Ah, that ye would renounce all HALF-willing, and would decide for\r idleness as ye decide for action!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1897},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-62","text":"Ah, that ye understood my word: “Do ever what ye will—but first be such\r as CAN WILL.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1898},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-63","text":"Love ever your neighbour as yourselves—but first be such as LOVE\r THEMSELVES—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1899},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-64","text":"—Such as love with great love, such as love with great contempt!” Thus\r speaketh Zarathustra the godless.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1900},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-65","text":"But why talk I, when no one hath MINE ears! It is still an hour too\r early for me here.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1901},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-66","text":"Mine own forerunner am I among this people, mine own cockcrow in dark\r lanes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1902},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-67","text":"But THEIR hour cometh! And there cometh also mine! Hourly do they become\r smaller, poorer, unfruitfuller,—poor herbs! poor earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1903},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-68","text":"And SOON shall they stand before me like dry grass and prairie, and\r verily, weary of themselves—and panting for FIRE, more than for water!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1904},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-69","text":"O blessed hour of the lightning! O mystery before noontide!—Running\r fires will I one day make of them, and heralds with flaming tongues:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1905},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-70-70","text":"—Herald shall they one day with flaming tongues: It cometh, it is nigh,\r THE GREAT NOONTIDE!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":1906},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-1","text":"Winter, a bad guest, sitteth with me at home; blue are my hands with his\r friendly hand-shaking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1907},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-2","text":"I honour him, that bad guest, but gladly leave him alone. Gladly do I\r run away from him; and when one runneth WELL, then one escapeth him!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1908},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-3","text":"With warm feet and warm thoughts do I run where the wind is calm—to the\r sunny corner of mine olive-mount.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1909},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-4","text":"There do I laugh at my stern guest, and am still fond of him; because he\r cleareth my house of flies, and quieteth many little noises.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1910},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-5","text":"For he suffereth it not if a gnat wanteth to buzz, or even two of them;\r also the lanes maketh he lonesome, so that the moonlight is afraid there\r at night.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1911},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-6","text":"A hard guest is he,—but I honour him, and do not worship, like the\r tenderlings, the pot-bellied fire-idol.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1912},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-7","text":"Better even a little teeth-chattering than idol-adoration!—so willeth\r my nature. And especially have I a grudge against all ardent, steaming,\r steamy fire-idols.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1913},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-8","text":"Him whom I love, I love better in winter than in summer; better do I\r now mock at mine enemies, and more heartily, when winter sitteth in my\r house.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1914},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-9","text":"Heartily, verily, even when I CREEP into bed—: there, still laugheth\r and wantoneth my hidden happiness; even my deceptive dream laugheth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1915},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-10","text":"I, a—creeper? Never in my life did I creep before the powerful; and if\r ever I lied, then did I lie out of love. Therefore am I glad even in my\r winter-bed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1916},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-11","text":"A poor bed warmeth me more than a rich one, for I am jealous of my\r poverty. And in winter she is most faithful unto me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1917},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-12","text":"With a wickedness do I begin every day: I mock at the winter with a cold\r bath: on that account grumbleth my stern house-mate.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1918},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-13","text":"Also do I like to tickle him with a wax-taper, that he may finally let\r the heavens emerge from ashy-grey twilight.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1919},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-14","text":"For especially wicked am I in the morning: at the early hour when the\r pail rattleth at the well, and horses neigh warmly in grey lanes:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1920},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-15","text":"Impatiently do I then wait, that the clear sky may finally dawn for me,\r the snow-bearded winter-sky, the hoary one, the whitehead,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1921},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-16","text":"—The winter-sky, the silent winter-sky, which often stifleth even its\r sun!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1922},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-17","text":"Did I perhaps learn from it the long clear silence? Or did it learn it\r from me? Or hath each of us devised it himself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1923},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-18","text":"Of all good things the origin is a thousandfold,—all good roguish\r things spring into existence for joy: how could they always do so—for\r once only!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1924},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-19","text":"A good roguish thing is also the long silence, and to look, like the\r winter-sky, out of a clear, round-eyed countenance:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1925},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-20","text":"—Like it to stifle one’s sun, and one’s inflexible solar will: verily,\r this art and this winter-roguishness have I learnt WELL!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1926},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-21","text":"My best-loved wickedness and art is it, that my silence hath learned not\r to betray itself by silence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1927},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-22","text":"Clattering with diction and dice, I outwit the solemn assistants: all\r those stern watchers, shall my will and purpose elude.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1928},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-23","text":"That no one might see down into my depth and into mine ultimate\r will—for that purpose did I devise the long clear silence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1929},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-24","text":"Many a shrewd one did I find: he veiled his countenance and made his\r water muddy, that no one might see therethrough and thereunder.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1930},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-25","text":"But precisely unto him came the shrewder distrusters and nut-crackers:\r precisely from him did they fish his best-concealed fish!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1931},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-26","text":"But the clear, the honest, the transparent—these are for me the wisest\r silent ones: in them, so PROFOUND is the depth that even the clearest\r water doth not—betray it.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1932},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-27","text":"Thou snow-bearded, silent, winter-sky, thou round-eyed whitehead above\r me! Oh, thou heavenly simile of my soul and its wantonness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1933},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-28","text":"And MUST I not conceal myself like one who hath swallowed gold—lest my\r soul should be ripped up?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1934},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-29","text":"MUST I not wear stilts, that they may OVERLOOK my long legs—all those\r enviers and injurers around me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1935},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-30","text":"Those dingy, fire-warmed, used-up, green-tinted, ill-natured souls—how\r COULD their envy endure my happiness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1936},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-31","text":"Thus do I show them only the ice and winter of my peaks—and NOT that my\r mountain windeth all the solar girdles around it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1937},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-32","text":"They hear only the whistling of my winter-storms: and know NOT that I\r also travel over warm seas, like longing, heavy, hot south-winds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1938},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-33","text":"They commiserate also my accidents and chances:—but MY word saith:\r “Suffer the chance to come unto me: innocent is it as a little child!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1939},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-34","text":"How COULD they endure my happiness, if I did not put around it\r accidents, and winter-privations, and bear-skin caps, and enmantling\r snowflakes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1940},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-35","text":"—If I did not myself commiserate their PITY, the pity of those enviers\r and injurers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1941},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-36","text":"—If I did not myself sigh before them, and chatter with cold, and\r patiently LET myself be swathed in their pity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1942},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-37","text":"This is the wise waggish-will and good-will of my soul, that it\r CONCEALETH NOT its winters and glacial storms; it concealeth not its\r chilblains either.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1943},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-38","text":"To one man, lonesomeness is the flight of the sick one; to another, it\r is the flight FROM the sick ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1944},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-39","text":"Let them HEAR me chattering and sighing with winter-cold, all those poor\r squinting knaves around me! With such sighing and chattering do I flee\r from their heated rooms.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1945},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-40","text":"Let them sympathise with me and sigh with me on account of my\r chilblains: “At the ice of knowledge will he yet FREEZE TO DEATH!”—so\r they mourn.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1946},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-71-41","text":"Meanwhile do I run with warm feet hither and thither on mine\r olive-mount: in the sunny corner of mine olive-mount do I sing, and mock\r at all pity.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":1947},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-1","text":"Thus slowly wandering through many peoples and divers cities, did\r Zarathustra return by round-about roads to his mountains and his cave.\r And behold, thereby came he unawares also to the gate of the GREAT CITY.\r Here, however, a foaming fool, with extended hands, sprang forward to\r him and stood in his way. It was the same fool whom the people called\r “the ape of Zarathustra:” for he had learned from him something of the\r expression and modulation of language, and perhaps liked also to borrow\r from the store of his wisdom. And the fool talked thus to Zarathustra:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1948},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-2","text":"O Zarathustra, here is the great city: here hast thou nothing to seek\r and everything to lose.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1949},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-3","text":"Why wouldst thou wade through this mire? Have pity upon thy foot! Spit\r rather on the gate of the city, and—turn back!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1950},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-4","text":"Here is the hell for anchorites’ thoughts: here are great thoughts\r seethed alive and boiled small.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1951},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-5","text":"Here do all great sentiments decay: here may only rattle-boned\r sensations rattle!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1952},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-6","text":"Smellest thou not already the shambles and cookshops of the spirit?\r Steameth not this city with the fumes of slaughtered spirit?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1953},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-7","text":"Seest thou not the souls hanging like limp dirty rags?—And they make\r newspapers also out of these rags!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1954},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-8","text":"Hearest thou not how spirit hath here become a verbal game? Loathsome\r verbal swill doth it vomit forth!—And they make newspapers also out of\r this verbal swill.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1955},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-9","text":"They hound one another, and know not whither! They inflame one another,\r and know not why! They tinkle with their pinchbeck, they jingle with\r their gold.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1956},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-10","text":"They are cold, and seek warmth from distilled waters: they are inflamed,\r and seek coolness from frozen spirits; they are all sick and sore\r through public opinion.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1957},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-11","text":"All lusts and vices are here at home; but here there are also the\r virtuous; there is much appointable appointed virtue:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1958},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-12","text":"Much appointable virtue with scribe-fingers, and hardy sitting-flesh and\r waiting-flesh, blessed with small breast-stars, and padded, haunchless\r daughters.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1959},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-13","text":"There is here also much piety, and much faithful spittle-licking and\r spittle-backing, before the God of Hosts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1960},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-14","text":"“From on high,” drippeth the star, and the gracious spittle; for the\r high, longeth every starless bosom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1961},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-15","text":"The moon hath its court, and the court hath its moon-calves: unto all,\r however, that cometh from the court do the mendicant people pray, and\r all appointable mendicant virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1962},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-16","text":"“I serve, thou servest, we serve”—so prayeth all appointable virtue\r to the prince: that the merited star may at last stick on the slender\r breast!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1963},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-17","text":"But the moon still revolveth around all that is earthly: so revolveth\r also the prince around what is earthliest of all—that, however, is the\r gold of the shopman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1964},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-18","text":"The God of the Hosts of war is not the God of the golden bar; the prince\r proposeth, but the shopman—disposeth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1965},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-19","text":"By all that is luminous and strong and good in thee, O Zarathustra! Spit\r on this city of shopmen and return back!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1966},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-20","text":"Here floweth all blood putridly and tepidly and frothily through all\r veins: spit on the great city, which is the great slum where all the\r scum frotheth together!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1967},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-21","text":"Spit on the city of compressed souls and slender breasts, of pointed\r eyes and sticky fingers—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1968},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-22","text":"—On the city of the obtrusive, the brazen-faced, the pen-demagogues and\r tongue-demagogues, the overheated ambitious:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1969},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-23","text":"Where everything maimed, ill-famed, lustful, untrustful, over-mellow,\r sickly-yellow and seditious, festereth pernicious:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1970},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-24","text":"Here, however, did Zarathustra interrupt the foaming fool, and shut his\r mouth.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1971},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-25","text":"Stop this at once! called out Zarathustra, long have thy speech and thy\r species disgusted me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1972},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-26","text":"Why didst thou live so long by the swamp, that thou thyself hadst to\r become a frog and a toad?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1973},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-27","text":"Floweth there not a tainted, frothy, swamp-blood in thine own veins,\r when thou hast thus learned to croak and revile?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1974},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-28","text":"Why wentest thou not into the forest? Or why didst thou not till the\r ground? Is the sea not full of green islands?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1975},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-29","text":"I despise thy contempt; and when thou warnedst me—why didst thou not\r warn thyself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1976},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-30","text":"Out of love alone shall my contempt and my warning bird take wing; but\r not out of the swamp!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1977},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-31","text":"They call thee mine ape, thou foaming fool: but I call thee my\r grunting-pig,—by thy grunting, thou spoilest even my praise of folly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1978},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-32","text":"What was it that first made thee grunt? Because no one sufficiently\r FLATTERED thee:—therefore didst thou seat thyself beside this filth,\r that thou mightest have cause for much grunting,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1979},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-33","text":"—That thou mightest have cause for much VENGEANCE! For vengeance, thou\r vain fool, is all thy foaming; I have divined thee well!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1980},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-34","text":"But thy fools’-word injureth ME, even when thou art right! And even if\r Zarathustra’s word WERE a hundred times justified, thou wouldst ever—DO\r wrong with my word!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1981},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-35","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. Then did he look on the great city and sighed,\r and was long silent. At last he spake thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1982},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-36","text":"I loathe also this great city, and not only this fool. Here and there—\r there is nothing to better, nothing to worsen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1983},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-37","text":"Woe to this great city!—And I would that I already saw the pillar of\r fire in which it will be consumed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1984},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-38","text":"For such pillars of fire must precede the great noontide. But this hath\r its time and its own fate.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1985},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-39","text":"This precept, however, give I unto thee, in parting, thou fool: Where\r one can no longer love, there should one—PASS BY!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1986},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-72-40","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and passed by the fool and the great city.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":1987},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-1","text":"Ah, lieth everything already withered and grey which but lately stood\r green and many-hued on this meadow! And how much honey of hope did I\r carry hence into my beehives!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1988},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-2","text":"Those young hearts have already all become old—and not old even! only\r weary, ordinary, comfortable:—they declare it: “We have again become\r pious.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1989},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-3","text":"Of late did I see them run forth at early morn with valorous steps: but\r the feet of their knowledge became weary, and now do they malign even\r their morning valour!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1990},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-4","text":"Verily, many of them once lifted their legs like the dancer; to them\r winked the laughter of my wisdom:—then did they bethink themselves.\r Just now have I seen them bent down—to creep to the cross.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1991},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-5","text":"Around light and liberty did they once flutter like gnats and young\r poets. A little older, a little colder: and already are they mystifiers,\r and mumblers and mollycoddles.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1992},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-6","text":"Did perhaps their hearts despond, because lonesomeness had swallowed me\r like a whale? Did their ear perhaps hearken yearningly-long for me IN\r VAIN, and for my trumpet-notes and herald-calls?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1993},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-7","text":"—Ah! Ever are there but few of those whose hearts have persistent\r courage and exuberance; and in such remaineth also the spirit patient.\r The rest, however, are COWARDLY.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1994},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-8","text":"The rest: these are always the great majority, the common-place, the\r superfluous, the far too many—those all are cowardly!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1995},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-9","text":"Him who is of my type, will also the experiences of my type meet on the\r way: so that his first companions must be corpses and buffoons.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1996},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-10","text":"His second companions, however—they will call themselves his\r BELIEVERS,—will be a living host, with much love, much folly, much\r unbearded veneration.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1997},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-11","text":"To those believers shall he who is of my type among men not bind his\r heart; in those spring-times and many-hued meadows shall he not believe,\r who knoweth the fickly faint-hearted human species!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1998},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-12","text":"COULD they do otherwise, then would they also WILL otherwise. The\r half-and-half spoil every whole. That leaves become withered,—what is\r there to lament about that!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":1999},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-13","text":"Let them go and fall away, O Zarathustra, and do not lament! Better even\r to blow amongst them with rustling winds,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2000},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-14","text":"—Blow amongst those leaves, O Zarathustra, that everything WITHERED may\r run away from thee the faster!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2001},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-15","text":"“We have again become pious”—so do those apostates confess; and some of\r them are still too pusillanimous thus to confess.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2002},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-16","text":"Unto them I look into the eye,—before them I say it unto their face and\r unto the blush on their cheeks: Ye are those who again PRAY!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2003},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-17","text":"It is however a shame to pray! Not for all, but for thee, and me, and\r whoever hath his conscience in his head. For THEE it is a shame to pray!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2004},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-18","text":"Thou knowest it well: the faint-hearted devil in thee, which would\r fain fold its arms, and place its hands in its bosom, and take it\r easier:—this faint-hearted devil persuadeth thee that “there IS a God!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2005},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-19","text":"THEREBY, however, dost thou belong to the light-dreading type, to whom\r light never permitteth repose: now must thou daily thrust thy head\r deeper into obscurity and vapour!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2006},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-20","text":"And verily, thou choosest the hour well: for just now do the nocturnal\r birds again fly abroad. The hour hath come for all light-dreading\r people, the vesper hour and leisure hour, when they do not—“take\r leisure.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2007},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-21","text":"I hear it and smell it: it hath come—their hour for hunt and\r procession, not indeed for a wild hunt, but for a tame, lame, snuffling,\r soft-treaders’, soft-prayers’ hunt,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2008},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-22","text":"—For a hunt after susceptible simpletons: all mouse-traps for the heart\r have again been set! And whenever I lift a curtain, a night-moth rusheth\r out of it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2009},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-23","text":"Did it perhaps squat there along with another night-moth? For everywhere\r do I smell small concealed communities; and wherever there are closets\r there are new devotees therein, and the atmosphere of devotees.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2010},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-24","text":"They sit for long evenings beside one another, and say: “Let us again\r become like little children and say, ‘good God!’”—ruined in mouths and\r stomachs by the pious confectioners.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2011},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-25","text":"Or they look for long evenings at a crafty, lurking cross-spider, that\r preacheth prudence to the spiders themselves, and teacheth that “under\r crosses it is good for cobweb-spinning!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2012},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-26","text":"Or they sit all day at swamps with angle-rods, and on that account think\r themselves PROFOUND; but whoever fisheth where there are no fish, I do\r not even call him superficial!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2013},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-27","text":"Or they learn in godly-gay style to play the harp with a hymn-poet,\r who would fain harp himself into the heart of young girls:—for he hath\r tired of old girls and their praises.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2014},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-28","text":"Or they learn to shudder with a learned semi-madcap, who waiteth in\r darkened rooms for spirits to come to him—and the spirit runneth away\r entirely!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2015},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-29","text":"Or they listen to an old roving howl- and growl-piper, who hath learnt\r from the sad winds the sadness of sounds; now pipeth he as the wind, and\r preacheth sadness in sad strains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2016},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-30","text":"And some of them have even become night-watchmen: they know now how to\r blow horns, and go about at night and awaken old things which have long\r fallen asleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2017},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-31","text":"Five words about old things did I hear yester-night at the garden-wall:\r they came from such old, sorrowful, arid night-watchmen.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2018},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-32","text":"“For a father he careth not sufficiently for his children: human fathers\r do this better!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2019},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-33","text":"“He is too old! He now careth no more for his children,”—answered the\r other night-watchman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2020},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-34","text":"“HATH he then children? No one can prove it unless he himself prove it!\r I have long wished that he would for once prove it thoroughly.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2021},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-35","text":"“Prove? As if HE had ever proved anything! Proving is difficult to him;\r he layeth great stress on one’s BELIEVING him.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2022},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-36","text":"“Ay! Ay! Belief saveth him; belief in him. That is the way with old\r people! So it is with us also!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2023},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-37","text":"—Thus spake to each other the two old night-watchmen and light-scarers,\r and tooted thereupon sorrowfully on their horns: so did it happen\r yester-night at the garden-wall.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2024},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-38","text":"To me, however, did the heart writhe with laughter, and was like to\r break; it knew not where to go, and sunk into the midriff.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2025},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-39","text":"Verily, it will be my death yet—to choke with laughter when I see asses\r drunken, and hear night-watchmen thus doubt about God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2026},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-40","text":"Hath the time not LONG since passed for all such doubts? Who may\r nowadays awaken such old slumbering, light-shunning things!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2027},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-41","text":"With the old Deities hath it long since come to an end:—and verily, a\r good joyful Deity-end had they!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2028},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-42","text":"They did not “begloom” themselves to death—that do people fabricate! On\r the contrary, they—LAUGHED themselves to death once on a time!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2029},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-43","text":"That took place when the unGodliest utterance came from a God\r himself—the utterance: “There is but one God! Thou shalt have no other\r Gods before me!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2030},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-44","text":"—An old grim-beard of a God, a jealous one, forgot himself in such\r wise:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2031},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-45","text":"And all the Gods then laughed, and shook upon their thrones, and\r exclaimed: “Is it not just divinity that there are Gods, but no God?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2032},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-73-46","text":"Thus talked Zarathustra in the city he loved, which is surnamed “The\r Pied Cow.” For from here he had but two days to travel to reach once\r more his cave and his animals; his soul, however, rejoiced unceasingly\r on account of the nighness of his return home.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2033},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-1","text":"O lonesomeness! My HOME, lonesomeness! Too long have I lived wildly in\r wild remoteness, to return to thee without tears!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2034},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-2","text":"Now threaten me with the finger as mothers threaten; now smile upon me\r as mothers smile; now say just: “Who was it that like a whirlwind once\r rushed away from me?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2035},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-3","text":"—Who when departing called out: ‘Too long have I sat with lonesomeness;\r there have I unlearned silence!’ THAT hast thou learned now—surely?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2036},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-4","text":"O Zarathustra, everything do I know; and that thou wert MORE FORSAKEN\r amongst the many, thou unique one, than thou ever wert with me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2037},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-5","text":"One thing is forsakenness, another matter is lonesomeness: THAT hast\r thou now learned! And that amongst men thou wilt ever be wild and\r strange:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2038},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-6","text":"—Wild and strange even when they love thee: for above all they want to\r be TREATED INDULGENTLY!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2039},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-7","text":"Here, however, art thou at home and house with thyself; here canst thou\r utter everything, and unbosom all motives; nothing is here ashamed of\r concealed, congealed feelings.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2040},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-8","text":"Here do all things come caressingly to thy talk and flatter thee: for\r they want to ride upon thy back. On every simile dost thou here ride to\r every truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2041},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-9","text":"Uprightly and openly mayest thou here talk to all things: and verily,\r it soundeth as praise in their ears, for one to talk to all\r things—directly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2042},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-10","text":"Another matter, however, is forsakenness. For, dost thou remember, O\r Zarathustra? When thy bird screamed overhead, when thou stoodest in the\r forest, irresolute, ignorant where to go, beside a corpse:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2043},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-11","text":"—When thou spakest: ‘Let mine animals lead me! More dangerous have I\r found it among men than among animals:’—THAT was forsakenness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2044},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-12","text":"And dost thou remember, O Zarathustra? When thou sattest in thine isle,\r a well of wine giving and granting amongst empty buckets, bestowing and\r distributing amongst the thirsty:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2045},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-13","text":"—Until at last thou alone sattest thirsty amongst the drunken ones, and\r wailedst nightly: ‘Is taking not more blessed than giving? And stealing\r yet more blessed than taking?’—THAT was forsakenness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2046},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-14","text":"And dost thou remember, O Zarathustra? When thy stillest hour came and\r drove thee forth from thyself, when with wicked whispering it said:\r ‘Speak and succumb!’—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2047},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-15","text":"—When it disgusted thee with all thy waiting and silence, and\r discouraged thy humble courage: THAT was forsakenness!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2048},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-16","text":"O lonesomeness! My home, lonesomeness! How blessedly and tenderly\r speaketh thy voice unto me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2049},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-17","text":"We do not question each other, we do not complain to each other; we go\r together openly through open doors.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2050},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-18","text":"For all is open with thee and clear; and even the hours run here on\r lighter feet. For in the dark, time weigheth heavier upon one than in\r the light.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2051},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-19","text":"Here fly open unto me all being’s words and word-cabinets: here all\r being wanteth to become words, here all becoming wanteth to learn of me\r how to talk.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2052},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-20","text":"Down there, however—all talking is in vain! There, forgetting and\r passing-by are the best wisdom: THAT have I learned now!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2053},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-21","text":"He who would understand everything in man must handle everything. But\r for that I have too clean hands.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2054},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-22","text":"I do not like even to inhale their breath; alas! that I have lived so\r long among their noise and bad breaths!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2055},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-23","text":"O blessed stillness around me! O pure odours around me! How from a deep\r breast this stillness fetcheth pure breath! How it hearkeneth, this\r blessed stillness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2056},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-24","text":"But down there—there speaketh everything, there is everything misheard.\r If one announce one’s wisdom with bells, the shopmen in the market-place\r will out-jingle it with pennies!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2057},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-25","text":"Everything among them talketh; no one knoweth any longer how to\r understand. Everything falleth into the water; nothing falleth any\r longer into deep wells.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2058},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-26","text":"Everything among them talketh, nothing succeedeth any longer and\r accomplisheth itself. Everything cackleth, but who will still sit\r quietly on the nest and hatch eggs?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2059},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-27","text":"Everything among them talketh, everything is out-talked. And that which\r yesterday was still too hard for time itself and its tooth, hangeth\r to-day, outchamped and outchewed, from the mouths of the men of to-day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2060},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-28","text":"Everything among them talketh, everything is betrayed. And what was once\r called the secret and secrecy of profound souls, belongeth to-day to the\r street-trumpeters and other butterflies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2061},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-29","text":"O human hubbub, thou wonderful thing! Thou noise in dark streets! Now\r art thou again behind me:—my greatest danger lieth behind me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2062},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-30","text":"In indulging and pitying lay ever my greatest danger; and all human\r hubbub wisheth to be indulged and tolerated.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2063},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-31","text":"With suppressed truths, with fool’s hand and befooled heart, and rich in\r petty lies of pity:—thus have I ever lived among men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2064},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-32","text":"Disguised did I sit amongst them, ready to misjudge MYSELF that I might\r endure THEM, and willingly saying to myself: “Thou fool, thou dost not\r know men!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2065},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-33","text":"One unlearneth men when one liveth amongst them: there is too much\r foreground in all men—what can far-seeing, far-longing eyes do THERE!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2066},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-34","text":"And, fool that I was, when they misjudged me, I indulged them on that\r account more than myself, being habitually hard on myself, and often\r even taking revenge on myself for the indulgence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2067},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-35","text":"Stung all over by poisonous flies, and hollowed like the stone by\r many drops of wickedness: thus did I sit among them, and still said to\r myself: “Innocent is everything petty of its pettiness!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2068},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-36","text":"Especially did I find those who call themselves “the good,” the most\r poisonous flies; they sting in all innocence, they lie in all innocence;\r how COULD they—be just towards me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2069},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-37","text":"He who liveth amongst the good—pity teacheth him to lie. Pity maketh\r stifling air for all free souls. For the stupidity of the good is\r unfathomable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2070},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-38","text":"To conceal myself and my riches—THAT did I learn down there: for every\r one did I still find poor in spirit. It was the lie of my pity, that I\r knew in every one,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2071},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-39","text":"—That I saw and scented in every one, what was ENOUGH of spirit for\r him, and what was TOO MUCH!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2072},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-40","text":"Their stiff wise men: I call them wise, not stiff—thus did I learn to\r slur over words.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2073},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-41","text":"The grave-diggers dig for themselves diseases. Under old rubbish rest\r bad vapours. One should not stir up the marsh. One should live on\r mountains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2074},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-42","text":"With blessed nostrils do I again breathe mountain-freedom. Freed at last\r is my nose from the smell of all human hubbub!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2075},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-74-43","text":"With sharp breezes tickled, as with sparkling wine, SNEEZETH my soul—\r sneezeth, and shouteth self-congratulatingly: “Health to thee!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2076},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-1","text":"In my dream, in my last morning-dream, I stood to-day on a promontory—\r beyond the world; I held a pair of scales, and WEIGHED the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2077},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-2","text":"Alas, that the rosy dawn came too early to me: she glowed me awake, the\r jealous one! Jealous is she always of the glows of my morning-dream.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2078},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-3","text":"Measurable by him who hath time, weighable by a good weigher, attainable\r by strong pinions, divinable by divine nut-crackers: thus did my dream\r find the world:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2079},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-4","text":"My dream, a bold sailor, half-ship, half-hurricane, silent as the\r butterfly, impatient as the falcon: how had it the patience and leisure\r to-day for world-weighing!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2080},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-5","text":"Did my wisdom perhaps speak secretly to it, my laughing, wide-awake\r day-wisdom, which mocketh at all “infinite worlds”? For it saith: “Where\r force is, there becometh NUMBER the master: it hath more force.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2081},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-6","text":"How confidently did my dream contemplate this finite world, not\r new-fangledly, not old-fangledly, not timidly, not entreatingly:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2082},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-7","text":"—As if a big round apple presented itself to my hand, a ripe golden\r apple, with a coolly-soft, velvety skin:—thus did the world present\r itself unto me:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2083},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-8","text":"—As if a tree nodded unto me, a broad-branched, strong-willed tree,\r curved as a recline and a foot-stool for weary travellers: thus did the\r world stand on my promontory:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2084},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-9","text":"—As if delicate hands carried a casket towards me—a casket open for\r the delectation of modest adoring eyes: thus did the world present\r itself before me to-day:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2085},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-10","text":"—Not riddle enough to scare human love from it, not solution enough\r to put to sleep human wisdom:—a humanly good thing was the world to me\r to-day, of which such bad things are said!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2086},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-11","text":"How I thank my morning-dream that I thus at to-day’s dawn, weighed\r the world! As a humanly good thing did it come unto me, this dream and\r heart-comforter!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2087},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-12","text":"And that I may do the like by day, and imitate and copy its best, now\r will I put the three worst things on the scales, and weigh them humanly\r well.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2088},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-13","text":"He who taught to bless taught also to curse: what are the three best\r cursed things in the world? These will I put on the scales.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2089},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-14","text":"VOLUPTUOUSNESS, PASSION FOR POWER, and SELFISHNESS: these three things\r have hitherto been best cursed, and have been in worst and falsest\r repute—these three things will I weigh humanly well.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2090},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-15","text":"Well! Here is my promontory, and there is the sea—IT rolleth hither\r unto me, shaggily and fawningly, the old, faithful, hundred-headed\r dog-monster that I love!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2091},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-16","text":"Well! Here will I hold the scales over the weltering sea: and also a\r witness do I choose to look on—thee, the anchorite-tree, thee, the\r strong-odoured, broad-arched tree that I love!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2092},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-17","text":"On what bridge goeth the now to the hereafter? By what constraint doth\r the high stoop to the low? And what enjoineth even the highest still—to\r grow upwards?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2093},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-18","text":"Now stand the scales poised and at rest: three heavy questions have I\r thrown in; three heavy answers carrieth the other scale.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2094},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-19","text":"Voluptuousness: unto all hair-shirted despisers of the body, a sting and\r stake; and, cursed as “the world,” by all backworldsmen: for it mocketh\r and befooleth all erring, misinferring teachers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2095},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-20","text":"Voluptuousness: to the rabble, the slow fire at which it is burnt;\r to all wormy wood, to all stinking rags, the prepared heat and stew\r furnace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2096},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-21","text":"Voluptuousness: to free hearts, a thing innocent and free, the\r garden-happiness of the earth, all the future’s thanks-overflow to the\r present.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2097},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-22","text":"Voluptuousness: only to the withered a sweet poison; to the lion-willed,\r however, the great cordial, and the reverently saved wine of wines.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2098},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-23","text":"Voluptuousness: the great symbolic happiness of a higher happiness\r and highest hope. For to many is marriage promised, and more than\r marriage,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2099},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-24","text":"—To many that are more unknown to each other than man and woman:—and\r who hath fully understood HOW UNKNOWN to each other are man and woman!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2100},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-25","text":"Voluptuousness:—but I will have hedges around my thoughts, and\r even around my words, lest swine and libertine should break into my\r gardens!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2101},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-26","text":"Passion for power: the glowing scourge of the hardest of the heart-hard;\r the cruel torture reserved for the cruellest themselves; the gloomy\r flame of living pyres.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2102},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-27","text":"Passion for power: the wicked gadfly which is mounted on the vainest\r peoples; the scorner of all uncertain virtue; which rideth on every\r horse and on every pride.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2103},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-28","text":"Passion for power: the earthquake which breaketh and upbreaketh all\r that is rotten and hollow; the rolling, rumbling, punitive demolisher\r of whited sepulchres; the flashing interrogative-sign beside premature\r answers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2104},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-29","text":"Passion for power: before whose glance man creepeth and croucheth and\r drudgeth, and becometh lower than the serpent and the swine:—until at\r last great contempt crieth out of him—,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2105},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-30","text":"Passion for power: the terrible teacher of great contempt, which\r preacheth to their face to cities and empires: “Away with thee!”—until\r a voice crieth out of themselves: “Away with ME!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2106},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-31","text":"Passion for power: which, however, mounteth alluringly even to the pure\r and lonesome, and up to self-satisfied elevations, glowing like a love\r that painteth purple felicities alluringly on earthly heavens.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2107},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-32","text":"Passion for power: but who would call it PASSION, when the height\r longeth to stoop for power! Verily, nothing sick or diseased is there in\r such longing and descending!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2108},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-33","text":"That the lonesome height may not for ever remain lonesome and\r self-sufficing; that the mountains may come to the valleys and the winds\r of the heights to the plains:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2109},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-34","text":"Oh, who could find the right prenomen and honouring name for such\r longing! “Bestowing virtue”—thus did Zarathustra once name the\r unnamable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2110},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-35","text":"And then it happened also,—and verily, it happened for the first\r time!—that his word blessed SELFISHNESS, the wholesome, healthy\r selfishness, that springeth from the powerful soul:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2111},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-36","text":"—From the powerful soul, to which the high body appertaineth, the\r handsome, triumphing, refreshing body, around which everything becometh\r a mirror:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2112},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-37","text":"—The pliant, persuasive body, the dancer, whose symbol and epitome\r is the self-enjoying soul. Of such bodies and souls the self-enjoyment\r calleth itself “virtue.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2113},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-38","text":"With its words of good and bad doth such self-enjoyment shelter itself\r as with sacred groves; with the names of its happiness doth it banish\r from itself everything contemptible.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2114},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-39","text":"Away from itself doth it banish everything cowardly; it saith:\r “Bad—THAT IS cowardly!” Contemptible seem to it the ever-solicitous,\r the sighing, the complaining, and whoever pick up the most trifling\r advantage.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2115},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-40","text":"It despiseth also all bitter-sweet wisdom: for verily, there is also\r wisdom that bloometh in the dark, a night-shade wisdom, which ever\r sigheth: “All is vain!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2116},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-41","text":"Shy distrust is regarded by it as base, and every one who wanteth oaths\r instead of looks and hands: also all over-distrustful wisdom,—for such\r is the mode of cowardly souls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2117},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-42","text":"Baser still it regardeth the obsequious, doggish one, who immediately\r lieth on his back, the submissive one; and there is also wisdom that is\r submissive, and doggish, and pious, and obsequious.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2118},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-43","text":"Hateful to it altogether, and a loathing, is he who will never defend\r himself, he who swalloweth down poisonous spittle and bad looks, the\r all-too-patient one, the all-endurer, the all-satisfied one: for that is\r the mode of slaves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2119},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-44","text":"Whether they be servile before Gods and divine spurnings, or before men\r and stupid human opinions: at ALL kinds of slaves doth it spit, this\r blessed selfishness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2120},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-45","text":"Bad: thus doth it call all that is spirit-broken, and\r sordidly-servile—constrained, blinking eyes, depressed hearts, and the\r false submissive style, which kisseth with broad cowardly lips.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2121},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-46","text":"And spurious wisdom: so doth it call all the wit that slaves, and\r hoary-headed and weary ones affect; and especially all the cunning,\r spurious-witted, curious-witted foolishness of priests!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2122},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-47","text":"The spurious wise, however, all the priests, the world-weary, and those\r whose souls are of feminine and servile nature—oh, how hath their game\r all along abused selfishness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2123},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-48","text":"And precisely THAT was to be virtue and was to be called virtue—to\r abuse selfishness! And “selfless”—so did they wish themselves with good\r reason, all those world-weary cowards and cross-spiders!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2124},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-49","text":"But to all those cometh now the day, the change, the sword of judgment,\r THE GREAT NOONTIDE: then shall many things be revealed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2125},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-75-50","text":"And he who proclaimeth the EGO wholesome and holy, and selfishness\r blessed, verily, he, the prognosticator, speaketh also what he knoweth:\r “BEHOLD, IT COMETH, IT IS NIGH, THE GREAT NOONTIDE!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2126},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-1","text":"My mouthpiece—is of the people: too coarsely and cordially do I\r talk for Angora rabbits. And still stranger soundeth my word unto all\r ink-fish and pen-foxes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2127},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-2","text":"My hand—is a fool’s hand: woe unto all tables and walls, and whatever\r hath room for fool’s sketching, fool’s scrawling!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2128},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-3","text":"My foot—is a horse-foot; therewith do I trample and trot over stick and\r stone, in the fields up and down, and am bedevilled with delight in all\r fast racing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2129},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-4","text":"My stomach—is surely an eagle’s stomach? For it preferreth lamb’s\r flesh. Certainly it is a bird’s stomach.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2130},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-5","text":"Nourished with innocent things, and with few, ready and impatient\r to fly, to fly away—that is now my nature: why should there not be\r something of bird-nature therein!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2131},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-6","text":"And especially that I am hostile to the spirit of gravity, that is\r bird-nature:—verily, deadly hostile, supremely hostile, originally\r hostile! Oh, whither hath my hostility not flown and misflown!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2132},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-7","text":"Thereof could I sing a song—and WILL sing it: though I be alone in an\r empty house, and must sing it to mine own ears.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2133},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-8","text":"Other singers are there, to be sure, to whom only the full house\r maketh the voice soft, the hand eloquent, the eye expressive, the heart\r wakeful:—those do I not resemble.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2134},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-9","text":"He who one day teacheth men to fly will have shifted all landmarks; to\r him will all landmarks themselves fly into the air; the earth will he\r christen anew—as “the light body.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2135},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-10","text":"The ostrich runneth faster than the fastest horse, but it also thrusteth\r its head heavily into the heavy earth: thus is it with the man who\r cannot yet fly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2136},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-11","text":"Heavy unto him are earth and life, and so WILLETH the spirit of gravity!\r But he who would become light, and be a bird, must love himself:—thus\r do _I_ teach.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2137},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-12","text":"Not, to be sure, with the love of the sick and infected, for with them\r stinketh even self-love!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2138},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-13","text":"One must learn to love oneself—thus do I teach—with a wholesome and\r healthy love: that one may endure to be with oneself, and not go roving\r about.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2139},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-14","text":"Such roving about christeneth itself “brotherly love”; with these words\r hath there hitherto been the best lying and dissembling, and especially\r by those who have been burdensome to every one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2140},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-15","text":"And verily, it is no commandment for to-day and to-morrow to LEARN to\r love oneself. Rather is it of all arts the finest, subtlest, last and\r patientest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2141},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-16","text":"For to its possessor is all possession well concealed, and of all\r treasure-pits one’s own is last excavated—so causeth the spirit of\r gravity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2142},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-17","text":"Almost in the cradle are we apportioned with heavy words and worths:\r “good” and “evil”—so calleth itself this dowry. For the sake of it we\r are forgiven for living.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2143},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-18","text":"And therefore suffereth one little children to come unto one, to forbid\r them betimes to love themselves—so causeth the spirit of gravity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2144},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-19","text":"And we—we bear loyally what is apportioned unto us, on hard shoulders,\r over rugged mountains! And when we sweat, then do people say to us:\r “Yea, life is hard to bear!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2145},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-20","text":"But man himself only is hard to bear! The reason thereof is that he\r carrieth too many extraneous things on his shoulders. Like the camel\r kneeleth he down, and letteth himself be well laden.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2146},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-21","text":"Especially the strong load-bearing man in whom reverence resideth. Too\r many EXTRANEOUS heavy words and worths loadeth he upon himself—then\r seemeth life to him a desert!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2147},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-22","text":"And verily! Many a thing also that is OUR OWN is hard to bear! And many\r internal things in man are like the oyster—repulsive and slippery and\r hard to grasp;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2148},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-23","text":"So that an elegant shell, with elegant adornment, must plead for\r them. But this art also must one learn: to HAVE a shell, and a fine\r appearance, and sagacious blindness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2149},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-24","text":"Again, it deceiveth about many things in man, that many a shell is poor\r and pitiable, and too much of a shell. Much concealed goodness and power\r is never dreamt of; the choicest dainties find no tasters!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2150},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-25","text":"Women know that, the choicest of them: a little fatter a little leaner—\r oh, how much fate is in so little!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2151},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-26","text":"Man is difficult to discover, and unto himself most difficult of all;\r often lieth the spirit concerning the soul. So causeth the spirit of\r gravity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2152},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-27","text":"He, however, hath discovered himself who saith: This is MY good and\r evil: therewith hath he silenced the mole and the dwarf, who say: “Good\r for all, evil for all.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2153},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-28","text":"Verily, neither do I like those who call everything good, and this world\r the best of all. Those do I call the all-satisfied.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2154},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-29","text":"All-satisfiedness, which knoweth how to taste everything,—that is\r not the best taste! I honour the refractory, fastidious tongues and\r stomachs, which have learned to say “I” and “Yea” and “Nay.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2155},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-30","text":"To chew and digest everything, however—that is the genuine\r swine-nature! Ever to say YE-A—that hath only the ass learnt, and those\r like it!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2156},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-31","text":"Deep yellow and hot red—so wanteth MY taste—it mixeth blood with all\r colours. He, however, who whitewasheth his house, betrayeth unto me a\r whitewashed soul.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2157},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-32","text":"With mummies, some fall in love; others with phantoms: both alike\r hostile to all flesh and blood—oh, how repugnant are both to my taste!\r For I love blood.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2158},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-33","text":"And there will I not reside and abide where every one spitteth and\r speweth: that is now MY taste,—rather would I live amongst thieves and\r perjurers. Nobody carrieth gold in his mouth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2159},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-34","text":"Still more repugnant unto me, however, are all lickspittles; and the\r most repugnant animal of man that I found, did I christen “parasite”: it\r would not love, and would yet live by love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2160},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-35","text":"Unhappy do I call all those who have only one choice: either to become\r evil beasts, or evil beast-tamers. Amongst such would I not build my\r tabernacle.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2161},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-36","text":"Unhappy do I also call those who have ever to WAIT,—they are repugnant\r to my taste—all the toll-gatherers and traders, and kings, and other\r landkeepers and shopkeepers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2162},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-37","text":"Verily, I learned waiting also, and thoroughly so,—but only waiting for\r MYSELF. And above all did I learn standing and walking and running and\r leaping and climbing and dancing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2163},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-38","text":"This however is my teaching: he who wisheth one day to fly, must first\r learn standing and walking and running and climbing and dancing:—one\r doth not fly into flying!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2164},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-39","text":"With rope-ladders learned I to reach many a window, with nimble legs did\r I climb high masts: to sit on high masts of perception seemed to me no\r small bliss;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2165},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-40","text":"—To flicker like small flames on high masts: a small light, certainly,\r but a great comfort to cast-away sailors and shipwrecked ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2166},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-41","text":"By divers ways and wendings did I arrive at my truth; not by one ladder\r did I mount to the height where mine eye roveth into my remoteness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2167},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-42","text":"And unwillingly only did I ask my way—that was always counter to my\r taste! Rather did I question and test the ways themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2168},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-43","text":"A testing and a questioning hath been all my travelling:—and verily,\r one must also LEARN to answer such questioning! That, however,—is my\r taste:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2169},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-44","text":"—Neither a good nor a bad taste, but MY taste, of which I have no\r longer either shame or secrecy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2170},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-76-45","text":"“This—is now MY way,—where is yours?” Thus did I answer those who\r asked me “the way.” For THE way—it doth not exist!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2171},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-1","text":"Here do I sit and wait, old broken tables around me and also new\r half-written tables. When cometh mine hour?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2172},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-2","text":"—The hour of my descent, of my down-going: for once more will I go unto\r men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2173},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-3","text":"For that hour do I now wait: for first must the signs come unto me that\r it is MINE hour—namely, the laughing lion with the flock of doves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2174},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-4","text":"Meanwhile do I talk to myself as one who hath time. No one telleth me\r anything new, so I tell myself mine own story.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2175},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-5","text":"When I came unto men, then found I them resting on an old infatuation:\r all of them thought they had long known what was good and bad for men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2176},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-6","text":"An old wearisome business seemed to them all discourse about virtue; and\r he who wished to sleep well spake of “good” and “bad” ere retiring to\r rest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2177},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-7","text":"This somnolence did I disturb when I taught that NO ONE YET KNOWETH what\r is good and bad:—unless it be the creating one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2178},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-8","text":"—It is he, however, who createth man’s goal, and giveth to the earth\r its meaning and its future: he only EFFECTETH it THAT aught is good or\r bad.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2179},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-9","text":"And I bade them upset their old academic chairs, and wherever that old\r infatuation had sat; I bade them laugh at their great moralists, their\r saints, their poets, and their Saviours.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2180},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-10","text":"At their gloomy sages did I bid them laugh, and whoever had sat\r admonishing as a black scarecrow on the tree of life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2181},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-11","text":"On their great grave-highway did I seat myself, and even beside the\r carrion and vultures—and I laughed at all their bygone and its mellow\r decaying glory.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2182},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-12","text":"Verily, like penitential preachers and fools did I cry wrath and shame\r on all their greatness and smallness. Oh, that their best is so very\r small! Oh, that their worst is so very small! Thus did I laugh.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2183},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-13","text":"Thus did my wise longing, born in the mountains, cry and laugh in me; a\r wild wisdom, verily!—my great pinion-rustling longing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2184},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-14","text":"And oft did it carry me off and up and away and in the midst of\r laughter; then flew I quivering like an arrow with sun-intoxicated\r rapture:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2185},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-15","text":"—Out into distant futures, which no dream hath yet seen, into warmer\r souths than ever sculptor conceived,—where gods in their dancing are\r ashamed of all clothes:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2186},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-16","text":"(That I may speak in parables and halt and stammer like the poets: and\r verily I am ashamed that I have still to be a poet!)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2187},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-17","text":"Where all becoming seemed to me dancing of Gods, and wantoning of Gods,\r and the world unloosed and unbridled and fleeing back to itself:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2188},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-18","text":"—As an eternal self-fleeing and re-seeking of one another of many Gods,\r as the blessed self-contradicting, recommuning, and refraternising with\r one another of many Gods:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2189},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-19","text":"Where all time seemed to me a blessed mockery of moments, where\r necessity was freedom itself, which played happily with the goad of\r freedom:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2190},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-20","text":"Where I also found again mine old devil and arch-enemy, the spirit\r of gravity, and all that it created: constraint, law, necessity and\r consequence and purpose and will and good and evil:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2191},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-21","text":"For must there not be that which is danced OVER, danced beyond? Must\r there not, for the sake of the nimble, the nimblest,—be moles and\r clumsy dwarfs?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2192},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-22","text":"There was it also where I picked up from the path the word “Superman,”\r  and that man is something that must be surpassed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2193},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-23","text":"—That man is a bridge and not a goal—rejoicing over his noontides and\r evenings, as advances to new rosy dawns:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2194},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-24","text":"—The Zarathustra word of the great noontide, and whatever else I have\r hung up over men like purple evening-afterglows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2195},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-25","text":"Verily, also new stars did I make them see, along with new nights;\r and over cloud and day and night, did I spread out laughter like a\r gay-coloured canopy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2196},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-26","text":"I taught them all MY poetisation and aspiration: to compose and collect\r into unity what is fragment in man, and riddle and fearful chance;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2197},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-27","text":"—As composer, riddle-reader, and redeemer of chance, did I teach them\r to create the future, and all that HATH BEEN—to redeem by creating.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2198},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-28","text":"The past of man to redeem, and every “It was” to transform, until the\r Will saith: “But so did I will it! So shall I will it—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2199},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-29","text":"—This did I call redemption; this alone taught I them to call\r redemption.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2200},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-30","text":"Now do I await MY redemption—that I may go unto them for the last time.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2201},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-31","text":"For once more will I go unto men: AMONGST them will my sun set; in dying\r will I give them my choicest gift!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2202},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-32","text":"From the sun did I learn this, when it goeth down, the exuberant one:\r gold doth it then pour into the sea, out of inexhaustible riches,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2203},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-33","text":"—So that the poorest fisherman roweth even with GOLDEN oars! For this\r did I once see, and did not tire of weeping in beholding it.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2204},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-34","text":"Like the sun will also Zarathustra go down: now sitteth he here\r and waiteth, old broken tables around him, and also new\r tables—half-written.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2205},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-35","text":"Behold, here is a new table; but where are my brethren who will carry it\r with me to the valley and into hearts of flesh?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2206},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-36","text":"Thus demandeth my great love to the remotest ones: BE NOT CONSIDERATE OF\r THY NEIGHBOUR! Man is something that must be surpassed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2207},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-37","text":"There are many divers ways and modes of surpassing: see THOU thereto!\r But only a buffoon thinketh: “man can also be OVERLEAPT.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2208},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-38","text":"Surpass thyself even in thy neighbour: and a right which thou canst\r seize upon, shalt thou not allow to be given thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2209},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-39","text":"What thou doest can no one do to thee again. Lo, there is no requital.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2210},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-40","text":"He who cannot command himself shall obey. And many a one CAN command\r himself, but still sorely lacketh self-obedience!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2211},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-41","text":"Thus wisheth the type of noble souls: they desire to have nothing\r GRATUITOUSLY, least of all, life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2212},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-42","text":"He who is of the populace wisheth to live gratuitously; we others,\r however, to whom life hath given itself—we are ever considering WHAT we\r can best give IN RETURN!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2213},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-43","text":"And verily, it is a noble dictum which saith: “What life promiseth US,\r that promise will WE keep—to life!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2214},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-44","text":"One should not wish to enjoy where one doth not contribute to the\r enjoyment. And one should not WISH to enjoy!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2215},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-45","text":"For enjoyment and innocence are the most bashful things. Neither like\r to be sought for. One should HAVE them,—but one should rather SEEK for\r guilt and pain!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2216},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-46","text":"O my brethren, he who is a firstling is ever sacrificed. Now, however,\r are we firstlings!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2217},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-47","text":"We all bleed on secret sacrificial altars, we all burn and broil in\r honour of ancient idols.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2218},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-48","text":"Our best is still young: this exciteth old palates. Our flesh is tender,\r our skin is only lambs’ skin:—how could we not excite old idol-priests!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2219},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-49","text":"IN OURSELVES dwelleth he still, the old idol-priest, who broileth our\r best for his banquet. Ah, my brethren, how could firstlings fail to be\r sacrifices!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2220},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-50","text":"But so wisheth our type; and I love those who do not wish to preserve\r themselves, the down-going ones do I love with mine entire love: for\r they go beyond.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2221},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-51","text":"To be true—that CAN few be! And he who can, will not! Least of all,\r however, can the good be true.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2222},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-52","text":"Oh, those good ones! GOOD MEN NEVER SPEAK THE TRUTH. For the spirit,\r thus to be good, is a malady.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2223},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-53","text":"They yield, those good ones, they submit themselves; their heart\r repeateth, their soul obeyeth: HE, however, who obeyeth, DOTH NOT LISTEN\r TO HIMSELF!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2224},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-54","text":"All that is called evil by the good, must come together in order that\r one truth may be born. O my brethren, are ye also evil enough for THIS\r truth?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2225},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-55","text":"The daring venture, the prolonged distrust, the cruel Nay, the tedium,\r the cutting-into-the-quick—how seldom do THESE come together! Out of\r such seed, however—is truth produced!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2226},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-56","text":"BESIDE the bad conscience hath hitherto grown all KNOWLEDGE! Break up,\r break up, ye discerning ones, the old tables!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2227},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-57","text":"When the water hath planks, when gangways and railings o’erspan the\r stream, verily, he is not believed who then saith: “All is in flux.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2228},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-58","text":"But even the simpletons contradict him. “What?” say the simpletons, “all\r in flux? Planks and railings are still OVER the stream!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2229},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-59","text":"“OVER the stream all is stable, all the values of things, the bridges\r and bearings, all ‘good’ and ‘evil’: these are all STABLE!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2230},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-60","text":"Cometh, however, the hard winter, the stream-tamer, then learn even the\r wittiest distrust, and verily, not only the simpletons then say: “Should\r not everything—STAND STILL?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2231},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-61","text":"“Fundamentally standeth everything still”—that is an appropriate winter\r doctrine, good cheer for an unproductive period, a great comfort for\r winter-sleepers and fireside-loungers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2232},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-62","text":"“Fundamentally standeth everything still”—: but CONTRARY thereto,\r preacheth the thawing wind!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2233},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-63","text":"The thawing wind, a bullock, which is no ploughing bullock—a furious\r bullock, a destroyer, which with angry horns breaketh the ice! The ice\r however—BREAKETH GANGWAYS!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2234},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-64","text":"O my brethren, is not everything AT PRESENT IN FLUX? Have not all\r railings and gangways fallen into the water? Who would still HOLD ON to\r “good” and “evil”?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2235},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-65","text":"“Woe to us! Hail to us! The thawing wind bloweth!”—Thus preach, my\r brethren, through all the streets!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2236},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-66","text":"There is an old illusion—it is called good and evil. Around soothsayers\r and astrologers hath hitherto revolved the orbit of this illusion.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2237},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-67","text":"Once did one BELIEVE in soothsayers and astrologers; and THEREFORE did\r one believe, “Everything is fate: thou shalt, for thou must!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2238},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-68","text":"Then again did one distrust all soothsayers and astrologers; and\r THEREFORE did one believe, “Everything is freedom: thou canst, for thou\r willest!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2239},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-69","text":"O my brethren, concerning the stars and the future there hath hitherto\r been only illusion, and not knowledge; and THEREFORE concerning good and\r evil there hath hitherto been only illusion and not knowledge!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2240},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-70","text":"“Thou shalt not rob! Thou shalt not slay!”—such precepts were once\r called holy; before them did one bow the knee and the head, and take off\r one’s shoes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2241},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-71","text":"But I ask you: Where have there ever been better robbers and slayers in\r the world than such holy precepts?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2242},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-72","text":"Is there not even in all life—robbing and slaying? And for such\r precepts to be called holy, was not TRUTH itself thereby—slain?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2243},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-73","text":"—Or was it a sermon of death that called holy what contradicted and\r dissuaded from life?—O my brethren, break up, break up for me the old\r tables!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2244},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-74","text":"It is my sympathy with all the past that I see it is abandoned,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2245},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-75","text":"—Abandoned to the favour, the spirit and the madness of every\r generation that cometh, and reinterpreteth all that hath been as its\r bridge!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2246},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-76","text":"A great potentate might arise, an artful prodigy, who with approval and\r disapproval could strain and constrain all the past, until it became for\r him a bridge, a harbinger, a herald, and a cock-crowing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2247},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-77","text":"This however is the other danger, and mine other sympathy:—he who is\r of the populace, his thoughts go back to his grandfather,—with his\r grandfather, however, doth time cease.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2248},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-78","text":"Thus is all the past abandoned: for it might some day happen for the\r populace to become master, and drown all time in shallow waters.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2249},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-79","text":"Therefore, O my brethren, a NEW NOBILITY is needed, which shall be the\r adversary of all populace and potentate rule, and shall inscribe anew\r the word “noble” on new tables.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2250},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-80","text":"For many noble ones are needed, and many kinds of noble ones, FOR A NEW\r NOBILITY! Or, as I once said in parable: “That is just divinity, that\r there are Gods, but no God!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2251},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-81","text":"O my brethren, I consecrate you and point you to a new nobility: ye\r shall become procreators and cultivators and sowers of the future;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2252},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-82","text":"—Verily, not to a nobility which ye could purchase like traders with\r traders’ gold; for little worth is all that hath its price.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2253},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-83","text":"Let it not be your honour henceforth whence ye come, but whither ye go!\r Your Will and your feet which seek to surpass you—let these be your new\r honour!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2254},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-84","text":"Verily, not that ye have served a prince—of what account are princes\r now!—nor that ye have become a bulwark to that which standeth, that it\r may stand more firmly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2255},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-85","text":"Not that your family have become courtly at courts, and that ye have\r learned—gay-coloured, like the flamingo—to stand long hours in shallow\r pools:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2256},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-86","text":"(For ABILITY-to-stand is a merit in courtiers; and all courtiers believe\r that unto blessedness after death pertaineth—PERMISSION-to-sit!)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2257},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-87","text":"Nor even that a Spirit called Holy, led your forefathers into promised\r lands, which I do not praise: for where the worst of all trees grew—the\r cross,—in that land there is nothing to praise!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2258},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-88","text":"—And verily, wherever this “Holy Spirit” led its knights, always in\r such campaigns did—goats and geese, and wryheads and guyheads run\r FOREMOST!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2259},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-89","text":"O my brethren, not backward shall your nobility gaze, but OUTWARD!\r Exiles shall ye be from all fatherlands and forefather-lands!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2260},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-90","text":"Your CHILDREN’S LAND shall ye love: let this love be your new\r nobility,—the undiscovered in the remotest seas! For it do I bid your\r sails search and search!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2261},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-91","text":"Unto your children shall ye MAKE AMENDS for being the children of your\r fathers: all the past shall ye THUS redeem! This new table do I place\r over you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2262},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-92","text":"“Why should one live? All is vain! To live—that is to thrash straw; to\r live—that is to burn oneself and yet not get warm.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2263},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-93","text":"Such ancient babbling still passeth for “wisdom”; because it is old,\r however, and smelleth mustily, THEREFORE is it the more honoured. Even\r mould ennobleth.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2264},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-94","text":"Children might thus speak: they SHUN the fire because it hath burnt\r them! There is much childishness in the old books of wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2265},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-95","text":"And he who ever “thrasheth straw,” why should he be allowed to rail at\r thrashing! Such a fool one would have to muzzle!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2266},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-96","text":"Such persons sit down to the table and bring nothing with them, not even\r good hunger:—and then do they rail: “All is vain!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2267},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-97","text":"But to eat and drink well, my brethren, is verily no vain art! Break up,\r break up for me the tables of the never-joyous ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2268},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-98","text":"“To the clean are all things clean”—thus say the people. I, however,\r say unto you: To the swine all things become swinish!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2269},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-99","text":"Therefore preach the visionaries and bowed-heads (whose hearts are also\r bowed down): “The world itself is a filthy monster.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2270},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-100","text":"For these are all unclean spirits; especially those, however, who have\r no peace or rest, unless they see the world FROM THE BACKSIDE—the\r backworldsmen!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2271},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-101","text":"TO THOSE do I say it to the face, although it sound unpleasantly: the\r world resembleth man, in that it hath a backside,—SO MUCH is true!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2272},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-102","text":"There is in the world much filth: SO MUCH is true! But the world itself\r is not therefore a filthy monster!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2273},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-103","text":"There is wisdom in the fact that much in the world smelleth badly:\r loathing itself createth wings, and fountain-divining powers!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2274},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-104","text":"In the best there is still something to loathe; and the best is still\r something that must be surpassed!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2275},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-105","text":"O my brethren, there is much wisdom in the fact that much filth is in\r the world!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2276},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-106","text":"Such sayings did I hear pious backworldsmen speak to their consciences,\r and verily without wickedness or guile,—although there is nothing more\r guileful in the world, or more wicked.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2277},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-107","text":"“Let whoever will choke and stab and skin and scrape the people: raise\r not a finger against it! Thereby will they learn to renounce the world.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2278},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-108","text":"“And thine own reason—this shalt thou thyself stifle and choke; for it\r is a reason of this world,—thereby wilt thou learn thyself to renounce\r the world.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2279},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-109","text":"—Shatter, shatter, O my brethren, those old tables of the pious! Tatter\r the maxims of the world-maligners!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2280},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-110","text":"“He who learneth much unlearneth all violent cravings”—that do people\r now whisper to one another in all the dark lanes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2281},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-111","text":"“Wisdom wearieth, nothing is worth while; thou shalt not crave!”—this\r new table found I hanging even in the public markets.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2282},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-112","text":"Break up for me, O my brethren, break up also that NEW table! The\r weary-o’-the-world put it up, and the preachers of death and the jailer:\r for lo, it is also a sermon for slavery:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2283},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-113","text":"Because they learned badly and not the best, and everything too early\r and everything too fast; because they ATE badly: from thence hath\r resulted their ruined stomach;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2284},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-114","text":"—For a ruined stomach, is their spirit: IT persuadeth to death! For\r verily, my brethren, the spirit IS a stomach!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2285},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-115","text":"Life is a well of delight, but to him in whom the ruined stomach\r speaketh, the father of affliction, all fountains are poisoned.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2286},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-116","text":"To discern: that is DELIGHT to the lion-willed! But he who hath become\r weary, is himself merely “willed”; with him play all the waves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2287},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-117","text":"And such is always the nature of weak men: they lose themselves on their\r way. And at last asketh their weariness: “Why did we ever go on the way?\r All is indifferent!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2288},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-118","text":"TO THEM soundeth it pleasant to have preached in their ears: “Nothing is\r worth while! Ye shall not will!” That, however, is a sermon for slavery.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2289},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-119","text":"O my brethren, a fresh blustering wind cometh Zarathustra unto all\r way-weary ones; many noses will he yet make sneeze!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2290},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-120","text":"Even through walls bloweth my free breath, and in into prisons and\r imprisoned spirits!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2291},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-121","text":"Willing emancipateth: for willing is creating: so do I teach. And ONLY\r for creating shall ye learn!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2292},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-122","text":"And also the learning shall ye LEARN only from me, the learning\r well!—He who hath ears let him hear!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2293},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-123","text":"There standeth the boat—thither goeth it over, perhaps into vast\r nothingness—but who willeth to enter into this “Perhaps”?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2294},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-124","text":"None of you want to enter into the death-boat! How should ye then be\r WORLD-WEARY ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2295},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-125","text":"World-weary ones! And have not even withdrawn from the earth! Eager\r did I ever find you for the earth, amorous still of your own\r earth-weariness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2296},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-126","text":"Not in vain doth your lip hang down:—a small worldly wish still sitteth\r thereon! And in your eye—floateth there not a cloudlet of unforgotten\r earthly bliss?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2297},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-127","text":"There are on the earth many good inventions, some useful, some pleasant:\r for their sake is the earth to be loved.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2298},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-128","text":"And many such good inventions are there, that they are like woman’s\r breasts: useful at the same time, and pleasant.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2299},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-129","text":"Ye world-weary ones, however! Ye earth-idlers! You, shall one beat with\r stripes! With stripes shall one again make you sprightly limbs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2300},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-130","text":"For if ye be not invalids, or decrepit creatures, of whom the earth is\r weary, then are ye sly sloths, or dainty, sneaking pleasure-cats. And if\r ye will not again RUN gaily, then shall ye—pass away!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2301},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-131","text":"To the incurable shall one not seek to be a physician: thus teacheth\r Zarathustra:—so shall ye pass away!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2302},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-132","text":"But more COURAGE is needed to make an end than to make a new verse: that\r do all physicians and poets know well.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2303},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-133","text":"O my brethren, there are tables which weariness framed, and tables\r which slothfulness framed, corrupt slothfulness: although they speak\r similarly, they want to be heard differently.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2304},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-134","text":"See this languishing one! Only a span-breadth is he from his goal; but\r from weariness hath he lain down obstinately in the dust, this brave\r one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2305},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-135","text":"From weariness yawneth he at the path, at the earth, at the goal, and at\r himself: not a step further will he go,—this brave one!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2306},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-136","text":"Now gloweth the sun upon him, and the dogs lick at his sweat: but he\r lieth there in his obstinacy and preferreth to languish:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2307},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-137","text":"—A span-breadth from his goal, to languish! Verily, ye will have to\r drag him into his heaven by the hair of his head—this hero!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2308},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-138","text":"Better still that ye let him lie where he hath lain down, that sleep may\r come unto him, the comforter, with cooling patter-rain.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2309},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-139","text":"Let him lie, until of his own accord he awakeneth,—until of his own\r accord he repudiateth all weariness, and what weariness hath taught\r through him!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2310},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-140","text":"Only, my brethren, see that ye scare the dogs away from him, the idle\r skulkers, and all the swarming vermin:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2311},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-141","text":"—All the swarming vermin of the “cultured,” that—feast on the sweat of\r every hero!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2312},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-142","text":"I form circles around me and holy boundaries; ever fewer ascend with\r me ever higher mountains: I build a mountain-range out of ever holier\r mountains.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2313},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-143","text":"But wherever ye would ascend with me, O my brethren, take care lest a\r PARASITE ascend with you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2314},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-144","text":"A parasite: that is a reptile, a creeping, cringing reptile, that trieth\r to fatten on your infirm and sore places.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2315},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-145","text":"And THIS is its art: it divineth where ascending souls are weary, in\r your trouble and dejection, in your sensitive modesty, doth it build its\r loathsome nest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2316},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-146","text":"Where the strong are weak, where the noble are all-too-gentle—there\r buildeth it its loathsome nest; the parasite liveth where the great have\r small sore places.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2317},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-147","text":"What is the highest of all species of being, and what is the lowest?\r The parasite is the lowest species; he, however, who is of the highest\r species feedeth most parasites.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2318},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-148","text":"For the soul which hath the longest ladder, and can go deepest down: how\r could there fail to be most parasites upon it?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2319},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-149","text":"—The most comprehensive soul, which can run and stray and rove furthest\r in itself; the most necessary soul, which out of joy flingeth itself\r into chance:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2320},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-150","text":"—The soul in Being, which plungeth into Becoming; the possessing soul,\r which SEEKETH to attain desire and longing:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2321},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-151","text":"—The soul fleeing from itself, which overtaketh itself in the widest\r circuit; the wisest soul, unto which folly speaketh most sweetly:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2322},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-152","text":"—The soul most self-loving, in which all things have their current and\r counter-current, their ebb and their flow:—oh, how could THE LOFTIEST\r SOUL fail to have the worst parasites?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2323},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-153","text":"O my brethren, am I then cruel? But I say: What falleth, that shall one\r also push!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2324},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-154","text":"Everything of to-day—it falleth, it decayeth; who would preserve it!\r But I—I wish also to push it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2325},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-155","text":"Know ye the delight which rolleth stones into precipitous depths?—Those\r men of to-day, see just how they roll into my depths!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2326},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-156","text":"A prelude am I to better players, O my brethren! An example! DO\r according to mine example!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2327},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-157","text":"And him whom ye do not teach to fly, teach I pray you—TO FALL FASTER!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2328},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-158","text":"I love the brave: but it is not enough to be a swordsman,—one must also\r know WHEREON to use swordsmanship!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2329},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-159","text":"And often is it greater bravery to keep quiet and pass by, that THEREBY\r one may reserve oneself for a worthier foe!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2330},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-160","text":"Ye shall only have foes to be hated; but not foes to be despised: ye\r must be proud of your foes. Thus have I already taught.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2331},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-161","text":"For the worthier foe, O my brethren, shall ye reserve yourselves:\r therefore must ye pass by many a one,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2332},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-162","text":"—Especially many of the rabble, who din your ears with noise about\r people and peoples.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2333},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-163","text":"Keep your eye clear of their For and Against! There is there much right,\r much wrong: he who looketh on becometh wroth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2334},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-164","text":"Therein viewing, therein hewing—they are the same thing: therefore\r depart into the forests and lay your sword to sleep!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2335},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-165","text":"Go YOUR ways! and let the people and peoples go theirs!—gloomy ways,\r verily, on which not a single hope glinteth any more!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2336},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-166","text":"Let there the trader rule, where all that still glittereth is—traders’\r gold. It is the time of kings no longer: that which now calleth itself\r the people is unworthy of kings.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2337},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-167","text":"See how these peoples themselves now do just like the traders: they pick\r up the smallest advantage out of all kinds of rubbish!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2338},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-168","text":"They lay lures for one another, they lure things out of one\r another,—that they call “good neighbourliness.” O blessed remote period\r when a people said to itself: “I will be—MASTER over peoples!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2339},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-169","text":"For, my brethren, the best shall rule, the best also WILLETH to rule!\r And where the teaching is different, there—the best is LACKING.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2340},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-170","text":"If THEY had—bread for nothing, alas! for what would THEY cry! Their\r maintainment—that is their true entertainment; and they shall have it\r hard!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2341},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-171","text":"Beasts of prey, are they: in their “working”—there is even plundering,\r in their “earning”—there is even overreaching! Therefore shall they\r have it hard!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2342},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-172","text":"Better beasts of prey shall they thus become, subtler, cleverer, MORE\r MAN-LIKE: for man is the best beast of prey.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2343},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-173","text":"All the animals hath man already robbed of their virtues: that is why of\r all animals it hath been hardest for man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2344},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-174","text":"Only the birds are still beyond him. And if man should yet learn to fly,\r alas! TO WHAT HEIGHT—would his rapacity fly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2345},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-175","text":"Thus would I have man and woman: fit for war, the one; fit for\r maternity, the other; both, however, fit for dancing with head and legs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2346},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-176","text":"And lost be the day to us in which a measure hath not been danced. And\r false be every truth which hath not had laughter along with it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2347},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-177","text":"Your marriage-arranging: see that it be not a bad ARRANGING! Ye have\r arranged too hastily: so there FOLLOWETH therefrom—marriage-breaking!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2348},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-178","text":"And better marriage-breaking than marriage-bending,\r marriage-lying!—Thus spake a woman unto me: “Indeed, I broke the\r marriage, but first did the marriage break—me!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2349},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-179","text":"The badly paired found I ever the most revengeful: they make every one\r suffer for it that they no longer run singly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2350},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-180","text":"On that account want I the honest ones to say to one another: “We love\r each other: let us SEE TO IT that we maintain our love! Or shall our\r pledging be blundering?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2351},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-181","text":"—“Give us a set term and a small marriage, that we may see if we are\r fit for the great marriage! It is a great matter always to be twain.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2352},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-182","text":"Thus do I counsel all honest ones; and what would be my love to the\r Superman, and to all that is to come, if I should counsel and speak\r otherwise!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2353},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-183","text":"Not only to propagate yourselves onwards but UPWARDS—thereto, O my\r brethren, may the garden of marriage help you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2354},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-184","text":"He who hath grown wise concerning old origins, lo, he will at last seek\r after the fountains of the future and new origins.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2355},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-185","text":"O my brethren, not long will it be until NEW PEOPLES shall arise and new\r fountains shall rush down into new depths.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2356},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-186","text":"For the earthquake—it choketh up many wells, it causeth much\r languishing: but it bringeth also to light inner powers and secrets.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2357},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-187","text":"The earthquake discloseth new fountains. In the earthquake of old\r peoples new fountains burst forth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2358},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-188","text":"And whoever calleth out: “Lo, here is a well for many thirsty ones, one\r heart for many longing ones, one will for many instruments”:—around him\r collecteth a PEOPLE, that is to say, many attempting ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2359},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-189","text":"Who can command, who must obey—THAT IS THERE ATTEMPTED! Ah, with what\r long seeking and solving and failing and learning and re-attempting!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2360},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-190","text":"Human society: it is an attempt—so I teach—a long seeking: it seeketh\r however the ruler!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2361},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-191","text":"—An attempt, my brethren! And NO “contract”! Destroy, I pray you,\r destroy that word of the soft-hearted and half-and-half!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2362},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-192","text":"O my brethren! With whom lieth the greatest danger to the whole human\r future? Is it not with the good and just?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2363},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-193","text":"—As those who say and feel in their hearts: “We already know what\r is good and just, we possess it also; woe to those who still seek\r thereafter!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2364},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-194","text":"And whatever harm the wicked may do, the harm of the good is the\r harmfulest harm!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2365},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-195","text":"And whatever harm the world-maligners may do, the harm of the good is\r the harmfulest harm!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2366},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-196","text":"O my brethren, into the hearts of the good and just looked some one\r once on a time, who said: “They are the Pharisees.” But people did not\r understand him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2367},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-197","text":"The good and just themselves were not free to understand him; their\r spirit was imprisoned in their good conscience. The stupidity of the\r good is unfathomably wise.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2368},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-198","text":"It is the truth, however, that the good MUST be Pharisees—they have no\r choice!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2369},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-199","text":"The good MUST crucify him who deviseth his own virtue! That IS the\r truth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2370},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-200","text":"The second one, however, who discovered their country—the country,\r heart and soil of the good and just,—it was he who asked: “Whom do they\r hate most?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2371},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-201","text":"The CREATOR, hate they most, him who breaketh the tables and old values,\r the breaker,—him they call the law-breaker.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2372},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-202","text":"For the good—they CANNOT create; they are always the beginning of the\r end:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2373},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-203","text":"—They crucify him who writeth new values on new tables, they sacrifice\r UNTO THEMSELVES the future—they crucify the whole human future!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2374},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-204","text":"O my brethren, have ye also understood this word? And what I once said\r of the “last man”?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2375},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-205","text":"With whom lieth the greatest danger to the whole human future? Is it not\r with the good and just?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2376},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-206","text":"BREAK UP, BREAK UP, I PRAY YOU, THE GOOD AND JUST!—O my brethren, have\r ye understood also this word?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2377},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-207","text":"Ye flee from me? Ye are frightened? Ye tremble at this word?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2378},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-208","text":"O my brethren, when I enjoined you to break up the good, and the tables\r of the good, then only did I embark man on his high seas.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2379},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-209","text":"And now only cometh unto him the great terror, the great outlook, the\r great sickness, the great nausea, the great sea-sickness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2380},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-210","text":"False shores and false securities did the good teach you; in the lies of\r the good were ye born and bred. Everything hath been radically contorted\r and distorted by the good.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2381},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-211","text":"But he who discovered the country of “man,” discovered also the country\r of “man’s future.” Now shall ye be sailors for me, brave, patient!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2382},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-212","text":"Keep yourselves up betimes, my brethren, learn to keep yourselves up!\r The sea stormeth: many seek to raise themselves again by you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2383},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-213","text":"The sea stormeth: all is in the sea. Well! Cheer up! Ye old\r seaman-hearts!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2384},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-214","text":"What of fatherland! THITHER striveth our helm where our CHILDREN’S LAND\r is! Thitherwards, stormier than the sea, stormeth our great longing!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2385},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-215","text":"“Why so hard!”—said to the diamond one day the charcoal; “are we then\r not near relatives?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2386},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-216","text":"Why so soft? O my brethren; thus do _I_ ask you: are ye then not—my\r brethren?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2387},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-217","text":"Why so soft, so submissive and yielding? Why is there so much negation\r and abnegation in your hearts? Why is there so little fate in your\r looks?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2388},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-218","text":"And if ye will not be fates and inexorable ones, how can ye one day—\r conquer with me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2389},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-219","text":"And if your hardness will not glance and cut and chip to pieces, how can\r ye one day—create with me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2390},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-220","text":"For the creators are hard. And blessedness must it seem to you to press\r your hand upon millenniums as upon wax,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2391},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-221","text":"—Blessedness to write upon the will of millenniums as upon\r brass,—harder than brass, nobler than brass. Entirely hard is only the\r noblest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2392},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-222","text":"This new table, O my brethren, put I up over you: BECOME HARD!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2393},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-223","text":"O thou, my Will! Thou change of every need, MY needfulness! Preserve me\r from all small victories!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2394},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-224","text":"Thou fatedness of my soul, which I call fate! Thou In-me! Over-me!\r Preserve and spare me for one great fate!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2395},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-225","text":"And thy last greatness, my Will, spare it for thy last—that thou mayest\r be inexorable IN thy victory! Ah, who hath not succumbed to his victory!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2396},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-226","text":"Ah, whose eye hath not bedimmed in this intoxicated twilight! Ah, whose\r foot hath not faltered and forgotten in victory—how to stand!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2397},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-227","text":"—That I may one day be ready and ripe in the great noontide: ready and\r ripe like the glowing ore, the lightning-bearing cloud, and the swelling\r milk-udder:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2398},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-228","text":"—Ready for myself and for my most hidden Will: a bow eager for its\r arrow, an arrow eager for its star:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2399},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-229","text":"—A star, ready and ripe in its noontide, glowing, pierced, blessed, by\r annihilating sun-arrows:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2400},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-230","text":"—A sun itself, and an inexorable sun-will, ready for annihilation in\r victory!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2401},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-77-231","text":"O Will, thou change of every need, MY needfulness! Spare me for one\r great victory!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2402},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-1","text":"One morning, not long after his return to his cave, Zarathustra sprang\r up from his couch like a madman, crying with a frightful voice, and\r acting as if some one still lay on the couch who did not wish to rise.\r Zarathustra’s voice also resounded in such a manner that his animals\r came to him frightened, and out of all the neighbouring caves and\r lurking-places all the creatures slipped away—flying, fluttering,\r creeping or leaping, according to their variety of foot or wing.\r Zarathustra, however, spake these words:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2403},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-2","text":"Up, abysmal thought out of my depth! I am thy cock and morning dawn,\r thou overslept reptile: Up! Up! My voice shall soon crow thee awake!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2404},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-3","text":"Unbind the fetters of thine ears: listen! For I wish to hear thee! Up!\r Up! There is thunder enough to make the very graves listen!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2405},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-4","text":"And rub the sleep and all the dimness and blindness out of thine eyes!\r Hear me also with thine eyes: my voice is a medicine even for those born\r blind.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2406},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-5","text":"And once thou art awake, then shalt thou ever remain awake. It is not\r MY custom to awake great-grandmothers out of their sleep that I may bid\r them—sleep on!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2407},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-6","text":"Thou stirrest, stretchest thyself, wheezest? Up! Up! Not wheeze, shalt\r thou,—but speak unto me! Zarathustra calleth thee, Zarathustra the\r godless!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2408},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-7","text":"I, Zarathustra, the advocate of living, the advocate of suffering, the\r advocate of the circuit—thee do I call, my most abysmal thought!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2409},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-8","text":"Joy to me! Thou comest,—I hear thee! Mine abyss SPEAKETH, my lowest\r depth have I turned over into the light!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2410},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-9","text":"Joy to me! Come hither! Give me thy hand—ha! let be! aha!—Disgust,\r disgust, disgust—alas to me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2411},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-10","text":"Hardly, however, had Zarathustra spoken these words, when he fell down\r as one dead, and remained long as one dead. When however he again came\r to himself, then was he pale and trembling, and remained lying; and for\r long he would neither eat nor drink. This condition continued for seven\r days; his animals, however, did not leave him day nor night, except that\r the eagle flew forth to fetch food. And what it fetched and foraged,\r it laid on Zarathustra’s couch: so that Zarathustra at last lay among\r yellow and red berries, grapes, rosy apples, sweet-smelling herbage, and\r pine-cones. At his feet, however, two lambs were stretched, which the\r eagle had with difficulty carried off from their s","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2412},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-11","text":"At last, after seven days, Zarathustra raised himself upon his couch,\r took a rosy apple in his hand, smelt it and found its smell pleasant.\r Then did his animals think the time had come to speak unto him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2413},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-12","text":"“O Zarathustra,” said they, “now hast thou lain thus for seven days with\r heavy eyes: wilt thou not set thyself again upon thy feet?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2414},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-13","text":"Step out of thy cave: the world waiteth for thee as a garden. The wind\r playeth with heavy fragrance which seeketh for thee; and all brooks\r would like to run after thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2415},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-14","text":"All things long for thee, since thou hast remained alone for seven\r days—step forth out of thy cave! All things want to be thy physicians!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2416},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-15","text":"Did perhaps a new knowledge come to thee, a bitter, grievous knowledge?\r Like leavened dough layest thou, thy soul arose and swelled beyond all\r its bounds.—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2417},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-16","text":"—O mine animals, answered Zarathustra, talk on thus and let me listen!\r It refresheth me so to hear your talk: where there is talk, there is the\r world as a garden unto me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2418},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-17","text":"How charming it is that there are words and tones; are not words and\r tones rainbows and seeming bridges ‘twixt the eternally separated?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2419},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-18","text":"To each soul belongeth another world; to each soul is every other soul a\r back-world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2420},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-19","text":"Among the most alike doth semblance deceive most delightfully: for the\r smallest gap is most difficult to bridge over.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2421},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-20","text":"For me—how could there be an outside-of-me? There is no outside! But\r this we forget on hearing tones; how delightful it is that we forget!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2422},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-21","text":"Have not names and tones been given unto things that man may refresh\r himself with them? It is a beautiful folly, speaking; therewith danceth\r man over everything.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2423},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-22","text":"How lovely is all speech and all falsehoods of tones! With tones danceth\r our love on variegated rainbows.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2424},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-23","text":"—“O Zarathustra,” said then his animals, “to those who think like us,\r things all dance themselves: they come and hold out the hand and laugh\r and flee—and return.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2425},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-24","text":"Everything goeth, everything returneth; eternally rolleth the wheel\r of existence. Everything dieth, everything blossometh forth again;\r eternally runneth on the year of existence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2426},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-25","text":"Everything breaketh, everything is integrated anew; eternally buildeth\r itself the same house of existence. All things separate, all things\r again greet one another; eternally true to itself remaineth the ring of\r existence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2427},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-26","text":"Every moment beginneth existence, around every ‘Here’ rolleth the ball\r ‘There.’ The middle is everywhere. Crooked is the path of eternity.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2428},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-27","text":"—O ye wags and barrel-organs! answered Zarathustra, and smiled once\r more, how well do ye know what had to be fulfilled in seven days:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2429},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-28","text":"—And how that monster crept into my throat and choked me! But I bit off\r its head and spat it away from me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2430},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-29","text":"And ye—ye have made a lyre-lay out of it? Now, however, do I lie here,\r still exhausted with that biting and spitting-away, still sick with mine\r own salvation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2431},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-30","text":"AND YE LOOKED ON AT IT ALL? O mine animals, are ye also cruel? Did\r ye like to look at my great pain as men do? For man is the cruellest\r animal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2432},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-31","text":"At tragedies, bull-fights, and crucifixions hath he hitherto been\r happiest on earth; and when he invented his hell, behold, that was his\r heaven on earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2433},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-32","text":"When the great man crieth—: immediately runneth the little man thither,\r and his tongue hangeth out of his mouth for very lusting. He, however,\r calleth it his “pity.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2434},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-33","text":"The little man, especially the poet—how passionately doth he accuse\r life in words! Hearken to him, but do not fail to hear the delight which\r is in all accusation!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2435},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-34","text":"Such accusers of life—them life overcometh with a glance of the eye.\r “Thou lovest me?” saith the insolent one; “wait a little, as yet have I\r no time for thee.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2436},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-35","text":"Towards himself man is the cruellest animal; and in all who call\r themselves “sinners” and “bearers of the cross” and “penitents,” do not\r overlook the voluptuousness in their plaints and accusations!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2437},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-36","text":"And I myself—do I thereby want to be man’s accuser? Ah, mine animals,\r this only have I learned hitherto, that for man his baddest is necessary\r for his best,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2438},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-37","text":"—That all that is baddest is the best POWER, and the hardest stone for\r the highest creator; and that man must become better AND badder:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2439},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-38","text":"Not to THIS torture-stake was I tied, that I know man is bad,—but I\r cried, as no one hath yet cried:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2440},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-39","text":"“Ah, that his baddest is so very small! Ah, that his best is so very\r small!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2441},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-40","text":"The great disgust at man—IT strangled me and had crept into my throat:\r and what the soothsayer had presaged: “All is alike, nothing is worth\r while, knowledge strangleth.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2442},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-41","text":"A long twilight limped on before me, a fatally weary, fatally\r intoxicated sadness, which spake with yawning mouth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2443},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-42","text":"“Eternally he returneth, the man of whom thou art weary, the small\r man”—so yawned my sadness, and dragged its foot and could not go to\r sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2444},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-43","text":"A cavern, became the human earth to me; its breast caved in; everything\r living became to me human dust and bones and mouldering past.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2445},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-44","text":"My sighing sat on all human graves, and could no longer arise: my\r sighing and questioning croaked and choked, and gnawed and nagged day\r and night:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2446},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-45","text":"—“Ah, man returneth eternally! The small man returneth eternally!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2447},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-46","text":"Naked had I once seen both of them, the greatest man and the smallest\r man: all too like one another—all too human, even the greatest man!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2448},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-47","text":"All too small, even the greatest man!—that was my disgust at man! And\r the eternal return also of the smallest man!—that was my disgust at all\r existence!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2449},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-48","text":"Ah, Disgust! Disgust! Disgust!—Thus spake Zarathustra, and sighed and\r shuddered; for he remembered his sickness. Then did his animals prevent\r him from speaking further.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2450},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-49","text":"“Do not speak further, thou convalescent!”—so answered his animals,\r “but go out where the world waiteth for thee like a garden.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2451},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-50","text":"Go out unto the roses, the bees, and the flocks of doves! Especially,\r however, unto the singing birds, to learn SINGING from them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2452},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-51","text":"For singing is for the convalescent; the sound ones may talk. And\r when the sound also want songs, then want they other songs than the\r convalescent.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2453},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-52","text":"—“O ye wags and barrel-organs, do be silent!” answered Zarathustra, and\r smiled at his animals. “How well ye know what consolation I devised for\r myself in seven days!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2454},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-53","text":"That I have to sing once more—THAT consolation did I devise for myself,\r and THIS convalescence: would ye also make another lyre-lay thereof?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2455},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-54","text":"—“Do not talk further,” answered his animals once more; “rather, thou\r convalescent, prepare for thyself first a lyre, a new lyre!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2456},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-55","text":"For behold, O Zarathustra! For thy new lays there are needed new lyres.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2457},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-56","text":"Sing and bubble over, O Zarathustra, heal thy soul with new lays: that\r thou mayest bear thy great fate, which hath not yet been any one’s fate!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2458},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-57","text":"For thine animals know it well, O Zarathustra, who thou art and must\r become: behold, THOU ART THE TEACHER OF THE ETERNAL RETURN,—that is now\r THY fate!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2459},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-58","text":"That thou must be the first to teach this teaching—how could this great\r fate not be thy greatest danger and infirmity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2460},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-59","text":"Behold, we know what thou teachest: that all things eternally return,\r and ourselves with them, and that we have already existed times without\r number, and all things with us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2461},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-60","text":"Thou teachest that there is a great year of Becoming, a prodigy of a\r great year; it must, like a sand-glass, ever turn up anew, that it may\r anew run down and run out:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2462},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-61","text":"—So that all those years are like one another in the greatest and also\r in the smallest, so that we ourselves, in every great year, are like\r ourselves in the greatest and also in the smallest.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2463},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-62","text":"And if thou wouldst now die, O Zarathustra, behold, we know also how\r thou wouldst then speak to thyself:—but thine animals beseech thee not\r to die yet!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2464},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-63","text":"Thou wouldst speak, and without trembling, buoyant rather with bliss,\r for a great weight and worry would be taken from thee, thou patientest\r one!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2465},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-64","text":"‘Now do I die and disappear,’ wouldst thou say, ‘and in a moment I am\r nothing. Souls are as mortal as bodies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2466},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-65","text":"But the plexus of causes returneth in which I am intertwined,—it will\r again create me! I myself pertain to the causes of the eternal return.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2467},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-66","text":"I come again with this sun, with this earth, with this eagle, with this\r serpent—NOT to a new life, or a better life, or a similar life:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2468},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-67","text":"—I come again eternally to this identical and selfsame life, in its\r greatest and its smallest, to teach again the eternal return of all\r things,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2469},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-68","text":"—To speak again the word of the great noontide of earth and man, to\r announce again to man the Superman.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2470},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-69","text":"I have spoken my word. I break down by my word: so willeth mine eternal\r fate—as announcer do I succumb!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2471},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-70","text":"The hour hath now come for the down-goer to bless himself. Thus—ENDETH\r Zarathustra’s down-going.’”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2472},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-78-71","text":"When the animals had spoken these words they were silent and waited, so\r that Zarathustra might say something to them: but Zarathustra did not\r hear that they were silent. On the contrary, he lay quietly with closed\r eyes like a person sleeping, although he did not sleep; for he communed\r just then with his soul. The serpent, however, and the eagle, when they\r found him silent in such wise, respected the great stillness around him,\r and prudently retired.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2473},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-1","text":"O my soul, I have taught thee to say “to-day” as “once on a time” and\r “formerly,” and to dance thy measure over every Here and There and\r Yonder.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2474},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-2","text":"O my soul, I delivered thee from all by-places, I brushed down from thee\r dust and spiders and twilight.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2475},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-3","text":"O my soul, I washed the petty shame and the by-place virtue from thee,\r and persuaded thee to stand naked before the eyes of the sun.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2476},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-4","text":"With the storm that is called “spirit” did I blow over thy surging\r sea; all clouds did I blow away from it; I strangled even the strangler\r called “sin.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2477},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-5","text":"O my soul, I gave thee the right to say Nay like the storm, and to say\r Yea as the open heaven saith Yea: calm as the light remainest thou, and\r now walkest through denying storms.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2478},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-6","text":"O my soul, I restored to thee liberty over the created and the\r uncreated; and who knoweth, as thou knowest, the voluptuousness of the\r future?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2479},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-7","text":"O my soul, I taught thee the contempt which doth not come like\r worm-eating, the great, the loving contempt, which loveth most where it\r contemneth most.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2480},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-8","text":"O my soul, I taught thee so to persuade that thou persuadest even the\r grounds themselves to thee: like the sun, which persuadeth even the sea\r to its height.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2481},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-9","text":"O my soul, I have taken from thee all obeying and knee-bending and\r homage-paying; I have myself given thee the names, “Change of need” and\r “Fate.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2482},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-10","text":"O my soul, I have given thee new names and gay-coloured playthings,\r I have called thee “Fate” and “the Circuit of circuits” and “the\r Navel-string of time” and “the Azure bell.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2483},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-11","text":"O my soul, to thy domain gave I all wisdom to drink, all new wines, and\r also all immemorially old strong wines of wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2484},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-12","text":"O my soul, every sun shed I upon thee, and every night and every silence\r and every longing:—then grewest thou up for me as a vine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2485},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-13","text":"O my soul, exuberant and heavy dost thou now stand forth, a vine with\r swelling udders and full clusters of brown golden grapes:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2486},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-14","text":"—Filled and weighted by thy happiness, waiting from superabundance, and\r yet ashamed of thy waiting.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2487},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-15","text":"O my soul, there is nowhere a soul which could be more loving and more\r comprehensive and more extensive! Where could future and past be closer\r together than with thee?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2488},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-16","text":"O my soul, I have given thee everything, and all my hands have become\r empty by thee:—and now! Now sayest thou to me, smiling and full of\r melancholy: “Which of us oweth thanks?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2489},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-17","text":"—Doth the giver not owe thanks because the receiver received? Is\r bestowing not a necessity? Is receiving not—pitying?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2490},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-18","text":"O my soul, I understand the smiling of thy melancholy: thine\r over-abundance itself now stretcheth out longing hands!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2491},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-19","text":"Thy fulness looketh forth over raging seas, and seeketh and waiteth: the\r longing of over-fulness looketh forth from the smiling heaven of thine\r eyes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2492},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-20","text":"And verily, O my soul! Who could see thy smiling and not melt\r into tears? The angels themselves melt into tears through the\r over-graciousness of thy smiling.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2493},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-21","text":"Thy graciousness and over-graciousness, is it which will not complain\r and weep: and yet, O my soul, longeth thy smiling for tears, and thy\r trembling mouth for sobs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2494},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-22","text":"“Is not all weeping complaining? And all complaining, accusing?” Thus\r speakest thou to thyself; and therefore, O my soul, wilt thou rather\r smile than pour forth thy grief—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2495},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-23","text":"—Than in gushing tears pour forth all thy grief concerning thy\r fulness, and concerning the craving of the vine for the vintager and\r vintage-knife!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2496},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-24","text":"But wilt thou not weep, wilt thou not weep forth thy purple melancholy,\r then wilt thou have to SING, O my soul!—Behold, I smile myself, who\r foretell thee this:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2497},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-25","text":"—Thou wilt have to sing with passionate song, until all seas turn calm\r to hearken unto thy longing,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2498},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-26","text":"—Until over calm longing seas the bark glideth, the golden marvel,\r around the gold of which all good, bad, and marvellous things frisk:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2499},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-27","text":"—Also many large and small animals, and everything that hath light\r marvellous feet, so that it can run on violet-blue paths,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2500},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-28","text":"—Towards the golden marvel, the spontaneous bark, and its master: he,\r however, is the vintager who waiteth with the diamond vintage-knife,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2501},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-29","text":"—Thy great deliverer, O my soul, the nameless one—for whom future\r songs only will find names! And verily, already hath thy breath the\r fragrance of future songs,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2502},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-30","text":"—Already glowest thou and dreamest, already drinkest thou thirstily at\r all deep echoing wells of consolation, already reposeth thy melancholy\r in the bliss of future songs!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2503},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-31","text":"O my soul, now have I given thee all, and even my last possession, and\r all my hands have become empty by thee:—THAT I BADE THEE SING, behold,\r that was my last thing to give!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2504},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-79-32","text":"That I bade thee sing,—say now, say: WHICH of us now—oweth thanks?—\r Better still, however: sing unto me, sing, O my soul! And let me thank\r thee!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2505},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-1","text":"“Into thine eyes gazed I lately, O Life: gold saw I gleam in thy\r night-eyes,—my heart stood still with delight:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2506},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-2","text":"—A golden bark saw I gleam on darkened waters, a sinking, drinking,\r reblinking, golden swing-bark!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2507},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-3","text":"At my dance-frantic foot, dost thou cast a glance, a laughing,\r questioning, melting, thrown glance:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2508},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-4","text":"Twice only movedst thou thy rattle with thy little hands—then did my\r feet swing with dance-fury.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2509},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-5","text":"My heels reared aloft, my toes they hearkened,—thee they would know:\r hath not the dancer his ear—in his toe!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2510},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-6","text":"Unto thee did I spring: then fledst thou back from my bound; and towards\r me waved thy fleeing, flying tresses round!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2511},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-7","text":"Away from thee did I spring, and from thy snaky tresses: then stoodst\r thou there half-turned, and in thine eye caresses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2512},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-8","text":"With crooked glances—dost thou teach me crooked courses; on crooked\r courses learn my feet—crafty fancies!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2513},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-9","text":"I fear thee near, I love thee far; thy flight allureth me, thy seeking\r secureth me:—I suffer, but for thee, what would I not gladly bear!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2514},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-10","text":"For thee, whose coldness inflameth, whose hatred misleadeth, whose\r flight enchaineth, whose mockery—pleadeth:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2515},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-11","text":"—Who would not hate thee, thou great bindress, inwindress, temptress,\r seekress, findress! Who would not love thee, thou innocent, impatient,\r wind-swift, child-eyed sinner!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2516},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-12","text":"Whither pullest thou me now, thou paragon and tomboy? And now foolest\r thou me fleeing; thou sweet romp dost annoy!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2517},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-13","text":"I dance after thee, I follow even faint traces lonely. Where art thou?\r Give me thy hand! Or thy finger only!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2518},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-14","text":"Here are caves and thickets: we shall go astray!—Halt! Stand still!\r Seest thou not owls and bats in fluttering fray?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2519},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-15","text":"Thou bat! Thou owl! Thou wouldst play me foul? Where are we? From the\r dogs hast thou learned thus to bark and howl.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2520},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-16","text":"Thou gnashest on me sweetly with little white teeth; thine evil eyes\r shoot out upon me, thy curly little mane from underneath!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2521},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-17","text":"This is a dance over stock and stone: I am the hunter,—wilt thou be my\r hound, or my chamois anon?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2522},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-18","text":"Now beside me! And quickly, wickedly springing! Now up! And over!—Alas!\r I have fallen myself overswinging!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2523},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-19","text":"Oh, see me lying, thou arrogant one, and imploring grace! Gladly would I\r walk with thee—in some lovelier place!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2524},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-20","text":"—In the paths of love, through bushes variegated, quiet, trim! Or there\r along the lake, where gold-fishes dance and swim!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2525},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-21","text":"Thou art now aweary? There above are sheep and sun-set stripes: is it\r not sweet to sleep—the shepherd pipes?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2526},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-22","text":"Thou art so very weary? I carry thee thither; let just thine arm sink!\r And art thou thirsty—I should have something; but thy mouth would not\r like it to drink!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2527},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-23","text":"—Oh, that cursed, nimble, supple serpent and lurking-witch! Where art\r thou gone? But in my face do I feel through thy hand, two spots and red\r blotches itch!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2528},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-24","text":"I am verily weary of it, ever thy sheepish shepherd to be. Thou witch,\r if I have hitherto sung unto thee, now shalt THOU—cry unto me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2529},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-25","text":"To the rhythm of my whip shalt thou dance and cry! I forget not my\r whip?—Not I!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2530},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-26","text":"Then did Life answer me thus, and kept thereby her fine ears closed:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2531},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-27","text":"“O Zarathustra! Crack not so terribly with thy whip! Thou knowest surely\r that noise killeth thought,—and just now there came to me such delicate\r thoughts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2532},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-28","text":"We are both of us genuine ne’er-do-wells and ne’er-do-ills. Beyond\r good and evil found we our island and our green meadow—we two alone!\r Therefore must we be friendly to each other!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2533},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-29","text":"And even should we not love each other from the bottom of our\r hearts,—must we then have a grudge against each other if we do not love\r each other perfectly?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2534},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-30","text":"And that I am friendly to thee, and often too friendly, that knowest\r thou: and the reason is that I am envious of thy Wisdom. Ah, this mad\r old fool, Wisdom!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2535},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-31","text":"If thy Wisdom should one day run away from thee, ah! then would also my\r love run away from thee quickly.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2536},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-32","text":"Thereupon did Life look thoughtfully behind and around, and said softly:\r “O Zarathustra, thou art not faithful enough to me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2537},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-33","text":"Thou lovest me not nearly so much as thou sayest; I know thou thinkest\r of soon leaving me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2538},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-34","text":"There is an old heavy, heavy, booming-clock: it boometh by night up to\r thy cave:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2539},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-35","text":"—When thou hearest this clock strike the hours at midnight, then\r thinkest thou between one and twelve thereon—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2540},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-36","text":"—Thou thinkest thereon, O Zarathustra, I know it—of soon leaving\r me!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2541},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-37","text":"“Yea,” answered I, hesitatingly, “but thou knowest it also”—And I\r said something into her ear, in amongst her confused, yellow, foolish\r tresses.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2542},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-80-38","text":"And we gazed at each other, and looked at the green meadow o’er which\r the cool evening was just passing, and we wept together.—Then, however,\r was Life dearer unto me than all my Wisdom had ever been.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2543},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-1","text":"If I be a diviner and full of the divining spirit which wandereth on\r high mountain-ridges, ‘twixt two seas,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2544},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-2","text":"Wandereth ‘twixt the past and the future as a heavy cloud—hostile to\r sultry plains, and to all that is weary and can neither die nor live:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2545},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-3","text":"Ready for lightning in its dark bosom, and for the redeeming flash of\r light, charged with lightnings which say Yea! which laugh Yea! ready for\r divining flashes of lightning:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2546},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-4","text":"—Blessed, however, is he who is thus charged! And verily, long must he\r hang like a heavy tempest on the mountain, who shall one day kindle the\r light of the future!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2547},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2548},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-82-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2549},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-1","text":"If ever my wrath hath burst graves, shifted landmarks, or rolled old\r shattered tables into precipitous depths:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2550},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-2","text":"If ever my scorn hath scattered mouldered words to the winds, and if I\r have come like a besom to cross-spiders, and as a cleansing wind to old\r charnel-houses:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2551},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-3","text":"If ever I have sat rejoicing where old Gods lie buried, world-blessing,\r world-loving, beside the monuments of old world-maligners:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2552},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-4","text":"—For even churches and Gods’-graves do I love, if only heaven looketh\r through their ruined roofs with pure eyes; gladly do I sit like grass\r and red poppies on ruined churches—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2553},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2554},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-83-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2555},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-1","text":"If ever a breath hath come to me of the creative breath, and of the\r heavenly necessity which compelleth even chances to dance star-dances:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2556},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-2","text":"If ever I have laughed with the laughter of the creative lightning,\r to which the long thunder of the deed followeth, grumblingly, but\r obediently:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2557},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-3","text":"If ever I have played dice with the Gods at the divine table of\r the earth, so that the earth quaked and ruptured, and snorted forth\r fire-streams:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2558},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-4","text":"—For a divine table is the earth, and trembling with new creative\r dictums and dice-casts of the Gods:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2559},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2560},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-84-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2561},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-1","text":"If ever I have drunk a full draught of the foaming spice- and\r confection-bowl in which all things are well mixed:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2562},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-2","text":"If ever my hand hath mingled the furthest with the nearest, fire with\r spirit, joy with sorrow, and the harshest with the kindest:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2563},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-3","text":"If I myself am a grain of the saving salt which maketh everything in the\r confection-bowl mix well:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2564},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-4","text":"—For there is a salt which uniteth good with evil; and even the evilest\r is worthy, as spicing and as final over-foaming:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2565},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2566},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-85-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2567},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-1","text":"If I be fond of the sea, and all that is sealike, and fondest of it when\r it angrily contradicteth me:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2568},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-2","text":"If the exploring delight be in me, which impelleth sails to the\r undiscovered, if the seafarer’s delight be in my delight:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2569},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-3","text":"If ever my rejoicing hath called out: “The shore hath vanished,—now\r hath fallen from me the last chain—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2570},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-4","text":"The boundless roareth around me, far away sparkle for me space and\r time,—well! cheer up! old heart!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2571},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2572},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-86-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2573},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-1","text":"If my virtue be a dancer’s virtue, and if I have often sprung with both\r feet into golden-emerald rapture:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2574},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-2","text":"If my wickedness be a laughing wickedness, at home among rose-banks and\r hedges of lilies:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2575},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-3","text":"—For in laughter is all evil present, but it is sanctified and absolved\r by its own bliss:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2576},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-4","text":"And if it be my Alpha and Omega that everything heavy shall become\r light, every body a dancer, and every spirit a bird: and verily, that is\r my Alpha and Omega!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2577},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2578},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-87-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2579},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-1","text":"If ever I have spread out a tranquil heaven above me, and have flown\r into mine own heaven with mine own pinions:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2580},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-2","text":"If I have swum playfully in profound luminous distances, and if my\r freedom’s avian wisdom hath come to me:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2581},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-3","text":"—Thus however speaketh avian wisdom:—“Lo, there is no above and no\r below! Throw thyself about,—outward, backward, thou light one! Sing!\r speak no more!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2582},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-4","text":"—Are not all words made for the heavy? Do not all words lie to the\r light ones? Sing! speak no more!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2583},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-5","text":"Oh, how could I not be ardent for Eternity, and for the marriage-ring of\r rings—the ring of the return?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2584},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-88-6","text":"Never yet have I found the woman by whom I should like to have children,\r unless it be this woman whom I love: for I love thee, O Eternity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2585},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-90-1","text":"Ah, where in the world have there been greater follies than with the\r pitiful? And what in the world hath caused more suffering than the\r follies of the pitiful?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":2586},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-90-2","text":"Woe unto all loving ones who have not an elevation which is above their\r pity!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":2587},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-90-3","text":"Thus spake the devil unto me, once on a time: “Even God hath his hell:\r it is his love for man.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":2588},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-90-4","text":"And lately did I hear him say these words: “God is dead: of his pity for\r man hath God died.”—ZARATHUSTRA, II., “The Pitiful.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":2589},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-1","text":"—And again passed moons and years over Zarathustra’s soul, and he\r heeded it not; his hair, however, became white. One day when he sat on\r a stone in front of his cave, and gazed calmly into the distance—one\r there gazeth out on the sea, and away beyond sinuous abysses,—then went\r his animals thoughtfully round about him, and at last set themselves in\r front of him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2590},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-2","text":"“O Zarathustra,” said they, “gazest thou out perhaps for thy\r happiness?”—“Of what account is my happiness!” answered he, “I have\r long ceased to strive any more for happiness, I strive for my work.”—“O\r Zarathustra,” said the animals once more, “that sayest thou as one\r who hath overmuch of good things. Liest thou not in a sky-blue lake of\r happiness?”—“Ye wags,” answered Zarathustra, and smiled, “how well did\r ye choose the simile! But ye know also that my happiness is heavy, and\r not like a fluid wave of water: it presseth me and will not leave me,\r and is like molten pitch.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2591},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-3","text":"Then went his animals again thoughtfully around him, and placed\r themselves once more in front of him. “O Zarathustra,” said they, “it is\r consequently FOR THAT REASON that thou thyself always becometh yellower\r and darker, although thy hair looketh white and flaxen? Lo, thou sittest\r in thy pitch!”—“What do ye say, mine animals?” said Zarathustra,\r laughing; “verily I reviled when I spake of pitch. As it happeneth with\r me, so is it with all fruits that turn ripe. It is the HONEY in my veins\r that maketh my blood thicker, and also my soul stiller.”—“So will it\r be, O Zarathustra,” answered his animals, and pressed up to him; “but\r wilt thou not to-day ascend a high mountain? The air is pure","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2592},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-4","text":"When Zarathustra, however, was aloft on the summit, he sent his animals\r home that had accompanied him, and found that he was now alone:—then he\r laughed from the bottom of his heart, looked around him, and spake thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2593},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-5","text":"That I spake of sacrifices and honey-sacrifices, it was merely a ruse\r in talking and verily, a useful folly! Here aloft can I now speak freer\r than in front of mountain-caves and anchorites’ domestic animals.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2594},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-6","text":"What to sacrifice! I squander what is given me, a squanderer with a\r thousand hands: how could I call that—sacrificing?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2595},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-7","text":"And when I desired honey I only desired bait, and sweet mucus and\r mucilage, for which even the mouths of growling bears, and strange,\r sulky, evil birds, water:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2596},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-8","text":"—The best bait, as huntsmen and fishermen require it. For if the world\r be as a gloomy forest of animals, and a pleasure-ground for all wild\r huntsmen, it seemeth to me rather—and preferably—a fathomless, rich\r sea;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2597},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-9","text":"—A sea full of many-hued fishes and crabs, for which even the Gods\r might long, and might be tempted to become fishers in it, and casters of\r nets,—so rich is the world in wonderful things, great and small!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2598},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-10","text":"Especially the human world, the human sea:—towards IT do I now throw\r out my golden angle-rod and say: Open up, thou human abyss!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2599},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-11","text":"Open up, and throw unto me thy fish and shining crabs! With my best bait\r shall I allure to myself to-day the strangest human fish!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2600},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-12","text":"—My happiness itself do I throw out into all places far and wide ‘twixt\r orient, noontide, and occident, to see if many human fish will not learn\r to hug and tug at my happiness;—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2601},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-13","text":"Until, biting at my sharp hidden hooks, they have to come up unto MY\r height, the motleyest abyss-groundlings, to the wickedest of all fishers\r of men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2602},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-14","text":"For THIS am I from the heart and from the beginning—drawing,\r hither-drawing, upward-drawing, upbringing; a drawer, a trainer, a\r training-master, who not in vain counselled himself once on a time:\r “Become what thou art!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2603},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-15","text":"Thus may men now come UP to me; for as yet do I await the signs that it\r is time for my down-going; as yet do I not myself go down, as I must do,\r amongst men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2604},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-16","text":"Therefore do I here wait, crafty and scornful upon high mountains,\r no impatient one, no patient one; rather one who hath even unlearnt\r patience,—because he no longer “suffereth.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2605},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-17","text":"For my fate giveth me time: it hath forgotten me perhaps? Or doth it sit\r behind a big stone and catch flies?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2606},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-18","text":"And verily, I am well disposed to mine eternal fate, because it doth not\r hound and hurry me, but leaveth me time for merriment and mischief; so\r that I have to-day ascended this high mountain to catch fish.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2607},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-19","text":"Did ever any one catch fish upon high mountains? And though it be a\r folly what I here seek and do, it is better so than that down below I\r should become solemn with waiting, and green and yellow—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2608},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-20","text":"—A posturing wrath-snorter with waiting, a holy howl-storm from\r the mountains, an impatient one that shouteth down into the valleys:\r “Hearken, else I will scourge you with the scourge of God!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2609},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-21","text":"Not that I would have a grudge against such wrathful ones on that\r account: they are well enough for laughter to me! Impatient must they\r now be, those big alarm-drums, which find a voice now or never!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2610},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-22","text":"Myself, however, and my fate—we do not talk to the Present, neither\r do we talk to the Never: for talking we have patience and time and more\r than time. For one day must it yet come, and may not pass by.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2611},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-23","text":"What must one day come and may not pass by? Our great Hazar, that is\r to say, our great, remote human-kingdom, the Zarathustra-kingdom of a\r thousand years—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2612},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-24","text":"How remote may such “remoteness” be? What doth it concern me? But on\r that account it is none the less sure unto me—, with both feet stand I\r secure on this ground;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2613},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-25","text":"—On an eternal ground, on hard primary rock, on this highest, hardest,\r primary mountain-ridge, unto which all winds come, as unto the\r storm-parting, asking Where? and Whence? and Whither?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2614},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-26","text":"Here laugh, laugh, my hearty, healthy wickedness! From high mountains\r cast down thy glittering scorn-laughter! Allure for me with thy\r glittering the finest human fish!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2615},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-27","text":"And whatever belongeth unto ME in all seas, my in-and-for-me in all\r things—fish THAT out for me, bring THAT up to me: for that do I wait,\r the wickedest of all fish-catchers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2616},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-28","text":"Out! out! my fishing-hook! In and down, thou bait of my happiness! Drip\r thy sweetest dew, thou honey of my heart! Bite, my fishing-hook, into\r the belly of all black affliction!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2617},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-91-29","text":"Look out, look out, mine eye! Oh, how many seas round about me, what\r dawning human futures! And above me—what rosy red stillness! What\r unclouded silence!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2618},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-1","text":"The next day sat Zarathustra again on the stone in front of his cave,\r whilst his animals roved about in the world outside to bring home new\r food,—also new honey: for Zarathustra had spent and wasted the old\r honey to the very last particle. When he thus sat, however, with a\r stick in his hand, tracing the shadow of his figure on the earth, and\r reflecting—verily! not upon himself and his shadow,—all at once he\r startled and shrank back: for he saw another shadow beside his own.\r And when he hastily looked around and stood up, behold, there stood the\r soothsayer beside him, the same whom he had once given to eat and drink\r at his table, the proclaimer of the great weariness, who taught: “Al","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2619},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-2","text":"The soothsayer, who had perceived what went on in Zarathustra’s soul,\r wiped his face with his hand, as if he would wipe out the impression;\r the same did also Zarathustra. And when both of them had thus silently\r composed and strengthened themselves, they gave each other the hand, as\r a token that they wanted once more to recognise each other.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2620},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-3","text":"“Welcome hither,” said Zarathustra, “thou soothsayer of the great\r weariness, not in vain shalt thou once have been my messmate and guest.\r Eat and drink also with me to-day, and forgive it that a cheerful old\r man sitteth with thee at table!”—“A cheerful old man?” answered the\r soothsayer, shaking his head, “but whoever thou art, or wouldst be, O\r Zarathustra, thou hast been here aloft the longest time,—in a little\r while thy bark shall no longer rest on dry land!”—“Do I then rest\r on dry land?”—asked Zarathustra, laughing.—“The waves around thy\r mountain,” answered the soothsayer, “rise and rise, the waves of great\r distress and affliction: they will soon raise thy bark also and carry\r the","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2621},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-4","text":"“Thou ill announcer,” said Zarathustra at last, “that is a cry of\r distress, and the cry of a man; it may come perhaps out of a black sea.\r But what doth human distress matter to me! My last sin which hath been\r reserved for me,—knowest thou what it is called?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2622},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-5","text":"—“PITY!” answered the soothsayer from an overflowing heart, and raised\r both his hands aloft—“O Zarathustra, I have come that I may seduce thee\r to thy last sin!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2623},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-6","text":"And hardly had those words been uttered when there sounded the cry\r once more, and longer and more alarming than before—also much nearer.\r “Hearest thou? Hearest thou, O Zarathustra?” called out the soothsayer,\r “the cry concerneth thee, it calleth thee: Come, come, come; it is time,\r it is the highest time!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2624},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-7","text":"Zarathustra was silent thereupon, confused and staggered; at last he\r asked, like one who hesitateth in himself: “And who is it that there\r calleth me?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2625},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-8","text":"“But thou knowest it, certainly,” answered the soothsayer warmly, “why\r dost thou conceal thyself? It is THE HIGHER MAN that crieth for thee!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2626},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-9","text":"“The higher man?” cried Zarathustra, horror-stricken: “what wanteth HE?\r What wanteth HE? The higher man! What wanteth he here?”—and his skin\r covered with perspiration.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2627},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-10","text":"The soothsayer, however, did not heed Zarathustra’s alarm, but listened\r and listened in the downward direction. When, however, it had been still\r there for a long while, he looked behind, and saw Zarathustra standing\r trembling.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2628},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-11","text":"“O Zarathustra,” he began, with sorrowful voice, “thou dost not stand\r there like one whose happiness maketh him giddy: thou wilt have to dance\r lest thou tumble down!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2629},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-12","text":"But although thou shouldst dance before me, and leap all thy side-leaps,\r no one may say unto me: ‘Behold, here danceth the last joyous man!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2630},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-13","text":"In vain would any one come to this height who sought HIM here: caves\r would he find, indeed, and back-caves, hiding-places for hidden ones;\r but not lucky mines, nor treasure-chambers, nor new gold-veins of\r happiness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2631},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-14","text":"Happiness—how indeed could one find happiness among such buried-alive\r and solitary ones! Must I yet seek the last happiness on the Happy\r Isles, and far away among forgotten seas?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2632},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-15","text":"But all is alike, nothing is worth while, no seeking is of service,\r there are no longer any Happy Isles!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2633},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-16","text":"Thus sighed the soothsayer; with his last sigh, however, Zarathustra\r again became serene and assured, like one who hath come out of a deep\r chasm into the light. “Nay! Nay! Three times Nay!” exclaimed he with a\r strong voice, and stroked his beard—“THAT do I know better! There are\r still Happy Isles! Silence THEREON, thou sighing sorrow-sack!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2634},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-17","text":"Cease to splash THEREON, thou rain-cloud of the forenoon! Do I not\r already stand here wet with thy misery, and drenched like a dog?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2635},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-18","text":"Now do I shake myself and run away from thee, that I may again become\r dry: thereat mayest thou not wonder! Do I seem to thee discourteous?\r Here however is MY court.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2636},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-19","text":"But as regards the higher man: well! I shall seek him at once in those\r forests: FROM THENCE came his cry. Perhaps he is there hard beset by an\r evil beast.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2637},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-20","text":"He is in MY domain: therein shall he receive no scath! And verily, there\r are many evil beasts about me.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2638},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-21","text":"With those words Zarathustra turned around to depart. Then said the\r soothsayer: “O Zarathustra, thou art a rogue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2639},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-22","text":"I know it well: thou wouldst fain be rid of me! Rather wouldst thou run\r into the forest and lay snares for evil beasts!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2640},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-23","text":"But what good-will it do thee? In the evening wilt thou have me again:\r in thine own cave will I sit, patient and heavy like a block—and wait\r for thee!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2641},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-24","text":"“So be it!” shouted back Zarathustra, as he went away: “and what is mine\r in my cave belongeth also unto thee, my guest!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2642},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-25","text":"Shouldst thou however find honey therein, well! just lick it up, thou\r growling bear, and sweeten thy soul! For in the evening we want both to\r be in good spirits;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2643},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-26","text":"—In good spirits and joyful, because this day hath come to an end! And\r thou thyself shalt dance to my lays, as my dancing-bear.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2644},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-92-27","text":"Thou dost not believe this? Thou shakest thy head? Well! Cheer up, old\r bear! But I also—am a soothsayer.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2645},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-1","text":"Ere Zarathustra had been an hour on his way in the mountains and\r forests, he saw all at once a strange procession. Right on the path\r which he was about to descend came two kings walking, bedecked with\r crowns and purple girdles, and variegated like flamingoes: they drove\r before them a laden ass. “What do these kings want in my domain?” said\r Zarathustra in astonishment to his heart, and hid himself hastily behind\r a thicket. When however the kings approached to him, he said half-aloud,\r like one speaking only to himself: “Strange! Strange! How doth this\r harmonise? Two kings do I see—and only one ass!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2646},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-2","text":"Thereupon the two kings made a halt; they smiled and looked towards the\r spot whence the voice proceeded, and afterwards looked into each other’s\r faces. “Such things do we also think among ourselves,” said the king on\r the right, “but we do not utter them.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2647},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-3","text":"The king on the left, however, shrugged his shoulders and answered:\r “That may perhaps be a goat-herd. Or an anchorite who hath lived too\r long among rocks and trees. For no society at all spoileth also good\r manners.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2648},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-4","text":"“Good manners?” replied angrily and bitterly the other king: “what\r then do we run out of the way of? Is it not ‘good manners’? Our ‘good\r society’?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2649},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-5","text":"Better, verily, to live among anchorites and goatherds, than with\r our gilded, false, over-rouged populace—though it call itself ‘good\r society.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2650},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-6","text":"—Though it call itself ‘nobility.’ But there all is false and foul,\r above all the blood—thanks to old evil diseases and worse curers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2651},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-7","text":"The best and dearest to me at present is still a sound peasant, coarse,\r artful, obstinate and enduring: that is at present the noblest type.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2652},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-8","text":"The peasant is at present the best; and the peasant type should be\r master! But it is the kingdom of the populace—I no longer allow\r anything to be imposed upon me. The populace, however—that meaneth,\r hodgepodge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2653},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-9","text":"Populace-hodgepodge: therein is everything mixed with everything, saint\r and swindler, gentleman and Jew, and every beast out of Noah’s ark.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2654},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-10","text":"Good manners! Everything is false and foul with us. No one knoweth any\r longer how to reverence: it is THAT precisely that we run away from.\r They are fulsome obtrusive dogs; they gild palm-leaves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2655},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-11","text":"This loathing choketh me, that we kings ourselves have become false,\r draped and disguised with the old faded pomp of our ancestors,\r show-pieces for the stupidest, the craftiest, and whosoever at present\r trafficketh for power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2656},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-12","text":"We ARE NOT the first men—and have nevertheless to STAND FOR them: of\r this imposture have we at last become weary and disgusted.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2657},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-13","text":"From the rabble have we gone out of the way, from all those bawlers and\r scribe-blowflies, from the trader-stench, the ambition-fidgeting, the\r bad breath—: fie, to live among the rabble;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2658},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-14","text":"—Fie, to stand for the first men among the rabble! Ah, loathing!\r Loathing! Loathing! What doth it now matter about us kings!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2659},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-15","text":"“Thine old sickness seizeth thee,” said here the king on the left, “thy\r loathing seizeth thee, my poor brother. Thou knowest, however, that some\r one heareth us.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2660},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-16","text":"Immediately thereupon, Zarathustra, who had opened ears and eyes to this\r talk, rose from his hiding-place, advanced towards the kings, and thus\r began:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2661},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-17","text":"“He who hearkeneth unto you, he who gladly hearkeneth unto you, is\r called Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2662},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-18","text":"I am Zarathustra who once said: ‘What doth it now matter about kings!’\r Forgive me; I rejoiced when ye said to each other: ‘What doth it matter\r about us kings!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2663},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-19","text":"Here, however, is MY domain and jurisdiction: what may ye be seeking in\r my domain? Perhaps, however, ye have FOUND on your way what _I_ seek:\r namely, the higher man.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2664},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-20","text":"When the kings heard this, they beat upon their breasts and said with\r one voice: “We are recognised!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2665},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-21","text":"With the sword of thine utterance severest thou the thickest darkness of\r our hearts. Thou hast discovered our distress; for lo! we are on our way\r to find the higher man—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2666},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-22","text":"—The man that is higher than we, although we are kings. To him do we\r convey this ass. For the highest man shall also be the highest lord on\r earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2667},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-23","text":"There is no sorer misfortune in all human destiny, than when the mighty\r of the earth are not also the first men. Then everything becometh false\r and distorted and monstrous.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2668},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-24","text":"And when they are even the last men, and more beast than man, then\r riseth and riseth the populace in honour, and at last saith even the\r populace-virtue: ‘Lo, I alone am virtue!’”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2669},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-25","text":"What have I just heard? answered Zarathustra. What wisdom in kings! I\r am enchanted, and verily, I have already promptings to make a rhyme\r thereon:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2670},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-26","text":"—Even if it should happen to be a rhyme not suited for every one’s\r ears. I unlearned long ago to have consideration for long ears. Well\r then! Well now!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2671},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-27","text":"(Here, however, it happened that the ass also found utterance: it said\r distinctly and with malevolence, Y-E-A.)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2672},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-28","text":"‘Twas once—methinks year one of our blessed Lord,—Drunk without wine,\r the Sybil thus deplored:—“How ill things go! Decline! Decline! Ne’er\r sank the world so low! Rome now hath turned harlot and harlot-stew,\r Rome’s Caesar a beast, and God—hath turned Jew!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2673},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-29","text":"With those rhymes of Zarathustra the kings were delighted; the king on\r the right, however, said: “O Zarathustra, how well it was that we set\r out to see thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2674},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-30","text":"For thine enemies showed us thy likeness in their mirror: there lookedst\r thou with the grimace of a devil, and sneeringly: so that we were afraid\r of thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2675},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-31","text":"But what good did it do! Always didst thou prick us anew in heart and\r ear with thy sayings. Then did we say at last: What doth it matter how\r he look!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2676},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-32","text":"We must HEAR him; him who teacheth: ‘Ye shall love peace as a means to\r new wars, and the short peace more than the long!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2677},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-33","text":"No one ever spake such warlike words: ‘What is good? To be brave is\r good. It is the good war that halloweth every cause.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2678},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-34","text":"O Zarathustra, our fathers’ blood stirred in our veins at such words: it\r was like the voice of spring to old wine-casks.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2679},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-35","text":"When the swords ran among one another like red-spotted serpents, then\r did our fathers become fond of life; the sun of every peace seemed to\r them languid and lukewarm, the long peace, however, made them ashamed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2680},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-36","text":"How they sighed, our fathers, when they saw on the wall brightly\r furbished, dried-up swords! Like those they thirsted for war. For a\r sword thirsteth to drink blood, and sparkleth with desire.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2681},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-37","text":"—When the kings thus discoursed and talked eagerly of the happiness of\r their fathers, there came upon Zarathustra no little desire to mock at\r their eagerness: for evidently they were very peaceable kings whom he\r saw before him, kings with old and refined features. But he restrained\r himself. “Well!” said he, “thither leadeth the way, there lieth the\r cave of Zarathustra; and this day is to have a long evening! At present,\r however, a cry of distress calleth me hastily away from you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2682},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-38","text":"It will honour my cave if kings want to sit and wait in it: but, to be\r sure, ye will have to wait long!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2683},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-93-39","text":"Well! What of that! Where doth one at present learn better to wait\r than at courts? And the whole virtue of kings that hath remained unto\r them—is it not called to-day: ABILITY to wait?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2684},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-1","text":"And Zarathustra went thoughtfully on, further and lower down, through\r forests and past moory bottoms; as it happeneth, however, to every one\r who meditateth upon hard matters, he trod thereby unawares upon a man.\r And lo, there spurted into his face all at once a cry of pain, and two\r curses and twenty bad invectives, so that in his fright he raised his\r stick and also struck the trodden one. Immediately afterwards, however,\r he regained his composure, and his heart laughed at the folly he had\r just committed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2685},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-2","text":"“Pardon me,” said he to the trodden one, who had got up enraged, and had\r seated himself, “pardon me, and hear first of all a parable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2686},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-3","text":"As a wanderer who dreameth of remote things on a lonesome highway,\r runneth unawares against a sleeping dog, a dog which lieth in the sun:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2687},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-4","text":"—As both of them then start up and snap at each other, like deadly\r enemies, those two beings mortally frightened—so did it happen unto us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2688},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-5","text":"And yet! And yet—how little was lacking for them to caress each other,\r that dog and that lonesome one! Are they not both—lonesome ones!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2689},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-6","text":"—“Whoever thou art,” said the trodden one, still enraged, “thou\r treadest also too nigh me with thy parable, and not only with thy foot!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2690},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-7","text":"Lo! am I then a dog?”—And thereupon the sitting one got up, and pulled\r his naked arm out of the swamp. For at first he had lain outstretched\r on the ground, hidden and indiscernible, like those who lie in wait for\r swamp-game.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2691},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-8","text":"“But whatever art thou about!” called out Zarathustra in alarm, for he\r saw a deal of blood streaming over the naked arm,—“what hath hurt thee?\r Hath an evil beast bit thee, thou unfortunate one?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2692},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-9","text":"The bleeding one laughed, still angry, “What matter is it to thee!” said\r he, and was about to go on. “Here am I at home and in my province.\r Let him question me whoever will: to a dolt, however, I shall hardly\r answer.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2693},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-10","text":"“Thou art mistaken,” said Zarathustra sympathetically, and held him\r fast; “thou art mistaken. Here thou art not at home, but in my domain,\r and therein shall no one receive any hurt.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2694},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-11","text":"Call me however what thou wilt—I am who I must be. I call myself\r Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2695},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-12","text":"Well! Up thither is the way to Zarathustra’s cave: it is not far,—wilt\r thou not attend to thy wounds at my home?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2696},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-13","text":"It hath gone badly with thee, thou unfortunate one, in this life: first\r a beast bit thee, and then—a man trod upon thee!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2697},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-14","text":"When however the trodden one had heard the name of Zarathustra he was\r transformed. “What happeneth unto me!” he exclaimed, “WHO preoccupieth\r me so much in this life as this one man, namely Zarathustra, and that\r one animal that liveth on blood, the leech?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2698},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-15","text":"For the sake of the leech did I lie here by this swamp, like a fisher,\r and already had mine outstretched arm been bitten ten times, when there\r biteth a still finer leech at my blood, Zarathustra himself!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2699},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-16","text":"O happiness! O miracle! Praised be this day which enticed me into the\r swamp! Praised be the best, the livest cupping-glass, that at present\r liveth; praised be the great conscience-leech Zarathustra!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2700},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-17","text":"Thus spake the trodden one, and Zarathustra rejoiced at his words and\r their refined reverential style. “Who art thou?” asked he, and gave\r him his hand, “there is much to clear up and elucidate between us, but\r already methinketh pure clear day is dawning.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2701},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-18","text":"“I am THE SPIRITUALLY CONSCIENTIOUS ONE,” answered he who was asked,\r “and in matters of the spirit it is difficult for any one to take it\r more rigorously, more restrictedly, and more severely than I, except him\r from whom I learnt it, Zarathustra himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2702},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-19","text":"Better know nothing than half-know many things! Better be a fool on\r one’s own account, than a sage on other people’s approbation! I—go to\r the basis:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2703},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-20","text":"—What matter if it be great or small? If it be called swamp or sky?\r A handbreadth of basis is enough for me, if it be actually basis and\r ground!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2704},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-21","text":"—A handbreadth of basis: thereon can one stand. In the true\r knowing-knowledge there is nothing great and nothing small.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2705},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-22","text":"“Then thou art perhaps an expert on the leech?” asked Zarathustra; “and\r thou investigatest the leech to its ultimate basis, thou conscientious\r one?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2706},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-23","text":"“O Zarathustra,” answered the trodden one, “that would be something\r immense; how could I presume to do so!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2707},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-24","text":"That, however, of which I am master and knower, is the BRAIN of the\r leech:—that is MY world!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2708},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-25","text":"And it is also a world! Forgive it, however, that my pride here findeth\r expression, for here I have not mine equal. Therefore said I: ‘here am I\r at home.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2709},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-26","text":"How long have I investigated this one thing, the brain of the leech, so\r that here the slippery truth might no longer slip from me! Here is MY\r domain!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2710},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-27","text":"—For the sake of this did I cast everything else aside, for the sake of\r this did everything else become indifferent to me; and close beside my\r knowledge lieth my black ignorance.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2711},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-28","text":"My spiritual conscience requireth from me that it should be so—that I\r should know one thing, and not know all else: they are a loathing unto\r me, all the semi-spiritual, all the hazy, hovering, and visionary.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2712},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-29","text":"Where mine honesty ceaseth, there am I blind, and want also to be blind.\r Where I want to know, however, there want I also to be honest—namely,\r severe, rigorous, restricted, cruel and inexorable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2713},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-30","text":"Because THOU once saidest, O Zarathustra: ‘Spirit is life which itself\r cutteth into life’;—that led and allured me to thy doctrine. And\r verily, with mine own blood have I increased mine own knowledge!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2714},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-31","text":"—“As the evidence indicateth,” broke in Zarathustra; for still was the\r blood flowing down on the naked arm of the conscientious one. For there\r had ten leeches bitten into it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2715},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-32","text":"“O thou strange fellow, how much doth this very evidence teach\r me—namely, thou thyself! And not all, perhaps, might I pour into thy\r rigorous ear!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2716},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-33","text":"Well then! We part here! But I would fain find thee again. Up thither is\r the way to my cave: to-night shalt thou there be my welcome guest!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2717},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-94-34","text":"Fain would I also make amends to thy body for Zarathustra treading upon\r thee with his feet: I think about that. Just now, however, a cry of\r distress calleth me hastily away from thee.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2718},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-1","text":"When however Zarathustra had gone round a rock, then saw he on the same\r path, not far below him, a man who threw his limbs about like a maniac,\r and at last tumbled to the ground on his belly. “Halt!” said then\r Zarathustra to his heart, “he there must surely be the higher man, from\r him came that dreadful cry of distress,—I will see if I can help him.”\r  When, however, he ran to the spot where the man lay on the ground,\r he found a trembling old man, with fixed eyes; and in spite of all\r Zarathustra’s efforts to lift him and set him again on his feet, it was\r all in vain. The unfortunate one, also, did not seem to notice that some\r one was beside him; on the contrary, he continually looked","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2719},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-2","text":"Who warm’th me, who lov’th me still?\r      Give ardent fingers!\r      Give heartening charcoal-warmers!\r      Prone, outstretched, trembling,\r      Like him, half dead and cold, whose feet one warm’th—\r      And shaken, ah! by unfamiliar fevers,\r      Shivering with sharpened, icy-cold frost-arrows,\r      By thee pursued, my fancy!\r      Ineffable!  Recondite!  Sore-frightening!\r      Thou huntsman ’hind the cloud-banks!\r      Now lightning-struck by thee,\r      Thou mocking eye that me in darkness watcheth:\r      —Thus do I lie,\r      Bend myself, twist myself, convulsed\r      With all eternal torture,\r      And smitten\r      By thee, cruellest huntsman,\r      Thou unfamiliar—GOD...","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2720},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-3","text":"Smite deeper!\r      Smite yet once more!\r      Pierce through and rend my heart!\r      What mean’th this torture\r      With dull, indented arrows?\r      Why look’st thou hither,\r      Of human pain not weary,\r      With mischief-loving, godly flash-glances?\r      Not murder wilt thou,\r      But torture, torture?\r      For why—ME torture,\r      Thou mischief-loving, unfamiliar God?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2721},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-4","text":"Ha!  Ha!\r      Thou stealest nigh\r      In midnight’s gloomy hour?...\r      What wilt thou?\r      Speak!\r      Thou crowdst me, pressest—\r      Ha! now far too closely!\r      Thou hearst me breathing,\r      Thou o’erhearst my heart,\r      Thou ever jealous one!\r      —Of what, pray, ever jealous?\r      Off!  Off!\r      For why the ladder?\r      Wouldst thou GET IN?\r      To heart in-clamber?\r      To mine own secretest\r      Conceptions in-clamber?\r      Shameless one!  Thou unknown one!—Thief!\r      What seekst thou by thy stealing?\r      What seekst thou by thy hearkening?\r      What seekst thou by thy torturing?\r      Thou torturer!\r      Thou—hangman-God!\r      Or shall I, as the mastiff","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2722},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-5","text":"In vain!\r      Goad further!\r      Cruellest goader!\r      No dog—thy game just am I,\r      Cruellest huntsman!\r      Thy proudest of captives,\r      Thou robber ’hind the cloud-banks ...\r      Speak finally!\r      Thou lightning-veiled one!  Thou unknown one!  Speak!\r      What wilt thou, highway-ambusher, from—ME?\r      What WILT thou, unfamiliar—God?\r      What?\r      Ransom-gold?\r      How much of ransom-gold?\r      Solicit much—that bid’th my pride!\r      And be concise—that bid’th mine other pride!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2723},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-6","text":"Ha!  Ha!\r      And torturest me, fool that thou art,\r      Dead-torturest quite my pride?\r      Give LOVE to me—who warm’th me still?\r      Who lov’th me still?—\r      Give ardent fingers,\r      Give heartening charcoal-warmers,\r      Give me, the lonesomest,\r      The ice (ah! seven-fold frozen ice,\r      For very enemies,\r      For foes, doth make one thirst),\r      Give, yield to me,\r      Cruellest foe,\r      —THYSELF!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2724},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-7","text":"Away!\r      There fled he surely,\r      My final, only comrade,\r      My greatest foe,\r      Mine unfamiliar—\r      My hangman-God!...","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2725},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-8","text":"—Nay!\r      Come thou back!\r      WITH all of thy great tortures!\r      To me the last of lonesome ones,\r      Oh, come thou back!\r      All my hot tears in streamlets trickle\r      Their course to thee!\r      And all my final hearty fervour—\r      Up-glow’th to THEE!\r      Oh, come thou back,\r      Mine unfamiliar God! my PAIN!\r      My final bliss!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2726},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-9","text":"—Here, however, Zarathustra could no longer restrain himself; he took\r his staff and struck the wailer with all his might. “Stop this,” cried\r he to him with wrathful laughter, “stop this, thou stage-player! Thou\r false coiner! Thou liar from the very heart! I know thee well!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2727},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-10","text":"I will soon make warm legs to thee, thou evil magician: I know well\r how—to make it hot for such as thou!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2728},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-11","text":"—“Leave off,” said the old man, and sprang up from the ground, “strike\r me no more, O Zarathustra! I did it only for amusement!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2729},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-12","text":"That kind of thing belongeth to mine art. Thee thyself, I wanted to put\r to the proof when I gave this performance. And verily, thou hast well\r detected me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2730},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-13","text":"But thou thyself—hast given me no small proof of thyself: thou art\r HARD, thou wise Zarathustra! Hard strikest thou with thy ‘truths,’ thy\r cudgel forceth from me—THIS truth!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2731},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-14","text":"—“Flatter not,” answered Zarathustra, still excited and frowning,\r “thou stage-player from the heart! Thou art false: why speakest thou—of\r truth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2732},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-15","text":"Thou peacock of peacocks, thou sea of vanity; WHAT didst thou represent\r before me, thou evil magician; WHOM was I meant to believe in when thou\r wailedst in such wise?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2733},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-16","text":"“THE PENITENT IN SPIRIT,” said the old man, “it was him—I represented;\r thou thyself once devisedst this expression—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2734},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-17","text":"—The poet and magician who at last turneth his spirit against himself,\r the transformed one who freezeth to death by his bad science and\r conscience.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2735},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-18","text":"And just acknowledge it: it was long, O Zarathustra, before thou\r discoveredst my trick and lie! Thou BELIEVEDST in my distress when thou\r heldest my head with both thy hands,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2736},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-19","text":"—I heard thee lament ‘we have loved him too little, loved him too\r little!’ Because I so far deceived thee, my wickedness rejoiced in me.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2737},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-20","text":"“Thou mayest have deceived subtler ones than I,” said Zarathustra\r sternly. “I am not on my guard against deceivers; I HAVE TO BE without\r precaution: so willeth my lot.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2738},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-21","text":"Thou, however,—MUST deceive: so far do I know thee! Thou must ever be\r equivocal, trivocal, quadrivocal, and quinquivocal! Even what thou hast\r now confessed, is not nearly true enough nor false enough for me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2739},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-22","text":"Thou bad false coiner, how couldst thou do otherwise! Thy very malady\r wouldst thou whitewash if thou showed thyself naked to thy physician.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2740},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-23","text":"Thus didst thou whitewash thy lie before me when thou saidst: ‘I did\r so ONLY for amusement!’ There was also SERIOUSNESS therein, thou ART\r something of a penitent-in-spirit!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2741},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-24","text":"I divine thee well: thou hast become the enchanter of all the world; but\r for thyself thou hast no lie or artifice left,—thou art disenchanted to\r thyself!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2742},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-25","text":"Thou hast reaped disgust as thy one truth. No word in thee is any longer\r genuine, but thy mouth is so: that is to say, the disgust that cleaveth\r unto thy mouth.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2743},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-26","text":"—“Who art thou at all!” cried here the old magician with defiant voice,\r “who dareth to speak thus unto ME, the greatest man now living?”—and a\r green flash shot from his eye at Zarathustra. But immediately after he\r changed, and said sadly:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2744},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-27","text":"“O Zarathustra, I am weary of it, I am disgusted with mine arts, I am\r not GREAT, why do I dissemble! But thou knowest it well—I sought for\r greatness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2745},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-28","text":"A great man I wanted to appear, and persuaded many; but the lie hath\r been beyond my power. On it do I collapse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2746},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-29","text":"O Zarathustra, everything is a lie in me; but that I collapse—this my\r collapsing is GENUINE!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2747},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-30","text":"“It honoureth thee,” said Zarathustra gloomily, looking down with\r sidelong glance, “it honoureth thee that thou soughtest for greatness,\r but it betrayeth thee also. Thou art not great.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2748},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-31","text":"Thou bad old magician, THAT is the best and the honestest thing I honour\r in thee, that thou hast become weary of thyself, and hast expressed it:\r ‘I am not great.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2749},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-32","text":"THEREIN do I honour thee as a penitent-in-spirit, and although only for\r the twinkling of an eye, in that one moment wast thou—genuine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2750},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-33","text":"But tell me, what seekest thou here in MY forests and rocks? And if thou\r hast put thyself in MY way, what proof of me wouldst thou have?—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2751},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-34","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and his eyes sparkled. But the old magician kept\r silence for a while; then said he: “Did I put thee to the test? I—seek\r only.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2752},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-35","text":"O Zarathustra, I seek a genuine one, a right one, a simple one, an\r unequivocal one, a man of perfect honesty, a vessel of wisdom, a saint\r of knowledge, a great man!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2753},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-36","text":"—And here there arose a long silence between them: Zarathustra,\r however, became profoundly absorbed in thought, so that he shut his\r eyes. But afterwards coming back to the situation, he grasped the hand\r of the magician, and said, full of politeness and policy:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2754},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-37","text":"“Well! Up thither leadeth the way, there is the cave of Zarathustra. In\r it mayest thou seek him whom thou wouldst fain find.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2755},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-38","text":"And ask counsel of mine animals, mine eagle and my serpent: they shall\r help thee to seek. My cave however is large.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2756},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-39","text":"I myself, to be sure—I have as yet seen no great man. That which is\r great, the acutest eye is at present insensible to it. It is the kingdom\r of the populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2757},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-40","text":"Many a one have I found who stretched and inflated himself, and the\r people cried: ‘Behold; a great man!’ But what good do all bellows do!\r The wind cometh out at last.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2758},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-41","text":"At last bursteth the frog which hath inflated itself too long: then\r cometh out the wind. To prick a swollen one in the belly, I call good\r pastime. Hear that, ye boys!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2759},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-42","text":"Our to-day is of the populace: who still KNOWETH what is great and what\r is small! Who could there seek successfully for greatness! A fool only:\r it succeedeth with fools.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2760},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-43","text":"Thou seekest for great men, thou strange fool? Who TAUGHT that to thee?\r Is to-day the time for it? Oh, thou bad seeker, why dost thou—tempt\r me?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2761},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-95-44","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, comforted in his heart, and went laughing on his\r way.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2762},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-1","text":"Not long, however, after Zarathustra had freed himself from the\r magician, he again saw a person sitting beside the path which he\r followed, namely a tall, black man, with a haggard, pale countenance:\r THIS MAN grieved him exceedingly. “Alas,” said he to his heart, “there\r sitteth disguised affliction; methinketh he is of the type of the\r priests: what do THEY want in my domain?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2763},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-2","text":"What! Hardly have I escaped from that magician, and must another\r necromancer again run across my path,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2764},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-3","text":"—Some sorcerer with laying-on-of-hands, some sombre wonder-worker by\r the grace of God, some anointed world-maligner, whom, may the devil\r take!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2765},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-4","text":"But the devil is never at the place which would be his right place: he\r always cometh too late, that cursed dwarf and club-foot!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2766},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-5","text":"Thus cursed Zarathustra impatiently in his heart, and considered how\r with averted look he might slip past the black man. But behold, it came\r about otherwise. For at the same moment had the sitting one already\r perceived him; and not unlike one whom an unexpected happiness\r overtaketh, he sprang to his feet, and went straight towards\r Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2767},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-6","text":"“Whoever thou art, thou traveller,” said he, “help a strayed one, a\r seeker, an old man, who may here easily come to grief!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2768},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-7","text":"The world here is strange to me, and remote; wild beasts also did I hear\r howling; and he who could have given me protection—he is himself no\r more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2769},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-8","text":"I was seeking the pious man, a saint and an anchorite, who, alone in his\r forest, had not yet heard of what all the world knoweth at present.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2770},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-9","text":"“WHAT doth all the world know at present?” asked Zarathustra. “Perhaps\r that the old God no longer liveth, in whom all the world once believed?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2771},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-10","text":"“Thou sayest it,” answered the old man sorrowfully. “And I served that\r old God until his last hour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2772},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-11","text":"Now, however, am I out of service, without master, and yet not free;\r likewise am I no longer merry even for an hour, except it be in\r recollections.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2773},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-12","text":"Therefore did I ascend into these mountains, that I might finally have\r a festival for myself once more, as becometh an old pope and\r church-father: for know it, that I am the last pope!—a festival of\r pious recollections and divine services.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2774},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-13","text":"Now, however, is he himself dead, the most pious of men, the saint in\r the forest, who praised his God constantly with singing and mumbling.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2775},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-14","text":"He himself found I no longer when I found his cot—but two wolves found\r I therein, which howled on account of his death,—for all animals loved\r him. Then did I haste away.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2776},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-15","text":"Had I thus come in vain into these forests and mountains? Then did my\r heart determine that I should seek another, the most pious of all\r those who believe not in God—, my heart determined that I should seek\r Zarathustra!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2777},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-16","text":"Thus spake the hoary man, and gazed with keen eyes at him who stood\r before him. Zarathustra however seized the hand of the old pope and\r regarded it a long while with admiration.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2778},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-17","text":"“Lo! thou venerable one,” said he then, “what a fine and long hand! That\r is the hand of one who hath ever dispensed blessings. Now, however, doth\r it hold fast him whom thou seekest, me, Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2779},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-18","text":"It is I, the ungodly Zarathustra, who saith: ‘Who is ungodlier than I,\r that I may enjoy his teaching?’”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2780},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-19","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and penetrated with his glances the thoughts and\r arrear-thoughts of the old pope. At last the latter began:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2781},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-20","text":"“He who most loved and possessed him hath now also lost him most—:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2782},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-21","text":"—Lo, I myself am surely the most godless of us at present? But who\r could rejoice at that!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2783},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-22","text":"—“Thou servedst him to the last?” asked Zarathustra thoughtfully, after\r a deep silence, “thou knowest HOW he died? Is it true what they say,\r that sympathy choked him;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2784},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-23","text":"—That he saw how MAN hung on the cross, and could not endure it;—that\r his love to man became his hell, and at last his death?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2785},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-24","text":"The old pope however did not answer, but looked aside timidly, with a\r painful and gloomy expression.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2786},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-25","text":"“Let him go,” said Zarathustra, after prolonged meditation, still\r looking the old man straight in the eye.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2787},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-26","text":"“Let him go, he is gone. And though it honoureth thee that thou speakest\r only in praise of this dead one, yet thou knowest as well as I WHO he\r was, and that he went curious ways.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2788},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-27","text":"“To speak before three eyes,” said the old pope cheerfully (he was blind\r of one eye), “in divine matters I am more enlightened than Zarathustra\r himself—and may well be so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2789},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-28","text":"My love served him long years, my will followed all his will. A good\r servant, however, knoweth everything, and many a thing even which a\r master hideth from himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2790},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-29","text":"He was a hidden God, full of secrecy. Verily, he did not come by his\r son otherwise than by secret ways. At the door of his faith standeth\r adultery.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2791},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-30","text":"Whoever extolleth him as a God of love, doth not think highly enough of\r love itself. Did not that God want also to be judge? But the loving one\r loveth irrespective of reward and requital.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2792},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-31","text":"When he was young, that God out of the Orient, then was he harsh and\r revengeful, and built himself a hell for the delight of his favourites.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2793},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-32","text":"At last, however, he became old and soft and mellow and pitiful,\r more like a grandfather than a father, but most like a tottering old\r grandmother.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2794},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-33","text":"There did he sit shrivelled in his chimney-corner, fretting on account\r of his weak legs, world-weary, will-weary, and one day he suffocated of\r his all-too-great pity.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2795},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-34","text":"“Thou old pope,” said here Zarathustra interposing, “hast thou seen THAT\r with thine eyes? It could well have happened in that way: in that way,\r AND also otherwise. When Gods die they always die many kinds of death.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2796},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-35","text":"Well! At all events, one way or other—he is gone! He was counter to the\r taste of mine ears and eyes; worse than that I should not like to say\r against him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2797},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-36","text":"I love everything that looketh bright and speaketh honestly. But\r he—thou knowest it, forsooth, thou old priest, there was something of\r thy type in him, the priest-type—he was equivocal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2798},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-37","text":"He was also indistinct. How he raged at us, this wrath-snorter, because\r we understood him badly! But why did he not speak more clearly?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2799},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-38","text":"And if the fault lay in our ears, why did he give us ears that heard him\r badly? If there was dirt in our ears, well! who put it in them?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2800},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-39","text":"Too much miscarried with him, this potter who had not learned\r thoroughly! That he took revenge on his pots and creations, however,\r because they turned out badly—that was a sin against GOOD TASTE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2801},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-40","text":"There is also good taste in piety: THIS at last said: ‘Away with SUCH\r a God! Better to have no God, better to set up destiny on one’s own\r account, better to be a fool, better to be God oneself!’”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2802},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-41","text":"—“What do I hear!” said then the old pope, with intent ears; “O\r Zarathustra, thou art more pious than thou believest, with such an\r unbelief! Some God in thee hath converted thee to thine ungodliness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2803},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-42","text":"Is it not thy piety itself which no longer letteth thee believe in a\r God? And thine over-great honesty will yet lead thee even beyond good\r and evil!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2804},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-43","text":"Behold, what hath been reserved for thee? Thou hast eyes and hands and\r mouth, which have been predestined for blessing from eternity. One doth\r not bless with the hand alone.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2805},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-44","text":"Nigh unto thee, though thou professest to be the ungodliest one, I feel\r a hale and holy odour of long benedictions: I feel glad and grieved\r thereby.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2806},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-45","text":"Let me be thy guest, O Zarathustra, for a single night! Nowhere on earth\r shall I now feel better than with thee!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2807},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-46","text":"“Amen! So shall it be!” said Zarathustra, with great astonishment; “up\r thither leadeth the way, there lieth the cave of Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2808},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-47","text":"Gladly, forsooth, would I conduct thee thither myself, thou venerable\r one; for I love all pious men. But now a cry of distress calleth me\r hastily away from thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2809},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-48","text":"In my domain shall no one come to grief; my cave is a good haven. And\r best of all would I like to put every sorrowful one again on firm land\r and firm legs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2810},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-96-49","text":"Who, however, could take THY melancholy off thy shoulders? For that I am\r too weak. Long, verily, should we have to wait until some one re-awoke\r thy God for thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2811},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-1","text":"—And again did Zarathustra’s feet run through mountains and forests,\r and his eyes sought and sought, but nowhere was he to be seen whom they\r wanted to see—the sorely distressed sufferer and crier. On the whole\r way, however, he rejoiced in his heart and was full of gratitude. “What\r good things,” said he, “hath this day given me, as amends for its bad\r beginning! What strange interlocutors have I found!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2812},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-2","text":"At their words will I now chew a long while as at good corn; small\r shall my teeth grind and crush them, until they flow like milk into my\r soul!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2813},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-3","text":"When, however, the path again curved round a rock, all at once the\r landscape changed, and Zarathustra entered into a realm of death. Here\r bristled aloft black and red cliffs, without any grass, tree, or bird’s\r voice. For it was a valley which all animals avoided, even the beasts of\r prey, except that a species of ugly, thick, green serpent came here to\r die when they became old. Therefore the shepherds called this valley:\r “Serpent-death.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2814},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-4","text":"Zarathustra, however, became absorbed in dark recollections, for it\r seemed to him as if he had once before stood in this valley. And much\r heaviness settled on his mind, so that he walked slowly and always more\r slowly, and at last stood still. Then, however, when he opened his eyes,\r he saw something sitting by the wayside shaped like a man, and hardly\r like a man, something nondescript. And all at once there came over\r Zarathustra a great shame, because he had gazed on such a thing.\r Blushing up to the very roots of his white hair, he turned aside his\r glance, and raised his foot that he might leave this ill-starred place.\r Then, however, became the dead wilderness vocal: for from the gro","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2815},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-5","text":"“Zarathustra! Zarathustra! Read my riddle! Say, say! WHAT IS THE REVENGE\r ON THE WITNESS?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2816},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-6","text":"I entice thee back; here is smooth ice! See to it, see to it, that thy\r pride doth not here break its legs!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2817},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-7","text":"Thou thinkest thyself wise, thou proud Zarathustra! Read then the\r riddle, thou hard nut-cracker,—the riddle that I am! Say then: who am\r _I_!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2818},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-8","text":"—When however Zarathustra had heard these words,—what think ye then\r took place in his soul? PITY OVERCAME HIM; and he sank down all at\r once, like an oak that hath long withstood many tree-fellers,—heavily,\r suddenly, to the terror even of those who meant to fell it. But\r immediately he got up again from the ground, and his countenance became\r stern.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2819},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-9","text":"“I know thee well,” said he, with a brazen voice, “THOU ART THE MURDERER\r OF GOD! Let me go.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2820},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-10","text":"Thou couldst not ENDURE him who beheld THEE,—who ever beheld thee\r through and through, thou ugliest man. Thou tookest revenge on this\r witness!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2821},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-11","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra and was about to go; but the nondescript grasped\r at a corner of his garment and began anew to gurgle and seek for words.\r “Stay,” said he at last—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2822},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-12","text":"—“Stay! Do not pass by! I have divined what axe it was that struck thee\r to the ground: hail to thee, O Zarathustra, that thou art again upon thy\r feet!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2823},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-13","text":"Thou hast divined, I know it well, how the man feeleth who killed\r him,—the murderer of God. Stay! Sit down here beside me; it is not to\r no purpose.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2824},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-14","text":"To whom would I go but unto thee? Stay, sit down! Do not however look at\r me! Honour thus—mine ugliness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2825},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-15","text":"They persecute me: now art THOU my last refuge. NOT with their hatred,\r NOT with their bailiffs;—Oh, such persecution would I mock at, and be\r proud and cheerful!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2826},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-16","text":"Hath not all success hitherto been with the well-persecuted ones? And\r he who persecuteth well learneth readily to be OBSEQUENT—when once he\r is—put behind! But it is their PITY—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2827},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-17","text":"—Their pity is it from which I flee away and flee to thee. O\r Zarathustra, protect me, thou, my last refuge, thou sole one who\r divinedst me:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2828},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-18","text":"—Thou hast divined how the man feeleth who killed HIM. Stay! And if\r thou wilt go, thou impatient one, go not the way that I came. THAT way\r is bad.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2829},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-19","text":"Art thou angry with me because I have already racked language too long?\r Because I have already counselled thee? But know that it is I, the\r ugliest man,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2830},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-20","text":"—Who have also the largest, heaviest feet. Where _I_ have gone, the way\r is bad. I tread all paths to death and destruction.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2831},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-21","text":"But that thou passedst me by in silence, that thou blushedst—I saw it\r well: thereby did I know thee as Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2832},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-22","text":"Every one else would have thrown to me his alms, his pity, in look and\r speech. But for that—I am not beggar enough: that didst thou divine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2833},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-23","text":"For that I am too RICH, rich in what is great, frightful, ugliest, most\r unutterable! Thy shame, O Zarathustra, HONOURED me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2834},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-24","text":"With difficulty did I get out of the crowd of the pitiful,—that I might\r find the only one who at present teacheth that ‘pity is obtrusive’—\r thyself, O Zarathustra!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2835},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-25","text":"—Whether it be the pity of a God, or whether it be human pity, it is\r offensive to modesty. And unwillingness to help may be nobler than the\r virtue that rusheth to do so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2836},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-26","text":"THAT however—namely, pity—is called virtue itself at present by\r all petty people:—they have no reverence for great misfortune, great\r ugliness, great failure.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2837},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-27","text":"Beyond all these do I look, as a dog looketh over the backs of thronging\r flocks of sheep. They are petty, good-wooled, good-willed, grey people.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2838},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-28","text":"As the heron looketh contemptuously at shallow pools, with backward-bent\r head, so do I look at the throng of grey little waves and wills and\r souls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2839},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-29","text":"Too long have we acknowledged them to be right, those petty people: SO\r we have at last given them power as well;—and now do they teach that\r ‘good is only what petty people call good.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2840},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-30","text":"And ‘truth’ is at present what the preacher spake who himself sprang\r from them, that singular saint and advocate of the petty people, who\r testified of himself: ‘I—am the truth.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2841},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-31","text":"That immodest one hath long made the petty people greatly puffed up,—he\r who taught no small error when he taught: ‘I—am the truth.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2842},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-32","text":"Hath an immodest one ever been answered more courteously?—Thou,\r however, O Zarathustra, passedst him by, and saidst: ‘Nay! Nay! Three\r times Nay!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2843},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-33","text":"Thou warnedst against his error; thou warnedst—the first to do\r so—against pity:—not every one, not none, but thyself and thy type.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2844},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-34","text":"Thou art ashamed of the shame of the great sufferer; and verily when\r thou sayest: ‘From pity there cometh a heavy cloud; take heed, ye men!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2845},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-35","text":"—When thou teachest: ‘All creators are hard, all great love is beyond\r their pity:’ O Zarathustra, how well versed dost thou seem to me in\r weather-signs!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2846},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-36","text":"Thou thyself, however,—warn thyself also against THY pity! For many are\r on their way to thee, many suffering, doubting, despairing, drowning,\r freezing ones—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2847},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-37","text":"I warn thee also against myself. Thou hast read my best, my worst\r riddle, myself, and what I have done. I know the axe that felleth thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2848},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-38","text":"But he—HAD TO die: he looked with eyes which beheld EVERYTHING,—he\r beheld men’s depths and dregs, all his hidden ignominy and ugliness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2849},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-39","text":"His pity knew no modesty: he crept into my dirtiest corners. This most\r prying, over-intrusive, over-pitiful one had to die.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2850},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-40","text":"He ever beheld ME: on such a witness I would have revenge—or not live\r myself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2851},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-41","text":"The God who beheld everything, AND ALSO MAN: that God had to die! Man\r cannot ENDURE it that such a witness should live.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2852},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-42","text":"Thus spake the ugliest man. Zarathustra however got up, and prepared to\r go on: for he felt frozen to the very bowels.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2853},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-43","text":"“Thou nondescript,” said he, “thou warnedst me against thy path. As\r thanks for it I praise mine to thee. Behold, up thither is the cave of\r Zarathustra.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2854},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-44","text":"My cave is large and deep and hath many corners; there findeth he\r that is most hidden his hiding-place. And close beside it, there are\r a hundred lurking-places and by-places for creeping, fluttering, and\r hopping creatures.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2855},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-45","text":"Thou outcast, who hast cast thyself out, thou wilt not live amongst men\r and men’s pity? Well then, do like me! Thus wilt thou learn also from\r me; only the doer learneth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2856},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-46","text":"And talk first and foremost to mine animals! The proudest animal and the\r wisest animal—they might well be the right counsellors for us both!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2857},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-47","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra and went his way, more thoughtfully and slowly\r even than before: for he asked himself many things, and hardly knew what\r to answer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2858},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-48","text":"“How poor indeed is man,” thought he in his heart, “how ugly, how\r wheezy, how full of hidden shame!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2859},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-49","text":"They tell me that man loveth himself. Ah, how great must that self-love\r be! How much contempt is opposed to it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2860},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-50","text":"Even this man hath loved himself, as he hath despised himself,—a great\r lover methinketh he is, and a great despiser.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2861},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-51","text":"No one have I yet found who more thoroughly despised himself: even THAT\r is elevation. Alas, was THIS perhaps the higher man whose cry I heard?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2862},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-97-52","text":"I love the great despisers. Man is something that hath to be\r surpassed.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2863},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-1","text":"When Zarathustra had left the ugliest man, he was chilled and felt\r lonesome: for much coldness and lonesomeness came over his spirit, so\r that even his limbs became colder thereby. When, however, he wandered\r on and on, uphill and down, at times past green meadows, though also\r sometimes over wild stony couches where formerly perhaps an impatient\r brook had made its bed, then he turned all at once warmer and heartier\r again.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2864},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-2","text":"“What hath happened unto me?” he asked himself, “something warm and\r living quickeneth me; it must be in the neighbourhood.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2865},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-3","text":"Already am I less alone; unconscious companions and brethren rove around\r me; their warm breath toucheth my soul.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2866},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-4","text":"When, however, he spied about and sought for the comforters of his\r lonesomeness, behold, there were kine there standing together on an\r eminence, whose proximity and smell had warmed his heart. The kine,\r however, seemed to listen eagerly to a speaker, and took no heed of him\r who approached. When, however, Zarathustra was quite nigh unto them,\r then did he hear plainly that a human voice spake in the midst of the\r kine, and apparently all of them had turned their heads towards the\r speaker.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2867},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-5","text":"Then ran Zarathustra up speedily and drove the animals aside; for he\r feared that some one had here met with harm, which the pity of the\r kine would hardly be able to relieve. But in this he was deceived; for\r behold, there sat a man on the ground who seemed to be persuading\r the animals to have no fear of him, a peaceable man and\r Preacher-on-the-Mount, out of whose eyes kindness itself preached. “What\r dost thou seek here?” called out Zarathustra in astonishment.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2868},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-6","text":"“What do I here seek?” answered he: “the same that thou seekest, thou\r mischief-maker; that is to say, happiness upon earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2869},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-7","text":"To that end, however, I would fain learn of these kine. For I tell thee\r that I have already talked half a morning unto them, and just now were\r they about to give me their answer. Why dost thou disturb them?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2870},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-8","text":"Except we be converted and become as kine, we shall in no wise enter\r into the kingdom of heaven. For we ought to learn from them one thing:\r ruminating.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2871},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-9","text":"And verily, although a man should gain the whole world, and yet not\r learn one thing, ruminating, what would it profit him! He would not be\r rid of his affliction,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2872},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-10","text":"—His great affliction: that, however, is at present called DISGUST. Who\r hath not at present his heart, his mouth and his eyes full of disgust?\r Thou also! Thou also! But behold these kine!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2873},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-11","text":"Thus spake the Preacher-on-the-Mount, and turned then his own look\r towards Zarathustra—for hitherto it had rested lovingly on the kine—:\r then, however, he put on a different expression. “Who is this with whom\r I talk?” he exclaimed frightened, and sprang up from the ground.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2874},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-12","text":"“This is the man without disgust, this is Zarathustra himself, the\r surmounter of the great disgust, this is the eye, this is the mouth,\r this is the heart of Zarathustra himself.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2875},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-13","text":"And whilst he thus spake he kissed with o’erflowing eyes the hands\r of him with whom he spake, and behaved altogether like one to whom a\r precious gift and jewel hath fallen unawares from heaven. The kine,\r however, gazed at it all and wondered.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2876},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-14","text":"“Speak not of me, thou strange one; thou amiable one!” said Zarathustra,\r and restrained his affection, “speak to me firstly of thyself! Art thou\r not the voluntary beggar who once cast away great riches,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2877},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-15","text":"—Who was ashamed of his riches and of the rich, and fled to the poorest\r to bestow upon them his abundance and his heart? But they received him\r not.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2878},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-16","text":"“But they received me not,” said the voluntary beggar, “thou knowest it,\r forsooth. So I went at last to the animals and to those kine.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2879},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-17","text":"“Then learnedst thou,” interrupted Zarathustra, “how much harder it is\r to give properly than to take properly, and that bestowing well is an\r ART—the last, subtlest master-art of kindness.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2880},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-18","text":"“Especially nowadays,” answered the voluntary beggar: “at present, that\r is to say, when everything low hath become rebellious and exclusive and\r haughty in its manner—in the manner of the populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2881},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-19","text":"For the hour hath come, thou knowest it forsooth, for the great, evil,\r long, slow mob-and-slave-insurrection: it extendeth and extendeth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2882},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-20","text":"Now doth it provoke the lower classes, all benevolence and petty giving;\r and the over-rich may be on their guard!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2883},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-21","text":"Whoever at present drip, like bulgy bottles out of all-too-small\r necks:—of such bottles at present one willingly breaketh the necks.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2884},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-22","text":"Wanton avidity, bilious envy, careworn revenge, populace-pride: all\r these struck mine eye. It is no longer true that the poor are blessed.\r The kingdom of heaven, however, is with the kine.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2885},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-23","text":"“And why is it not with the rich?” asked Zarathustra temptingly, while\r he kept back the kine which sniffed familiarly at the peaceful one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2886},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-24","text":"“Why dost thou tempt me?” answered the other. “Thou knowest it thyself\r better even than I. What was it drove me to the poorest, O Zarathustra?\r Was it not my disgust at the richest?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2887},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-25","text":"—At the culprits of riches, with cold eyes and rank thoughts, who pick\r up profit out of all kinds of rubbish—at this rabble that stinketh to\r heaven,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2888},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-26","text":"—At this gilded, falsified populace, whose fathers were pickpockets,\r or carrion-crows, or rag-pickers, with wives compliant, lewd and\r forgetful:—for they are all of them not far different from harlots—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2889},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-27","text":"Populace above, populace below! What are ‘poor’ and ‘rich’ at present!\r That distinction did I unlearn,—then did I flee away further and ever\r further, until I came to those kine.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2890},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-28","text":"Thus spake the peaceful one, and puffed himself and perspired with\r his words: so that the kine wondered anew. Zarathustra, however, kept\r looking into his face with a smile, all the time the man talked so\r severely—and shook silently his head.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2891},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-29","text":"“Thou doest violence to thyself, thou Preacher-on-the-Mount, when thou\r usest such severe words. For such severity neither thy mouth nor thine\r eye have been given thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2892},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-30","text":"Nor, methinketh, hath thy stomach either: unto IT all such rage and\r hatred and foaming-over is repugnant. Thy stomach wanteth softer things:\r thou art not a butcher.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2893},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-31","text":"Rather seemest thou to me a plant-eater and a root-man. Perhaps thou\r grindest corn. Certainly, however, thou art averse to fleshly joys, and\r thou lovest honey.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2894},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-32","text":"“Thou hast divined me well,” answered the voluntary beggar, with\r lightened heart. “I love honey, I also grind corn; for I have sought out\r what tasteth sweetly and maketh pure breath:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2895},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-33","text":"—Also what requireth a long time, a day’s-work and a mouth’s-work for\r gentle idlers and sluggards.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2896},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-34","text":"Furthest, to be sure, have those kine carried it: they have devised\r ruminating and lying in the sun. They also abstain from all heavy\r thoughts which inflate the heart.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2897},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-35","text":"—“Well!” said Zarathustra, “thou shouldst also see MINE animals, mine\r eagle and my serpent,—their like do not at present exist on earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2898},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-36","text":"Behold, thither leadeth the way to my cave: be to-night its guest. And\r talk to mine animals of the happiness of animals,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2899},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-37","text":"—Until I myself come home. For now a cry of distress calleth me hastily\r away from thee. Also, shouldst thou find new honey with me, ice-cold,\r golden-comb-honey, eat it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2900},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-38","text":"Now, however, take leave at once of thy kine, thou strange one! thou\r amiable one! though it be hard for thee. For they are thy warmest\r friends and preceptors!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2901},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-39","text":"—“One excepted, whom I hold still dearer,” answered the voluntary\r beggar. “Thou thyself art good, O Zarathustra, and better even than a\r cow!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2902},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-40","text":"“Away, away with thee! thou evil flatterer!” cried Zarathustra\r mischievously, “why dost thou spoil me with such praise and\r flattery-honey?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2903},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-98-41","text":"“Away, away from me!” cried he once more, and heaved his stick at the\r fond beggar, who, however, ran nimbly away.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2904},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-1","text":"Scarcely however was the voluntary beggar gone in haste, and Zarathustra\r again alone, when he heard behind him a new voice which called out:\r “Stay! Zarathustra! Do wait! It is myself, forsooth, O Zarathustra,\r myself, thy shadow!” But Zarathustra did not wait; for a sudden\r irritation came over him on account of the crowd and the crowding in his\r mountains. “Whither hath my lonesomeness gone?” spake he.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2905},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-2","text":"“It is verily becoming too much for me; these mountains swarm; my\r kingdom is no longer of THIS world; I require new mountains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2906},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-3","text":"My shadow calleth me? What matter about my shadow! Let it run after me!\r I—run away from it.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2907},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-4","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra to his heart and ran away. But the one behind\r followed after him, so that immediately there were three runners,\r one after the other—namely, foremost the voluntary beggar, then\r Zarathustra, and thirdly, and hindmost, his shadow. But not long had\r they run thus when Zarathustra became conscious of his folly, and shook\r off with one jerk all his irritation and detestation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2908},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-5","text":"“What!” said he, “have not the most ludicrous things always happened to\r us old anchorites and saints?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2909},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-6","text":"Verily, my folly hath grown big in the mountains! Now do I hear six old\r fools’ legs rattling behind one another!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2910},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-7","text":"But doth Zarathustra need to be frightened by his shadow? Also,\r methinketh that after all it hath longer legs than mine.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2911},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-8","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and, laughing with eyes and entrails, he stood\r still and turned round quickly—and behold, he almost thereby threw his\r shadow and follower to the ground, so closely had the latter followed at\r his heels, and so weak was he. For when Zarathustra scrutinised him\r with his glance he was frightened as by a sudden apparition, so slender,\r swarthy, hollow and worn-out did this follower appear.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2912},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-9","text":"“Who art thou?” asked Zarathustra vehemently, “what doest thou here? And\r why callest thou thyself my shadow? Thou art not pleasing unto me.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2913},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-10","text":"“Forgive me,” answered the shadow, “that it is I; and if I please thee\r not—well, O Zarathustra! therein do I admire thee and thy good taste.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2914},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-11","text":"A wanderer am I, who have walked long at thy heels; always on the way,\r but without a goal, also without a home: so that verily, I lack little\r of being the eternally Wandering Jew, except that I am not eternal and\r not a Jew.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2915},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-12","text":"What? Must I ever be on the way? Whirled by every wind, unsettled,\r driven about? O earth, thou hast become too round for me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2916},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-13","text":"On every surface have I already sat, like tired dust have I fallen\r asleep on mirrors and window-panes: everything taketh from me, nothing\r giveth; I become thin—I am almost equal to a shadow.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2917},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-14","text":"After thee, however, O Zarathustra, did I fly and hie longest; and\r though I hid myself from thee, I was nevertheless thy best shadow:\r wherever thou hast sat, there sat I also.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2918},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-15","text":"With thee have I wandered about in the remotest, coldest worlds, like a\r phantom that voluntarily haunteth winter roofs and snows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2919},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-16","text":"With thee have I pushed into all the forbidden, all the worst and the\r furthest: and if there be anything of virtue in me, it is that I have\r had no fear of any prohibition.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2920},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-17","text":"With thee have I broken up whatever my heart revered; all\r boundary-stones and statues have I o’erthrown; the most dangerous wishes\r did I pursue,—verily, beyond every crime did I once go.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2921},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-18","text":"With thee did I unlearn the belief in words and worths and in great\r names. When the devil casteth his skin, doth not his name also fall\r away? It is also skin. The devil himself is perhaps—skin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2922},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-19","text":"‘Nothing is true, all is permitted’: so said I to myself. Into the\r coldest water did I plunge with head and heart. Ah, how oft did I stand\r there naked on that account, like a red crab!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2923},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-20","text":"Ah, where have gone all my goodness and all my shame and all my belief\r in the good! Ah, where is the lying innocence which I once possessed,\r the innocence of the good and of their noble lies!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2924},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-21","text":"Too oft, verily, did I follow close to the heels of truth: then did it\r kick me on the face. Sometimes I meant to lie, and behold! then only did\r I hit—the truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2925},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-22","text":"Too much hath become clear unto me: now it doth not concern me any more.\r Nothing liveth any longer that I love,—how should I still love myself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2926},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-23","text":"‘To live as I incline, or not to live at all’: so do I wish; so wisheth\r also the holiest. But alas! how have _I_ still—inclination?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2927},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-24","text":"Have _I_—still a goal? A haven towards which MY sail is set?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2928},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-25","text":"A good wind? Ah, he only who knoweth WHITHER he saileth, knoweth what\r wind is good, and a fair wind for him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2929},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-26","text":"What still remaineth to me? A heart weary and flippant; an unstable\r will; fluttering wings; a broken backbone.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2930},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-27","text":"This seeking for MY home: O Zarathustra, dost thou know that this\r seeking hath been MY home-sickening; it eateth me up.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2931},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-28","text":"‘WHERE is—MY home?’ For it do I ask and seek, and have sought, but\r have not found it. O eternal everywhere, O eternal nowhere, O\r eternal—in-vain!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2932},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-29","text":"Thus spake the shadow, and Zarathustra’s countenance lengthened at his\r words. “Thou art my shadow!” said he at last sadly.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2933},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-30","text":"“Thy danger is not small, thou free spirit and wanderer! Thou hast had a\r bad day: see that a still worse evening doth not overtake thee!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2934},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-31","text":"To such unsettled ones as thou, seemeth at last even a prisoner blessed.\r Didst thou ever see how captured criminals sleep? They sleep quietly,\r they enjoy their new security.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2935},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-32","text":"Beware lest in the end a narrow faith capture thee, a hard, rigorous\r delusion! For now everything that is narrow and fixed seduceth and\r tempteth thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2936},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-33","text":"Thou hast lost thy goal. Alas, how wilt thou forego and forget that\r loss? Thereby—hast thou also lost thy way!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2937},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-34","text":"Thou poor rover and rambler, thou tired butterfly! wilt thou have a rest\r and a home this evening? Then go up to my cave!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2938},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-35","text":"Thither leadeth the way to my cave. And now will I run quickly away from\r thee again. Already lieth as it were a shadow upon me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2939},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-99-36","text":"I will run alone, so that it may again become bright around me.\r Therefore must I still be a long time merrily upon my legs. In the\r evening, however, there will be—dancing with me!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2940},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-1","text":"—And Zarathustra ran and ran, but he found no one else, and was alone\r and ever found himself again; he enjoyed and quaffed his solitude, and\r thought of good things—for hours. About the hour of noontide, however,\r when the sun stood exactly over Zarathustra’s head, he passed an old,\r bent and gnarled tree, which was encircled round by the ardent love of\r a vine, and hidden from itself; from this there hung yellow grapes in\r abundance, confronting the wanderer. Then he felt inclined to quench a\r little thirst, and to break off for himself a cluster of grapes. When,\r however, he had already his arm outstretched for that purpose, he felt\r still more inclined for something else—namely, to lie d","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2941},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-2","text":"This Zarathustra did; and no sooner had he laid himself on the ground in\r the stillness and secrecy of the variegated grass, than he had forgotten\r his little thirst, and fell asleep. For as the proverb of Zarathustra\r saith: “One thing is more necessary than the other.” Only that his eyes\r remained open:—for they never grew weary of viewing and admiring the\r tree and the love of the vine. In falling asleep, however, Zarathustra\r spake thus to his heart:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2942},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-3","text":"“Hush! Hush! Hath not the world now become perfect? What hath happened\r unto me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2943},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-4","text":"As a delicate wind danceth invisibly upon parqueted seas, light,\r feather-light, so—danceth sleep upon me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2944},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-5","text":"No eye doth it close to me, it leaveth my soul awake. Light is it,\r verily, feather-light.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2945},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-6","text":"It persuadeth me, I know not how, it toucheth me inwardly with a\r caressing hand, it constraineth me. Yea, it constraineth me, so that my\r soul stretcheth itself out:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2946},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-7","text":"—How long and weary it becometh, my strange soul! Hath a seventh-day\r evening come to it precisely at noontide? Hath it already wandered too\r long, blissfully, among good and ripe things?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2947},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-8","text":"It stretcheth itself out, long—longer! it lieth still, my strange\r soul. Too many good things hath it already tasted; this golden sadness\r oppresseth it, it distorteth its mouth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2948},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-9","text":"—As a ship that putteth into the calmest cove:—it now draweth up to\r the land, weary of long voyages and uncertain seas. Is not the land more\r faithful?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2949},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-10","text":"As such a ship huggeth the shore, tuggeth the shore:—then it sufficeth\r for a spider to spin its thread from the ship to the land. No stronger\r ropes are required there.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2950},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-11","text":"As such a weary ship in the calmest cove, so do I also now repose, nigh\r to the earth, faithful, trusting, waiting, bound to it with the lightest\r threads.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2951},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-12","text":"O happiness! O happiness! Wilt thou perhaps sing, O my soul? Thou liest\r in the grass. But this is the secret, solemn hour, when no shepherd\r playeth his pipe.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2952},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-13","text":"Take care! Hot noontide sleepeth on the fields. Do not sing! Hush! The\r world is perfect.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2953},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-14","text":"Do not sing, thou prairie-bird, my soul! Do not even whisper! Lo—hush!\r The old noontide sleepeth, it moveth its mouth: doth it not just now\r drink a drop of happiness—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2954},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-15","text":"—An old brown drop of golden happiness, golden wine? Something whisketh\r over it, its happiness laugheth. Thus—laugheth a God. Hush!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2955},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-16","text":"—‘For happiness, how little sufficeth for happiness!’ Thus spake I\r once and thought myself wise. But it was a blasphemy: THAT have I now\r learned. Wise fools speak better.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2956},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-17","text":"The least thing precisely, the gentlest thing, the lightest thing, a\r lizard’s rustling, a breath, a whisk, an eye-glance—LITTLE maketh up\r the BEST happiness. Hush!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2957},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-18","text":"—What hath befallen me: Hark! Hath time flown away? Do I not fall? Have\r I not fallen—hark! into the well of eternity?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2958},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-19","text":"—What happeneth to me? Hush! It stingeth me—alas—to the heart? To\r the heart! Oh, break up, break up, my heart, after such happiness, after\r such a sting!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2959},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-20","text":"—What? Hath not the world just now become perfect? Round and ripe? Oh,\r for the golden round ring—whither doth it fly? Let me run after it!\r Quick!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2960},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-21","text":"Hush—” (and here Zarathustra stretched himself, and felt that he was\r asleep.)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2961},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-22","text":"“Up!” said he to himself, “thou sleeper! Thou noontide sleeper! Well\r then, up, ye old legs! It is time and more than time; many a good\r stretch of road is still awaiting you—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2962},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-23","text":"Now have ye slept your fill; for how long a time? A half-eternity! Well\r then, up now, mine old heart! For how long after such a sleep mayest\r thou—remain awake?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2963},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-24","text":"(But then did he fall asleep anew, and his soul spake against him and\r defended itself, and lay down again)—“Leave me alone! Hush! Hath not\r the world just now become perfect? Oh, for the golden round ball!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2964},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-25","text":"“Get up,” said Zarathustra, “thou little thief, thou sluggard! What!\r Still stretching thyself, yawning, sighing, falling into deep wells?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2965},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-26","text":"Who art thou then, O my soul!” (and here he became frightened, for a\r sunbeam shot down from heaven upon his face.)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2966},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-27","text":"“O heaven above me,” said he sighing, and sat upright, “thou gazest at\r me? Thou hearkenest unto my strange soul?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2967},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-28","text":"When wilt thou drink this drop of dew that fell down upon all earthly\r things,—when wilt thou drink this strange soul—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2968},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-29","text":"—When, thou well of eternity! thou joyous, awful, noontide abyss! when\r wilt thou drink my soul back into thee?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2969},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-100-30","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and rose from his couch beside the tree, as if\r awakening from a strange drunkenness: and behold! there stood the\r sun still exactly above his head. One might, however, rightly infer\r therefrom that Zarathustra had not then slept long.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2970},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-1","text":"It was late in the afternoon only when Zarathustra, after long useless\r searching and strolling about, again came home to his cave. When,\r however, he stood over against it, not more than twenty paces therefrom,\r the thing happened which he now least of all expected: he heard anew the\r great CRY OF DISTRESS. And extraordinary! this time the cry came out\r of his own cave. It was a long, manifold, peculiar cry, and Zarathustra\r plainly distinguished that it was composed of many voices: although\r heard at a distance it might sound like the cry out of a single mouth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2971},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-2","text":"Thereupon Zarathustra rushed forward to his cave, and behold! what a\r spectacle awaited him after that concert! For there did they all sit\r together whom he had passed during the day: the king on the right and\r the king on the left, the old magician, the pope, the voluntary\r beggar, the shadow, the intellectually conscientious one, the sorrowful\r soothsayer, and the ass; the ugliest man, however, had set a crown on\r his head, and had put round him two purple girdles,—for he liked, like\r all ugly ones, to disguise himself and play the handsome person. In the\r midst, however, of that sorrowful company stood Zarathustra’s eagle,\r ruffled and disquieted, for it had been called upon to answer too","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2972},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-3","text":"All this did Zarathustra behold with great astonishment; then however he\r scrutinised each individual guest with courteous curiosity, read their\r souls and wondered anew. In the meantime the assembled ones had risen\r from their seats, and waited with reverence for Zarathustra to speak.\r Zarathustra however spake thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2973},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-4","text":"“Ye despairing ones! Ye strange ones! So it was YOUR cry of distress\r that I heard? And now do I know also where he is to be sought, whom I\r have sought for in vain to-day: THE HIGHER MAN—:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2974},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-5","text":"—In mine own cave sitteth he, the higher man! But why do I wonder! Have\r not I myself allured him to me by honey-offerings and artful lure-calls\r of my happiness?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2975},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-6","text":"But it seemeth to me that ye are badly adapted for company: ye make\r one another’s hearts fretful, ye that cry for help, when ye sit here\r together? There is one that must first come,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2976},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-7","text":"—One who will make you laugh once more, a good jovial buffoon, a\r dancer, a wind, a wild romp, some old fool:—what think ye?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2977},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-8","text":"Forgive me, however, ye despairing ones, for speaking such trivial words\r before you, unworthy, verily, of such guests! But ye do not divine WHAT\r maketh my heart wanton:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2978},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-9","text":"—Ye yourselves do it, and your aspect, forgive it me! For every one\r becometh courageous who beholdeth a despairing one. To encourage a\r despairing one—every one thinketh himself strong enough to do so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2979},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-10","text":"To myself have ye given this power,—a good gift, mine honourable\r guests! An excellent guest’s-present! Well, do not then upbraid when I\r also offer you something of mine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2980},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-11","text":"This is mine empire and my dominion: that which is mine, however, shall\r this evening and to-night be yours. Mine animals shall serve you: let my\r cave be your resting-place!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2981},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-12","text":"At house and home with me shall no one despair: in my purlieus do I\r protect every one from his wild beasts. And that is the first thing\r which I offer you: security!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2982},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-13","text":"The second thing, however, is my little finger. And when ye have THAT,\r then take the whole hand also, yea, and the heart with it! Welcome here,\r welcome to you, my guests!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2983},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-14","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and laughed with love and mischief. After this\r greeting his guests bowed once more and were reverentially silent; the\r king on the right, however, answered him in their name.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2984},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-15","text":"“O Zarathustra, by the way in which thou hast given us thy hand and thy\r greeting, we recognise thee as Zarathustra. Thou hast humbled thyself\r before us; almost hast thou hurt our reverence—:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2985},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-16","text":"—Who however could have humbled himself as thou hast done, with such\r pride? THAT uplifteth us ourselves; a refreshment is it, to our eyes and\r hearts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2986},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-17","text":"To behold this, merely, gladly would we ascend higher mountains than\r this. For as eager beholders have we come; we wanted to see what\r brighteneth dim eyes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2987},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-18","text":"And lo! now is it all over with our cries of distress. Now are our minds\r and hearts open and enraptured. Little is lacking for our spirits to\r become wanton.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2988},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-19","text":"There is nothing, O Zarathustra, that groweth more pleasingly on earth\r than a lofty, strong will: it is the finest growth. An entire landscape\r refresheth itself at one such tree.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2989},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-20","text":"To the pine do I compare him, O Zarathustra, which groweth up like\r thee—tall, silent, hardy, solitary, of the best, supplest wood,\r stately,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2990},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-21","text":"—In the end, however, grasping out for ITS dominion with strong, green\r branches, asking weighty questions of the wind, the storm, and whatever\r is at home on high places;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2991},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-22","text":"—Answering more weightily, a commander, a victor! Oh! who should not\r ascend high mountains to behold such growths?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2992},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-23","text":"At thy tree, O Zarathustra, the gloomy and ill-constituted also refresh\r themselves; at thy look even the wavering become steady and heal their\r hearts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2993},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-24","text":"And verily, towards thy mountain and thy tree do many eyes turn to-day;\r a great longing hath arisen, and many have learned to ask: ‘Who is\r Zarathustra?’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2994},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-25","text":"And those into whose ears thou hast at any time dripped thy song and thy\r honey: all the hidden ones, the lone-dwellers and the twain-dwellers,\r have simultaneously said to their hearts:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2995},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-26","text":"‘Doth Zarathustra still live? It is no longer worth while to live,\r everything is indifferent, everything is useless: or else—we must live\r with Zarathustra!’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2996},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-27","text":"‘Why doth he not come who hath so long announced himself?’ thus do many\r people ask; ‘hath solitude swallowed him up? Or should we perhaps go to\r him?’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2997},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-28","text":"Now doth it come to pass that solitude itself becometh fragile and\r breaketh open, like a grave that breaketh open and can no longer hold\r its dead. Everywhere one seeth resurrected ones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2998},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-29","text":"Now do the waves rise and rise around thy mountain, O Zarathustra. And\r however high be thy height, many of them must rise up to thee: thy boat\r shall not rest much longer on dry ground.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2999},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-30","text":"And that we despairing ones have now come into thy cave, and already no\r longer despair:—it is but a prognostic and a presage that better ones\r are on the way to thee,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3000},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-31","text":"—For they themselves are on the way to thee, the last remnant of\r God among men—that is to say, all the men of great longing, of great\r loathing, of great satiety,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3001},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-32","text":"—All who do not want to live unless they learn again to HOPE—unless\r they learn from thee, O Zarathustra, the GREAT hope!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3002},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-33","text":"Thus spake the king on the right, and seized the hand of Zarathustra in\r order to kiss it; but Zarathustra checked his veneration, and stepped\r back frightened, fleeing as it were, silently and suddenly into the far\r distance. After a little while, however, he was again at home with his\r guests, looked at them with clear scrutinising eyes, and said:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3003},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-34","text":"“My guests, ye higher men, I will speak plain language and plainly with\r you. It is not for YOU that I have waited here in these mountains.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3004},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-35","text":"(“‘Plain language and plainly?’ Good God!” said here the king on the\r left to himself; “one seeth he doth not know the good Occidentals, this\r sage out of the Orient!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3005},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-36","text":"But he meaneth ‘blunt language and bluntly’—well! That is not the worst\r taste in these days!”)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3006},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-37","text":"“Ye may, verily, all of you be higher men,” continued Zarathustra; “but\r for me—ye are neither high enough, nor strong enough.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3007},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-38","text":"For me, that is to say, for the inexorable which is now silent in me,\r but will not always be silent. And if ye appertain to me, still it is\r not as my right arm.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3008},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-39","text":"For he who himself standeth, like you, on sickly and tender legs,\r wisheth above all to be TREATED INDULGENTLY, whether he be conscious of\r it or hide it from himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3009},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-40","text":"My arms and my legs, however, I do not treat indulgently, I DO NOT TREAT\r MY WARRIORS INDULGENTLY: how then could ye be fit for MY warfare?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3010},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-41","text":"With you I should spoil all my victories. And many of you would tumble\r over if ye but heard the loud beating of my drums.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3011},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-42","text":"Moreover, ye are not sufficiently beautiful and well-born for me. I\r require pure, smooth mirrors for my doctrines; on your surface even mine\r own likeness is distorted.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3012},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-43","text":"On your shoulders presseth many a burden, many a recollection; many a\r mischievous dwarf squatteth in your corners. There is concealed populace\r also in you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3013},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-44","text":"And though ye be high and of a higher type, much in you is crooked and\r misshapen. There is no smith in the world that could hammer you right\r and straight for me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3014},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-45","text":"Ye are only bridges: may higher ones pass over upon you! Ye signify\r steps: so do not upbraid him who ascendeth beyond you into HIS height!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3015},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-46","text":"Out of your seed there may one day arise for me a genuine son and\r perfect heir: but that time is distant. Ye yourselves are not those unto\r whom my heritage and name belong.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3016},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-47","text":"Not for you do I wait here in these mountains; not with you may I\r descend for the last time. Ye have come unto me only as a presage that\r higher ones are on the way to me,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3017},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-48","text":"—NOT the men of great longing, of great loathing, of great satiety, and\r that which ye call the remnant of God;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3018},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-49","text":"—Nay! Nay! Three times Nay! For OTHERS do I wait here in these\r mountains, and will not lift my foot from thence without them;","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3019},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-50","text":"—For higher ones, stronger ones, triumphanter ones, merrier ones, for\r such as are built squarely in body and soul: LAUGHING LIONS must come!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3020},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-51","text":"O my guests, ye strange ones—have ye yet heard nothing of my children?\r And that they are on the way to me?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3021},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-52","text":"Do speak unto me of my gardens, of my Happy Isles, of my new beautiful\r race—why do ye not speak unto me thereof?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3022},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-53","text":"This guests’-present do I solicit of your love, that ye speak unto me of\r my children. For them am I rich, for them I became poor: what have I not\r surrendered,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3023},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-54","text":"—What would I not surrender that I might have one thing: THESE\r children, THIS living plantation, THESE life-trees of my will and of my\r highest hope!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3024},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-101-55","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra, and stopped suddenly in his discourse: for his\r longing came over him, and he closed his eyes and his mouth, because\r of the agitation of his heart. And all his guests also were silent, and\r stood still and confounded: except only that the old soothsayer made\r signs with his hands and his gestures.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":3025},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-1","text":"For at this point the soothsayer interrupted the greeting of Zarathustra\r and his guests: he pressed forward as one who had no time to lose,\r seized Zarathustra’s hand and exclaimed: “But Zarathustra!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3026},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-2","text":"One thing is more necessary than the other, so sayest thou thyself:\r well, one thing is now more necessary UNTO ME than all others.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3027},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-3","text":"A word at the right time: didst thou not invite me to TABLE? And here\r are many who have made long journeys. Thou dost not mean to feed us\r merely with discourses?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3028},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-4","text":"Besides, all of you have thought too much about freezing, drowning,\r suffocating, and other bodily dangers: none of you, however, have\r thought of MY danger, namely, perishing of hunger—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3029},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-5","text":"(Thus spake the soothsayer. When Zarathustra’s animals, however, heard\r these words, they ran away in terror. For they saw that all they\r had brought home during the day would not be enough to fill the one\r soothsayer.)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3030},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-6","text":"“Likewise perishing of thirst,” continued the soothsayer. “And although\r I hear water splashing here like words of wisdom—that is to say,\r plenteously and unweariedly, I—want WINE!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3031},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-7","text":"Not every one is a born water-drinker like Zarathustra. Neither doth\r water suit weary and withered ones: WE deserve wine—IT alone giveth\r immediate vigour and improvised health!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3032},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-8","text":"On this occasion, when the soothsayer was longing for wine, it happened\r that the king on the left, the silent one, also found expression for\r once. “WE took care,” said he, “about wine, I, along with my brother the\r king on the right: we have enough of wine,—a whole ass-load of it. So\r there is nothing lacking but bread.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3033},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-9","text":"“Bread,” replied Zarathustra, laughing when he spake, “it is precisely\r bread that anchorites have not. But man doth not live by bread alone,\r but also by the flesh of good lambs, of which I have two:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3034},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-10","text":"—THESE shall we slaughter quickly, and cook spicily with sage: it is\r so that I like them. And there is also no lack of roots and fruits,\r good enough even for the fastidious and dainty,—nor of nuts and other\r riddles for cracking.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3035},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-11","text":"Thus will we have a good repast in a little while. But whoever wish to\r eat with us must also give a hand to the work, even the kings. For with\r Zarathustra even a king may be a cook.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3036},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-12","text":"This proposal appealed to the hearts of all of them, save that the\r voluntary beggar objected to the flesh and wine and spices.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3037},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-13","text":"“Just hear this glutton Zarathustra!” said he jokingly: “doth one go\r into caves and high mountains to make such repasts?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3038},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-14","text":"Now indeed do I understand what he once taught us: Blessed be moderate\r poverty!’ And why he wisheth to do away with beggars.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3039},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-15","text":"“Be of good cheer,” replied Zarathustra, “as I am. Abide by thy\r customs, thou excellent one: grind thy corn, drink thy water, praise thy\r cooking,—if only it make thee glad!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3040},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-16","text":"I am a law only for mine own; I am not a law for all. He, however, who\r belongeth unto me must be strong of bone and light of foot,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3041},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-17","text":"—Joyous in fight and feast, no sulker, no John o’ Dreams, ready for the\r hardest task as for the feast, healthy and hale.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3042},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-18","text":"The best belongeth unto mine and me; and if it be not given us, then do\r we take it:—the best food, the purest sky, the strongest thoughts, the\r fairest women!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3043},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-19","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra; the king on the right however answered and said:\r “Strange! Did one ever hear such sensible things out of the mouth of a\r wise man?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3044},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-20","text":"And verily, it is the strangest thing in a wise man, if over and above,\r he be still sensible, and not an ass.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3045},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-102-21","text":"Thus spake the king on the right and wondered; the ass however, with\r ill-will, said YE-A to his remark. This however was the beginning of\r that long repast which is called “The Supper” in the history-books. At\r this there was nothing else spoken of but THE HIGHER MAN.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":3046},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-1","text":"When I came unto men for the first time, then did I commit the anchorite\r folly, the great folly: I appeared on the market-place.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3047},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-2","text":"And when I spake unto all, I spake unto none. In the evening, however,\r rope-dancers were my companions, and corpses; and I myself almost a\r corpse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3048},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-3","text":"With the new morning, however, there came unto me a new truth: then did\r I learn to say: “Of what account to me are market-place and populace and\r populace-noise and long populace-ears!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3049},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-4","text":"Ye higher men, learn THIS from me: On the market-place no one believeth\r in higher men. But if ye will speak there, very well! The populace,\r however, blinketh: “We are all equal.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3050},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-5","text":"“Ye higher men,”—so blinketh the populace—“there are no higher men, we\r are all equal; man is man, before God—we are all equal!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3051},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-6","text":"Before God!—Now, however, this God hath died. Before the populace,\r however, we will not be equal. Ye higher men, away from the\r market-place!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3052},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-7","text":"Before God!—Now however this God hath died! Ye higher men, this God was\r your greatest danger.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3053},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-8","text":"Only since he lay in the grave have ye again arisen. Now only cometh the\r great noontide, now only doth the higher man become—master!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3054},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-9","text":"Have ye understood this word, O my brethren? Ye are frightened: do your\r hearts turn giddy? Doth the abyss here yawn for you? Doth the hell-hound\r here yelp at you?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3055},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-10","text":"Well! Take heart! ye higher men! Now only travaileth the mountain of the\r human future. God hath died: now do WE desire—the Superman to live.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3056},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-11","text":"The most careful ask to-day: “How is man to be maintained?” Zarathustra\r however asketh, as the first and only one: “How is man to be SURPASSED?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3057},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-12","text":"The Superman, I have at heart; THAT is the first and only thing to\r me—and NOT man: not the neighbour, not the poorest, not the sorriest,\r not the best.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3058},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-13","text":"O my brethren, what I can love in man is that he is an over-going and a\r down-going. And also in you there is much that maketh me love and hope.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3059},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-14","text":"In that ye have despised, ye higher men, that maketh me hope. For the\r great despisers are the great reverers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3060},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-15","text":"In that ye have despaired, there is much to honour. For ye have not\r learned to submit yourselves, ye have not learned petty policy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3061},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-16","text":"For to-day have the petty people become master: they all preach\r submission and humility and policy and diligence and consideration and\r the long et cetera of petty virtues.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3062},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-17","text":"Whatever is of the effeminate type, whatever originateth from the\r servile type, and especially the populace-mishmash:—THAT wisheth now to\r be master of all human destiny—O disgust! Disgust! Disgust!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3063},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-18","text":"THAT asketh and asketh and never tireth: “How is man to maintain himself\r best, longest, most pleasantly?” Thereby—are they the masters of\r to-day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3064},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-19","text":"These masters of to-day—surpass them, O my brethren—these petty\r people: THEY are the Superman’s greatest danger!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3065},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-20","text":"Surpass, ye higher men, the petty virtues, the petty policy, the\r sand-grain considerateness, the ant-hill trumpery, the pitiable\r comfortableness, the “happiness of the greatest number”—!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3066},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-21","text":"And rather despair than submit yourselves. And verily, I love you,\r because ye know not to-day how to live, ye higher men! For thus do YE\r live—best!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3067},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-22","text":"Have ye courage, O my brethren? Are ye stout-hearted? NOT the courage\r before witnesses, but anchorite and eagle courage, which not even a God\r any longer beholdeth?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3068},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-23","text":"Cold souls, mules, the blind and the drunken, I do not call\r stout-hearted. He hath heart who knoweth fear, but VANQUISHETH it; who\r seeth the abyss, but with PRIDE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3069},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-24","text":"He who seeth the abyss, but with eagle’s eyes,—he who with eagle’s\r talons GRASPETH the abyss: he hath courage.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3070},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-25","text":"“Man is evil”—so said to me for consolation, all the wisest ones. Ah,\r if only it be still true to-day! For the evil is man’s best force.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3071},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-26","text":"“Man must become better and eviler”—so do _I_ teach. The evilest is\r necessary for the Superman’s best.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3072},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-27","text":"It may have been well for the preacher of the petty people to suffer and\r be burdened by men’s sin. I, however, rejoice in great sin as my great\r CONSOLATION.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3073},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-28","text":"Such things, however, are not said for long ears. Every word, also,\r is not suited for every mouth. These are fine far-away things: at them\r sheep’s claws shall not grasp!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3074},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-29","text":"Ye higher men, think ye that I am here to put right what ye have put\r wrong?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3075},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-30","text":"Or that I wished henceforth to make snugger couches for you sufferers?\r Or show you restless, miswandering, misclimbing ones, new and easier\r footpaths?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3076},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-31","text":"Nay! Nay! Three times Nay! Always more, always better ones of your\r type shall succumb,—for ye shall always have it worse and harder. Thus\r only—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3077},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-32","text":"—Thus only groweth man aloft to the height where the lightning striketh\r and shattereth him: high enough for the lightning!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3078},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-33","text":"Towards the few, the long, the remote go forth my soul and my seeking:\r of what account to me are your many little, short miseries!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3079},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-34","text":"Ye do not yet suffer enough for me! For ye suffer from yourselves, ye\r have not yet suffered FROM MAN. Ye would lie if ye spake otherwise! None\r of you suffereth from what _I_ have suffered.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3080},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-35","text":"It is not enough for me that the lightning no longer doeth harm. I do\r not wish to conduct it away: it shall learn—to work for ME.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3081},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-36","text":"My wisdom hath accumulated long like a cloud, it becometh stiller and\r darker. So doeth all wisdom which shall one day bear LIGHTNINGS.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3082},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-37","text":"Unto these men of to-day will I not be LIGHT, nor be called light.\r THEM—will I blind: lightning of my wisdom! put out their eyes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3083},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-38","text":"Do not will anything beyond your power: there is a bad falseness in\r those who will beyond their power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3084},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-39","text":"Especially when they will great things! For they awaken distrust in\r great things, these subtle false-coiners and stage-players:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3085},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-40","text":"—Until at last they are false towards themselves, squint-eyed, whited\r cankers, glossed over with strong words, parade virtues and brilliant\r false deeds.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3086},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-41","text":"Take good care there, ye higher men! For nothing is more precious to me,\r and rarer, than honesty.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3087},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-42","text":"Is this to-day not that of the populace? The populace however knoweth\r not what is great and what is small, what is straight and what is\r honest: it is innocently crooked, it ever lieth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3088},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-43","text":"Have a good distrust to-day ye, higher men, ye enheartened ones! Ye\r open-hearted ones! And keep your reasons secret! For this to-day is that\r of the populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3089},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-44","text":"What the populace once learned to believe without reasons, who could—\r refute it to them by means of reasons?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3090},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-45","text":"And on the market-place one convinceth with gestures. But reasons make\r the populace distrustful.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3091},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-46","text":"And when truth hath once triumphed there, then ask yourselves with good\r distrust: “What strong error hath fought for it?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3092},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-47","text":"Be on your guard also against the learned! They hate you, because they\r are unproductive! They have cold, withered eyes before which every bird\r is unplumed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3093},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-48","text":"Such persons vaunt about not lying: but inability to lie is still far\r from being love to truth. Be on your guard!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3094},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-49","text":"Freedom from fever is still far from being knowledge! Refrigerated\r spirits I do not believe in. He who cannot lie, doth not know what truth\r is.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3095},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-50","text":"If ye would go up high, then use your own legs! Do not get yourselves\r CARRIED aloft; do not seat yourselves on other people’s backs and heads!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3096},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-51","text":"Thou hast mounted, however, on horseback? Thou now ridest briskly up\r to thy goal? Well, my friend! But thy lame foot is also with thee on\r horseback!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3097},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-52","text":"When thou reachest thy goal, when thou alightest from thy horse:\r precisely on thy HEIGHT, thou higher man,—then wilt thou stumble!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3098},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-53","text":"Ye creating ones, ye higher men! One is only pregnant with one’s own\r child.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3099},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-54","text":"Do not let yourselves be imposed upon or put upon! Who then is YOUR\r neighbour? Even if ye act “for your neighbour”—ye still do not create\r for him!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3100},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-55","text":"Unlearn, I pray you, this “for,” ye creating ones: your very virtue\r wisheth you to have naught to do with “for” and “on account of” and\r “because.” Against these false little words shall ye stop your ears.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3101},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-56","text":"“For one’s neighbour,” is the virtue only of the petty people: there it\r is said “like and like,” and “hand washeth hand”:—they have neither the\r right nor the power for YOUR self-seeking!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3102},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-57","text":"In your self-seeking, ye creating ones, there is the foresight and\r foreseeing of the pregnant! What no one’s eye hath yet seen, namely, the\r fruit—this, sheltereth and saveth and nourisheth your entire love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3103},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-58","text":"Where your entire love is, namely, with your child, there is also your\r entire virtue! Your work, your will is YOUR “neighbour”: let no false\r values impose upon you!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3104},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-59","text":"Ye creating ones, ye higher men! Whoever hath to give birth is sick;\r whoever hath given birth, however, is unclean.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3105},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-60","text":"Ask women: one giveth birth, not because it giveth pleasure. The pain\r maketh hens and poets cackle.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3106},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-61","text":"Ye creating ones, in you there is much uncleanliness. That is because ye\r have had to be mothers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3107},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-62","text":"A new child: oh, how much new filth hath also come into the world! Go\r apart! He who hath given birth shall wash his soul!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3108},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-63","text":"Be not virtuous beyond your powers! And seek nothing from yourselves\r opposed to probability!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3109},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-64","text":"Walk in the footsteps in which your fathers’ virtue hath already walked!\r How would ye rise high, if your fathers’ will should not rise with you?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3110},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-65","text":"He, however, who would be a firstling, let him take care lest he also\r become a lastling! And where the vices of your fathers are, there should\r ye not set up as saints!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3111},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-66","text":"He whose fathers were inclined for women, and for strong wine and flesh\r of wildboar swine; what would it be if he demanded chastity of himself?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3112},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-67","text":"A folly would it be! Much, verily, doth it seem to me for such a one, if\r he should be the husband of one or of two or of three women.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3113},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-68","text":"And if he founded monasteries, and inscribed over their portals: “The\r way to holiness,”—I should still say: What good is it! it is a new\r folly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3114},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-69","text":"He hath founded for himself a penance-house and refuge-house: much good\r may it do! But I do not believe in it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3115},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-70","text":"In solitude there groweth what any one bringeth into it—also the brute\r in one’s nature. Thus is solitude inadvisable unto many.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3116},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-71","text":"Hath there ever been anything filthier on earth than the saints of\r the wilderness? AROUND THEM was not only the devil loose—but also the\r swine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3117},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-72","text":"Shy, ashamed, awkward, like the tiger whose spring hath failed—thus, ye\r higher men, have I often seen you slink aside. A CAST which ye made had\r failed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3118},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-73","text":"But what doth it matter, ye dice-players! Ye had not learned to play and\r mock, as one must play and mock! Do we not ever sit at a great table of\r mocking and playing?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3119},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-74","text":"And if great things have been a failure with you, have ye yourselves\r therefore—been a failure? And if ye yourselves have been a failure,\r hath man therefore—been a failure? If man, however, hath been a\r failure: well then! never mind!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3120},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-75","text":"The higher its type, always the seldomer doth a thing succeed. Ye higher\r men here, have ye not all—been failures?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3121},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-76","text":"Be of good cheer; what doth it matter? How much is still possible! Learn\r to laugh at yourselves, as ye ought to laugh!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3122},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-77","text":"What wonder even that ye have failed and only half-succeeded, ye\r half-shattered ones! Doth not—man’s FUTURE strive and struggle in you?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3123},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-78","text":"Man’s furthest, profoundest, star-highest issues, his prodigious\r powers—do not all these foam through one another in your vessel?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3124},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-79","text":"What wonder that many a vessel shattereth! Learn to laugh at yourselves,\r as ye ought to laugh! Ye higher men, O, how much is still possible!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3125},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-80","text":"And verily, how much hath already succeeded! How rich is this earth in\r small, good, perfect things, in well-constituted things!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3126},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-81","text":"Set around you small, good, perfect things, ye higher men. Their golden\r maturity healeth the heart. The perfect teacheth one to hope.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3127},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-82","text":"What hath hitherto been the greatest sin here on earth? Was it not the\r word of him who said: “Woe unto them that laugh now!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3128},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-83","text":"Did he himself find no cause for laughter on the earth? Then he sought\r badly. A child even findeth cause for it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3129},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-84","text":"He—did not love sufficiently: otherwise would he also have loved\r us, the laughing ones! But he hated and hooted us; wailing and\r teeth-gnashing did he promise us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3130},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-85","text":"Must one then curse immediately, when one doth not love? That—seemeth\r to me bad taste. Thus did he, however, this absolute one. He sprang from\r the populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3131},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-86","text":"And he himself just did not love sufficiently; otherwise would he have\r raged less because people did not love him. All great love doth not SEEK\r love:—it seeketh more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3132},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-87","text":"Go out of the way of all such absolute ones! They are a poor sickly\r type, a populace-type: they look at this life with ill-will, they have\r an evil eye for this earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3133},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-88","text":"Go out of the way of all such absolute ones! They have heavy feet and\r sultry hearts:—they do not know how to dance. How could the earth be\r light to such ones!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3134},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-89","text":"Tortuously do all good things come nigh to their goal. Like cats\r they curve their backs, they purr inwardly with their approaching\r happiness,—all good things laugh.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3135},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-90","text":"His step betrayeth whether a person already walketh on HIS OWN path:\r just see me walk! He, however, who cometh nigh to his goal, danceth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3136},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-91","text":"And verily, a statue have I not become, not yet do I stand there stiff,\r stupid and stony, like a pillar; I love fast racing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3137},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-92","text":"And though there be on earth fens and dense afflictions, he who hath\r light feet runneth even across the mud, and danceth, as upon well-swept\r ice.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3138},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-93","text":"Lift up your hearts, my brethren, high, higher! And do not forget your\r legs! Lift up also your legs, ye good dancers, and better still, if ye\r stand upon your heads!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3139},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-94","text":"This crown of the laughter, this rose-garland crown: I myself have put\r on this crown, I myself have consecrated my laughter. No one else have I\r found to-day potent enough for this.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3140},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-95","text":"Zarathustra the dancer, Zarathustra the light one, who beckoneth with\r his pinions, one ready for flight, beckoning unto all birds, ready and\r prepared, a blissfully light-spirited one:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3141},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-96","text":"Zarathustra the soothsayer, Zarathustra the sooth-laugher, no impatient\r one, no absolute one, one who loveth leaps and side-leaps; I myself have\r put on this crown!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3142},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-97","text":"Lift up your hearts, my brethren, high, higher! And do not forget your\r legs! Lift up also your legs, ye good dancers, and better still if ye\r stand upon your heads!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3143},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-98","text":"There are also heavy animals in a state of happiness, there are\r club-footed ones from the beginning. Curiously do they exert themselves,\r like an elephant which endeavoureth to stand upon its head.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3144},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-99","text":"Better, however, to be foolish with happiness than foolish with\r misfortune, better to dance awkwardly than walk lamely. So learn, I\r pray you, my wisdom, ye higher men: even the worst thing hath two good\r reverse sides,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3145},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-100","text":"—Even the worst thing hath good dancing-legs: so learn, I pray you, ye\r higher men, to put yourselves on your proper legs!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3146},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-101","text":"So unlearn, I pray you, the sorrow-sighing, and all the\r populace-sadness! Oh, how sad the buffoons of the populace seem to me\r to-day! This to-day, however, is that of the populace.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3147},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-102","text":"Do like unto the wind when it rusheth forth from its mountain-caves:\r unto its own piping will it dance; the seas tremble and leap under its\r footsteps.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3148},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-103","text":"That which giveth wings to asses, that which milketh the lionesses:—\r praised be that good, unruly spirit, which cometh like a hurricane unto\r all the present and unto all the populace,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3149},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-104","text":"—Which is hostile to thistle-heads and puzzle-heads, and to all\r withered leaves and weeds:—praised be this wild, good, free spirit of\r the storm, which danceth upon fens and afflictions, as upon meadows!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3150},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-105","text":"Which hateth the consumptive populace-dogs, and all the ill-constituted,\r sullen brood:—praised be this spirit of all free spirits, the laughing\r storm, which bloweth dust into the eyes of all the melanopic and\r melancholic!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3151},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-106","text":"Ye higher men, the worst thing in you is that ye have none of you\r learned to dance as ye ought to dance—to dance beyond yourselves! What\r doth it matter that ye have failed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3152},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-107","text":"How many things are still possible! So LEARN to laugh beyond yourselves!\r Lift up your hearts, ye good dancers, high! higher! And do not forget\r the good laughter!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3153},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-103-108","text":"This crown of the laughter, this rose-garland crown: to you my brethren\r do I cast this crown! Laughing have I consecrated; ye higher men, LEARN,\r I pray you—to laugh!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":3154},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-1","text":"When Zarathustra spake these sayings, he stood nigh to the entrance of\r his cave; with the last words, however, he slipped away from his guests,\r and fled for a little while into the open air.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3155},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-2","text":"“O pure odours around me,” cried he, “O blessed stillness around me! But\r where are mine animals? Hither, hither, mine eagle and my serpent!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3156},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-3","text":"Tell me, mine animals: these higher men, all of them—do they perhaps\r not SMELL well? O pure odours around me! Now only do I know and feel how\r I love you, mine animals.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3157},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-4","text":"—And Zarathustra said once more: “I love you, mine animals!” The eagle,\r however, and the serpent pressed close to him when he spake these\r words, and looked up to him. In this attitude were they all three silent\r together, and sniffed and sipped the good air with one another. For the\r air here outside was better than with the higher men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3158},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-5","text":"Hardly, however, had Zarathustra left the cave when the old magician got\r up, looked cunningly about him, and said: “He is gone!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3159},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-6","text":"And already, ye higher men—let me tickle you with this complimentary\r and flattering name, as he himself doeth—already doth mine evil spirit\r of deceit and magic attack me, my melancholy devil,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3160},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-7","text":"—Which is an adversary to this Zarathustra from the very heart: forgive\r it for this! Now doth it wish to conjure before you, it hath just ITS\r hour; in vain do I struggle with this evil spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3161},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-8","text":"Unto all of you, whatever honours ye like to assume in your names,\r whether ye call yourselves ‘the free spirits’ or ‘the conscientious,’\r or ‘the penitents of the spirit,’ or ‘the unfettered,’ or ‘the great\r longers,’—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3162},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-9","text":"—Unto all of you, who like me suffer FROM THE GREAT LOATHING, to\r whom the old God hath died, and as yet no new God lieth in cradles and\r swaddling clothes—unto all of you is mine evil spirit and magic-devil\r favourable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3163},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-10","text":"I know you, ye higher men, I know him,—I know also this fiend whom I\r love in spite of me, this Zarathustra: he himself often seemeth to me\r like the beautiful mask of a saint,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3164},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-11","text":"—Like a new strange mummery in which mine evil spirit, the melancholy\r devil, delighteth:—I love Zarathustra, so doth it often seem to me, for\r the sake of mine evil spirit.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3165},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-12","text":"But already doth IT attack me and constrain me, this spirit of\r melancholy, this evening-twilight devil: and verily, ye higher men, it\r hath a longing—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3166},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-13","text":"—Open your eyes!—it hath a longing to come NAKED, whether male or\r female, I do not yet know: but it cometh, it constraineth me, alas! open\r your wits!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3167},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-14","text":"The day dieth out, unto all things cometh now the evening, also unto\r the best things; hear now, and see, ye higher men, what devil—man or\r woman—this spirit of evening-melancholy is!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3168},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-15","text":"Thus spake the old magician, looked cunningly about him, and then seized\r his harp.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3169},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-16","text":"In evening’s limpid air,\r      What time the dew’s soothings\r      Unto the earth downpour,\r      Invisibly and unheard—\r      For tender shoe-gear wear\r      The soothing dews, like all that’s kind-gentle—:\r      Bethinkst thou then, bethinkst thou, burning heart,\r      How once thou thirstedest\r      For heaven’s kindly teardrops and dew’s down-droppings,\r      All singed and weary thirstedest,\r      What time on yellow grass-pathways\r      Wicked, occidental sunny glances\r      Through sombre trees about thee sported,\r      Blindingly sunny glow-glances, gladly-hurting?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3170},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-17","text":"“Of TRUTH the wooer?  Thou?”—so taunted they—\r      “Nay!  Merely poet!\r      A brute insidious, plundering, grovelling,\r      That aye must lie,\r      That wittingly, wilfully, aye must lie:\r      For booty lusting,\r      Motley masked,\r      Self-hidden, shrouded,\r      Himself his booty—\r      HE—of truth the wooer?\r      Nay!  Mere fool!  Mere poet!\r      Just motley speaking,\r      From mask of fool confusedly shouting,\r      Circumambling on fabricated word-bridges,\r      On motley rainbow-arches,\r      ‘Twixt the spurious heavenly,\r      And spurious earthly,\r      Round us roving, round us soaring,—\r      MERE FOOL!  MERE POET!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3171},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-18","text":"HE—of truth the wooer?\r      Not still, stiff, smooth and cold,\r      Become an image,\r      A godlike statue,\r      Set up in front of temples,\r      As a God’s own door-guard:\r      Nay! hostile to all such truthfulness-statues,\r      In every desert homelier than at temples,\r      With cattish wantonness,\r      Through every window leaping\r      Quickly into chances,\r      Every wild forest a-sniffing,\r      Greedily-longingly, sniffing,\r      That thou, in wild forests,\r      ’Mong the motley-speckled fierce creatures,\r      Shouldest rove, sinful-sound and fine-coloured,\r      With longing lips smacking,\r      Blessedly mocking, blessedly hellish, blessedly bloodthirsty,\r      Robbing, ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3172},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-19","text":"Or unto eagles like which fixedly,\r      Long adown the precipice look,\r      Adown THEIR precipice:—\r      Oh, how they whirl down now,\r      Thereunder, therein,\r      To ever deeper profoundness whirling!—\r      Then,\r      Sudden,\r      With aim aright,\r      With quivering flight,\r      On LAMBKINS pouncing,\r      Headlong down, sore-hungry,\r      For lambkins longing,\r      Fierce ’gainst all lamb-spirits,\r      Furious-fierce ’gainst all that look\r      Sheeplike, or lambeyed, or crisp-woolly,\r      —Grey, with lambsheep kindliness!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3173},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-20","text":"Even thus,\r      Eaglelike, pantherlike,\r      Are the poet’s desires,\r      Are THINE OWN desires ‘neath a thousand guises,\r      Thou fool!  Thou poet!\r      Thou who all mankind viewedst—\r      So God, as sheep—:\r      The God TO REND within mankind,\r      As the sheep in mankind,\r      And in rending LAUGHING—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3174},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-21","text":"THAT, THAT is thine own blessedness!\r      Of a panther and eagle—blessedness!\r      Of a poet and fool—the blessedness!—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3175},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-22","text":"In evening’s limpid air,\r      What time the moon’s sickle,\r      Green, ‘twixt the purple-glowings,\r      And jealous, steal’th forth:\r      —Of day the foe,\r      With every step in secret,\r      The rosy garland-hammocks\r      Downsickling, till they’ve sunken\r      Down nightwards, faded, downsunken:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3176},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-104-23","text":"Thus had I sunken one day\r      From mine own truth-insanity,\r      From mine own fervid day-longings,\r      Of day aweary, sick of sunshine,\r      —Sunk downwards, evenwards, shadowwards:\r      By one sole trueness\r      All scorched and thirsty:\r      —Bethinkst thou still, bethinkst thou, burning heart,\r      How then thou thirstedest?—\r      THAT I SHOULD BANNED BE\r      FROM ALL THE TRUENESS!\r      MERE FOOL!  MERE POET!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":3177},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-1","text":"Thus sang the magician; and all who were present went like birds\r unawares into the net of his artful and melancholy voluptuousness.\r Only the spiritually conscientious one had not been caught: he at once\r snatched the harp from the magician and called out: “Air! Let in good\r air! Let in Zarathustra! Thou makest this cave sultry and poisonous,\r thou bad old magician!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3178},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-2","text":"Thou seducest, thou false one, thou subtle one, to unknown desires and\r deserts. And alas, that such as thou should talk and make ado about the\r TRUTH!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3179},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-3","text":"Alas, to all free spirits who are not on their guard against SUCH\r magicians! It is all over with their freedom: thou teachest and temptest\r back into prisons,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3180},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-4","text":"—Thou old melancholy devil, out of thy lament soundeth a lurement: thou\r resemblest those who with their praise of chastity secretly invite to\r voluptuousness!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3181},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-5","text":"Thus spake the conscientious one; the old magician, however, looked\r about him, enjoying his triumph, and on that account put up with the\r annoyance which the conscientious one caused him. “Be still!” said he\r with modest voice, “good songs want to re-echo well; after good songs\r one should be long silent.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3182},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-6","text":"Thus do all those present, the higher men. Thou, however, hast perhaps\r understood but little of my song? In thee there is little of the magic\r spirit.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3183},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-7","text":"“Thou praisest me,” replied the conscientious one, “in that thou\r separatest me from thyself; very well! But, ye others, what do I see? Ye\r still sit there, all of you, with lusting eyes—:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3184},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-8","text":"Ye free spirits, whither hath your freedom gone! Ye almost seem to me\r to resemble those who have long looked at bad girls dancing naked: your\r souls themselves dance!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3185},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-9","text":"In you, ye higher men, there must be more of that which the magician\r calleth his evil spirit of magic and deceit:—we must indeed be\r different.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3186},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-10","text":"And verily, we spake and thought long enough together ere Zarathustra\r came home to his cave, for me not to be unaware that we ARE different.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3187},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-11","text":"We SEEK different things even here aloft, ye and I. For I seek more\r SECURITY; on that account have I come to Zarathustra. For he is still\r the most steadfast tower and will—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3188},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-12","text":"—To-day, when everything tottereth, when all the earth quaketh. Ye,\r however, when I see what eyes ye make, it almost seemeth to me that ye\r seek MORE INSECURITY,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3189},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-13","text":"—More horror, more danger, more earthquake. Ye long (it almost seemeth\r so to me—forgive my presumption, ye higher men)—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3190},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-14","text":"—Ye long for the worst and dangerousest life, which frighteneth ME\r most,—for the life of wild beasts, for forests, caves, steep mountains\r and labyrinthine gorges.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3191},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-15","text":"And it is not those who lead OUT OF danger that please you best, but\r those who lead you away from all paths, the misleaders. But if\r such longing in you be ACTUAL, it seemeth to me nevertheless to be\r IMPOSSIBLE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3192},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-16","text":"For fear—that is man’s original and fundamental feeling; through fear\r everything is explained, original sin and original virtue. Through fear\r there grew also MY virtue, that is to say: Science.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3193},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-17","text":"For fear of wild animals—that hath been longest fostered in\r man, inclusive of the animal which he concealeth and feareth in\r himself:—Zarathustra calleth it ‘the beast inside.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3194},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-18","text":"Such prolonged ancient fear, at last become subtle, spiritual and\r intellectual—at present, me thinketh, it is called SCIENCE.”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3195},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-19","text":"Thus spake the conscientious one; but Zarathustra, who had just come\r back into his cave and had heard and divined the last discourse, threw a\r handful of roses to the conscientious one, and laughed on account of\r his “truths.” “Why!” he exclaimed, “what did I hear just now? Verily, it\r seemeth to me, thou art a fool, or else I myself am one: and quietly and\r quickly will I put thy ‘truth’ upside down.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3196},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-20","text":"For FEAR—is an exception with us. Courage, however, and adventure, and\r delight in the uncertain, in the unattempted—COURAGE seemeth to me the\r entire primitive history of man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3197},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-21","text":"The wildest and most courageous animals hath he envied and robbed of all\r their virtues: thus only did he become—man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3198},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-22","text":"THIS courage, at last become subtle, spiritual and intellectual, this\r human courage, with eagle’s pinions and serpent’s wisdom: THIS, it\r seemeth to me, is called at present—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3199},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-23","text":"“ZARATHUSTRA!” cried all of them there assembled, as if with one voice,\r and burst out at the same time into a great laughter; there arose,\r however, from them as it were a heavy cloud. Even the magician laughed,\r and said wisely: “Well! It is gone, mine evil spirit!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3200},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-24","text":"And did I not myself warn you against it when I said that it was a\r deceiver, a lying and deceiving spirit?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3201},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-25","text":"Especially when it showeth itself naked. But what can _I_ do with regard\r to its tricks! Have _I_ created it and the world?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3202},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-26","text":"Well! Let us be good again, and of good cheer! And although Zarathustra\r looketh with evil eye—just see him! he disliketh me—:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3203},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-27","text":"—Ere night cometh will he again learn to love and laud me; he cannot\r live long without committing such follies.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3204},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-28","text":"HE—loveth his enemies: this art knoweth he better than any one I have\r seen. But he taketh revenge for it—on his friends!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3205},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-105-29","text":"Thus spake the old magician, and the higher men applauded him; so that\r Zarathustra went round, and mischievously and lovingly shook hands with\r his friends,—like one who hath to make amends and apologise to every\r one for something. When however he had thereby come to the door of his\r cave, lo, then had he again a longing for the good air outside, and for\r his animals,—and wished to steal out.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":3206},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-1","text":"“Go not away!” said then the wanderer who called himself Zarathustra’s\r shadow, “abide with us—otherwise the old gloomy affliction might again\r fall upon us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3207},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-2","text":"Now hath that old magician given us of his worst for our good, and\r lo! the good, pious pope there hath tears in his eyes, and hath quite\r embarked again upon the sea of melancholy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3208},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-3","text":"Those kings may well put on a good air before us still: for that have\r THEY learned best of us all at present! Had they however no one to see\r them, I wager that with them also the bad game would again commence,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3209},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-4","text":"—The bad game of drifting clouds, of damp melancholy, of curtained\r heavens, of stolen suns, of howling autumn-winds,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3210},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-5","text":"—The bad game of our howling and crying for help! Abide with us, O\r Zarathustra! Here there is much concealed misery that wisheth to speak,\r much evening, much cloud, much damp air!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3211},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-6","text":"Thou hast nourished us with strong food for men, and powerful proverbs:\r do not let the weakly, womanly spirits attack us anew at dessert!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3212},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-7","text":"Thou alone makest the air around thee strong and clear! Did I ever find\r anywhere on earth such good air as with thee in thy cave?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3213},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-8","text":"Many lands have I seen, my nose hath learned to test and estimate many\r kinds of air: but with thee do my nostrils taste their greatest delight!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3214},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-9","text":"Unless it be,—unless it be—, do forgive an old recollection! Forgive\r me an old after-dinner song, which I once composed amongst daughters of\r the desert:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3215},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-10","text":"For with them was there equally good, clear, Oriental air; there was I\r furthest from cloudy, damp, melancholy Old-Europe!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3216},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-11","text":"Then did I love such Oriental maidens and other blue kingdoms of heaven,\r over which hang no clouds and no thoughts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3217},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-12","text":"Ye would not believe how charmingly they sat there, when they did\r not dance, profound, but without thoughts, like little secrets, like\r beribboned riddles, like dessert-nuts—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3218},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-13","text":"Many-hued and foreign, forsooth! but without clouds: riddles which\r can be guessed: to please such maidens I then composed an after-dinner\r psalm.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3219},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-106-14","text":"Thus spake the wanderer who called himself Zarathustra’s shadow; and\r before any one answered him, he had seized the harp of the old magician,\r crossed his legs, and looked calmly and sagely around him:—with his\r nostrils, however, he inhaled the air slowly and questioningly, like one\r who in new countries tasteth new foreign air. Afterward he began to sing\r with a kind of roaring.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":3220},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-1","text":"—Ha!\r      Solemnly!\r      In effect solemnly!\r      A worthy beginning!\r      Afric manner, solemnly!\r      Of a lion worthy,\r      Or perhaps of a virtuous howl-monkey—\r      —But it’s naught to you,\r      Ye friendly damsels dearly loved,\r      At whose own feet to me,\r      The first occasion,\r      To a European under palm-trees,\r      A seat is now granted.  Selah.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3221},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-2","text":"Wonderful, truly!\r      Here do I sit now,\r      The desert nigh, and yet I am\r      So far still from the desert,\r      Even in naught yet deserted:\r      That is, I’m swallowed down\r      By this the smallest oasis—:\r      —It opened up just yawning,\r      Its loveliest mouth agape,\r      Most sweet-odoured of all mouthlets:\r      Then fell I right in,\r      Right down, right through—in ’mong you,\r      Ye friendly damsels dearly loved!  Selah.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3222},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-3","text":"Hail! hail! to that whale, fishlike,\r      If it thus for its guest’s convenience\r      Made things nice!—(ye well know,\r      Surely, my learned allusion?)\r      Hail to its belly,\r      If it had e’er\r      A such loveliest oasis-belly\r      As this is:  though however I doubt about it,\r      —With this come I out of Old-Europe,\r      That doubt’th more eagerly than doth any\r      Elderly married woman.\r      May the Lord improve it!\r      Amen!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3223},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-4","text":"Here do I sit now,\r      In this the smallest oasis,\r      Like a date indeed,\r      Brown, quite sweet, gold-suppurating,\r      For rounded mouth of maiden longing,\r      But yet still more for youthful, maidlike,\r      Ice-cold and snow-white and incisory\r      Front teeth:  and for such assuredly,\r      Pine the hearts all of ardent date-fruits.  Selah.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3224},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-5","text":"To the there-named south-fruits now,\r      Similar, all-too-similar,\r      Do I lie here; by little\r      Flying insects\r      Round-sniffled and round-played,\r      And also by yet littler,\r      Foolisher, and peccabler\r      Wishes and phantasies,—\r      Environed by you,\r      Ye silent, presentientest\r      Maiden-kittens,\r      Dudu and Suleika,\r      —ROUNDSPHINXED, that into one word\r      I may crowd much feeling:\r      (Forgive me, O God,\r      All such speech-sinning!)\r      —Sit I here the best of air sniffling,\r      Paradisal air, truly,\r      Bright and buoyant air, golden-mottled,\r      As goodly air as ever\r      From lunar orb downfell—\r      Be it by hazard,\r      Or super","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3225},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-6","text":"This the finest air drinking,\r      With nostrils out-swelled like goblets,\r      Lacking future, lacking remembrances\r      Thus do I sit here, ye\r      Friendly damsels dearly loved,\r      And look at the palm-tree there,\r      How it, to a dance-girl, like,\r      Doth bow and bend and on its haunches bob,\r      —One doth it too, when one view’th it long!—\r      To a dance-girl like, who as it seem’th to me,\r      Too long, and dangerously persistent,\r      Always, always, just on SINGLE leg hath stood?\r      —Then forgot she thereby, as it seem’th to me,\r      The OTHER leg?\r      For vainly I, at least,\r      Did search for the amissing\r      Fellow-jewel\r      —Namely, the other leg—\r  ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3226},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-107-7","text":"Oh, weep ye not,\r      Gentle spirits!\r      Weep ye not, ye\r      Date-fruit spirits!  Milk-bosoms!\r      Ye sweetwood-heart\r      Purselets!\r      Weep ye no more,\r      Pallid Dudu!\r      Be a man, Suleika!  Bold!  Bold!\r      —Or else should there perhaps\r      Something strengthening, heart-strengthening,\r      Here most proper be?\r      Some inspiring text?\r      Some solemn exhortation?—\r      Ha!  Up now! honour!\r      Moral honour!  European honour!\r      Blow again, continue,\r      Bellows-box of virtue!\r      Ha!\r      Once more thy roaring,\r      Thy moral roaring!\r      As a virtuous lion\r      Nigh the daughters of deserts roaring!\r      —For virtue’s out-howl,\r      Ye very de","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":3227},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-1","text":"After the song of the wanderer and shadow, the cave became all at once\r full of noise and laughter: and since the assembled guests all spake\r simultaneously, and even the ass, encouraged thereby, no longer\r remained silent, a little aversion and scorn for his visitors came over\r Zarathustra, although he rejoiced at their gladness. For it seemed to\r him a sign of convalescence. So he slipped out into the open air and\r spake to his animals.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3228},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-2","text":"“Whither hath their distress now gone?” said he, and already did he\r himself feel relieved of his petty disgust—“with me, it seemeth that\r they have unlearned their cries of distress!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3229},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-3","text":"—Though, alas! not yet their crying.” And Zarathustra stopped his\r ears, for just then did the YE-A of the ass mix strangely with the noisy\r jubilation of those higher men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3230},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-4","text":"“They are merry,” he began again, “and who knoweth? perhaps at their\r host’s expense; and if they have learned of me to laugh, still it is not\r MY laughter they have learned.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3231},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-5","text":"But what matter about that! They are old people: they recover in their\r own way, they laugh in their own way; mine ears have already endured\r worse and have not become peevish.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3232},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-6","text":"This day is a victory: he already yieldeth, he fleeth, THE SPIRIT OF\r GRAVITY, mine old arch-enemy! How well this day is about to end, which\r began so badly and gloomily!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3233},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-7","text":"And it is ABOUT TO end. Already cometh the evening: over the sea\r rideth it hither, the good rider! How it bobbeth, the blessed one, the\r home-returning one, in its purple saddles!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3234},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-8","text":"The sky gazeth brightly thereon, the world lieth deep. Oh, all ye\r strange ones who have come to me, it is already worth while to have\r lived with me!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3235},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-9","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra. And again came the cries and laughter of the\r higher men out of the cave: then began he anew:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3236},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-10","text":"“They bite at it, my bait taketh, there departeth also from them their\r enemy, the spirit of gravity. Now do they learn to laugh at themselves:\r do I hear rightly?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3237},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-11","text":"My virile food taketh effect, my strong and savoury sayings: and verily,\r I did not nourish them with flatulent vegetables! But with warrior-food,\r with conqueror-food: new desires did I awaken.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3238},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-12","text":"New hopes are in their arms and legs, their hearts expand. They find new\r words, soon will their spirits breathe wantonness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3239},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-13","text":"Such food may sure enough not be proper for children, nor even for\r longing girls old and young. One persuadeth their bowels otherwise; I am\r not their physician and teacher.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3240},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-14","text":"The DISGUST departeth from these higher men; well! that is my victory.\r In my domain they become assured; all stupid shame fleeth away; they\r empty themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3241},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-15","text":"They empty their hearts, good times return unto them, they keep holiday\r and ruminate,—they become THANKFUL.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3242},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-16","text":"THAT do I take as the best sign: they become thankful. Not long will it\r be ere they devise festivals, and put up memorials to their old joys.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3243},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-17","text":"They are CONVALESCENTS!” Thus spake Zarathustra joyfully to his heart\r and gazed outward; his animals, however, pressed up to him, and honoured\r his happiness and his silence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3244},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-18","text":"All on a sudden however, Zarathustra’s ear was frightened: for the cave\r which had hitherto been full of noise and laughter, became all at once\r still as death;—his nose, however, smelt a sweet-scented vapour and\r incense-odour, as if from burning pine-cones.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3245},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-19","text":"“What happeneth? What are they about?” he asked himself, and stole up\r to the entrance, that he might be able unobserved to see his guests.\r But wonder upon wonder! what was he then obliged to behold with his own\r eyes!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3246},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-20","text":"“They have all of them become PIOUS again, they PRAY, they are\r mad!”—said he, and was astonished beyond measure. And forsooth! all\r these higher men, the two kings, the pope out of service, the evil\r magician, the voluntary beggar, the wanderer and shadow, the old\r soothsayer, the spiritually conscientious one, and the ugliest man—they\r all lay on their knees like children and credulous old women, and\r worshipped the ass. And just then began the ugliest man to gurgle and\r snort, as if something unutterable in him tried to find expression;\r when, however, he had actually found words, behold! it was a pious,\r strange litany in praise of the adored and censed ass. And the litany\r sounded thus:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3247},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-21","text":"Amen! And glory and honour and wisdom and thanks and praise and strength\r be to our God, from everlasting to everlasting!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3248},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-22","text":"He carrieth our burdens, he hath taken upon him the form of a servant,\r he is patient of heart and never saith Nay; and he who loveth his God\r chastiseth him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3249},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-23","text":"He speaketh not: except that he ever saith Yea to the world which\r he created: thus doth he extol his world. It is his artfulness that\r speaketh not: thus is he rarely found wrong.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3250},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-24","text":"Uncomely goeth he through the world. Grey is the favourite colour in\r which he wrappeth his virtue. Hath he spirit, then doth he conceal it;\r every one, however, believeth in his long ears.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3251},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-25","text":"What hidden wisdom it is to wear long ears, and only to say Yea and\r never Nay! Hath he not created the world in his own image, namely, as\r stupid as possible?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3252},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-26","text":"Thou goest straight and crooked ways; it concerneth thee little what\r seemeth straight or crooked unto us men. Beyond good and evil is thy\r domain. It is thine innocence not to know what innocence is.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3253},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-27","text":"Lo! how thou spurnest none from thee, neither beggars nor kings. Thou\r sufferest little children to come unto thee, and when the bad boys decoy\r thee, then sayest thou simply, YE-A.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3254},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-109-28","text":"Thou lovest she-asses and fresh figs, thou art no food-despiser. A\r thistle tickleth thy heart when thou chancest to be hungry. There is the\r wisdom of a God therein.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":3255},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-1","text":"At this place in the litany, however, Zarathustra could no longer\r control himself; he himself cried out YE-A, louder even than the ass,\r and sprang into the midst of his maddened guests. “Whatever are you\r about, ye grown-up children?” he exclaimed, pulling up the praying ones\r from the ground. “Alas, if any one else, except Zarathustra, had seen\r you:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3256},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-2","text":"Every one would think you the worst blasphemers, or the very foolishest\r old women, with your new belief!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3257},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-3","text":"And thou thyself, thou old pope, how is it in accordance with thee, to\r adore an ass in such a manner as God?”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3258},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-4","text":"“O Zarathustra,” answered the pope, “forgive me, but in divine matters\r I am more enlightened even than thou. And it is right that it should be\r so.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3259},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-5","text":"Better to adore God so, in this form, than in no form at all! Think over\r this saying, mine exalted friend: thou wilt readily divine that in such\r a saying there is wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3260},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-6","text":"He who said ‘God is a Spirit’—made the greatest stride and slide\r hitherto made on earth towards unbelief: such a dictum is not easily\r amended again on earth!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3261},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-7","text":"Mine old heart leapeth and boundeth because there is still something\r to adore on earth. Forgive it, O Zarathustra, to an old, pious\r pontiff-heart!—”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3262},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-8","text":"—“And thou,” said Zarathustra to the wanderer and shadow, “thou callest\r and thinkest thyself a free spirit? And thou here practisest such\r idolatry and hierolatry?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3263},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-9","text":"Worse verily, doest thou here than with thy bad brown girls, thou bad,\r new believer!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3264},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-10","text":"“It is sad enough,” answered the wanderer and shadow, “thou art right:\r but how can I help it! The old God liveth again, O Zarathustra, thou\r mayst say what thou wilt.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3265},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-11","text":"The ugliest man is to blame for it all: he hath reawakened him. And\r if he say that he once killed him, with Gods DEATH is always just a\r prejudice.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3266},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-12","text":"—“And thou,” said Zarathustra, “thou bad old magician, what didst thou\r do! Who ought to believe any longer in thee in this free age, when THOU\r believest in such divine donkeyism?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3267},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-13","text":"It was a stupid thing that thou didst; how couldst thou, a shrewd man,\r do such a stupid thing!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3268},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-14","text":"“O Zarathustra,” answered the shrewd magician, “thou art right, it was a\r stupid thing,—it was also repugnant to me.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3269},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-15","text":"—“And thou even,” said Zarathustra to the spiritually conscientious\r one, “consider, and put thy finger to thy nose! Doth nothing go against\r thy conscience here? Is thy spirit not too cleanly for this praying and\r the fumes of those devotees?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3270},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-16","text":"“There is something therein,” said the spiritually conscientious one,\r and put his finger to his nose, “there is something in this spectacle\r which even doeth good to my conscience.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3271},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-17","text":"Perhaps I dare not believe in God: certain it is however, that God\r seemeth to me most worthy of belief in this form.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3272},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-18","text":"God is said to be eternal, according to the testimony of the most pious:\r he who hath so much time taketh his time. As slow and as stupid as\r possible: THEREBY can such a one nevertheless go very far.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3273},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-19","text":"And he who hath too much spirit might well become infatuated with\r stupidity and folly. Think of thyself, O Zarathustra!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3274},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-20","text":"Thou thyself—verily! even thou couldst well become an ass through\r superabundance of wisdom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3275},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-21","text":"Doth not the true sage willingly walk on the crookedest paths? The\r evidence teacheth it, O Zarathustra,—THINE OWN evidence!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3276},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-22","text":"—“And thou thyself, finally,” said Zarathustra, and turned towards the\r ugliest man, who still lay on the ground stretching up his arm to the\r ass (for he gave it wine to drink). “Say, thou nondescript, what hast\r thou been about!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3277},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-23","text":"Thou seemest to me transformed, thine eyes glow, the mantle of the\r sublime covereth thine ugliness: WHAT didst thou do?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3278},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-24","text":"Is it then true what they say, that thou hast again awakened him? And\r why? Was he not for good reasons killed and made away with?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3279},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-25","text":"Thou thyself seemest to me awakened: what didst thou do? why didst THOU\r turn round? Why didst THOU get converted? Speak, thou nondescript!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3280},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-26","text":"“O Zarathustra,” answered the ugliest man, “thou art a rogue!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3281},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-27","text":"Whether HE yet liveth, or again liveth, or is thoroughly dead—which of\r us both knoweth that best? I ask thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3282},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-28","text":"One thing however do I know,—from thyself did I learn it once, O\r Zarathustra: he who wanteth to kill most thoroughly, LAUGHETH.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3283},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-29","text":"‘Not by wrath but by laughter doth one kill’—thus spakest thou once,\r O Zarathustra, thou hidden one, thou destroyer without wrath, thou\r dangerous saint,—thou art a rogue!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3284},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-30","text":"Then, however, did it come to pass that Zarathustra, astonished at such\r merely roguish answers, jumped back to the door of his cave, and turning\r towards all his guests, cried out with a strong voice:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3285},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-31","text":"“O ye wags, all of you, ye buffoons! Why do ye dissemble and disguise\r yourselves before me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3286},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-32","text":"How the hearts of all of you convulsed with delight and wickedness,\r because ye had at last become again like little children—namely,\r pious,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3287},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-33","text":"—Because ye at last did again as children do—namely, prayed, folded\r your hands and said ‘good God’!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3288},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-34","text":"But now leave, I pray you, THIS nursery, mine own cave, where to-day\r all childishness is carried on. Cool down, here outside, your hot\r child-wantonness and heart-tumult!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3289},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-35","text":"To be sure: except ye become as little children ye shall not enter into\r THAT kingdom of heaven.” (And Zarathustra pointed aloft with his hands.)","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3290},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-36","text":"“But we do not at all want to enter into the kingdom of heaven: we have\r become men,—SO WE WANT THE KINGDOM OF EARTH.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3291},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-37","text":"And once more began Zarathustra to speak. “O my new friends,” said he,—\r “ye strange ones, ye higher men, how well do ye now please me,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3292},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-38","text":"—Since ye have again become joyful! Ye have, verily, all blossomed\r forth: it seemeth to me that for such flowers as you, NEW FESTIVALS are\r required.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3293},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-39","text":"—A little valiant nonsense, some divine service and ass-festival, some\r old joyful Zarathustra fool, some blusterer to blow your souls bright.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3294},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-40","text":"Forget not this night and this ass-festival, ye higher men! THAT did ye\r devise when with me, that do I take as a good omen,—such things only\r the convalescents devise!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3295},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-110-41","text":"And should ye celebrate it again, this ass-festival, do it from love to\r yourselves, do it also from love to me! And in remembrance of me!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":3296},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-1","text":"Meanwhile one after another had gone out into the open air, and into the\r cool, thoughtful night; Zarathustra himself, however, led the ugliest\r man by the hand, that he might show him his night-world, and the great\r round moon, and the silvery water-falls near his cave. There they at\r last stood still beside one another; all of them old people, but with\r comforted, brave hearts, and astonished in themselves that it was so\r well with them on earth; the mystery of the night, however, came nigher\r and nigher to their hearts. And anew Zarathustra thought to himself:\r “Oh, how well do they now please me, these higher men!”—but he did not\r say it aloud, for he respected their happiness and their ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3297},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-2","text":"Then, however, there happened that which in this astonishing long day\r was most astonishing: the ugliest man began once more and for the last\r time to gurgle and snort, and when he had at length found expression,\r behold! there sprang a question plump and plain out of his mouth, a\r good, deep, clear question, which moved the hearts of all who listened\r to him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3298},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-3","text":"“My friends, all of you,” said the ugliest man, “what think ye? For the\r sake of this day—_I_ am for the first time content to have lived mine\r entire life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3299},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-4","text":"And that I testify so much is still not enough for me. It is worth while\r living on the earth: one day, one festival with Zarathustra, hath taught\r me to love the earth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3300},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-5","text":"My friends, what think ye? Will ye not, like me, say unto death: ‘Was\r THAT—life? For the sake of Zarathustra, well! Once more!’”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3301},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-6","text":"Thus spake the ugliest man; it was not, however, far from midnight.\r And what took place then, think ye? As soon as the higher men heard his\r question, they became all at once conscious of their transformation and\r convalescence, and of him who was the cause thereof: then did they rush\r up to Zarathustra, thanking, honouring, caressing him, and kissing his\r hands, each in his own peculiar way; so that some laughed and some wept.\r The old soothsayer, however, danced with delight; and though he was\r then, as some narrators suppose, full of sweet wine, he was certainly\r still fuller of sweet life, and had renounced all weariness. There are\r even those who narrate that the ass then danced: for n","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3302},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-7","text":"When, however, this took place with the ugliest man, Zarathustra stood\r there like one drunken: his glance dulled, his tongue faltered and his\r feet staggered. And who could divine what thoughts then passed through\r Zarathustra’s soul? Apparently, however, his spirit retreated and fled\r in advance and was in remote distances, and as it were “wandering on\r high mountain-ridges,” as it standeth written, “‘twixt two seas,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3303},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-8","text":"—Wandering ‘twixt the past and the future as a heavy cloud.” Gradually,\r however, while the higher men held him in their arms, he came back to\r himself a little, and resisted with his hands the crowd of the honouring\r and caring ones; but he did not speak. All at once, however, he turned\r his head quickly, for he seemed to hear something: then laid he his\r finger on his mouth and said: “COME!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3304},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-9","text":"And immediately it became still and mysterious round about; from\r the depth however there came up slowly the sound of a clock-bell.\r Zarathustra listened thereto, like the higher men; then, however, laid\r he his finger on his mouth the second time, and said again: “COME! COME!\r IT IS GETTING ON TO MIDNIGHT!”—and his voice had changed. But still\r he had not moved from the spot. Then it became yet stiller and more\r mysterious, and everything hearkened, even the ass, and Zarathustra’s\r noble animals, the eagle and the serpent,—likewise the cave of\r Zarathustra and the big cool moon, and the night itself. Zarathustra,\r however, laid his hand upon his mouth for the third time, and said:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3305},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-10","text":"Ye higher men, it is getting on to midnight: then will I say something\r into your ears, as that old clock-bell saith it into mine ear,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3306},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-11","text":"—As mysteriously, as frightfully, and as cordially as that midnight\r clock-bell speaketh it to me, which hath experienced more than one man:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3307},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-12","text":"—Which hath already counted the smarting throbbings of your fathers’\r hearts—ah! ah! how it sigheth! how it laugheth in its dream! the old,\r deep, deep midnight!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3308},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-13","text":"Hush! Hush! Then is there many a thing heard which may not be heard\r by day; now however, in the cool air, when even all the tumult of your\r hearts hath become still,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3309},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-14","text":"—Now doth it speak, now is it heard, now doth it steal into\r overwakeful, nocturnal souls: ah! ah! how the midnight sigheth! how it\r laugheth in its dream!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3310},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-111-15","text":"—Hearest thou not how it mysteriously, frightfully, and cordially\r speaketh unto THEE, the old deep, deep midnight?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":3311},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-1","text":"Woe to me! Whither hath time gone? Have I not sunk into deep wells? The\r world sleepeth—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3312},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-2","text":"Ah! Ah! The dog howleth, the moon shineth. Rather will I die, rather\r will I die, than say unto you what my midnight-heart now thinketh.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3313},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-3","text":"Already have I died. It is all over. Spider, why spinnest thou around\r me? Wilt thou have blood? Ah! Ah! The dew falleth, the hour cometh—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3314},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-4","text":"—The hour in which I frost and freeze, which asketh and asketh and\r asketh: “Who hath sufficient courage for it?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3315},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-5","text":"—Who is to be master of the world? Who is going to say: THUS shall ye\r flow, ye great and small streams!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3316},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-6","text":"—The hour approacheth: O man, thou higher man, take heed! this talk is\r for fine ears, for thine ears—WHAT SAITH DEEP MIDNIGHT’S VOICE INDEED?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3317},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-7","text":"It carrieth me away, my soul danceth. Day’s-work! Day’s-work! Who is to\r be master of the world?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3318},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-8","text":"The moon is cool, the wind is still. Ah! Ah! Have ye already flown high\r enough? Ye have danced: a leg, nevertheless, is not a wing.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3319},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-9","text":"Ye good dancers, now is all delight over: wine hath become lees, every\r cup hath become brittle, the sepulchres mutter.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3320},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-10","text":"Ye have not flown high enough: now do the sepulchres mutter: “Free the\r dead! Why is it so long night? Doth not the moon make us drunken?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3321},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-11","text":"Ye higher men, free the sepulchres, awaken the corpses! Ah, why doth the\r worm still burrow? There approacheth, there approacheth, the hour,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3322},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-12","text":"—There boometh the clock-bell, there thrilleth still the heart, there\r burroweth still the wood-worm, the heart-worm. Ah! Ah! THE WORLD IS\r DEEP!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3323},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-13","text":"Sweet lyre! Sweet lyre! I love thy tone, thy drunken, ranunculine\r tone!—how long, how far hath come unto me thy tone, from the distance,\r from the ponds of love!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3324},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-14","text":"Thou old clock-bell, thou sweet lyre! Every pain hath torn thy heart,\r father-pain, fathers’-pain, forefathers’-pain; thy speech hath become\r ripe,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3325},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-15","text":"—Ripe like the golden autumn and the afternoon, like mine anchorite\r heart—now sayest thou: The world itself hath become ripe, the grape\r turneth brown,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3326},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-16","text":"—Now doth it wish to die, to die of happiness. Ye higher men, do ye not\r feel it? There welleth up mysteriously an odour,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3327},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-17","text":"—A perfume and odour of eternity, a rosy-blessed, brown,\r gold-wine-odour of old happiness,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3328},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-18","text":"—Of drunken midnight-death happiness, which singeth: the world is deep,\r AND DEEPER THAN THE DAY COULD READ!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3329},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-19","text":"Leave me alone! Leave me alone! I am too pure for thee. Touch me not!\r Hath not my world just now become perfect?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3330},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-20","text":"My skin is too pure for thy hands. Leave me alone, thou dull, doltish,\r stupid day! Is not the midnight brighter?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3331},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-21","text":"The purest are to be masters of the world, the least known, the\r strongest, the midnight-souls, who are brighter and deeper than any day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3332},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-22","text":"O day, thou gropest for me? Thou feelest for my happiness? For thee am I\r rich, lonesome, a treasure-pit, a gold chamber?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3333},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-23","text":"O world, thou wantest ME? Am I worldly for thee? Am I spiritual for\r thee? Am I divine for thee? But day and world, ye are too coarse,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3334},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-24","text":"—Have cleverer hands, grasp after deeper happiness, after deeper\r unhappiness, grasp after some God; grasp not after me:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3335},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-25","text":"—Mine unhappiness, my happiness is deep, thou strange day, but yet am I\r no God, no God’s-hell: DEEP IS ITS WOE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3336},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-26","text":"God’s woe is deeper, thou strange world! Grasp at God’s woe, not at me!\r What am I! A drunken sweet lyre,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3337},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-27","text":"—A midnight-lyre, a bell-frog, which no one understandeth, but which\r MUST speak before deaf ones, ye higher men! For ye do not understand me!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3338},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-28","text":"Gone! Gone! O youth! O noontide! O afternoon! Now have come evening and\r night and midnight,—the dog howleth, the wind:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3339},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-29","text":"—Is the wind not a dog? It whineth, it barketh, it howleth. Ah! Ah!\r how she sigheth! how she laugheth, how she wheezeth and panteth, the\r midnight!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3340},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-30","text":"How she just now speaketh soberly, this drunken poetess! hath she\r perhaps overdrunk her drunkenness? hath she become overawake? doth she\r ruminate?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3341},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-31","text":"—Her woe doth she ruminate over, in a dream, the old, deep\r midnight—and still more her joy. For joy, although woe be deep, JOY IS\r DEEPER STILL THAN GRIEF CAN BE.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3342},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-32","text":"Thou grape-vine! Why dost thou praise me? Have I not cut thee! I am\r cruel, thou bleedest—: what meaneth thy praise of my drunken cruelty?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3343},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-33","text":"“Whatever hath become perfect, everything mature—wanteth to die!” so\r sayest thou. Blessed, blessed be the vintner’s knife! But everything\r immature wanteth to live: alas!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3344},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-34","text":"Woe saith: “Hence! Go! Away, thou woe!” But everything that suffereth\r wanteth to live, that it may become mature and lively and longing,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3345},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-35","text":"—Longing for the further, the higher, the brighter. “I want heirs,”\r  so saith everything that suffereth, “I want children, I do not want\r MYSELF,”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3346},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-36","text":"Joy, however, doth not want heirs, it doth not want children,—joy\r wanteth itself, it wanteth eternity, it wanteth recurrence, it wanteth\r everything eternally-like-itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3347},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-37","text":"Woe saith: “Break, bleed, thou heart! Wander, thou leg! Thou wing, fly!\r Onward! upward! thou pain!” Well! Cheer up! O mine old heart: WOE SAITH:\r “HENCE! GO!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3348},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-38","text":"Ye higher men, what think ye? Am I a soothsayer? Or a dreamer? Or a\r drunkard? Or a dream-reader? Or a midnight-bell?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3349},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-39","text":"Or a drop of dew? Or a fume and fragrance of eternity? Hear ye it not?\r Smell ye it not? Just now hath my world become perfect, midnight is also\r midday,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3350},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-40","text":"Pain is also a joy, curse is also a blessing, night is also a sun,—go\r away! or ye will learn that a sage is also a fool.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3351},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-41","text":"Said ye ever Yea to one joy? O my friends, then said ye Yea also unto\r ALL woe. All things are enlinked, enlaced and enamoured,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3352},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-42","text":"—Wanted ye ever once to come twice; said ye ever: “Thou pleasest me,\r happiness! Instant! Moment!” then wanted ye ALL to come back again!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3353},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-43","text":"—All anew, all eternal, all enlinked, enlaced and enamoured, Oh, then\r did ye LOVE the world,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3354},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-44","text":"—Ye eternal ones, ye love it eternally and for all time: and also unto\r woe do ye say: Hence! Go! but come back! FOR JOYS ALL WANT—ETERNITY!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3355},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-45","text":"All joy wanteth the eternity of all things, it wanteth honey, it\r wanteth lees, it wanteth drunken midnight, it wanteth graves, it wanteth\r grave-tears’ consolation, it wanteth gilded evening-red—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3356},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-46","text":"—WHAT doth not joy want! it is thirstier, heartier, hungrier, more\r frightful, more mysterious, than all woe: it wanteth ITSELF, it biteth\r into ITSELF, the ring’s will writheth in it,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3357},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-47","text":"—It wanteth love, it wanteth hate, it is over-rich, it bestoweth, it\r throweth away, it beggeth for some one to take from it, it thanketh the\r taker, it would fain be hated,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3358},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-48","text":"—So rich is joy that it thirsteth for woe, for hell, for hate, for\r shame, for the lame, for the WORLD,—for this world, Oh, ye know it\r indeed!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3359},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-49","text":"Ye higher men, for you doth it long, this joy, this irrepressible,\r blessed joy—for your woe, ye failures! For failures, longeth all\r eternal joy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3360},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-50","text":"For joys all want themselves, therefore do they also want grief! O\r happiness, O pain! Oh break, thou heart! Ye higher men, do learn it,\r that joys want eternity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3361},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-51","text":"—Joys want the eternity of ALL things, they WANT DEEP, PROFOUND\r ETERNITY!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3362},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-52","text":"Have ye now learned my song? Have ye divined what it would say? Well!\r Cheer up! Ye higher men, sing now my roundelay!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3363},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-53","text":"Sing now yourselves the song, the name of which is “Once more,” the\r signification of which is “Unto all eternity!”—sing, ye higher men,\r Zarathustra’s roundelay!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3364},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-112-54","text":"O man!  Take heed!\r      What saith deep midnight’s voice indeed?\r      “I slept my sleep—,\r      “From deepest dream I’ve woke, and plead:—\r      “The world is deep,\r      “And deeper than the day could read.\r      “Deep is its woe—,\r      “Joy—deeper still than grief can be:\r      “Woe saith:  Hence!  Go!\r      “But joys all want eternity—,\r      “—Want deep, profound eternity!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":3365},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-1","text":"In the morning, however, after this night, Zarathustra jumped up from\r his couch, and, having girded his loins, he came out of his cave glowing\r and strong, like a morning sun coming out of gloomy mountains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3366},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-2","text":"“Thou great star,” spake he, as he had spoken once before, “thou deep\r eye of happiness, what would be all thy happiness if thou hadst not\r THOSE for whom thou shinest!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3367},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-3","text":"And if they remained in their chambers whilst thou art already awake,\r and comest and bestowest and distributest, how would thy proud modesty\r upbraid for it!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3368},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-4","text":"Well! they still sleep, these higher men, whilst _I_ am awake: THEY are\r not my proper companions! Not for them do I wait here in my mountains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3369},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-5","text":"At my work I want to be, at my day: but they understand not what are the\r signs of my morning, my step—is not for them the awakening-call.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3370},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-6","text":"They still sleep in my cave; their dream still drinketh at my drunken\r songs. The audient ear for ME—the OBEDIENT ear, is yet lacking in their\r limbs.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3371},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-7","text":"—This had Zarathustra spoken to his heart when the sun arose: then\r looked he inquiringly aloft, for he heard above him the sharp call of\r his eagle. “Well!” called he upwards, “thus is it pleasing and proper to\r me. Mine animals are awake, for I am awake.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3372},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-8","text":"Mine eagle is awake, and like me honoureth the sun. With eagle-talons\r doth it grasp at the new light. Ye are my proper animals; I love you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3373},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-9","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra; then, however, it happened that all on a sudden\r he became aware that he was flocked around and fluttered around, as if\r by innumerable birds,—the whizzing of so many wings, however, and the\r crowding around his head was so great that he shut his eyes. And verily,\r there came down upon him as it were a cloud, like a cloud of arrows\r which poureth upon a new enemy. But behold, here it was a cloud of love,\r and showered upon a new friend.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3374},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-10","text":"“What happeneth unto me?” thought Zarathustra in his astonished heart,\r and slowly seated himself on the big stone which lay close to the exit\r from his cave. But while he grasped about with his hands, around him,\r above him and below him, and repelled the tender birds, behold, there\r then happened to him something still stranger: for he grasped thereby\r unawares into a mass of thick, warm, shaggy hair; at the same time,\r however, there sounded before him a roar,—a long, soft lion-roar.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3375},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-11","text":"“THE SIGN COMETH,” said Zarathustra, and a change came over his heart.\r And in truth, when it turned clear before him, there lay a yellow,\r powerful animal at his feet, resting its head on his knee,—unwilling to\r leave him out of love, and doing like a dog which again findeth its old\r master. The doves, however, were no less eager with their love than the\r lion; and whenever a dove whisked over its nose, the lion shook its head\r and wondered and laughed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3376},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-12","text":"When all this went on Zarathustra spake only a word: “MY CHILDREN ARE\r NIGH, MY CHILDREN”—, then he became quite mute. His heart, however,\r was loosed, and from his eyes there dropped down tears and fell upon\r his hands. And he took no further notice of anything, but sat there\r motionless, without repelling the animals further. Then flew the doves\r to and fro, and perched on his shoulder, and caressed his white hair,\r and did not tire of their tenderness and joyousness. The strong lion,\r however, licked always the tears that fell on Zarathustra’s hands, and\r roared and growled shyly. Thus did these animals do.—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3377},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-13","text":"All this went on for a long time, or a short time: for properly\r speaking, there is NO time on earth for such things—. Meanwhile,\r however, the higher men had awakened in Zarathustra’s cave, and\r marshalled themselves for a procession to go to meet Zarathustra, and\r give him their morning greeting: for they had found when they awakened\r that he no longer tarried with them. When, however, they reached the\r door of the cave and the noise of their steps had preceded them, the\r lion started violently; it turned away all at once from Zarathustra, and\r roaring wildly, sprang towards the cave. The higher men, however, when\r they heard the lion roaring, cried all aloud as with one voice, fled\r back ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3378},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-14","text":"Zarathustra himself, however, stunned and strange, rose from his seat,\r looked around him, stood there astonished, inquired of his heart,\r bethought himself, and remained alone. “What did I hear?” said he at\r last, slowly, “what happened unto me just now?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3379},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-15","text":"But soon there came to him his recollection, and he took in at a glance\r all that had taken place between yesterday and to-day. “Here is indeed\r the stone,” said he, and stroked his beard, “on IT sat I yester-morn;\r and here came the soothsayer unto me, and here heard I first the cry\r which I heard just now, the great cry of distress.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3380},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-16","text":"O ye higher men, YOUR distress was it that the old soothsayer foretold\r to me yester-morn,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3381},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-17","text":"—Unto your distress did he want to seduce and tempt me: ‘O\r Zarathustra,’ said he to me, ‘I come to seduce thee to thy last sin.’","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3382},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-18","text":"To my last sin?” cried Zarathustra, and laughed angrily at his own\r words: “WHAT hath been reserved for me as my last sin?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3383},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-19","text":"—And once more Zarathustra became absorbed in himself, and sat down\r again on the big stone and meditated. Suddenly he sprang up,—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3384},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-20","text":"“FELLOW-SUFFERING! FELLOW-SUFFERING WITH THE HIGHER MEN!” he cried out,\r and his countenance changed into brass. “Well! THAT—hath had its time!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3385},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-21","text":"My suffering and my fellow-suffering—what matter about them! Do I then\r strive after HAPPINESS? I strive after my WORK!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3386},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-22","text":"Well! The lion hath come, my children are nigh, Zarathustra hath grown\r ripe, mine hour hath come:—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3387},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-23","text":"This is MY morning, MY day beginneth: ARISE NOW, ARISE, THOU GREAT\r NOONTIDE!”—","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3388},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-113-24","text":"Thus spake Zarathustra and left his cave, glowing and strong, like a\r morning sun coming out of gloomy mountains.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":3389},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-1","text":"I have had some opportunities of studying the conditions under which\r Nietzsche is read in Germany, France, and England, and I have found\r that, in each of these countries, students of his philosophy, as if\r actuated by precisely similar motives and desires, and misled by the\r same mistaken tactics on the part of most publishers, all proceed in the\r same happy-go-lucky style when “taking him up.” They have had it said to\r them that he wrote without any system, and they very naturally conclude\r that it does not matter in the least whether they begin with his first,\r third, or last book, provided they can obtain a few vague ideas as to\r what his leading and most sensational principles were.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3390},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-2","text":"Now, it is clear that the book with the most mysterious, startling, or\r suggestive title, will always stand the best chance of being purchased\r by those who have no other criteria to guide them in their choice\r than the aspect of a title-page; and this explains why “Thus Spake\r Zarathustra” is almost always the first and often the only one of\r Nietzsche’s books that falls into the hands of the uninitiated.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3391},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-3","text":"The title suggests all kinds of mysteries; a glance at the\r chapter-headings quickly confirms the suspicions already aroused,\r and the sub-title: “A Book for All and None”, generally succeeds in\r dissipating the last doubts the prospective purchaser may entertain\r concerning his fitness for the book or its fitness for him. And what\r happens?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3392},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-4","text":"“Thus Spake Zarathustra” is taken home; the reader, who perchance may\r know no more concerning Nietzsche than a magazine article has told him,\r tries to read it and, understanding less than half he reads, probably\r never gets further than the second or third part,—and then only to feel\r convinced that Nietzsche himself was “rather hazy” as to what he was\r talking about. Such chapters as “The Child with the Mirror”, “In the\r Happy Isles”, “The Grave-Song,” “Immaculate Perception,” “The Stillest\r Hour”, “The Seven Seals”, and many others, are almost utterly devoid of\r meaning to all those who do not know something of Nietzsche’s life, his\r aims and his friendships.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3393},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-5","text":"As a matter of fact, “Thus Spake Zarathustra”, though it is\r unquestionably Nietzsche’s opus magnum, is by no means the first of\r Nietzsche’s works that the beginner ought to undertake to read. The\r author himself refers to it as the deepest work ever offered to the\r German public, and elsewhere speaks of his other writings as being\r necessary for the understanding of it. But when it is remembered that\r in Zarathustra we not only have the history of his most intimate\r experiences, friendships, feuds, disappointments, triumphs and the like,\r but that the very form in which they are narrated is one which tends\r rather to obscure than to throw light upon them, the difficulties which\r meet the r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3394},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-6","text":"Zarathustra, then,—this shadowy, allegorical personality, speaking in\r allegories and parables, and at times not even refraining from relating\r his own dreams—is a figure we can understand but very imperfectly if we\r have no knowledge of his creator and counterpart, Friedrich Nietzsche;\r and it were therefore well, previous to our study of the more abstruse\r parts of this book, if we were to turn to some authoritative book on\r Nietzsche’s life and works and to read all that is there said on the\r subject. Those who can read German will find an excellent guide, in this\r respect, in Frau Foerster-Nietzsche’s exhaustive and highly interesting\r biography of her brother: “Das Leben Friedrich Nietz","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3395},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-7","text":"In regard to the actual philosophical views expounded in this work,\r there is an excellent way of clearing up any difficulties they may\r present, and that is by an appeal to Nietzsche’s other works. Again and\r again, of course, he will be found to express himself so clearly that\r all reference to his other writings may be dispensed with; but where\r this is not the case, the advice he himself gives is after all the best\r to be followed here, viz.:—to regard such works as: “Joyful Science”,\r “Beyond Good and Evil”, “The Genealogy of Morals”, “The Twilight of\r the Idols”, “The Antichrist”, “The Will to Power”, etc., etc., as the\r necessary preparation for “Thus Spake Zarathustra”.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3396},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-8","text":"These directions, though they are by no means simple to carry out, seem\r at least to possess the quality of definiteness and straightforwardness.\r “Follow them and all will be clear,” I seem to imply. But I regret to\r say that this is not really the case. For my experience tells me that\r even after the above directions have been followed with the greatest\r possible zeal, the student will still halt in perplexity before certain\r passages in the book before us, and wonder what they mean. Now, it is\r with the view of giving a little additional help to all those who find\r themselves in this position that I proceed to put forth my own personal\r interpretation of the more abstruse passages in this","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3397},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-9","text":"In offering this little commentary to the Nietzsche student, I should\r like it to be understood that I make no claim as to its infallibility or\r indispensability. It represents but an attempt on my part—a very feeble\r one perhaps—to give the reader what little help I can in surmounting\r difficulties which a long study of Nietzsche’s life and works has\r enabled me, partially I hope, to overcome.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3398},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-10","text":"Perhaps it would be as well to start out with a broad and rapid sketch\r of Nietzsche as a writer on Morals, Evolution, and Sociology, so that\r the reader may be prepared to pick out for himself, so to speak, all\r passages in this work bearing in any way upon Nietzsche’s views in those\r three important branches of knowledge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3399},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-11","text":"In morality, Nietzsche starts out by adopting the position of the\r relativist. He says there are no absolute values “good” and “evil”;\r these are mere means adopted by all in order to acquire power to\r maintain their place in the world, or to become supreme. It is the\r lion’s good to devour an antelope. It is the dead-leaf butterfly’s\r good to tell a foe a falsehood. For when the dead-leaf butterfly is in\r danger, it clings to the side of a twig, and what it says to its foe is\r practically this: “I am not a butterfly, I am a dead leaf, and can be\r of no use to thee.” This is a lie which is good to the butterfly, for\r it preserves it. In nature every species of organic being instinctively\r ad","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3400},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-12","text":"Concepts of good and evil are therefore, in their origin, merely a means\r to an end, they are expedients for acquiring power.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3401},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-13","text":"Applying this principle to mankind, Nietzsche attacked Christian\r moral values. He declared them to be, like all other morals, merely\r an expedient for protecting a certain type of man. In the case of\r Christianity this type was, according to Nietzsche, a low one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3402},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-14","text":"Conflicting moral codes have been no more than the conflicting weapons\r of different classes of men; for in mankind there is a continual war\r between the powerful, the noble, the strong, and the well-constituted\r on the one side, and the impotent, the mean, the weak, and the\r ill-constituted on the other. The war is a war of moral principles.\r The morality of the powerful class, Nietzsche calls NOBLE- or\r MASTER-MORALITY; that of the weak and subordinate class he calls\r SLAVE-MORALITY. In the first morality it is the eagle which, looking\r down upon a browsing lamb, contends that “eating lamb is good.” In the\r second, the slave-morality, it is the lamb which, looking up from the\r sward, bleat","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3403},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-15","text":"The first morality is active, creative, Dionysian. The second is\r passive, defensive,—to it belongs the “struggle for existence.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3404},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-16","text":"Where attempts have not been made to reconcile the two moralities, they\r may be described as follows:—All is GOOD in the noble morality which\r proceeds from strength, power, health, well-constitutedness, happiness,\r and awfulness; for, the motive force behind the people practising it is\r “the struggle for power.” The antithesis “good and bad” to this\r first class means the same as “noble” and “despicable.” “Bad” in the\r master-morality must be applied to the coward, to all acts that spring\r from weakness, to the man with “an eye to the main chance,” who would\r forsake everything in order to live.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3405},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-17","text":"With the second, the slave-morality, the case is different. There,\r inasmuch as the community is an oppressed, suffering, unemancipated, and\r weary one, all THAT will be held to be good which alleviates the\r state of suffering. Pity, the obliging hand, the warm heart, patience,\r industry, and humility—these are unquestionably the qualities we shall\r here find flooded with the light of approval and admiration; because\r they are the most USEFUL qualities—; they make life endurable, they are\r of assistance in the “struggle for existence” which is the motive force\r behind the people practising this morality. To this class, all that is\r AWFUL is bad, in fact it is THE evil par excellence. Strengt","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3406},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-18","text":"Now Nietzsche believed that the first or the noble-morality conduced to\r an ascent in the line of life; because it was creative and active. On\r the other hand, he believed that the second or slave-morality, where\r it became paramount, led to degeneration, because it was passive and\r defensive, wanting merely to keep those who practised it alive. Hence\r his earnest advocacy of noble-morality.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3407},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-19","text":"Nietzsche as an evolutionist I shall have occasion to define and discuss\r in the course of these notes (see Notes on Chapter LVI., par. 10, and on\r Chapter LVII.). For the present let it suffice for us to know that he\r accepted the “Development Hypothesis” as an explanation of the origin of\r species: but he did not halt where most naturalists have halted. He\r by no means regarded man as the highest possible being which evolution\r could arrive at; for though his physical development may have reached\r its limit, this is not the case with his mental or spiritual attributes.\r If the process be a fact; if things have BECOME what they are, then, he\r contends, we may describe no limit to man’s aspi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3408},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-20","text":"Nietzsche as a sociologist aims at an aristocratic arrangement of\r society. He would have us rear an ideal race. Honest and truthful in\r intellectual matters, he could not even think that men are equal. “With\r these preachers of equality will I not be mixed up and confounded. For\r thus speaketh justice unto ME: ‘Men are not equal.’” He sees precisely\r in this inequality a purpose to be served, a condition to be exploited.\r “Every elevation of the type ‘man,’” he writes in “Beyond Good and\r Evil”, “has hitherto been the work of an aristocratic society—and so\r will it always be—a society believing in a long scale of gradations of\r rank and differences of worth among human beings.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3409},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-115-21","text":"Those who are sufficiently interested to desire to read his own detailed\r account of the society he would fain establish, will find an excellent\r passage in Aphorism 57 of “The Antichrist”.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":3410},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-116-1","text":"In Part I. including the Prologue, no very great difficulties will\r appear. Zarathustra’s habit of designating a whole class of men or a\r whole school of thought by a single fitting nickname may perhaps lead to\r a little confusion at first; but, as a rule, when the general drift\r of his arguments is grasped, it requires but a slight effort of the\r imagination to discover whom he is referring to. In the ninth paragraph\r of the Prologue, for instance, it is quite obvious that “Herdsmen” in\r the verse “Herdsmen, I say, etc., etc.,” stands for all those to-day\r who are the advocates of gregariousness—of the ant-hill. And when our\r author says: “A robber shall Zarathustra be called by the herdsme","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"116"},"sequenceIndex":3411},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-116-2","text":"In the last paragraph of the Prologue, verse 7, Zarathustra gives us a\r foretaste of his teaching concerning the big and the little sagacities,\r expounded subsequently. He says he would he were as wise as his serpent;\r this desire will be found explained in the discourse entitled “The\r Despisers of the Body”, which I shall have occasion to refer to later.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"116"},"sequenceIndex":3412},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-1","text":"This opening discourse is a parable in which Zarathustra discloses the\r mental development of all creators of new values. It is the story of\r a life which reaches its consummation in attaining to a second\r ingenuousness or in returning to childhood. Nietzsche, the supposed\r anarchist, here plainly disclaims all relationship whatever to anarchy,\r for he shows us that only by bearing the burdens of the existing law and\r submitting to it patiently, as the camel submits to being laden, does\r the free spirit acquire that ascendancy over tradition which enables him\r to meet and master the dragon “Thou shalt,”—the dragon with the values\r of a thousand years glittering on its scales. There are two l","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3413},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-2","text":"Almost the whole of this is quite comprehensible. It is a discourse\r against all those who confound virtue with tameness and smug ease, and\r who regard as virtuous only that which promotes security and tends to\r deepen sleep.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3414},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-3","text":"Here Zarathustra gives names to the intellect and the instincts; he\r calls the one “the little sagacity” and the latter “the big sagacity.”\r  Schopenhauer’s teaching concerning the intellect is fully endorsed here.\r “An instrument of thy body is also thy little sagacity, my brother,\r which thou callest ‘spirit,’” says Zarathustra. From beginning to end it\r is a warning to those who would think too lightly of the instincts\r and unduly exalt the intellect and its derivatives: Reason and\r Understanding.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3415},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-4","text":"This is an analysis of the psychology of all those who have the “evil\r eye” and are pessimists by virtue of their constitutions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3416},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-5","text":"In this discourse Zarathustra opens his exposition of the doctrine of\r relativity in morality, and declares all morality to be a mere means\r to power. Needless to say that verses 9, 10, 11, and 12 refer to the\r Greeks, the Persians, the Jews, and the Germans respectively. In the\r penultimate verse he makes known his discovery concerning the root of\r modern Nihilism and indifference,—i.e., that modern man has no goal, no\r aim, no ideals (see Note A).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3417},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-6","text":"Nietzsche’s views on women have either to be loved at first sight\r or they become perhaps the greatest obstacle in the way of those who\r otherwise would be inclined to accept his philosophy. Women especially,\r of course, have been taught to dislike them, because it has been\r rumoured that his views are unfriendly to themselves. Now, to my mind,\r all this is pure misunderstanding and error.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3418},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-7","text":"German philosophers, thanks to Schopenhauer, have earned rather a bad\r name for their views on women. It is almost impossible for one of them\r to write a line on the subject, however kindly he may do so, without\r being suspected of wishing to open a crusade against the fair sex.\r Despite the fact, therefore, that all Nietzsche’s views in this respect\r were dictated to him by the profoundest love; despite Zarathustra’s\r reservation in this discourse, that “with women nothing (that can be\r said) is impossible,” and in the face of other overwhelming evidence\r to the contrary, Nietzsche is universally reported to have mis son\r pied dans le plat, where the female sex is concerned. And what is the","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3419},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-8","text":"It is interesting to observe that the last line of the discourse, which\r has so frequently been used by women as a weapon against Nietzsche’s\r views concerning them, was suggested to Nietzsche by a woman (see “Das\r Leben F. Nietzsche’s”).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3420},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-9","text":"In regard to this discourse, I should only like to point out that\r Nietzsche had a particular aversion to the word “suicide”—self-murder.\r He disliked the evil it suggested, and in rechristening the act\r Voluntary Death, i.e., the death that comes from no other hand than\r one’s own, he was desirous of elevating it to the position it held in\r classical antiquity (see Aphorism 36 in “The Twilight of the Idols”).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3421},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-117-10","text":"An important aspect of Nietzsche’s philosophy is brought to light in\r this discourse. His teaching, as is well known, places the Aristotelian\r man of spirit, above all others in the natural divisions of man. The\r man with overflowing strength, both of mind and body, who must discharge\r this strength or perish, is the Nietzschean ideal. To such a man, giving\r from his overflow becomes a necessity; bestowing develops into a means\r of existence, and this is the only giving, the only charity, that\r Nietzsche recognises. In paragraph 3 of the discourse, we read\r Zarathustra’s healthy exhortation to his disciples to become independent\r thinkers and to find themselves before they learn any more fro","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":3422},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-1","text":"Nietzsche tells us here, in a poetical form, how deeply grieved he was\r by the manifold misinterpretations and misunderstandings which were\r becoming rife concerning his publications. He does not recognise\r himself in the mirror of public opinion, and recoils terrified from the\r distorted reflection of his features. In verse 20 he gives us a\r hint which it were well not to pass over too lightly; for, in the\r introduction to “The Genealogy of Morals” (written in 1887) he finds it\r necessary to refer to the matter again and with greater precision. The\r point is this, that a creator of new values meets with his surest and\r strongest obstacles in the very spirit of the language which is at his\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3423},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-2","text":"While writing this, Nietzsche is supposed to have been thinking of the\r island of Ischia which was ultimately destroyed by an earthquake. His\r teaching here is quite clear. He was among the first thinkers of Europe\r to overcome the pessimism which godlessness generally brings in its\r wake. He points to creating as the surest salvation from the suffering\r which is a concomitant of all higher life. “What would there be to\r create,” he asks, “if there were—Gods?” His ideal, the Superman, lends\r him the cheerfulness necessary to the overcoming of that despair usually\r attendant upon godlessness and upon the apparent aimlessness of a world\r without a god.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3424},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-3","text":"The tarantulas are the Socialists and Democrats. This discourse offers\r us an analysis of their mental attitude. Nietzsche refuses to be\r confounded with those resentful and revengeful ones who condemn society\r FROM BELOW, and whose criticism is only suppressed envy. “There are\r those who preach my doctrine of life,” he says of the Nietzschean\r Socialists, “and are at the same time preachers of equality and\r tarantulas” (see Notes on Chapter XL. and Chapter LI.).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3425},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-4","text":"This refers to all those philosophers hitherto, who have run in the\r harness of established values and have not risked their reputation with\r the people in pursuit of truth. The philosopher, however, as Nietzsche\r understood him, is a man who creates new values, and thus leads mankind\r in a new direction.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3426},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-5","text":"Here Zarathustra sings about the ideals and friendships of his youth.\r Verses 27 to 31 undoubtedly refer to Richard Wagner (see Note on Chapter\r LXV.).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3427},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-6","text":"In this discourse we get the best exposition in the whole book of\r Nietzsche’s doctrine of the Will to Power. I go into this question\r thoroughly in the Note on Chapter LVII.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3428},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-7","text":"Nietzsche was not an iconoclast from choice. Those who hastily class him\r with the anarchists (or the Progressivists of the last century) fail\r to understand the high esteem in which he always held both law and\r discipline. In verse 41 of this most decisive discourse he truly\r explains his position when he says: “...he who hath to be a creator in\r good and evil—verily he hath first to be a destroyer, and break values\r in pieces.” This teaching in regard to self-control is evidence enough\r of his reverence for law.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3429},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-8","text":"These belong to a type which Nietzsche did not altogether dislike, but\r which he would fain have rendered more subtle and plastic. It is the\r type that takes life and itself too seriously, that never surmounts the\r camel-stage mentioned in the first discourse, and that is obdurately\r sublime and earnest. To be able to smile while speaking of lofty things\r and NOT TO BE OPPRESSED by them, is the secret of real greatness. He\r whose hand trembles when it lays hold of a beautiful thing, has the\r quality of reverence, without the artist’s unembarrassed friendship\r with the beautiful. Hence the mistakes which have arisen in regard to\r confounding Nietzsche with his extreme opposites the anarchists","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3430},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-9","text":"This is a poetical epitome of some of the scathing criticism of\r scholars which appears in the first of the “Thoughts out of Season”—the\r polemical pamphlet (written in 1873) against David Strauss and his\r school. He reproaches his former colleagues with being sterile and\r shows them that their sterility is the result of their not believing\r in anything. “He who had to create, had always his presaging dreams and\r astral premonitions—and believed in believing!” (See Note on Chapter\r LXXVII.) In the last two verses he reveals the nature of his altruism.\r How far it differs from that of Christianity we have already read in the\r discourse “Neighbour-Love”, but here he tells us definitely the nat","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3431},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-10","text":"An important feature of Nietzsche’s interpretation of Life is disclosed\r in this discourse. As Buckle suggests in his “Influence of Women on the\r Progress of Knowledge”, the scientific spirit of the investigator is\r both helped and supplemented by the latter’s emotions and personality,\r and the divorce of all emotionalism and individual temperament from\r science is a fatal step towards sterility. Zarathustra abjures all those\r who would fain turn an IMPERSONAL eye upon nature and contemplate her\r phenomena with that pure objectivity to which the scientific idealists\r of to-day would so much like to attain. He accuses such idealists of\r hypocrisy and guile; he says they lack innocence in thei","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3432},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-11","text":"This is a record of Nietzsche’s final breach with his former\r colleagues—the scholars of Germany. Already after the publication of\r the “Birth of Tragedy”, numbers of German philologists and professional\r philosophers had denounced him as one who had strayed too far from\r their flock, and his lectures at the University of Bale were deserted\r in consequence; but it was not until 1879, when he finally severed all\r connection with University work, that he may be said to have attained to\r the freedom and independence which stamp this discourse.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3433},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-12","text":"People have sometimes said that Nietzsche had no sense of humour. I\r have no intention of defending him here against such foolish critics; I\r should only like to point out to the reader that we have him here at\r his best, poking fun at himself, and at his fellow-poets (see Note on\r Chapter LXIII., pars. 16, 17, 18, 19, 20).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3434},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-13","text":"Here we seem to have a puzzle. Zarathustra himself, while relating\r his experience with the fire-dog to his disciples, fails to get them\r interested in his narrative, and we also may be only too ready to turn\r over these pages under the impression that they are little more than\r a mere phantasy or poetical flight. Zarathustra’s interview with the\r fire-dog is, however, of great importance. In it we find Nietzsche\r face to face with the creature he most sincerely loathes—the spirit\r of revolution, and we obtain fresh hints concerning his hatred of the\r anarchist and rebel. “‘Freedom’ ye all roar most eagerly,” he says to\r the fire-dog, “but I have unlearned the belief in ‘Great Events’ when\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3435},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-14","text":"This refers, of course, to Schopenhauer. Nietzsche, as is well known,\r was at one time an ardent follower of Schopenhauer. He overcame\r Pessimism by discovering an object in existence; he saw the possibility\r of raising society to a higher level and preached the profoundest\r Optimism in consequence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3436},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-15","text":"Zarathustra here addresses cripples. He tells them of other\r cripples—the GREAT MEN in this world who have one organ or faculty\r inordinately developed at the cost of their other faculties. This is\r doubtless a reference to a fact which is too often noticeable in the\r case of so many of the world’s giants in art, science, or religion. In\r verse 19 we are told what Nietzsche called Redemption—that is to say,\r the ability to say of all that is past: “Thus would I have it.” The\r in ability to say this, and the resentment which results therefrom,\r he regards as the source of all our feelings of revenge, and all our\r desires to punish—punishment meaning to him merely a euphemism for the\r word rev","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3437},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-16","text":"This discourse is very important. In “Beyond Good and Evil” we hear\r often enough that the select and superior man must wear a mask, and\r here we find this injunction explained. “And he who would not languish\r amongst men, must learn to drink out of all glasses: and he who would\r keep clean amongst men, must know how to wash himself even with dirty\r water.” This, I venture to suggest, requires some explanation. At a time\r when individuality is supposed to be shown most tellingly by putting\r boots on one’s hands and gloves on one’s feet, it is somewhat refreshing\r to come across a true individualist who feels the chasm between himself\r and others so deeply, that he must perforce adapt himself","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3438},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-118-17","text":"This seems to me to give an account of the great struggle which must\r have taken place in Nietzsche’s soul before he finally resolved to make\r known the more esoteric portions of his teaching. Our deepest feelings\r crave silence. There is a certain self-respect in the serious man which\r makes him hold his profoundest feelings sacred. Before they are uttered\r they are full of the modesty of a virgin, and often the oldest sage will\r blush like a girl when this virginity is violated by an indiscretion\r which forces him to reveal his deepest thoughts.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":3439},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-1","text":"This is perhaps the most important of all the four parts. If it\r contained only “The Vision and the Enigma” and “The Old and New Tables”\r  I should still be of this opinion; for in the former of these discourses\r we meet with what Nietzsche regarded as the crowning doctrine of his\r philosophy and in “The Old and New Tables” we have a valuable epitome of\r practically all his leading principles.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3440},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-2","text":"“The Vision and the Enigma” is perhaps an example of Nietzsche in his\r most obscure vein. We must know how persistently he inveighed against\r the oppressing and depressing influence of man’s sense of guilt and\r consciousness of sin in order fully to grasp the significance of this\r discourse. Slowly but surely, he thought the values of Christianity and\r Judaic traditions had done their work in the minds of men. What were\r once but expedients devised for the discipline of a certain portion of\r humanity, had now passed into man’s blood and had become instincts. This\r oppressive and paralysing sense of guilt and of sin is what Nietzsche\r refers to when he speaks of “the spirit of gravity.” This ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3441},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-3","text":"That there is much to be said for Nietzsche’s hypothesis of the Eternal\r Recurrence of all things great and small, nobody who has read the\r literature on the subject will doubt for an instant; but it remains a\r very daring conjecture notwithstanding and even in its ultimate effect,\r as a dogma, on the minds of men, I venture to doubt whether Nietzsche\r ever properly estimated its worth (see Note on Chapter LVII.).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3442},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-4","text":"What follows is clear enough. Zarathustra sees a young shepherd\r struggling on the ground with a snake holding fast to the back of his\r throat. The sage, assuming that the snake must have crawled into the\r young man’s mouth while he lay sleeping, runs to his help and pulls\r at the loathsome reptile with all his might, but in vain. At last, in\r despair, Zarathustra appeals to the young man’s will. Knowing full well\r what a ghastly operation he is recommending, he nevertheless cries,\r “Bite! Bite! Its head off! Bite!” as the only possible solution of the\r difficulty. The young shepherd bites, and far away he spits the\r snake’s head, whereupon he rises, “No longer shepherd, no longer man—a\r tra","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3443},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-5","text":"In this parable the young shepherd is obviously the man of to-day; the\r snake that chokes him represents the stultifying and paralysing social\r values that threaten to shatter humanity, and the advice “Bite! Bite!”\r  is but Nietzsche’s exasperated cry to mankind to alter their values\r before it is too late.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3444},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-6","text":"This, like “The Wanderer”, is one of the many introspective passages\r in the work, and is full of innuendos and hints as to the Nietzschean\r outlook on life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3445},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-7","text":"Here we have a record of Zarathustra’s avowal of optimism, as also the\r important statement concerning “Chance” or “Accident” (verse 27). Those\r who are familiar with Nietzsche’s philosophy will not require to be told\r what an important role his doctrine of chance plays in his teaching.\r The Giant Chance has hitherto played with the puppet “man,”—this is\r the fact he cannot contemplate with equanimity. Man shall now exploit\r chance, he says again and again, and make it fall on its knees before\r him! (See verse 33 in “On the Olive-Mount”, and verses 9–10 in “The\r Bedwarfing Virtue”).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3446},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-8","text":"This requires scarcely any comment. It is a satire on modern man and\r his belittling virtues. In verses 23 and 24 of the second part of the\r discourse we are reminded of Nietzsche’s powerful indictment of the\r great of to-day, in the Antichrist (Aphorism 43):—“At present\r nobody has any longer the courage for separate rights, for rights of\r domination, for a feeling of reverence for himself and his equals,—FOR\r PATHOS OF DISTANCE.... Our politics are MORBID from this want of\r courage!—The aristocracy of character has been undermined most craftily\r by the lie of the equality of souls; and if the belief in the ‘privilege\r of the many,’ makes revolutions and WILL CONTINUE TO MAKE them, it is\r C","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3447},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-9","text":"In Part III., we get the sentiments of the discourse “In the Happy\r Isles”, but perhaps in stronger terms. Once again we find Nietzsche\r thoroughly at ease, if not cheerful, as an atheist, and speaking with\r vertiginous daring of making chance go on its knees to him. In verse\r 20, Zarathustra makes yet another attempt at defining his entirely\r anti-anarchical attitude, and unless such passages have been completely\r overlooked or deliberately ignored hitherto by those who will persist in\r laying anarchy at his door, it is impossible to understand how he ever\r became associated with that foul political party.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3448},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-10","text":"The last verse introduces the expression, “THE GREAT NOONTIDE!” In the\r poem to be found at the end of “Beyond Good and Evil”, we meet with\r the expression again, and we shall find it occurring time and again in\r Nietzsche’s works. It will be found fully elucidated in the fifth part\r of “The Twilight of the Idols”; but for those who cannot refer to\r this book, it were well to point out that Nietzsche called the present\r period—our period—the noon of man’s history. Dawn is behind us. The\r childhood of mankind is over. Now we KNOW; there is now no longer any\r excuse for mistakes which will tend to botch and disfigure the type man.\r “With respect to what is past,” he says, “I have, like all dis","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3449},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-11","text":"Here we find Nietzsche confronted with his extreme opposite, with\r him therefore for whom he is most frequently mistaken by the unwary.\r “Zarathustra’s ape” he is called in the discourse. He is one of those\r at whose hands Nietzsche had to suffer most during his life-time, and\r at whose hands his philosophy has suffered most since his death. In this\r respect it may seem a little trivial to speak of extremes meeting; but\r it is wonderfully apt. Many have adopted Nietzsche’s mannerisms and\r word-coinages, who had nothing in common with him beyond the ideas and\r “business” they plagiarised; but the superficial observer and a large\r portion of the public, not knowing of these things,—not knowing","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3450},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-12","text":"If we now read what the fool says to Zarathustra, and note the tricks of\r speech he has borrowed from him: if we carefully follow the attitude\r he assumes, we shall understand why Zarathustra finally interrupts him.\r “Stop this at once,” Zarathustra cries, “long have thy speech and\r thy species disgusted me.... Out of love alone shall my contempt and my\r warning bird take wing; BUT NOT OUT OF THE SWAMP!” It were well if\r this discourse were taken to heart by all those who are too ready to\r associate Nietzsche with lesser and noiser men,—with mountebanks and\r mummers.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3451},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-13","text":"It is clear that this applies to all those breathless and hasty “tasters\r of everything,” who plunge too rashly into the sea of independent\r thought and “heresy,” and who, having miscalculated their strength, find\r it impossible to keep their head above water. “A little older, a little\r colder,” says Nietzsche. They soon clamber back to the conventions of\r the age they intended reforming. The French then say “le diable se fait\r hermite,” but these men, as a rule, have never been devils, neither\r do they become angels; for, in order to be really good or evil, some\r strength and deep breathing is required. Those who are more interested\r in supporting orthodoxy than in being over nice concernin","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3452},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-14","text":"This is an example of a class of writing which may be passed over too\r lightly by those whom poetasters have made distrustful of poetry. From\r first to last it is extremely valuable as an autobiographical note. The\r inevitable superficiality of the rabble is contrasted with the peaceful\r and profound depths of the anchorite. Here we first get a direct hint\r concerning Nietzsche’s fundamental passion—the main force behind all\r his new values and scathing criticism of existing values. In verse 30\r we are told that pity was his greatest danger. The broad altruism of the\r law-giver, thinking over vast eras of time, was continually being pitted\r by Nietzsche, in himself, against that transient an","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3453},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-15","text":"Nietzsche is here completely in his element. Three things hitherto\r best cursed and most calumniated on earth, are brought forward to be\r weighed. Voluptuousness, thirst of power, and selfishness,—the three\r forces in humanity which Christianity has done most to garble and\r besmirch,—Nietzsche endeavours to reinstate in their former places of\r honour. Voluptuousness, or sensual pleasure, is a dangerous thing to\r discuss nowadays. If we mention it with favour we may be regarded,\r however unjustly, as the advocate of savages, satyrs, and pure\r sensuality. If we condemn it, we either go over to the Puritans or we\r join those who are wont to come to table with no edge to their appetites\r and who","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3454},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-16","text":"(See Note on Chapter XLVI.) In Part II. of this discourse we meet with\r a doctrine not touched upon hitherto, save indirectly;—I refer to the\r doctrine of self-love. We should try to understand this perfectly before\r proceeding; for it is precisely views of this sort which, after having\r been cut out of the original context, are repeated far and wide as\r internal evidence proving the general unsoundness of Nietzsche’s\r philosophy. Already in the last of the “Thoughts out of Season”\r  Nietzsche speaks as follows about modern men: “...these modern creatures\r wish rather to be hunted down, wounded and torn to shreds, than to\r live alone with themselves in solitary calm. Alone with oneself!—this","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3455},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-17","text":"In the last verse Nietzsche challenges us to show that our way is\r the right way. In his teaching he does not coerce us, nor does he\r overpersuade; he simply says: “I am a law only for mine own, I am not a\r law for all. This—is now MY way,—where is yours?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3456},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-18","text":"Nietzsche himself declares this to be the most decisive portion of\r the whole of “Thus Spake Zarathustra”. It is a sort of epitome of his\r leading doctrines. In verse 12 of the second paragraph, we learn how he\r himself would fain have abandoned the poetical method of expression had\r he not known only too well that the only chance a new doctrine has of\r surviving, nowadays, depends upon its being given to the world in some\r kind of art-form. Just as prophets, centuries ago, often had to have\r recourse to the mask of madness in order to mitigate the hatred of those\r who did not and could not see as they did; so, to-day, the struggle for\r existence among opinions and values is so great, that a","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3457},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-19","text":"Many of the paragraphs will be found to be merely reminiscent of former\r discourses. For instance, par. 3 recalls “Redemption”. The last verse\r of par. 4 is important. Freedom which, as I have pointed out before,\r Nietzsche considered a dangerous acquisition in inexperienced or\r unworthy hands, here receives its death-blow as a general desideratum.\r In the first Part we read under “The Way of the Creating One”, that\r freedom as an end in itself does not concern Zarathustra at all. He says\r there: “Free from what? What doth that matter to Zarathustra? Clearly,\r however, shall thine eye answer me: free FOR WHAT?” And in “The\r Bedwarfing Virtue”: “Ah that ye understood my word: ‘Do ever what ye","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3458},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-20","text":"Here we have a description of the kind of altruism Nietzsche exacted\r from higher men. It is really a comment upon “The Bestowing Virtue” (see\r Note on Chapter XXII.).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3459},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-21","text":"This refers, of course, to the reception pioneers of Nietzsche’s stamp\r meet with at the hands of their contemporaries.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3460},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-22","text":"Nietzsche teaches that nothing is stable,—not even values,—not\r even the concepts good and evil. He likens life unto a stream. But\r foot-bridges and railings span the stream, and they seem to stand\r firm. Many will be reminded of good and evil when they look upon these\r structures; for thus these same values stand over the stream of life,\r and life flows on beneath them and leaves them standing. When, however,\r winter comes and the stream gets frozen, many inquire: “Should not\r everything—STAND STILL? Fundamentally everything standeth still.” But\r soon the spring cometh and with it the thaw-wind. It breaks the ice, and\r the ice breaks down the foot-bridges and railings, whereupon everything\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3461},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-23","text":"So far, this is perhaps the most important paragraph. It is a protest\r against reading a moral order of things in life. “Life is something\r essentially immoral!” Nietzsche tells us in the introduction to the\r “Birth of Tragedy”. Even to call life “activity,” or to define it\r further as “the continuous adjustment of internal relations to external\r relations,” as Spencer has it, Nietzsche characterises as a “democratic\r idiosyncracy.” He says to define it in this way, “is to mistake the\r true nature and function of life, which is Will to Power.... Life is\r ESSENTIALLY appropriation, injury, conquest of the strange and weak,\r suppression, severity, obtrusion of its own forms, incorporation and\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3462},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-24","text":"These deal with Nietzsche’s principle of the desirability of rearing a\r select race. The biological and historical grounds for his insistence\r upon this principle are, of course, manifold. Gobineau in his great\r work, “L’Inegalite des Races Humaines”, lays strong emphasis upon the\r evils which arise from promiscuous and inter-social marriages. He alone\r would suffice to carry Nietzsche’s point against all those who are\r opposed to the other conditions, to the conditions which would have\r saved Rome, which have maintained the strength of the Jewish race, and\r which are strictly maintained by every breeder of animals throughout the\r world. Darwin in his remarks relative to the degeneration of ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3463},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-25","text":"The last two verses of par. 12 were discussed in the Notes on Chapters\r XXXVI. and LIII.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3464},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-26","text":"This, like the first part of “The Soothsayer”, is obviously a reference\r to the Schopenhauerian Pessimism.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3465},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-27","text":"We must be careful to separate this paragraph, in sense, from the\r previous four paragraphs. Nietzsche is still dealing with Pessimism\r here; but it is the pessimism of the hero—the man most susceptible of\r all to desperate views of life, owing to the obstacles that are arrayed\r against him in a world where men of his kind are very rare and are\r continually being sacrificed. It was to save this man that Nietzsche\r wrote. Heroism foiled, thwarted, and wrecked, hoping and fighting until\r the last, is at length overtaken by despair, and renounces all struggle\r for sleep. This is not the natural or constitutional pessimism which\r proceeds from an unhealthy body—the dyspeptic’s lack of appetite; ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3466},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-28","text":"“All that increases power is good, all that springs from weakness is\r bad. The weak and ill-constituted shall perish: first principle of our\r charity. And one shall also help them thereto.” Nietzsche partly divined\r the kind of reception moral values of this stamp would meet with at\r the hands of the effeminate manhood of Europe. Here we see that he had\r anticipated the most likely form their criticism would take (see also\r the last two verses of par. 17).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3467},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-29","text":"The first ten verses, here, are reminiscent of “War and Warriors” and\r of “The Flies in the Market-place.” Verses 11 and 12, however, are\r particularly important. There is a strong argument in favour of the\r sharp differentiation of castes and of races (and even of sexes; see\r Note on Chapter XVIII.) running all through Nietzsche’s writings.\r But sharp differentiation also implies antagonism in some form or\r other—hence Nietzsche’s fears for modern men. What modern men desire\r above all, is peace and the cessation of pain. But neither great races\r nor great castes have ever been built up in this way. “Who still wanteth\r to rule?” Zarathustra asks in the “Prologue”. “Who still wanteth to\r obe","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3468},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-30","text":"This should be read in conjunction with “Child and Marriage”. In the\r fifth verse we shall recognise our old friend “Marriage on the ten-years\r system,” which George Meredith suggested some years ago. This, however,\r must not be taken too literally. I do not think Nietzsche’s profoundest\r views on marriage were ever intended to be given over to the public at\r all, at least not for the present. They appear in the biography by his\r sister, and although their wisdom is unquestionable, the nature of the\r reforms he suggests render it impossible for them to become popular just\r now.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3469},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-31","text":"Nietzsche was not an iconoclast from predilection. No bitterness or\r empty hate dictated his vituperations against existing values and\r against the dogmas of his parents and forefathers. He knew too well what\r these things meant to the millions who profess them, to approach the\r task of uprooting them with levity or even with haste. He saw what\r modern anarchists and revolutionists do NOT see—namely, that man is in\r danger of actual destruction when his customs and values are broken.\r I need hardly point out, therefore, how deeply he was conscious of\r the responsibility he threw upon our shoulders when he invited us to\r reconsider our position. The lines in this paragraph are evidence enough","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3470},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-32","text":"We meet with several puzzles here. Zarathustra calls himself the\r advocate of the circle (the Eternal Recurrence of all things), and he\r calls this doctrine his abysmal thought. In the last verse of the\r first paragraph, however, after hailing his deepest thought, he cries:\r “Disgust, disgust, disgust!” We know Nietzsche’s ideal man was that\r “world-approving, exuberant, and vivacious creature, who has not only\r learnt to compromise and arrange with that which was and is, but wishes\r to have it again, AS IT WAS AND IS, for all eternity insatiably calling\r out da capo, not only to himself, but to the whole piece and play” (see\r Note on Chapter XLII.). But if one ask oneself what the condition","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3471},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-33","text":"In verses 15 and 16, we have Nietzsche declaring himself an evolutionist\r in the broadest sense—that is to say, that he believes in the\r Development Hypothesis as the description of the process by which\r species have originated. Now, to understand his position correctly\r we must show his relationship to the two greatest of modern\r evolutionists—Darwin and Spencer. As a philosopher, however, Nietzsche\r does not stand or fall by his objections to the Darwinian or Spencerian\r cosmogony. He never laid claim to a very profound knowledge of biology,\r and his criticism is far more valuable as the attitude of a fresh mind\r than as that of a specialist towards the question. Moreover, in his\r objectio","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3472},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-34","text":"In verses 28, 29, and 30 of the second portion of this discourse we meet\r with a doctrine which, at first sight, seems to be merely “le manoir\r a l’envers,” indeed one English critic has actually said of Nietzsche,\r that “Thus Spake Zarathustra” is no more than a compendium of modern\r views and maxims turned upside down. Examining these heterodox\r pronouncements a little more closely, however, we may possibly perceive\r their truth. Regarding good and evil as purely relative values, it\r stands to reason that what may be bad or evil in a given man, relative\r to a certain environment, may actually be good if not highly virtuous\r in him relative to a certain other environment. If this hypothetic","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3473},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-35","text":"By depriving a man of his wickedness—more particularly nowadays—\r therefore, one may unwittingly be doing violence to the greatest in him.\r It may be an outrage against his wholeness, just as the lopping-off of a\r leg would be. Fortunately, the natural so-called “wickedness” of higher\r men has in a certain measure been able to resist this lopping process\r which successive slave-moralities have practised; but signs are not\r wanting which show that the noblest wickedness is fast vanishing from\r society—the wickedness of courage and determination—and that Nietzsche\r had good reasons for crying: “Ah, that (man’s) baddest is so very small!\r Ah, that his best is so very small. What is good? To be ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3474},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-119-36","text":"This is a final paean which Zarathustra sings to Eternity and the\r marriage-ring of rings, the ring of the Eternal Recurrence.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":3475},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-1","text":"In my opinion this part is Nietzsche’s open avowal that all his\r philosophy, together with all his hopes, enthusiastic outbursts,\r blasphemies, prolixities, and obscurities, were merely so many gifts\r laid at the feet of higher men. He had no desire to save the world. What\r he wished to determine was: Who is to be master of the world? This is\r a very different thing. He came to save higher men;—to give them that\r freedom by which, alone, they can develop and reach their zenith (see\r Note on Chapter LIV., end). It has been argued, and with considerable\r force, that no such philosophy is required by higher men, that, as a\r matter of fact, higher men, by virtue of their constitutions always, do","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3476},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-2","text":"In the fourteenth verse of this discourse Nietzsche defines the solemn\r duty he imposed upon himself: “Become what thou art.” Surely the\r criticism which has been directed against this maxim must all fall to\r the ground when it is remembered, once and for all, that Nietzsche’s\r teaching was never intended to be other than an esoteric one. “I am a\r law only for mine own,” he says emphatically, “I am not a law for\r all.” It is of the greatest importance to humanity that its highest\r individuals should be allowed to attain to their full development; for,\r only by means of its heroes can the human race be led forward step by\r step to higher and yet higher levels. “Become what thou art” applied\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3477},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-3","text":"At the last eight verses many readers may be tempted to laugh. In\r England we almost always laugh when a man takes himself seriously at\r anything save sport. And there is of course no reason why the reader\r should not be hilarious.—A certain greatness is requisite, both in\r order to be sublime and to have reverence for the sublime. Nietzsche\r earnestly believed that the Zarathustra-kingdom—his dynasty of a\r thousand years—would one day come; if he had not believed it so\r earnestly, if every artist in fact had not believed so earnestly in\r his Hazar, whether of ten, fifteen, a hundred, or a thousand years, we\r should have lost all our higher men; they would have become pessimists,\r suicides, ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3478},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-4","text":"We now meet with Zarathustra in extraordinary circumstances. He is\r confronted with Schopenhauer and tempted by the old Soothsayer to commit\r the sin of pity. “I have come that I may seduce thee to thy last sin!”\r  says the Soothsayer to Zarathustra. It will be remembered that in\r Schopenhauer’s ethics, pity is elevated to the highest place among the\r virtues, and very consistently too, seeing that the Weltanschauung is\r a pessimistic one. Schopenhauer appeals to Nietzsche’s deepest and\r strongest sentiment—his sympathy for higher men. “Why dost thou conceal\r thyself?” he cries. “It is THE HIGHER MAN that calleth for thee!”\r  Zarathustra is almost overcome by the Soothsayer’s pleading, as he","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3479},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-5","text":"On his way Zarathustra meets two more higher men of his time; two\r kings cross his path. They are above the average modern type; for their\r instincts tell them what real ruling is, and they despise the mockery\r which they have been taught to call “Reigning.” “We ARE NOT the first\r men,” they say, “and have nevertheless to STAND FOR them: of this\r imposture have we at last become weary and disgusted.” It is the kings\r who tell Zarathustra: “There is no sorer misfortune in all human destiny\r than when the mighty of the earth are not also the first men. There\r everything becometh false and distorted and monstrous.” The kings are\r also asked by Zarathustra to accept the shelter of his cave, wher","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3480},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-6","text":"Among the higher men whom Zarathustra wishes to save, is also the\r scientific specialist—the man who honestly and scrupulously pursues his\r investigations, as Darwin did, in one department of knowledge. “I love\r him who liveth in order to know, and seeketh to know in order that the\r Superman may hereafter live. Thus seeketh he his own down-going.”\r  “The spiritually conscientious one,” he is called in this discourse.\r Zarathustra steps on him unawares, and the slave of science, bleeding\r from the violence he has done to himself by his self-imposed task,\r speaks proudly of his little sphere of knowledge—his little hand’s\r breadth of ground on Zarathustra’s territory, philosophy. “Where mine\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3481},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-7","text":"The Magician is of course an artist, and Nietzsche’s intimate knowledge\r of perhaps the greatest artist of his age rendered the selection of\r Wagner, as the type in this discourse, almost inevitable. Most readers\r will be acquainted with the facts relating to Nietzsche’s and Wagner’s\r friendship and ultimate separation. As a boy and a youth Nietzsche had\r shown such a remarkable gift for music that it had been a question at\r one time whether he should not perhaps give up everything else in order\r to develop this gift, but he became a scholar notwithstanding, although\r he never entirely gave up composing, and playing the piano. While\r still in his teens, he became acquainted with Wagner’s mus","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3482},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-8","text":"When the blow came it was therefore all the more severe. Nietzsche\r at length realised that the friend of his fancy and the real Richard\r Wagner—the composer of Parsifal—were not one; the fact dawned\r upon him slowly; disappointment upon disappointment, revelation after\r revelation, ultimately brought it home to him, and though his best\r instincts were naturally opposed to it at first, the revulsion of\r feeling at last became too strong to be ignored, and Nietzsche was\r plunged into the blackest despair. Years after his break with Wagner,\r he wrote “The Case of Wagner”, and “Nietzsche contra Wagner”, and these\r works are with us to prove the sincerity and depth of his views on the\r man who w","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3483},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-9","text":"The poem in this discourse is, of course, reminiscent of Wagner’s own\r poetical manner, and it must be remembered that the whole was written\r subsequent to Nietzsche’s final break with his friend. The dialogue\r between Zarathustra and the Magician reveals pretty fully what it\r was that Nietzsche grew to loathe so intensely in Wagner,—viz., his\r pronounced histrionic tendencies, his dissembling powers, his inordinate\r vanity, his equivocalness, his falseness. “It honoureth thee,” says\r Zarathustra, “that thou soughtest for greatness, but it betrayeth thee\r also. Thou art not great.” The Magician is nevertheless sent as a guest\r to Zarathustra’s cave; for, in his heart, Zarathustra believed un","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3484},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-10","text":"Zarathustra now meets the last pope, and, in a poetical form, we get\r Nietzsche’s description of the course Judaism and Christianity pursued\r before they reached their final break-up in Atheism, Agnosticism, and\r the like. The God of a strong, warlike race—the God of Israel—is a\r jealous, revengeful God. He is a power that can be pictured and endured\r only by a hardy and courageous race, a race rich enough to sacrifice and\r to lose in sacrifice. The image of this God degenerates with the people\r that appropriate it, and gradually He becomes a God of love—“soft and\r mellow,” a lower middle-class deity, who is “pitiful.” He can no longer\r be a God who requires sacrifice, for we ourselves are n","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3485},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-11","text":"This discourse contains perhaps the boldest of Nietzsche’s suggestions\r concerning Atheism, as well as some extremely penetrating remarks upon\r the sentiment of pity. Zarathustra comes across the repulsive creature\r sitting on the wayside, and what does he do? He manifests the only\r correct feelings that can be manifested in the presence of any great\r misery—that is to say, shame, reverence, embarrassment. Nietzsche\r detested the obtrusive and gushing pity that goes up to misery without\r a blush either on its cheek or in its heart—the pity which is only\r another form of self-glorification. “Thank God that I am not like\r thee!”—only this self-glorifying sentiment can lend a well-constituted\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3486},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-12","text":"Zarathustra calls the ugliest man the murderer of God! Certainly, this\r is one aspect of a certain kind of Atheism—the Atheism of the man who\r reveres beauty to such an extent that his own ugliness, which outrages\r him, must be concealed from every eye lest it should not be respected as\r Zarathustra respected it. If there be a God, He too must be evaded. His\r pity must be foiled. But God is ubiquitous and omniscient. Therefore,\r for the really GREAT ugly man, He must not exist. “Their pity IS it from\r which I flee away,” he says—that is to say: “It is from their want of\r reverence and lack of shame in presence of my great misery!” The ugliest\r man despises himself; but Zarathustra said in hi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3487},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-13","text":"In this discourse, we undoubtedly have the ideal Buddhist, if not\r Gautama Buddha himself. Nietzsche had the greatest respect for Buddhism,\r and almost wherever he refers to it in his works, it is in terms of\r praise. He recognised that though Buddhism is undoubtedly a religion for\r decadents, its decadent values emanate from the higher and not, as in\r Christianity, from the lower grades of society. In Aphorism 20 of “The\r Antichrist”, he compares it exhaustively with Christianity, and\r the result of his investigation is very much in favour of the older\r religion. Still, he recognised a most decided Buddhistic influence\r in Christ’s teaching, and the words in verses 29, 30, and 31 are very\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3488},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-14","text":"The figure of Christ has been introduced often enough into fiction, and\r many scholars have undertaken to write His life according to their own\r lights, but few perhaps have ever attempted to present Him to us bereft\r of all those characteristics which a lack of the sense of harmony has\r attached to His person through the ages in which His doctrines have been\r taught. Now Nietzsche disagreed entirely with Renan’s view, that Christ\r was “le grand maitre en ironie”; in Aphorism 31 of “The Antichrist”,\r he says that he (Nietzsche) always purged his picture of the Humble\r Nazarene of all those bitter and spiteful outbursts which, in view of\r the struggle the first Christians went through, may ve","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3489},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-15","text":"Here we have a description of that courageous and wayward spirit that\r literally haunts the footsteps of every great thinker and every great\r leader; sometimes with the result that it loses all aims, all hopes,\r and all trust in a definite goal. It is the case of the bravest and\r most broad-minded men of to-day. These literally shadow the most daring\r movements in the science and art of their generation; they completely\r lose their bearings and actually find themselves, in the end, without a\r way, a goal, or a home. “On every surface have I already sat!...I become\r thin, I am almost equal to a shadow!” At last, in despair, such men\r do indeed cry out: “Nothing is true; all is permitted,” and","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3490},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-16","text":"At the noon of life Nietzsche said he entered the world; with him\r man came of age. We are now held responsible for our actions; our old\r guardians, the gods and demi-gods of our youth, the superstitions and\r fears of our childhood, withdraw; the field lies open before us; we\r lived through our morning with but one master—chance—; let us see to\r it that we MAKE our afternoon our own (see Note XLIX., Part III.).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3491},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-17","text":"Here I think I may claim that my contention in regard to the purpose and\r aim of the whole of Nietzsche’s philosophy (as stated at the beginning\r of my Notes on Part IV.) is completely upheld. He fought for “all who\r do not want to live, unless they learn again to HOPE—unless THEY learn\r (from him) the GREAT hope!” Zarathustra’s address to his guests shows\r clearly enough how he wished to help them: “I DO NOT TREAT MY WARRIORS\r INDULGENTLY,” he says: “how then could ye be fit for MY warfare?” He\r rebukes and spurns them, no word of love comes from his lips. Elsewhere\r he says a man should be a hard bed to his friend, thus alone can he be\r of use to him. Nietzsche would be a hard bed to highe","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3492},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-18","text":"“Ye higher men, think ye that I am here to put right what ye have put\r wrong? Or that I wished henceforth to make snugger couches for you\r sufferers? Or show you restless, miswandering, misclimbing ones new and\r easier footpaths?”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3493},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-19","text":"“Nay! Nay! Three times nay! Always more, always better ones of your type\r shall succumb—for ye shall always have it worse and harder.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3494},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-20","text":"In the first seven verses of this discourse, I cannot help seeing\r a gentle allusion to Schopenhauer’s habits as a bon-vivant. For a\r pessimist, be it remembered, Schopenhauer led quite an extraordinary\r life. He ate well, loved well, played the flute well, and I believe he\r smoked the best cigars. What follows is clear enough.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3495},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-21","text":"Nietzsche admits, here, that at one time he had thought of appealing to\r the people, to the crowd in the market-place, but that he had ultimately\r to abandon the task. He bids higher men depart from the market-place.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3496},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-22","text":"Here we are told quite plainly what class of men actually owe all their\r impulses and desires to the instinct of self-preservation. The struggle\r for existence is indeed the only spur in the case of such people.\r To them it matters not in what shape or condition man be preserved,\r provided only he survive. The transcendental maxim that “Life per se is\r precious” is the ruling maxim here.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3497},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-23","text":"In the Note on Chapter LVII. (end) I speak of Nietzsche’s elevation of\r the virtue, Courage, to the highest place among the virtues. Here he\r tells higher men the class of courage he expects from them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3498},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-24","text":"These have already been referred to in the Notes on Chapters LVII. (end)\r and LXXI.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3499},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-25","text":"I suggest that the last verse in this paragraph strongly confirms the\r view that Nietzsche’s teaching was always meant by him to be esoteric\r and for higher man alone.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3500},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-26","text":"In the last verse, here, another shaft of light is thrown upon the\r Immaculate Perception or so-called “pure objectivity” of the scientific\r mind. “Freedom from fever is still far from being knowledge.” Where a\r man’s emotions cease to accompany him in his investigations, he is\r not necessarily nearer the truth. Says Spencer, in the Preface to his\r Autobiography:—“In the genesis of a system of thought, the emotional\r nature is a large factor: perhaps as large a factor as the intellectual\r nature” (see pages 134, 141 of Vol. I., “Thoughts out of Season”).","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3501},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-27","text":"When we approach Nietzsche’s philosophy we must be prepared to be\r independent thinkers; in fact, the greatest virtue of his works is\r perhaps the subtlety with which they impose the obligation upon one\r of thinking alone, of scoring off one’s own bat, and of shifting\r intellectually for oneself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3502},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-28","text":"“I am a railing alongside the torrent; whoever is able to grasp me, may\r grasp me! Your crutch, however, I am not.” These two paragraphs are an\r exhortation to higher men to become independent.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3503},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-29","text":"Here Nietzsche perhaps exaggerates the importance of heredity. As,\r however, the question is by no means one on which we are all agreed,\r what he says is not without value.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3504},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-30","text":"A very important principle in Nietzsche’s philosophy is enunciated in\r the first verse of this paragraph. “The higher its type, always the\r seldomer doth a thing succeed” (see page 82 of “Beyond Good and Evil”).\r Those who, like some political economists, talk in a business-like way\r about the terrific waste of human life and energy, deliberately overlook\r the fact that the waste most to be deplored usually occurs among\r higher individuals. Economy was never precisely one of nature’s leading\r principles. All this sentimental wailing over the larger proportion\r of failures than successes in human life, does not seem to take into\r account the fact that it is the rarest thing on earth for a hig","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3505},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-31","text":"These paragraphs deal with Nietzsche’s protest against the democratic\r seriousness (Pobelernst) of modern times. “All good things laugh,” he\r says, and his final command to the higher men is, “LEARN, I pray you—to\r laugh.” All that is GOOD, in Nietzsche’s sense, is cheerful. To be able\r to crack a joke about one’s deepest feelings is the greatest test of\r their value. The man who does not laugh, like the man who does not make\r faces, is already a buffoon at heart.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3506},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-32","text":"“What hath hitherto been the greatest sin here on earth? Was it not the\r word of him who said: ‘Woe unto them that laugh now!’ Did he himself\r find no cause for laughter on the earth? Then he sought badly. A child\r even findeth cause for it.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3507},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-33","text":"After his address to the higher men, Zarathustra goes out into the\r open to recover himself. Meanwhile the magician (Wagner), seizing the\r opportunity in order to draw them all into his net once more, sings the\r Song of Melancholy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3508},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-34","text":"The only one to resist the “melancholy voluptuousness” of his art, is\r the spiritually conscientious one—the scientific specialist of whom we\r read in the discourse entitled “The Leech”. He takes the harp from the\r magician and cries for air, while reproving the musician in the style\r of “The Case of Wagner”. When the magician retaliates by saying that the\r spiritually conscientious one could have understood little of his song,\r the latter replies: “Thou praisest me in that thou separatest me from\r thyself.” The speech of the scientific man to his fellow higher men is\r well worth studying. By means of it, Nietzsche pays a high tribute to\r the honesty of the true specialist, while, in represe","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3509},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-35","text":"In this discourse, Nietzsche wishes to give his followers a warning.\r He thinks he has so far helped them that they have become convalescent,\r that new desires are awakened in them and that new hopes are in their\r arms and legs. But he mistakes the nature of the change. True, he has\r helped them, he has given them back what they most need, i.e., belief in\r believing—the confidence in having confidence in something, but how\r do they use it? This belief in faith, if one can so express it without\r seeming tautological, has certainly been restored to them, and in\r the first flood of their enthusiasm they use it by bowing down and\r worshipping an ass! When writing this passage, Nietzsche was obvi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3510},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-36","text":"Now, with regard to the actual service and Ass-Festival, no reader who\r happens to be acquainted with the religious history of the Middle Ages\r will fail to see the allusion here to the asinaria festa which were by\r no means uncommon in France, Germany, and elsewhere in Europe during the\r thirteenth, fourteenth, and fifteenth centuries.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3511},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-37","text":"At length, in the middle of their feast, Zarathustra bursts in upon\r them and rebukes them soundly. But he does not do so long; in the\r Ass-Festival, it suddenly occurs to him, that he is concerned with a\r ceremony that may not be without its purpose, as something foolish but\r necessary—a recreation for wise men. He is therefore highly pleased\r that the higher men have all blossomed forth; they therefore require\r new festivals,—“A little valiant nonsense, some divine service and\r ass-festival, some old joyful Zarathustra fool, some blusterer to blow\r their souls bright.”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3512},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-38","text":"He tells them not to forget that night and the ass-festival, for “such\r things only the convalescent devise! And should ye celebrate it again,”\r  he concludes, “do it from love to yourselves, do it also from love to\r me! And in remembrance of ME!”","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3513},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-39","text":"It were the height of presumption to attempt to fix any particular\r interpretation of my own to the words of this song. With what has gone\r before, the reader, while reading it as poetry, should be able to seek\r and find his own meaning in it. The doctrine of the Eternal Recurrence\r appears for the last time here, in an art-form. Nietzsche lays stress\r upon the fact that all happiness, all delight, longs for repetitions,\r and just as a child cries “Again! Again!” to the adult who happens to\r be amusing him; so the man who sees a meaning, and a joyful meaning, in\r existence must also cry “Again!” and yet “Again!” to all his life.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3514},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-40","text":"In this discourse, Nietzsche disassociates himself finally from the\r higher men, and by the symbol of the lion, wishes to convey to us that\r he has won over and mastered the best and the most terrible in nature.\r That great power and tenderness are kin, was already his belief in\r 1875—eight years before he wrote this speech, and when the birds and\r the lion come to him, it is because he is the embodiment of the two\r qualities. All that is terrible and great in nature, the higher men are\r not yet prepared for; for they retreat horror-stricken into the cave\r when the lion springs at them; but Zarathustra makes not a move towards\r them. He was tempted to them on the previous day, he says, but “","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3515},{"id":"nietzsche-thus-spake-120-41","text":"The above I know to be open to much criticism. I shall be grateful to\r all those who will be kind enough to show me where and how I have gone\r wrong; but I should like to point out that, as they stand, I have not\r given to these Notes by any means their final form.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Thus Spake Zarathustra","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Thus Spake Zarathustra","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":3516},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-0-1","text":"Produced by John Mamoun, Charles Franks and the Online\r Distributed Proofreading Team","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"0"},"sequenceIndex":3517},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-2-1","text":"The following is a reprint of the Helen Zimmern translation from German\r into English of \"Beyond Good and Evil,\" as published in The Complete\r Works of Friedrich Nietzsche (1909-1913). Some adaptations from the\r original text were made to format it into an e-text. Italics in the\r original book are capitalized in this e-text, except for most foreign\r language phrases that were italicized. Original footnotes are put in\r brackets \"[]\" at the points where they are cited in the text. Some\r spellings were altered. \"To-day\" and \"To-morrow\" are spelled \"today\"\r and \"tomorrow.\" Some words containing the letters \"ise\" in the original\r text, such as \"idealise,\" had these letters changed to \"ize,\" such ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"2"},"sequenceIndex":3518},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-6-1","text":"SUPPOSING that Truth is a woman--what then? Is there not ground\r for suspecting that all philosophers, in so far as they have been\r dogmatists, have failed to understand women--that the terrible\r seriousness and clumsy importunity with which they have usually paid\r their addresses to Truth, have been unskilled and unseemly methods for\r winning a woman? Certainly she has never allowed herself to be won; and\r at present every kind of dogma stands with sad and discouraged mien--IF,\r indeed, it stands at all! For there are scoffers who maintain that it\r has fallen, that all dogma lies on the ground--nay more, that it is at\r its last gasp. But to speak seriously, there are good grounds for hoping","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":3519},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-1","text":"1. The Will to Truth, which is to tempt us to many a hazardous\r enterprise, the famous Truthfulness of which all philosophers have\r hitherto spoken with respect, what questions has this Will to Truth not\r laid before us! What strange, perplexing, questionable questions! It is\r already a long story; yet it seems as if it were hardly commenced. Is\r it any wonder if we at last grow distrustful, lose patience, and turn\r impatiently away? That this Sphinx teaches us at last to ask questions\r ourselves? WHO is it really that puts questions to us here? WHAT really\r is this \"Will to Truth\" in us? In fact we made a long halt at the\r question as to the origin of this Will--until at last we came to an\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3520},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-2","text":"2. \"HOW COULD anything originate out of its opposite? For example, truth\r out of error? or the Will to Truth out of the will to deception? or the\r generous deed out of selfishness? or the pure sun-bright vision of the\r wise man out of covetousness? Such genesis is impossible; whoever dreams\r of it is a fool, nay, worse than a fool; things of the highest\r value must have a different origin, an origin of THEIR own--in this\r transitory, seductive, illusory, paltry world, in this turmoil of\r delusion and cupidity, they cannot have their source. But rather in\r the lap of Being, in the intransitory, in the concealed God, in the\r 'Thing-in-itself--THERE must be their source, and nowhere else!\"--Thi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3521},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-3","text":"3. Having kept a sharp eye on philosophers, and having read between\r their lines long enough, I now say to myself that the greater part of\r conscious thinking must be counted among the instinctive functions, and\r it is so even in the case of philosophical thinking; one has here to\r learn anew, as one learned anew about heredity and \"innateness.\" As\r little as the act of birth comes into consideration in the whole process\r and procedure of heredity, just as little is \"being-conscious\" OPPOSED\r to the instinctive in any decisive sense; the greater part of the\r conscious thinking of a philosopher is secretly influenced by his\r instincts, and forced into definite channels. And behind all logic a","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3522},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-4","text":"4. The falseness of an opinion is not for us any objection to it: it is\r here, perhaps, that our new language sounds most strangely. The\r question is, how far an opinion is life-furthering, life-preserving,\r species-preserving, perhaps species-rearing, and we are fundamentally\r inclined to maintain that the falsest opinions (to which the synthetic\r judgments a priori belong), are the most indispensable to us, that\r without a recognition of logical fictions, without a comparison of\r reality with the purely IMAGINED world of the absolute and immutable,\r without a constant counterfeiting of the world by means of numbers,\r man could not live--that the renunciation of false opinions would be\r a r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3523},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-5","text":"5. That which causes philosophers to be regarded half-distrustfully\r and half-mockingly, is not the oft-repeated discovery how innocent they\r are--how often and easily they make mistakes and lose their way, in\r short, how childish and childlike they are,--but that there is not\r enough honest dealing with them, whereas they all raise a loud and\r virtuous outcry when the problem of truthfulness is even hinted at in\r the remotest manner. They all pose as though their real opinions had\r been discovered and attained through the self-evolving of a cold, pure,\r divinely indifferent dialectic (in contrast to all sorts of mystics,\r who, fairer and foolisher, talk of \"inspiration\"), whereas, in fact, ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3524},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-6","text":"6. It has gradually become clear to me what every great philosophy up\r till now has consisted of--namely, the confession of its originator, and\r a species of involuntary and unconscious auto-biography; and moreover\r that the moral (or immoral) purpose in every philosophy has constituted\r the true vital germ out of which the entire plant has always grown.\r Indeed, to understand how the abstrusest metaphysical assertions of a\r philosopher have been arrived at, it is always well (and wise) to first\r ask oneself: \"What morality do they (or does he) aim at?\" Accordingly,\r I do not believe that an \"impulse to knowledge\" is the father of\r philosophy; but that another impulse, here as elsewhere, has","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3525},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-7","text":"7. How malicious philosophers can be! I know of nothing more stinging\r than the joke Epicurus took the liberty of making on Plato and the\r Platonists; he called them Dionysiokolakes. In its original sense,\r and on the face of it, the word signifies \"Flatterers of\r Dionysius\"--consequently, tyrants' accessories and lick-spittles;\r besides this, however, it is as much as to say, \"They are all ACTORS,\r there is nothing genuine about them\" (for Dionysiokolax was a popular\r name for an actor). And the latter is really the malignant reproach that\r Epicurus cast upon Plato: he was annoyed by the grandiose manner, the\r mise en scene style of which Plato and his scholars were masters--of\r which Epicu","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3526},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-8","text":"8. There is a point in every philosophy at which the \"conviction\" of\r the philosopher appears on the scene; or, to put it in the words of an\r ancient mystery:","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3527},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-9","text":"9. You desire to LIVE \"according to Nature\"? Oh, you noble Stoics, what\r fraud of words! Imagine to yourselves a being like Nature, boundlessly\r extravagant, boundlessly indifferent, without purpose or consideration,\r without pity or justice, at once fruitful and barren and uncertain:\r imagine to yourselves INDIFFERENCE as a power--how COULD you live\r in accordance with such indifference? To live--is not that just\r endeavouring to be otherwise than this Nature? Is not living valuing,\r preferring, being unjust, being limited, endeavouring to be different?\r And granted that your imperative, \"living according to Nature,\" means\r actually the same as \"living according to life\"--how could you do\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3528},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-10","text":"10. The eagerness and subtlety, I should even say craftiness, with\r which the problem of \"the real and the apparent world\" is dealt with at\r present throughout Europe, furnishes food for thought and attention; and\r he who hears only a \"Will to Truth\" in the background, and nothing else,\r cannot certainly boast of the sharpest ears. In rare and isolated\r cases, it may really have happened that such a Will to Truth--a certain\r extravagant and adventurous pluck, a metaphysician's ambition of the\r forlorn hope--has participated therein: that which in the end always\r prefers a handful of \"certainty\" to a whole cartload of beautiful\r possibilities; there may even be puritanical fanatics of conscie","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3529},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-11","text":"11. It seems to me that there is everywhere an attempt at present to\r divert attention from the actual influence which Kant exercised on\r German philosophy, and especially to ignore prudently the value which\r he set upon himself. Kant was first and foremost proud of his Table of\r Categories; with it in his hand he said: \"This is the most difficult\r thing that could ever be undertaken on behalf of metaphysics.\" Let us\r only understand this \"could be\"! He was proud of having DISCOVERED a\r new faculty in man, the faculty of synthetic judgment a priori. Granting\r that he deceived himself in this matter; the development and rapid\r flourishing of German philosophy depended nevertheless on his prid","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3530},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-12","text":"Quia est in eo virtus dormitiva,\r     Cujus est natura sensus assoupire.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3531},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-13","text":"But such replies belong to the realm of comedy, and it is high time\r to replace the Kantian question, \"How are synthetic judgments a PRIORI\r possible?\" by another question, \"Why is belief in such judgments\r necessary?\"--in effect, it is high time that we should understand\r that such judgments must be believed to be true, for the sake of the\r preservation of creatures like ourselves; though they still might\r naturally be false judgments! Or, more plainly spoken, and roughly and\r readily--synthetic judgments a priori should not \"be possible\" at all;\r we have no right to them; in our mouths they are nothing but false\r judgments. Only, of course, the belief in their truth is necessary, as\r plaus","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3532},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-14","text":"12. As regards materialistic atomism, it is one of the best-refuted\r theories that have been advanced, and in Europe there is now perhaps\r no one in the learned world so unscholarly as to attach serious\r signification to it, except for convenient everyday use (as an\r abbreviation of the means of expression)--thanks chiefly to the Pole\r Boscovich: he and the Pole Copernicus have hitherto been the greatest\r and most successful opponents of ocular evidence. For while Copernicus\r has persuaded us to believe, contrary to all the senses, that the earth\r does NOT stand fast, Boscovich has taught us to abjure the belief in the\r last thing that \"stood fast\" of the earth--the belief in \"substance,\" in","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3533},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-15","text":"13. Psychologists should bethink themselves before putting down the\r instinct of self-preservation as the cardinal instinct of an organic\r being. A living thing seeks above all to DISCHARGE its strength--life\r itself is WILL TO POWER; self-preservation is only one of the indirect\r and most frequent RESULTS thereof. In short, here, as everywhere else,\r let us beware of SUPERFLUOUS teleological principles!--one of which\r is the instinct of self-preservation (we owe it to Spinoza's\r inconsistency). It is thus, in effect, that method ordains, which must\r be essentially economy of principles.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3534},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-16","text":"14. It is perhaps just dawning on five or six minds that natural\r philosophy is only a world-exposition and world-arrangement (according\r to us, if I may say so!) and NOT a world-explanation; but in so far as\r it is based on belief in the senses, it is regarded as more, and for a\r long time to come must be regarded as more--namely, as an explanation.\r It has eyes and fingers of its own, it has ocular evidence and\r palpableness of its own: this operates fascinatingly, persuasively, and\r CONVINCINGLY upon an age with fundamentally plebeian tastes--in fact, it\r follows instinctively the canon of truth of eternal popular sensualism.\r What is clear, what is \"explained\"? Only that which can be see","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3535},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-17","text":"15. To study physiology with a clear conscience, one must insist on\r the fact that the sense-organs are not phenomena in the sense of the\r idealistic philosophy; as such they certainly could not be causes!\r Sensualism, therefore, at least as regulative hypothesis, if not as\r heuristic principle. What? And others say even that the external world\r is the work of our organs? But then our body, as a part of this external\r world, would be the work of our organs! But then our organs themselves\r would be the work of our organs! It seems to me that this is a\r complete REDUCTIO AD ABSURDUM, if the conception CAUSA SUI is something\r fundamentally absurd. Consequently, the external world is NOT the wor","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3536},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-18","text":"16. There are still harmless self-observers who believe that there are\r \"immediate certainties\"; for instance, \"I think,\" or as the superstition\r of Schopenhauer puts it, \"I will\"; as though cognition here got hold\r of its object purely and simply as \"the thing in itself,\" without any\r falsification taking place either on the part of the subject or the\r object. I would repeat it, however, a hundred times, that \"immediate\r certainty,\" as well as \"absolute knowledge\" and the \"thing in itself,\"\r involve a CONTRADICTIO IN ADJECTO; we really ought to free ourselves\r from the misleading significance of words! The people on their part may\r think that cognition is knowing all about things, but the p","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3537},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-19","text":"17. With regard to the superstitions of logicians, I shall never tire\r of emphasizing a small, terse fact, which is unwillingly recognized by\r these credulous minds--namely, that a thought comes when \"it\" wishes,\r and not when \"I\" wish; so that it is a PERVERSION of the facts of the\r case to say that the subject \"I\" is the condition of the predicate\r \"think.\" ONE thinks; but that this \"one\" is precisely the famous old\r \"ego,\" is, to put it mildly, only a supposition, an assertion, and\r assuredly not an \"immediate certainty.\" After all, one has even gone too\r far with this \"one thinks\"--even the \"one\" contains an INTERPRETATION of\r the process, and does not belong to the process itself. One i","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3538},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-20","text":"18. It is certainly not the least charm of a theory that it is\r refutable; it is precisely thereby that it attracts the more subtle\r minds. It seems that the hundred-times-refuted theory of the \"free will\"\r owes its persistence to this charm alone; some one is always appearing\r who feels himself strong enough to refute it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3539},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-21","text":"19. Philosophers are accustomed to speak of the will as though it were\r the best-known thing in the world; indeed, Schopenhauer has given us\r to understand that the will alone is really known to us, absolutely and\r completely known, without deduction or addition. But it again and\r again seems to me that in this case Schopenhauer also only did what\r philosophers are in the habit of doing--he seems to have adopted a\r POPULAR PREJUDICE and exaggerated it. Willing seems to me to be above\r all something COMPLICATED, something that is a unity only in name--and\r it is precisely in a name that popular prejudice lurks, which has got\r the mastery over the inadequate precautions of philosophers in all ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3540},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-22","text":"20. That the separate philosophical ideas are not anything optional or\r autonomously evolving, but grow up in connection and relationship with\r each other, that, however suddenly and arbitrarily they seem to appear\r in the history of thought, they nevertheless belong just as much to\r a system as the collective members of the fauna of a Continent--is\r betrayed in the end by the circumstance: how unfailingly the most\r diverse philosophers always fill in again a definite fundamental scheme\r of POSSIBLE philosophies. Under an invisible spell, they always revolve\r once more in the same orbit, however independent of each other they\r may feel themselves with their critical or systematic wills, some","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3541},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-23","text":"21. The CAUSA SUI is the best self-contradiction that has yet been\r conceived, it is a sort of logical violation and unnaturalness; but the\r extravagant pride of man has managed to entangle itself profoundly and\r frightfully with this very folly. The desire for \"freedom of will\"\r in the superlative, metaphysical sense, such as still holds sway,\r unfortunately, in the minds of the half-educated, the desire to bear\r the entire and ultimate responsibility for one's actions oneself, and\r to absolve God, the world, ancestors, chance, and society therefrom,\r involves nothing less than to be precisely this CAUSA SUI, and, with\r more than Munchausen daring, to pull oneself up into existence by the\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3542},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-24","text":"22. Let me be pardoned, as an old philologist who cannot desist from\r the mischief of putting his finger on bad modes of interpretation, but\r \"Nature's conformity to law,\" of which you physicists talk so proudly,\r as though--why, it exists only owing to your interpretation and bad\r \"philology.\" It is no matter of fact, no \"text,\" but rather just a\r naively humanitarian adjustment and perversion of meaning, with which\r you make abundant concessions to the democratic instincts of the modern\r soul! \"Everywhere equality before the law--Nature is not different in\r that respect, nor better than we\": a fine instance of secret motive,\r in which the vulgar antagonism to everything privileged and\r aut","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3543},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-7-25","text":"23. All psychology hitherto has run aground on moral prejudices and\r timidities, it has not dared to launch out into the depths. In so far\r as it is allowable to recognize in that which has hitherto been written,\r evidence of that which has hitherto been kept silent, it seems as if\r nobody had yet harboured the notion of psychology as the Morphology\r and DEVELOPMENT-DOCTRINE OF THE WILL TO POWER, as I conceive of it.\r The power of moral prejudices has penetrated deeply into the most\r intellectual world, the world apparently most indifferent and\r unprejudiced, and has obviously operated in an injurious, obstructive,\r blinding, and distorting manner. A proper physio-psychology has to\r contend ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3544},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-1","text":"24. O sancta simplicitas! In what strange simplification and\r falsification man lives! One can never cease wondering when once one has\r got eyes for beholding this marvel! How we have made everything around\r us clear and free and easy and simple! how we have been able to give\r our senses a passport to everything superficial, our thoughts a godlike\r desire for wanton pranks and wrong inferences!--how from the beginning,\r we have contrived to retain our ignorance in order to enjoy an almost\r inconceivable freedom, thoughtlessness, imprudence, heartiness,\r and gaiety--in order to enjoy life! And only on this solidified,\r granite-like foundation of ignorance could knowledge rear itself\r hitherto","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3545},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-2","text":"25. After such a cheerful commencement, a serious word would fain be\r heard; it appeals to the most serious minds. Take care, ye philosophers\r and friends of knowledge, and beware of martyrdom! Of suffering \"for the\r truth's sake\"! even in your own defense! It spoils all the innocence\r and fine neutrality of your conscience; it makes you headstrong against\r objections and red rags; it stupefies, animalizes, and brutalizes, when\r in the struggle with danger, slander, suspicion, expulsion, and even\r worse consequences of enmity, ye have at last to play your last card\r as protectors of truth upon earth--as though \"the Truth\" were such an\r innocent and incompetent creature as to require protecto","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3546},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-3","text":"26. Every select man strives instinctively for a citadel and a privacy,\r where he is FREE from the crowd, the many, the majority--where he may\r forget \"men who are the rule,\" as their exception;--exclusive only of\r the case in which he is pushed straight to such men by a still stronger\r instinct, as a discerner in the great and exceptional sense. Whoever, in\r intercourse with men, does not occasionally glisten in all the green\r and grey colours of distress, owing to disgust, satiety, sympathy,\r gloominess, and solitariness, is assuredly not a man of elevated tastes;\r supposing, however, that he does not voluntarily take all this burden\r and disgust upon himself, that he persistently avoids i","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3547},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-4","text":"27. It is difficult to be understood, especially when one thinks and\r lives gangasrotogati [Footnote: Like the river Ganges: presto.] among\r those only who think and live otherwise--namely, kurmagati [Footnote:\r Like the tortoise: lento.], or at best \"froglike,\" mandeikagati\r [Footnote: Like the frog: staccato.] (I do everything to be \"difficultly\r understood\" myself!)--and one should be heartily grateful for the\r good will to some refinement of interpretation. As regards \"the good\r friends,\" however, who are always too easy-going, and think that as\r friends they have a right to ease, one does well at the very first to\r grant them a play-ground and romping-place for misunderstanding--one can","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3548},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-5","text":"28. What is most difficult to render from one language into another\r is the TEMPO of its style, which has its basis in the character of the\r race, or to speak more physiologically, in the average TEMPO of the\r assimilation of its nutriment. There are honestly meant translations,\r which, as involuntary vulgarizations, are almost falsifications of the\r original, merely because its lively and merry TEMPO (which overleaps and\r obviates all dangers in word and expression) could not also be\r rendered. A German is almost incapacitated for PRESTO in his language;\r consequently also, as may be reasonably inferred, for many of the most\r delightful and daring NUANCES of free, free-spirited thought. And","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3549},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-6","text":"29. It is the business of the very few to be independent; it is a\r privilege of the strong. And whoever attempts it, even with the best\r right, but without being OBLIGED to do so, proves that he is probably\r not only strong, but also daring beyond measure. He enters into a\r labyrinth, he multiplies a thousandfold the dangers which life in itself\r already brings with it; not the least of which is that no one can see\r how and where he loses his way, becomes isolated, and is torn piecemeal\r by some minotaur of conscience. Supposing such a one comes to grief, it\r is so far from the comprehension of men that they neither feel it, nor\r sympathize with it. And he cannot any longer go back! He canno","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3550},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-7","text":"30. Our deepest insights must--and should--appear as follies, and under\r certain circumstances as crimes, when they come unauthorizedly to\r the ears of those who are not disposed and predestined for them. The\r exoteric and the esoteric, as they were formerly distinguished by\r philosophers--among the Indians, as among the Greeks, Persians, and\r Mussulmans, in short, wherever people believed in gradations of rank and\r NOT in equality and equal rights--are not so much in contradistinction\r to one another in respect to the exoteric class, standing without, and\r viewing, estimating, measuring, and judging from the outside, and not\r from the inside; the more essential distinction is that the class","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3551},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-8","text":"31. In our youthful years we still venerate and despise without the art\r of NUANCE, which is the best gain of life, and we have rightly to do\r hard penance for having fallen upon men and things with Yea and Nay.\r Everything is so arranged that the worst of all tastes, THE TASTE FOR\r THE UNCONDITIONAL, is cruelly befooled and abused, until a man learns\r to introduce a little art into his sentiments, and prefers to try\r conclusions with the artificial, as do the real artists of life. The\r angry and reverent spirit peculiar to youth appears to allow itself no\r peace, until it has suitably falsified men and things, to be able\r to vent its passion upon them: youth in itself even, is something\r fa","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3552},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-9","text":"32. Throughout the longest period of human history--one calls it the\r prehistoric period--the value or non-value of an action was inferred\r from its CONSEQUENCES; the action in itself was not taken into\r consideration, any more than its origin; but pretty much as in China at\r present, where the distinction or disgrace of a child redounds to\r its parents, the retro-operating power of success or failure was what\r induced men to think well or ill of an action. Let us call this period\r the PRE-MORAL period of mankind; the imperative, \"Know thyself!\" was\r then still unknown.--In the last ten thousand years, on the other hand,\r on certain large portions of the earth, one has gradually got so far,\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3553},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-10","text":"33. It cannot be helped: the sentiment of surrender, of sacrifice for\r one's neighbour, and all self-renunciation-morality, must be mercilessly\r called to account, and brought to judgment; just as the aesthetics\r of \"disinterested contemplation,\" under which the emasculation of art\r nowadays seeks insidiously enough to create itself a good conscience.\r There is far too much witchery and sugar in the sentiments \"for others\"\r and \"NOT for myself,\" for one not needing to be doubly distrustful here,\r and for one asking promptly: \"Are they not perhaps--DECEPTIONS?\"--That\r they PLEASE--him who has them, and him who enjoys their fruit, and also\r the mere spectator--that is still no argument in thei","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3554},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-11","text":"34. At whatever standpoint of philosophy one may place oneself nowadays,\r seen from every position, the ERRONEOUSNESS of the world in which we\r think we live is the surest and most certain thing our eyes can light\r upon: we find proof after proof thereof, which would fain allure us into\r surmises concerning a deceptive principle in the \"nature of things.\"\r He, however, who makes thinking itself, and consequently \"the spirit,\"\r responsible for the falseness of the world--an honourable exit, which\r every conscious or unconscious advocatus dei avails himself of--he\r who regards this world, including space, time, form, and movement, as\r falsely DEDUCED, would have at least good reason in the end","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3555},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-12","text":"35. O Voltaire! O humanity! O idiocy! There is something ticklish in\r \"the truth,\" and in the SEARCH for the truth; and if man goes about it\r too humanely--\"il ne cherche le vrai que pour faire le bien\"--I wager he\r finds nothing!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3556},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-13","text":"36. Supposing that nothing else is \"given\" as real but our world of\r desires and passions, that we cannot sink or rise to any other \"reality\"\r but just that of our impulses--for thinking is only a relation of these\r impulses to one another:--are we not permitted to make the attempt and\r to ask the question whether this which is \"given\" does not SUFFICE, by\r means of our counterparts, for the understanding even of the so-called\r mechanical (or \"material\") world? I do not mean as an illusion, a\r \"semblance,\" a \"representation\" (in the Berkeleyan and Schopenhauerian\r sense), but as possessing the same degree of reality as our emotions\r themselves--as a more primitive form of the world of emotio","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3557},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-14","text":"37. \"What? Does not that mean in popular language: God is disproved, but\r not the devil?\"--On the contrary! On the contrary, my friends! And who\r the devil also compels you to speak popularly!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3558},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-15","text":"38. As happened finally in all the enlightenment of modern times with\r the French Revolution (that terrible farce, quite superfluous when\r judged close at hand, into which, however, the noble and visionary\r spectators of all Europe have interpreted from a distance their own\r indignation and enthusiasm so long and passionately, UNTIL THE TEXT HAS\r DISAPPEARED UNDER THE INTERPRETATION), so a noble posterity might once\r more misunderstand the whole of the past, and perhaps only thereby make\r ITS aspect endurable.--Or rather, has not this already happened? Have\r not we ourselves been--that \"noble posterity\"? And, in so far as we now\r comprehend this, is it not--thereby already past?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3559},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-16","text":"39. Nobody will very readily regard a doctrine as true merely because\r it makes people happy or virtuous--excepting, perhaps, the amiable\r \"Idealists,\" who are enthusiastic about the good, true, and beautiful,\r and let all kinds of motley, coarse, and good-natured desirabilities\r swim about promiscuously in their pond. Happiness and virtue are no\r arguments. It is willingly forgotten, however, even on the part of\r thoughtful minds, that to make unhappy and to make bad are just as\r little counter-arguments. A thing could be TRUE, although it were in\r the highest degree injurious and dangerous; indeed, the fundamental\r constitution of existence might be such that one succumbed by a full\r knowl","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3560},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-17","text":"40. Everything that is profound loves the mask: the profoundest things\r have a hatred even of figure and likeness. Should not the CONTRARY only\r be the right disguise for the shame of a God to go about in? A question\r worth asking!--it would be strange if some mystic has not already\r ventured on the same kind of thing. There are proceedings of such a\r delicate nature that it is well to overwhelm them with coarseness\r and make them unrecognizable; there are actions of love and of an\r extravagant magnanimity after which nothing can be wiser than to take\r a stick and thrash the witness soundly: one thereby obscures his\r recollection. Many a one is able to obscure and abuse his own memory, in\r o","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3561},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-18","text":"41. One must subject oneself to one's own tests that one is destined\r for independence and command, and do so at the right time. One must not\r avoid one's tests, although they constitute perhaps the most dangerous\r game one can play, and are in the end tests made only before ourselves\r and before no other judge. Not to cleave to any person, be it even the\r dearest--every person is a prison and also a recess. Not to cleave to\r a fatherland, be it even the most suffering and necessitous--it is even\r less difficult to detach one's heart from a victorious fatherland. Not\r to cleave to a sympathy, be it even for higher men, into whose peculiar\r torture and helplessness chance has given us an insi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3562},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-19","text":"42. A new order of philosophers is appearing; I shall venture to baptize\r them by a name not without danger. As far as I understand them, as far\r as they allow themselves to be understood--for it is their nature to\r WISH to remain something of a puzzle--these philosophers of the\r future might rightly, perhaps also wrongly, claim to be designated as\r \"tempters.\" This name itself is after all only an attempt, or, if it be\r preferred, a temptation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3563},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-20","text":"43. Will they be new friends of \"truth,\" these coming philosophers? Very\r probably, for all philosophers hitherto have loved their truths. But\r assuredly they will not be dogmatists. It must be contrary to their\r pride, and also contrary to their taste, that their truth should still\r be truth for every one--that which has hitherto been the secret wish\r and ultimate purpose of all dogmatic efforts. \"My opinion is MY opinion:\r another person has not easily a right to it\"--such a philosopher of the\r future will say, perhaps. One must renounce the bad taste of wishing to\r agree with many people. \"Good\" is no longer good when one's neighbour\r takes it into his mouth. And how could there be a \"com","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3564},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-8-21","text":"44. Need I say expressly after all this that they will be free, VERY\r free spirits, these philosophers of the future--as certainly also they\r will not be merely free spirits, but something more, higher, greater,\r and fundamentally different, which does not wish to be misunderstood and\r mistaken? But while I say this, I feel under OBLIGATION almost as much\r to them as to ourselves (we free spirits who are their heralds and\r forerunners), to sweep away from ourselves altogether a stupid old\r prejudice and misunderstanding, which, like a fog, has too long made the\r conception of \"free spirit\" obscure. In every country of Europe, and the\r same in America, there is at present something which make","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3565},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-1","text":"45. The human soul and its limits, the range of man's inner experiences\r hitherto attained, the heights, depths, and distances of these\r experiences, the entire history of the soul UP TO THE PRESENT TIME,\r and its still unexhausted possibilities: this is the preordained\r hunting-domain for a born psychologist and lover of a \"big hunt\". But\r how often must he say despairingly to himself: \"A single individual!\r alas, only a single individual! and this great forest, this virgin\r forest!\" So he would like to have some hundreds of hunting assistants,\r and fine trained hounds, that he could send into the history of the\r human soul, to drive HIS game together. In vain: again and again he\r experienc","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3566},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-2","text":"46. Faith, such as early Christianity desired, and not infrequently\r achieved in the midst of a skeptical and southernly free-spirited world,\r which had centuries of struggle between philosophical schools behind\r it and in it, counting besides the education in tolerance which\r the Imperium Romanum gave--this faith is NOT that sincere, austere\r slave-faith by which perhaps a Luther or a Cromwell, or some other\r northern barbarian of the spirit remained attached to his God and\r Christianity, it is much rather the faith of Pascal, which resembles in\r a terrible manner a continuous suicide of reason--a tough, long-lived,\r worm-like reason, which is not to be slain at once and with a single\r blow","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3567},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-3","text":"47. Wherever the religious neurosis has appeared on the earth so far,\r we find it connected with three dangerous prescriptions as to regimen:\r solitude, fasting, and sexual abstinence--but without its being possible\r to determine with certainty which is cause and which is effect, or IF\r any relation at all of cause and effect exists there. This latter doubt\r is justified by the fact that one of the most regular symptoms among\r savage as well as among civilized peoples is the most sudden and\r excessive sensuality, which then with equal suddenness transforms into\r penitential paroxysms, world-renunciation, and will-renunciation, both\r symptoms perhaps explainable as disguised epilepsy? But now","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3568},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-4","text":"48. It seems that the Latin races are far more deeply attached to their\r Catholicism than we Northerners are to Christianity generally, and\r that consequently unbelief in Catholic countries means something quite\r different from what it does among Protestants--namely, a sort of revolt\r against the spirit of the race, while with us it is rather a return to\r the spirit (or non-spirit) of the race.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3569},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-5","text":"We Northerners undoubtedly derive our origin from barbarous races, even\r as regards our talents for religion--we have POOR talents for it. One\r may make an exception in the case of the Celts, who have theretofore\r furnished also the best soil for Christian infection in the North: the\r Christian ideal blossomed forth in France as much as ever the pale sun\r of the north would allow it. How strangely pious for our taste are still\r these later French skeptics, whenever there is any Celtic blood in their\r origin! How Catholic, how un-German does Auguste Comte's Sociology\r seem to us, with the Roman logic of its instincts! How Jesuitical, that\r amiable and shrewd cicerone of Port Royal, Sainte-Beu","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3570},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-6","text":"49. That which is so astonishing in the religious life of the ancient\r Greeks is the irrestrainable stream of GRATITUDE which it pours\r forth--it is a very superior kind of man who takes SUCH an attitude\r towards nature and life.--Later on, when the populace got the upper hand\r in Greece, FEAR became rampant also in religion; and Christianity was\r preparing itself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3571},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-7","text":"50. The passion for God: there are churlish, honest-hearted, and\r importunate kinds of it, like that of Luther--the whole of Protestantism\r lacks the southern DELICATEZZA. There is an Oriental exaltation of the\r mind in it, like that of an undeservedly favoured or elevated slave, as\r in the case of St. Augustine, for instance, who lacks in an offensive\r manner, all nobility in bearing and desires. There is a feminine\r tenderness and sensuality in it, which modestly and unconsciously longs\r for a UNIO MYSTICA ET PHYSICA, as in the case of Madame de Guyon. In\r many cases it appears, curiously enough, as the disguise of a girl's\r or youth's puberty; here and there even as the hysteria of an old","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3572},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-8","text":"51. The mightiest men have hitherto always bowed reverently before\r the saint, as the enigma of self-subjugation and utter voluntary\r privation--why did they thus bow? They divined in him--and as it were\r behind the questionableness of his frail and wretched appearance--the\r superior force which wished to test itself by such a subjugation; the\r strength of will, in which they recognized their own strength and\r love of power, and knew how to honour it: they honoured something\r in themselves when they honoured the saint. In addition to this, the\r contemplation of the saint suggested to them a suspicion: such an\r enormity of self-negation and anti-naturalness will not have been\r coveted for not","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3573},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-9","text":"52. In the Jewish \"Old Testament,\" the book of divine justice, there are\r men, things, and sayings on such an immense scale, that Greek and Indian\r literature has nothing to compare with it. One stands with fear and\r reverence before those stupendous remains of what man was formerly, and\r one has sad thoughts about old Asia and its little out-pushed peninsula\r Europe, which would like, by all means, to figure before Asia as the\r \"Progress of Mankind.\" To be sure, he who is himself only a slender,\r tame house-animal, and knows only the wants of a house-animal (like\r our cultured people of today, including the Christians of \"cultured\"\r Christianity), need neither be amazed nor even sad amid th","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3574},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-10","text":"53. Why Atheism nowadays? \"The father\" in God is thoroughly refuted;\r equally so \"the judge,\" \"the rewarder.\" Also his \"free will\": he does\r not hear--and even if he did, he would not know how to help. The worst\r is that he seems incapable of communicating himself clearly; is he\r uncertain?--This is what I have made out (by questioning and listening\r at a variety of conversations) to be the cause of the decline of\r European theism; it appears to me that though the religious instinct is\r in vigorous growth,--it rejects the theistic satisfaction with profound\r distrust.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3575},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-11","text":"54. What does all modern philosophy mainly do? Since Descartes--and\r indeed more in defiance of him than on the basis of his procedure--an\r ATTENTAT has been made on the part of all philosophers on the old\r conception of the soul, under the guise of a criticism of the subject\r and predicate conception--that is to say, an ATTENTAT on the\r fundamental presupposition of Christian doctrine. Modern philosophy,\r as epistemological skepticism, is secretly or openly ANTI-CHRISTIAN,\r although (for keener ears, be it said) by no means anti-religious.\r Formerly, in effect, one believed in \"the soul\" as one believed in\r grammar and the grammatical subject: one said, \"I\" is the condition,\r \"think\" is the","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3576},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-12","text":"55. There is a great ladder of religious cruelty, with many rounds; but\r three of these are the most important. Once on a time men sacrificed\r human beings to their God, and perhaps just those they loved the\r best--to this category belong the firstling sacrifices of all primitive\r religions, and also the sacrifice of the Emperor Tiberius in the\r Mithra-Grotto on the Island of Capri, that most terrible of all Roman\r anachronisms. Then, during the moral epoch of mankind, they sacrificed\r to their God the strongest instincts they possessed, their \"nature\";\r THIS festal joy shines in the cruel glances of ascetics and\r \"anti-natural\" fanatics. Finally, what still remained to be sacrificed?\r Was i","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3577},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-13","text":"56. Whoever, like myself, prompted by some enigmatical desire, has long\r endeavoured to go to the bottom of the question of pessimism and free it\r from the half-Christian, half-German narrowness and stupidity in which\r it has finally presented itself to this century, namely, in the form of\r Schopenhauer's philosophy; whoever, with an Asiatic and super-Asiatic\r eye, has actually looked inside, and into the most world-renouncing of\r all possible modes of thought--beyond good and evil, and no longer\r like Buddha and Schopenhauer, under the dominion and delusion of\r morality,--whoever has done this, has perhaps just thereby, without\r really desiring it, opened his eyes to behold the opposite ide","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3578},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-14","text":"57. The distance, and as it were the space around man, grows with the\r strength of his intellectual vision and insight: his world becomes\r profounder; new stars, new enigmas, and notions are ever coming into\r view. Perhaps everything on which the intellectual eye has exercised\r its acuteness and profundity has just been an occasion for its exercise,\r something of a game, something for children and childish minds. Perhaps\r the most solemn conceptions that have caused the most fighting and\r suffering, the conceptions \"God\" and \"sin,\" will one day seem to us of\r no more importance than a child's plaything or a child's pain seems to\r an old man;--and perhaps another plaything and another pain wi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3579},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-15","text":"58. Has it been observed to what extent outward idleness, or\r semi-idleness, is necessary to a real religious life (alike for its\r favourite microscopic labour of self-examination, and for its soft\r placidity called \"prayer,\" the state of perpetual readiness for the\r \"coming of God\"), I mean the idleness with a good conscience, the\r idleness of olden times and of blood, to which the aristocratic\r sentiment that work is DISHONOURING--that it vulgarizes body and\r soul--is not quite unfamiliar? And that consequently the modern, noisy,\r time-engrossing, conceited, foolishly proud laboriousness educates\r and prepares for \"unbelief\" more than anything else? Among these, for\r instance, who are at p","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3580},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-16","text":"59. Whoever has seen deeply into the world has doubtless divined what\r wisdom there is in the fact that men are superficial. It is their\r preservative instinct which teaches them to be flighty, lightsome, and\r false. Here and there one finds a passionate and exaggerated adoration\r of \"pure forms\" in philosophers as well as in artists: it is not to be\r doubted that whoever has NEED of the cult of the superficial to that\r extent, has at one time or another made an unlucky dive BENEATH it.\r Perhaps there is even an order of rank with respect to those burnt\r children, the born artists who find the enjoyment of life only in trying\r to FALSIFY its image (as if taking wearisome revenge on it), one ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3581},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-17","text":"60. To love mankind FOR GOD'S SAKE--this has so far been the noblest and\r remotest sentiment to which mankind has attained. That love to mankind,\r without any redeeming intention in the background, is only an ADDITIONAL\r folly and brutishness, that the inclination to this love has first to\r get its proportion, its delicacy, its gram of salt and sprinkling\r of ambergris from a higher inclination--whoever first perceived\r and \"experienced\" this, however his tongue may have stammered as it\r attempted to express such a delicate matter, let him for all time be\r holy and respected, as the man who has so far flown highest and gone\r astray in the finest fashion!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3582},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-18","text":"61. The philosopher, as WE free spirits understand him--as the man of\r the greatest responsibility, who has the conscience for the general\r development of mankind,--will use religion for his disciplining and\r educating work, just as he will use the contemporary political\r and economic conditions. The selecting and disciplining\r influence--destructive, as well as creative and fashioning--which can be\r exercised by means of religion is manifold and varied, according to the\r sort of people placed under its spell and protection. For those who are\r strong and independent, destined and trained to command, in whom the\r judgment and skill of a ruling race is incorporated, religion is\r an additional ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3583},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-9-19","text":"62. To be sure--to make also the bad counter-reckoning against such\r religions, and to bring to light their secret dangers--the cost is\r always excessive and terrible when religions do NOT operate as an\r educational and disciplinary medium in the hands of the philosopher, but\r rule voluntarily and PARAMOUNTLY, when they wish to be the final end,\r and not a means along with other means. Among men, as among all other\r animals, there is a surplus of defective, diseased, degenerating,\r infirm, and necessarily suffering individuals; the successful cases,\r among men also, are always the exception; and in view of the fact that\r man is THE ANIMAL NOT YET PROPERLY ADAPTED TO HIS ENVIRONMENT, the rare","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3584},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-1","text":"63. He who is a thorough teacher takes things seriously--and even\r himself--only in relation to his pupils.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3585},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-2","text":"64. \"Knowledge for its own sake\"--that is the last snare laid by\r morality: we are thereby completely entangled in morals once more.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3586},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-3","text":"65. The charm of knowledge would be small, were it not so much shame has\r to be overcome on the way to it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3587},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-4","text":"65A. We are most dishonourable towards our God: he is not PERMITTED to\r sin.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3588},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-5","text":"66. The tendency of a person to allow himself to be degraded, robbed,\r deceived, and exploited might be the diffidence of a God among men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3589},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-6","text":"67. Love to one only is a barbarity, for it is exercised at the expense\r of all others. Love to God also!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3590},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-7","text":"68. \"I did that,\" says my memory. \"I could not have done that,\" says my\r pride, and remains inexorable. Eventually--the memory yields.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3591},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-8","text":"69. One has regarded life carelessly, if one has failed to see the hand\r that--kills with leniency.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3592},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-9","text":"70. If a man has character, he has also his typical experience, which\r always recurs.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3593},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-10","text":"71. THE SAGE AS ASTRONOMER.--So long as thou feelest the stars as an\r \"above thee,\" thou lackest the eye of the discerning one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3594},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-11","text":"72. It is not the strength, but the duration of great sentiments that\r makes great men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3595},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-12","text":"73. He who attains his ideal, precisely thereby surpasses it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3596},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-13","text":"73A. Many a peacock hides his tail from every eye--and calls it his\r pride.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3597},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-14","text":"74. A man of genius is unbearable, unless he possess at least two things\r besides: gratitude and purity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3598},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-15","text":"75. The degree and nature of a man's sensuality extends to the highest\r altitudes of his spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3599},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-16","text":"76. Under peaceful conditions the militant man attacks himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3600},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-17","text":"77. With his principles a man seeks either to dominate, or justify,\r or honour, or reproach, or conceal his habits: two men with the same\r principles probably seek fundamentally different ends therewith.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3601},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-18","text":"78. He who despises himself, nevertheless esteems himself thereby, as a\r despiser.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3602},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-19","text":"79. A soul which knows that it is loved, but does not itself love,\r betrays its sediment: its dregs come up.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3603},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-20","text":"80. A thing that is explained ceases to concern us--What did the God\r mean who gave the advice, \"Know thyself!\" Did it perhaps imply \"Cease to\r be concerned about thyself! become objective!\"--And Socrates?--And the\r \"scientific man\"?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3604},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-21","text":"81. It is terrible to die of thirst at sea. Is it necessary that you\r should so salt your truth that it will no longer--quench thirst?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3605},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-22","text":"82. \"Sympathy for all\"--would be harshness and tyranny for THEE, my good\r neighbour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3606},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-23","text":"83. INSTINCT--When the house is on fire one forgets even the\r dinner--Yes, but one recovers it from among the ashes.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3607},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-24","text":"84. Woman learns how to hate in proportion as she--forgets how to charm.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3608},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-25","text":"85. The same emotions are in man and woman, but in different TEMPO, on\r that account man and woman never cease to misunderstand each other.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3609},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-26","text":"86. In the background of all their personal vanity, women themselves\r have still their impersonal scorn--for \"woman\".","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3610},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-27","text":"87. FETTERED HEART, FREE SPIRIT--When one firmly fetters one's heart\r and keeps it prisoner, one can allow one's spirit many liberties: I said\r this once before But people do not believe it when I say so, unless they\r know it already.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3611},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-28","text":"88. One begins to distrust very clever persons when they become\r embarrassed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3612},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-29","text":"89. Dreadful experiences raise the question whether he who experiences\r them is not something dreadful also.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3613},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-30","text":"90. Heavy, melancholy men turn lighter, and come temporarily to their\r surface, precisely by that which makes others heavy--by hatred and love.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3614},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-31","text":"91. So cold, so icy, that one burns one's finger at the touch of him!\r Every hand that lays hold of him shrinks back!--And for that very reason\r many think him red-hot.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3615},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-32","text":"92. Who has not, at one time or another--sacrificed himself for the sake\r of his good name?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3616},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-33","text":"93. In affability there is no hatred of men, but precisely on that\r account a great deal too much contempt of men.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3617},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-34","text":"94. The maturity of man--that means, to have reacquired the seriousness\r that one had as a child at play.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3618},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-35","text":"95. To be ashamed of one's immorality is a step on the ladder at the end\r of which one is ashamed also of one's morality.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3619},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-36","text":"96. One should part from life as Ulysses parted from Nausicaa--blessing\r it rather than in love with it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3620},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-37","text":"97. What? A great man? I always see merely the play-actor of his own\r ideal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3621},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-38","text":"98. When one trains one's conscience, it kisses one while it bites.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3622},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-39","text":"99. THE DISAPPOINTED ONE SPEAKS--\"I listened for the echo and I heard\r only praise.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3623},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-40","text":"100. We all feign to ourselves that we are simpler than we are, we thus\r relax ourselves away from our fellows.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3624},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-41","text":"101. A discerning one might easily regard himself at present as the\r animalization of God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3625},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-42","text":"102. Discovering reciprocal love should really disenchant the lover with\r regard to the beloved. \"What! She is modest enough to love even you? Or\r stupid enough? Or--or---\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3626},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-43","text":"103. THE DANGER IN HAPPINESS.--\"Everything now turns out best for me, I\r now love every fate:--who would like to be my fate?\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3627},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-44","text":"104. Not their love of humanity, but the impotence of their love,\r prevents the Christians of today--burning us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3628},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-45","text":"105. The pia fraus is still more repugnant to the taste (the \"piety\")\r of the free spirit (the \"pious man of knowledge\") than the impia fraus.\r Hence the profound lack of judgment, in comparison with the Church,\r characteristic of the type \"free spirit\"--as ITS non-freedom.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3629},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-46","text":"107. A sign of strong character, when once the resolution has been\r taken, to shut the ear even to the best counter-arguments. Occasionally,\r therefore, a will to stupidity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3630},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-47","text":"108. There is no such thing as moral phenomena, but only a moral\r interpretation of phenomena.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3631},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-48","text":"109. The criminal is often enough not equal to his deed: he extenuates\r and maligns it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3632},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-49","text":"110. The advocates of a criminal are seldom artists enough to turn the\r beautiful terribleness of the deed to the advantage of the doer.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3633},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-50","text":"111. Our vanity is most difficult to wound just when our pride has been\r wounded.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3634},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-51","text":"112. To him who feels himself preordained to contemplation and not to\r belief, all believers are too noisy and obtrusive; he guards against\r them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3635},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-52","text":"113. \"You want to prepossess him in your favour? Then you must be\r embarrassed before him.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3636},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-53","text":"114. The immense expectation with regard to sexual love, and the coyness\r in this expectation, spoils all the perspectives of women at the outset.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3637},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-54","text":"115. Where there is neither love nor hatred in the game, woman's play is\r mediocre.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3638},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-55","text":"116. The great epochs of our life are at the points when we gain courage\r to rebaptize our badness as the best in us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3639},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-56","text":"117. The will to overcome an emotion, is ultimately only the will of\r another, or of several other, emotions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3640},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-57","text":"118. There is an innocence of admiration: it is possessed by him to whom\r it has not yet occurred that he himself may be admired some day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3641},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-58","text":"119. Our loathing of dirt may be so great as to prevent our cleaning\r ourselves--\"justifying\" ourselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3642},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-59","text":"120. Sensuality often forces the growth of love too much, so that its\r root remains weak, and is easily torn up.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3643},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-60","text":"121. It is a curious thing that God learned Greek when he wished to turn\r author--and that he did not learn it better.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3644},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-61","text":"122. To rejoice on account of praise is in many cases merely politeness\r of heart--and the very opposite of vanity of spirit.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3645},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-62","text":"124. He who exults at the stake, does not triumph over pain, but because\r of the fact that he does not feel pain where he expected it. A parable.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3646},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-63","text":"125. When we have to change an opinion about any one, we charge heavily\r to his account the inconvenience he thereby causes us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3647},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-64","text":"126. A nation is a detour of nature to arrive at six or seven great\r men.--Yes, and then to get round them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3648},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-65","text":"127. In the eyes of all true women science is hostile to the sense of\r shame. They feel as if one wished to peep under their skin with it--or\r worse still! under their dress and finery.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3649},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-66","text":"128. The more abstract the truth you wish to teach, the more must you\r allure the senses to it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3650},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-67","text":"129. The devil has the most extensive perspectives for God; on that\r account he keeps so far away from him:--the devil, in effect, as the\r oldest friend of knowledge.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3651},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-68","text":"130. What a person IS begins to betray itself when his talent\r decreases,--when he ceases to show what he CAN do. Talent is also an\r adornment; an adornment is also a concealment.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3652},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-69","text":"131. The sexes deceive themselves about each other: the reason is that\r in reality they honour and love only themselves (or their own ideal, to\r express it more agreeably). Thus man wishes woman to be peaceable: but\r in fact woman is ESSENTIALLY unpeaceable, like the cat, however well she\r may have assumed the peaceable demeanour.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3653},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-70","text":"133. He who cannot find the way to HIS ideal, lives more frivolously and\r shamelessly than the man without an ideal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3654},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-71","text":"134. From the senses originate all trustworthiness, all good conscience,\r all evidence of truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3655},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-72","text":"135. Pharisaism is not a deterioration of the good man; a considerable\r part of it is rather an essential condition of being good.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3656},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-73","text":"136. The one seeks an accoucheur for his thoughts, the other seeks some\r one whom he can assist: a good conversation thus originates.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3657},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-74","text":"137. In intercourse with scholars and artists one readily makes mistakes\r of opposite kinds: in a remarkable scholar one not infrequently finds\r a mediocre man; and often, even in a mediocre artist, one finds a very\r remarkable man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3658},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-75","text":"138. We do the same when awake as when dreaming: we only invent and\r imagine him with whom we have intercourse--and forget it immediately.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3659},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-76","text":"139. In revenge and in love woman is more barbarous than man.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3660},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-77","text":"140. ADVICE AS A RIDDLE.--\"If the band is not to break, bite it\r first--secure to make!\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3661},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-78","text":"141. The belly is the reason why man does not so readily take himself\r for a God.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3662},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-79","text":"142. The chastest utterance I ever heard: \"Dans le veritable amour c'est\r l'ame qui enveloppe le corps.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3663},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-80","text":"143. Our vanity would like what we do best to pass precisely for what is\r most difficult to us.--Concerning the origin of many systems of morals.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3664},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-81","text":"144. When a woman has scholarly inclinations there is generally\r something wrong with her sexual nature. Barrenness itself conduces to a\r certain virility of taste; man, indeed, if I may say so, is \"the barren\r animal.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3665},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-82","text":"145. Comparing man and woman generally, one may say that woman would\r not have the genius for adornment, if she had not the instinct for the\r SECONDARY role.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3666},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-83","text":"146. He who fights with monsters should be careful lest he thereby\r become a monster. And if thou gaze long into an abyss, the abyss will\r also gaze into thee.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3667},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-84","text":"147. From old Florentine novels--moreover, from life: Buona femmina e\r mala femmina vuol bastone.--Sacchetti, Nov. 86.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3668},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-85","text":"148. To seduce their neighbour to a favourable opinion, and afterwards\r to believe implicitly in this opinion of their neighbour--who can do\r this conjuring trick so well as women?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3669},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-86","text":"149. That which an age considers evil is usually an unseasonable echo of\r what was formerly considered good--the atavism of an old ideal.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3670},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-87","text":"150. Around the hero everything becomes a tragedy; around the\r demigod everything becomes a satyr-play; and around God everything\r becomes--what? perhaps a \"world\"?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3671},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-88","text":"151. It is not enough to possess a talent: one must also have your\r permission to possess it;--eh, my friends?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3672},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-89","text":"152. \"Where there is the tree of knowledge, there is always Paradise\":\r so say the most ancient and the most modern serpents.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3673},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-90","text":"153. What is done out of love always takes place beyond good and evil.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3674},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-91","text":"154. Objection, evasion, joyous distrust, and love of irony are signs of\r health; everything absolute belongs to pathology.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3675},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-92","text":"155. The sense of the tragic increases and declines with sensuousness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3676},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-93","text":"156. Insanity in individuals is something rare--but in groups, parties,\r nations, and epochs it is the rule.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3677},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-94","text":"157. The thought of suicide is a great consolation: by means of it one\r gets successfully through many a bad night.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3678},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-95","text":"158. Not only our reason, but also our conscience, truckles to our\r strongest impulse--the tyrant in us.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3679},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-96","text":"159. One MUST repay good and ill; but why just to the person who did us\r good or ill?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3680},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-97","text":"160. One no longer loves one's knowledge sufficiently after one has\r communicated it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3681},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-98","text":"161. Poets act shamelessly towards their experiences: they exploit them.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3682},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-99","text":"162. \"Our fellow-creature is not our neighbour, but our neighbour's\r neighbour\":--so thinks every nation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3683},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-100","text":"163. Love brings to light the noble and hidden qualities of a lover--his\r rare and exceptional traits: it is thus liable to be deceptive as to his\r normal character.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3684},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-101","text":"164. Jesus said to his Jews: \"The law was for servants;--love God as I\r love him, as his Son! What have we Sons of God to do with morals!\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3685},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-102","text":"165. IN SIGHT OF EVERY PARTY.--A shepherd has always need of a\r bell-wether--or he has himself to be a wether occasionally.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3686},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-103","text":"166. One may indeed lie with the mouth; but with the accompanying\r grimace one nevertheless tells the truth.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3687},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-104","text":"167. To vigorous men intimacy is a matter of shame--and something\r precious.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3688},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-105","text":"168. Christianity gave Eros poison to drink; he did not die of it,\r certainly, but degenerated to Vice.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3689},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-106","text":"169. To talk much about oneself may also be a means of concealing\r oneself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3690},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-107","text":"171. Pity has an almost ludicrous effect on a man of knowledge, like\r tender hands on a Cyclops.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3691},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-108","text":"172. One occasionally embraces some one or other, out of love to mankind\r (because one cannot embrace all); but this is what one must never\r confess to the individual.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3692},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-109","text":"173. One does not hate as long as one disesteems, but only when one\r esteems equal or superior.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3693},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-110","text":"174. Ye Utilitarians--ye, too, love the UTILE only as a VEHICLE for\r your inclinations,--ye, too, really find the noise of its wheels\r insupportable!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3694},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-111","text":"175. One loves ultimately one's desires, not the thing desired.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3695},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-112","text":"176. The vanity of others is only counter to our taste when it is\r counter to our vanity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3696},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-113","text":"177. With regard to what \"truthfulness\" is, perhaps nobody has ever been\r sufficiently truthful.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3697},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-114","text":"178. One does not believe in the follies of clever men: what a\r forfeiture of the rights of man!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3698},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-115","text":"179. The consequences of our actions seize us by the forelock, very\r indifferent to the fact that we have meanwhile \"reformed.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3699},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-116","text":"180. There is an innocence in lying which is the sign of good faith in a\r cause.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3700},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-117","text":"182. The familiarity of superiors embitters one, because it may not be\r returned.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3701},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-118","text":"183. \"I am affected, not because you have deceived me, but because I can\r no longer believe in you.\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3702},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-119","text":"184. There is a haughtiness of kindness which has the appearance of\r wickedness.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3703},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-10-120","text":"185. \"I dislike him.\"--Why?--\"I am not a match for him.\"--Did any one\r ever answer so?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3704},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-1","text":"186. The moral sentiment in Europe at present is perhaps as subtle,\r belated, diverse, sensitive, and refined, as the \"Science of Morals\"\r belonging thereto is recent, initial, awkward, and coarse-fingered:--an\r interesting contrast, which sometimes becomes incarnate and obvious\r in the very person of a moralist. Indeed, the expression, \"Science\r of Morals\" is, in respect to what is designated thereby, far too\r presumptuous and counter to GOOD taste,--which is always a foretaste of\r more modest expressions. One ought to avow with the utmost fairness WHAT\r is still necessary here for a long time, WHAT is alone proper for the\r present: namely, the collection of material, the comprehensive surv","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3705},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-2","text":"187. Apart from the value of such assertions as \"there is a categorical\r imperative in us,\" one can always ask: What does such an assertion\r indicate about him who makes it? There are systems of morals which are\r meant to justify their author in the eyes of other people; other systems\r of morals are meant to tranquilize him, and make him self-satisfied;\r with other systems he wants to crucify and humble himself, with others\r he wishes to take revenge, with others to conceal himself, with others\r to glorify himself and gave superiority and distinction,--this system of\r morals helps its author to forget, that system makes him, or something\r of him, forgotten, many a moralist would like to exer","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3706},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-3","text":"188. In contrast to laisser-aller, every system of morals is a sort of\r tyranny against \"nature\" and also against \"reason\", that is, however, no\r objection, unless one should again decree by some system of morals, that\r all kinds of tyranny and unreasonableness are unlawful What is\r essential and invaluable in every system of morals, is that it is a\r long constraint. In order to understand Stoicism, or Port Royal,\r or Puritanism, one should remember the constraint under which every\r language has attained to strength and freedom--the metrical constraint,\r the tyranny of rhyme and rhythm. How much trouble have the poets and\r orators of every nation given themselves!--not excepting some of\r the","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3707},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-4","text":"189. Industrious races find it a great hardship to be idle: it was a\r master stroke of ENGLISH instinct to hallow and begloom Sunday to such\r an extent that the Englishman unconsciously hankers for his week--and\r work-day again:--as a kind of cleverly devised, cleverly intercalated\r FAST, such as is also frequently found in the ancient world (although,\r as is appropriate in southern nations, not precisely with respect\r to work). Many kinds of fasts are necessary; and wherever powerful\r influences and habits prevail, legislators have to see that intercalary\r days are appointed, on which such impulses are fettered, and learn to\r hunger anew. Viewed from a higher standpoint, whole generations a","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3708},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-5","text":"190. There is something in the morality of Plato which does not really\r belong to Plato, but which only appears in his philosophy, one might\r say, in spite of him: namely, Socratism, for which he himself was\r too noble. \"No one desires to injure himself, hence all evil is done\r unwittingly. The evil man inflicts injury on himself; he would not do\r so, however, if he knew that evil is evil. The evil man, therefore, is\r only evil through error; if one free him from error one will necessarily\r make him--good.\"--This mode of reasoning savours of the POPULACE, who\r perceive only the unpleasant consequences of evil-doing, and practically\r judge that \"it is STUPID to do wrong\"; while they accept \"g","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3709},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-6","text":"191. The old theological problem of \"Faith\" and \"Knowledge,\" or more\r plainly, of instinct and reason--the question whether, in respect to the\r valuation of things, instinct deserves more authority than rationality,\r which wants to appreciate and act according to motives, according to\r a \"Why,\" that is to say, in conformity to purpose and utility--it\r is always the old moral problem that first appeared in the person of\r Socrates, and had divided men's minds long before Christianity. Socrates\r himself, following, of course, the taste of his talent--that of a\r surpassing dialectician--took first the side of reason; and, in fact,\r what did he do all his life but laugh at the awkward incapacity ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3710},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-7","text":"192. Whoever has followed the history of a single science, finds in\r its development a clue to the understanding of the oldest and commonest\r processes of all \"knowledge and cognizance\": there, as here, the\r premature hypotheses, the fictions, the good stupid will to \"belief,\"\r and the lack of distrust and patience are first developed--our senses\r learn late, and never learn completely, to be subtle, reliable, and\r cautious organs of knowledge. Our eyes find it easier on a given\r occasion to produce a picture already often produced, than to seize upon\r the divergence and novelty of an impression: the latter requires more\r force, more \"morality.\" It is difficult and painful for the ear to\r li","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3711},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-8","text":"193. Quidquid luce fuit, tenebris agit: but also contrariwise. What we\r experience in dreams, provided we experience it often, pertains at\r last just as much to the general belongings of our soul as anything\r \"actually\" experienced; by virtue thereof we are richer or poorer, we\r have a requirement more or less, and finally, in broad daylight, and\r even in the brightest moments of our waking life, we are ruled to some\r extent by the nature of our dreams. Supposing that someone has often\r flown in his dreams, and that at last, as soon as he dreams, he is\r conscious of the power and art of flying as his privilege and his\r peculiarly enviable happiness; such a person, who believes that on the\r s","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3712},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-9","text":"194. The difference among men does not manifest itself only in the\r difference of their lists of desirable things--in their regarding\r different good things as worth striving for, and being disagreed as to\r the greater or less value, the order of rank, of the commonly recognized\r desirable things:--it manifests itself much more in what they regard as\r actually HAVING and POSSESSING a desirable thing. As regards a woman,\r for instance, the control over her body and her sexual gratification\r serves as an amply sufficient sign of ownership and possession to the\r more modest man; another with a more suspicious and ambitious thirst for\r possession, sees the \"questionableness,\" the mere apparentne","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3713},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-10","text":"195. The Jews--a people \"born for slavery,\" as Tacitus and the whole\r ancient world say of them; \"the chosen people among the nations,\" as\r they themselves say and believe--the Jews performed the miracle of the\r inversion of valuations, by means of which life on earth obtained a new\r and dangerous charm for a couple of millenniums. Their prophets fused\r into one the expressions \"rich,\" \"godless,\" \"wicked,\" \"violent,\"\r \"sensual,\" and for the first time coined the word \"world\" as a term of\r reproach. In this inversion of valuations (in which is also included\r the use of the word \"poor\" as synonymous with \"saint\" and \"friend\") the\r significance of the Jewish people is to be found; it is with TH","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3714},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-11","text":"196. It is to be INFERRED that there are countless dark bodies near the\r sun--such as we shall never see. Among ourselves, this is an allegory;\r and the psychologist of morals reads the whole star-writing merely as an\r allegorical and symbolic language in which much may be unexpressed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3715},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-12","text":"197. The beast of prey and the man of prey (for instance, Caesar Borgia)\r are fundamentally misunderstood, \"nature\" is misunderstood, so long as\r one seeks a \"morbidness\" in the constitution of these healthiest of\r all tropical monsters and growths, or even an innate \"hell\" in them--as\r almost all moralists have done hitherto. Does it not seem that there is\r a hatred of the virgin forest and of the tropics among moralists? And\r that the \"tropical man\" must be discredited at all costs, whether\r as disease and deterioration of mankind, or as his own hell and\r self-torture? And why? In favour of the \"temperate zones\"? In favour\r of the temperate men? The \"moral\"? The mediocre?--This for the cha","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3716},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-13","text":"198. All the systems of morals which address themselves with a view to\r their \"happiness,\" as it is called--what else are they but suggestions\r for behaviour adapted to the degree of DANGER from themselves in which\r the individuals live; recipes for their passions, their good and bad\r propensities, insofar as such have the Will to Power and would like\r to play the master; small and great expediencies and elaborations,\r permeated with the musty odour of old family medicines and old-wife\r wisdom; all of them grotesque and absurd in their form--because\r they address themselves to \"all,\" because they generalize where\r generalization is not authorized; all of them speaking unconditionally,\r and t","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3717},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-14","text":"199. Inasmuch as in all ages, as long as mankind has existed, there have\r also been human herds (family alliances, communities, tribes, peoples,\r states, churches), and always a great number who obey in proportion\r to the small number who command--in view, therefore, of the fact that\r obedience has been most practiced and fostered among mankind hitherto,\r one may reasonably suppose that, generally speaking, the need thereof is\r now innate in every one, as a kind of FORMAL CONSCIENCE which gives\r the command \"Thou shalt unconditionally do something, unconditionally\r refrain from something\", in short, \"Thou shalt\". This need tries to\r satisfy itself and to fill its form with a content, accordi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3718},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-15","text":"200. The man of an age of dissolution which mixes the races with\r one another, who has the inheritance of a diversified descent in his\r body--that is to say, contrary, and often not only contrary, instincts\r and standards of value, which struggle with one another and are seldom\r at peace--such a man of late culture and broken lights, will, on an\r average, be a weak man. His fundamental desire is that the war which is\r IN HIM should come to an end; happiness appears to him in the character\r of a soothing medicine and mode of thought (for instance, Epicurean\r or Christian); it is above all things the happiness of repose, of\r undisturbedness, of repletion, of final unity--it is the \"Sabbath of\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3719},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-16","text":"201. As long as the utility which determines moral estimates is only\r gregarious utility, as long as the preservation of the community is only\r kept in view, and the immoral is sought precisely and exclusively in\r what seems dangerous to the maintenance of the community, there can be\r no \"morality of love to one's neighbour.\" Granted even that there is\r already a little constant exercise of consideration, sympathy, fairness,\r gentleness, and mutual assistance, granted that even in this condition\r of society all those instincts are already active which are latterly\r distinguished by honourable names as \"virtues,\" and eventually almost\r coincide with the conception \"morality\": in that period t","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3720},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-17","text":"202. Let us at once say again what we have already said a hundred\r times, for people's ears nowadays are unwilling to hear such truths--OUR\r truths. We know well enough how offensive it sounds when any one\r plainly, and without metaphor, counts man among the animals, but it will\r be accounted to us almost a CRIME, that it is precisely in respect to\r men of \"modern ideas\" that we have constantly applied the terms \"herd,\"\r \"herd-instincts,\" and such like expressions. What avail is it? We cannot\r do otherwise, for it is precisely here that our new insight is. We\r have found that in all the principal moral judgments, Europe has become\r unanimous, including likewise the countries where European i","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3721},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-11-18","text":"203. We, who hold a different belief--we, who regard the democratic\r movement, not only as a degenerating form of political organization, but\r as equivalent to a degenerating, a waning type of man, as involving his\r mediocrising and depreciation: where have WE to fix our hopes? In\r NEW PHILOSOPHERS--there is no other alternative: in minds strong and\r original enough to initiate opposite estimates of value, to transvalue\r and invert \"eternal valuations\"; in forerunners, in men of the future,\r who in the present shall fix the constraints and fasten the knots which\r will compel millenniums to take NEW paths. To teach man the future\r of humanity as his WILL, as depending on human will, and to ma","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3722},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-1","text":"204. At the risk that moralizing may also reveal itself here as that\r which it has always been--namely, resolutely MONTRER SES PLAIES,\r according to Balzac--I would venture to protest against an improper and\r injurious alteration of rank, which quite unnoticed, and as if with the\r best conscience, threatens nowadays to establish itself in the relations\r of science and philosophy. I mean to say that one must have the right\r out of one's own EXPERIENCE--experience, as it seems to me, always\r implies unfortunate experience?--to treat of such an important question\r of rank, so as not to speak of colour like the blind, or AGAINST science\r like women and artists (\"Ah! this dreadful science!\" sigh ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3723},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-2","text":"205. The dangers that beset the evolution of the philosopher are, in\r fact, so manifold nowadays, that one might doubt whether this fruit\r could still come to maturity. The extent and towering structure of the\r sciences have increased enormously, and therewith also the probability\r that the philosopher will grow tired even as a learner, or will attach\r himself somewhere and \"specialize\" so that he will no longer attain to\r his elevation, that is to say, to his superspection, his circumspection,\r and his DESPECTION. Or he gets aloft too late, when the best of his\r maturity and strength is past, or when he is impaired, coarsened, and\r deteriorated, so that his view, his general estimate of thi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3724},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-3","text":"206. In relation to the genius, that is to say, a being who either\r ENGENDERS or PRODUCES--both words understood in their fullest sense--the\r man of learning, the scientific average man, has always something of\r the old maid about him; for, like her, he is not conversant with the two\r principal functions of man. To both, of course, to the scholar and\r to the old maid, one concedes respectability, as if by way of\r indemnification--in these cases one emphasizes the respectability--and\r yet, in the compulsion of this concession, one has the same admixture\r of vexation. Let us examine more closely: what is the scientific man?\r Firstly, a commonplace type of man, with commonplace virtues: that is","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3725},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-4","text":"207. However gratefully one may welcome the OBJECTIVE spirit--and\r who has not been sick to death of all subjectivity and its confounded\r IPSISIMOSITY!--in the end, however, one must learn caution even with\r regard to one's gratitude, and put a stop to the exaggeration with\r which the unselfing and depersonalizing of the spirit has recently been\r celebrated, as if it were the goal in itself, as if it were salvation\r and glorification--as is especially accustomed to happen in the\r pessimist school, which has also in its turn good reasons for paying the\r highest honours to \"disinterested knowledge\" The objective man, who no\r longer curses and scolds like the pessimist, the IDEAL man of learnin","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3726},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-5","text":"208. When a philosopher nowadays makes known that he is not a skeptic--I\r hope that has been gathered from the foregoing description of the\r objective spirit?--people all hear it impatiently; they regard him on\r that account with some apprehension, they would like to ask so many,\r many questions... indeed among timid hearers, of whom there are now so\r many, he is henceforth said to be dangerous. With his repudiation of\r skepticism, it seems to them as if they heard some evil-threatening\r sound in the distance, as if a new kind of explosive were being tried\r somewhere, a dynamite of the spirit, perhaps a newly discovered Russian\r NIHILINE, a pessimism BONAE VOLUNTATIS, that not only denies, m","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3727},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-6","text":"209. As to how far the new warlike age on which we Europeans have\r evidently entered may perhaps favour the growth of another and stronger\r kind of skepticism, I should like to express myself preliminarily\r merely by a parable, which the lovers of German history will already\r understand. That unscrupulous enthusiast for big, handsome grenadiers\r (who, as King of Prussia, brought into being a military and skeptical\r genius--and therewith, in reality, the new and now triumphantly emerged\r type of German), the problematic, crazy father of Frederick the Great,\r had on one point the very knack and lucky grasp of the genius: he knew\r what was then lacking in Germany, the want of which was a hundre","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3728},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-7","text":"210. Supposing, then, that in the picture of the philosophers of the\r future, some trait suggests the question whether they must not perhaps\r be skeptics in the last-mentioned sense, something in them would only be\r designated thereby--and not they themselves. With equal right they might\r call themselves critics, and assuredly they will be men of experiments.\r By the name with which I ventured to baptize them, I have already\r expressly emphasized their attempting and their love of attempting is\r this because, as critics in body and soul, they will love to make use\r of experiments in a new, and perhaps wider and more dangerous sense? In\r their passion for knowledge, will they have to go furth","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3729},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-8","text":"211. I insist upon it that people finally cease confounding\r philosophical workers, and in general scientific men, with\r philosophers--that precisely here one should strictly give \"each his\r own,\" and not give those far too much, these far too little. It may\r be necessary for the education of the real philosopher that he himself\r should have once stood upon all those steps upon which his servants,\r the scientific workers of philosophy, remain standing, and MUST remain\r standing he himself must perhaps have been critic, and dogmatist,\r and historian, and besides, poet, and collector, and traveler, and\r riddle-reader, and moralist, and seer, and \"free spirit,\" and almost\r everything, in order ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3730},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-9","text":"212. It is always more obvious to me that the philosopher, as a man\r INDISPENSABLE for the morrow and the day after the morrow, has ever\r found himself, and HAS BEEN OBLIGED to find himself, in contradiction\r to the day in which he lives; his enemy has always been the ideal of his\r day. Hitherto all those extraordinary furtherers of humanity whom one\r calls philosophers--who rarely regarded themselves as lovers of wisdom,\r but rather as disagreeable fools and dangerous interrogators--have found\r their mission, their hard, involuntary, imperative mission (in the end,\r however, the greatness of their mission), in being the bad conscience of\r their age. In putting the vivisector's knife to the ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3731},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-12-10","text":"213. It is difficult to learn what a philosopher is, because it cannot\r be taught: one must \"know\" it by experience--or one should have the\r pride NOT to know it. The fact that at present people all talk of things\r of which they CANNOT have any experience, is true more especially\r and unfortunately as concerns the philosopher and philosophical\r matters:--the very few know them, are permitted to know them, and\r all popular ideas about them are false. Thus, for instance, the truly\r philosophical combination of a bold, exuberant spirituality which runs\r at presto pace, and a dialectic rigour and necessity which makes no\r false step, is unknown to most thinkers and scholars from their own\r exper","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3732},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-1","text":"214. OUR Virtues?--It is probable that we, too, have still our virtues,\r although naturally they are not those sincere and massive virtues on\r account of which we hold our grandfathers in esteem and also at a little\r distance from us. We Europeans of the day after tomorrow, we firstlings\r of the twentieth century--with all our dangerous curiosity, our\r multifariousness and art of disguising, our mellow and seemingly\r sweetened cruelty in sense and spirit--we shall presumably, IF we must\r have virtues, have those only which have come to agreement with our most\r secret and heartfelt inclinations, with our most ardent requirements:\r well, then, let us look for them in our labyrinths!--where, as","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3733},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-2","text":"215. As in the stellar firmament there are sometimes two suns which\r determine the path of one planet, and in certain cases suns of different\r colours shine around a single planet, now with red light, now with\r green, and then simultaneously illumine and flood it with motley\r colours: so we modern men, owing to the complicated mechanism of our\r \"firmament,\" are determined by DIFFERENT moralities; our actions shine\r alternately in different colours, and are seldom unequivocal--and there\r are often cases, also, in which our actions are MOTLEY-COLOURED.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3734},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-3","text":"216. To love one's enemies? I think that has been well learnt: it takes\r place thousands of times at present on a large and small scale; indeed,\r at times the higher and sublimer thing takes place:--we learn to DESPISE\r when we love, and precisely when we love best; all of it, however,\r unconsciously, without noise, without ostentation, with the shame and\r secrecy of goodness, which forbids the utterance of the pompous word\r and the formula of virtue. Morality as attitude--is opposed to our taste\r nowadays. This is ALSO an advance, as it was an advance in our fathers\r that religion as an attitude finally became opposed to their taste,\r including the enmity and Voltairean bitterness against r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3735},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-4","text":"217. Let us be careful in dealing with those who attach great importance\r to being credited with moral tact and subtlety in moral discernment!\r They never forgive us if they have once made a mistake BEFORE us\r (or even with REGARD to us)--they inevitably become our instinctive\r calumniators and detractors, even when they still remain our\r \"friends.\"--Blessed are the forgetful: for they \"get the better\" even of\r their blunders.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3736},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-5","text":"218. The psychologists of France--and where else are there still\r psychologists nowadays?--have never yet exhausted their bitter and\r manifold enjoyment of the betise bourgeoise, just as though... in\r short, they betray something thereby. Flaubert, for instance, the honest\r citizen of Rouen, neither saw, heard, nor tasted anything else in the\r end; it was his mode of self-torment and refined cruelty. As this is\r growing wearisome, I would now recommend for a change something else\r for a pleasure--namely, the unconscious astuteness with which good, fat,\r honest mediocrity always behaves towards loftier spirits and the tasks\r they have to perform, the subtle, barbed, Jesuitical astuteness, whi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3737},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-6","text":"219. The practice of judging and condemning morally, is the favourite\r revenge of the intellectually shallow on those who are less so, it is\r also a kind of indemnity for their being badly endowed by nature,\r and finally, it is an opportunity for acquiring spirit and BECOMING\r subtle--malice spiritualises. They are glad in their inmost heart that\r there is a standard according to which those who are over-endowed with\r intellectual goods and privileges, are equal to them, they contend for\r the \"equality of all before God,\" and almost NEED the belief in God for\r this purpose. It is among them that the most powerful antagonists of\r atheism are found. If any one were to say to them \"A lofty spir","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3738},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-7","text":"220. Now that the praise of the \"disinterested person\" is so popular\r one must--probably not without some danger--get an idea of WHAT people\r actually take an interest in, and what are the things generally which\r fundamentally and profoundly concern ordinary men--including the\r cultured, even the learned, and perhaps philosophers also, if\r appearances do not deceive. The fact thereby becomes obvious that the\r greater part of what interests and charms higher natures, and more\r refined and fastidious tastes, seems absolutely \"uninteresting\" to\r the average man--if, notwithstanding, he perceive devotion to these\r interests, he calls it desinteresse, and wonders how it is possible to\r act \"disin","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3739},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-8","text":"221. \"It sometimes happens,\" said a moralistic pedant and\r trifle-retailer, \"that I honour and respect an unselfish man: not,\r however, because he is unselfish, but because I think he has a right to\r be useful to another man at his own expense. In short, the question\r is always who HE is, and who THE OTHER is. For instance, in a person\r created and destined for command, self-denial and modest retirement,\r instead of being virtues, would be the waste of virtues: so it seems\r to me. Every system of unegoistic morality which takes itself\r unconditionally and appeals to every one, not only sins against good\r taste, but is also an incentive to sins of omission, an ADDITIONAL\r seduction under the ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3740},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-9","text":"222. Wherever sympathy (fellow-suffering) is preached nowadays--and,\r if I gather rightly, no other religion is any longer preached--let the\r psychologist have his ears open through all the vanity, through all the\r noise which is natural to these preachers (as to all preachers), he will\r hear a hoarse, groaning, genuine note of SELF-CONTEMPT. It belongs\r to the overshadowing and uglifying of Europe, which has been on\r the increase for a century (the first symptoms of which are already\r specified documentarily in a thoughtful letter of Galiani to Madame\r d'Epinay)--IF IT IS NOT REALLY THE CAUSE THEREOF! The man of\r \"modern ideas,\" the conceited ape, is excessively dissatisfied with\r himself--","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3741},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-10","text":"223. The hybrid European--a tolerably ugly plebeian, taken all in\r all--absolutely requires a costume: he needs history as a storeroom\r of costumes. To be sure, he notices that none of the costumes fit him\r properly--he changes and changes. Let us look at the nineteenth century\r with respect to these hasty preferences and changes in its masquerades\r of style, and also with respect to its moments of desperation on account\r of \"nothing suiting\" us. It is in vain to get ourselves up as romantic,\r or classical, or Christian, or Florentine, or barocco, or \"national,\"\r in moribus et artibus: it does not \"clothe us\"! But the \"spirit,\"\r especially the \"historical spirit,\" profits even by this desper","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3742},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-11","text":"224. The historical sense (or the capacity for divining quickly\r the order of rank of the valuations according to which a people, a\r community, or an individual has lived, the \"divining instinct\" for the\r relationships of these valuations, for the relation of the authority\r of the valuations to the authority of the operating forces),--this\r historical sense, which we Europeans claim as our specialty, has come\r to us in the train of the enchanting and mad semi-barbarity into which\r Europe has been plunged by the democratic mingling of classes and\r races--it is only the nineteenth century that has recognized this\r faculty as its sixth sense. Owing to this mingling, the past of every\r form and ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3743},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-12","text":"225. Whether it be hedonism, pessimism, utilitarianism, or eudaemonism,\r all those modes of thinking which measure the worth of things according\r to PLEASURE and PAIN, that is, according to accompanying circumstances\r and secondary considerations, are plausible modes of thought and\r naivetes, which every one conscious of CREATIVE powers and an artist's\r conscience will look down upon with scorn, though not without sympathy.\r Sympathy for you!--to be sure, that is not sympathy as you understand\r it: it is not sympathy for social \"distress,\" for \"society\" with its\r sick and misfortuned, for the hereditarily vicious and defective who lie\r on the ground around us; still less is it sympathy for t","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3744},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-13","text":"226. WE IMMORALISTS.--This world with which WE are concerned, in which\r we have to fear and love, this almost invisible, inaudible world of\r delicate command and delicate obedience, a world of \"almost\" in every\r respect, captious, insidious, sharp, and tender--yes, it is well\r protected from clumsy spectators and familiar curiosity! We are\r woven into a strong net and garment of duties, and CANNOT disengage\r ourselves--precisely here, we are \"men of duty,\" even we! Occasionally,\r it is true, we dance in our \"chains\" and betwixt our \"swords\"; it\r is none the less true that more often we gnash our teeth under the\r circumstances, and are impatient at the secret hardship of our lot. But\r do what","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3745},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-14","text":"227. Honesty, granting that it is the virtue of which we cannot rid\r ourselves, we free spirits--well, we will labour at it with all our\r perversity and love, and not tire of \"perfecting\" ourselves in OUR\r virtue, which alone remains: may its glance some day overspread like\r a gilded, blue, mocking twilight this aging civilization with its dull\r gloomy seriousness! And if, nevertheless, our honesty should one day\r grow weary, and sigh, and stretch its limbs, and find us too hard, and\r would fain have it pleasanter, easier, and gentler, like an agreeable\r vice, let us remain HARD, we latest Stoics, and let us send to its\r help whatever devilry we have in us:--our disgust at the clumsy\r and un","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3746},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-15","text":"228. I hope to be forgiven for discovering that all moral philosophy\r hitherto has been tedious and has belonged to the soporific\r appliances--and that \"virtue,\" in my opinion, has been MORE injured\r by the TEDIOUSNESS of its advocates than by anything else; at the same\r time, however, I would not wish to overlook their general usefulness. It\r is desirable that as few people as possible should reflect upon morals,\r and consequently it is very desirable that morals should not some day\r become interesting! But let us not be afraid! Things still remain today\r as they have always been: I see no one in Europe who has (or DISCLOSES)\r an idea of the fact that philosophizing concerning morals might ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3747},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-16","text":"Hail, ye worthies, barrow-wheeling,\r     \"Longer--better,\" aye revealing,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3748},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-13-17","text":"Stiffer aye in head and knee;\r     Unenraptured, never jesting,\r     Mediocre everlasting,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3749},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-1","text":"229. In these later ages, which may be proud of their humanity, there\r still remains so much fear, so much SUPERSTITION of the fear, of the\r \"cruel wild beast,\" the mastering of which constitutes the very pride of\r these humaner ages--that even obvious truths, as if by the agreement\r of centuries, have long remained unuttered, because they have the\r appearance of helping the finally slain wild beast back to life again.\r I perhaps risk something when I allow such a truth to escape; let\r others capture it again and give it so much \"milk of pious sentiment\"\r [FOOTNOTE: An expression from Schiller's William Tell, Act IV, Scene\r 3.] to drink, that it will lie down quiet and forgotten, in its old\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3750},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-2","text":"230. Perhaps what I have said here about a \"fundamental will of the\r spirit\" may not be understood without further details; I may be allowed\r a word of explanation.--That imperious something which is popularly\r called \"the spirit,\" wishes to be master internally and externally,\r and to feel itself master; it has the will of a multiplicity for a\r simplicity, a binding, taming, imperious, and essentially ruling will.\r Its requirements and capacities here, are the same as those assigned by\r physiologists to everything that lives, grows, and multiplies. The power\r of the spirit to appropriate foreign elements reveals itself in a strong\r tendency to assimilate the new to the old, to simplify the ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3751},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-3","text":"231. Learning alters us, it does what all nourishment does that does not\r merely \"conserve\"--as the physiologist knows. But at the bottom of our\r souls, quite \"down below,\" there is certainly something unteachable,\r a granite of spiritual fate, of predetermined decision and answer to\r predetermined, chosen questions. In each cardinal problem there speaks\r an unchangeable \"I am this\"; a thinker cannot learn anew about man and\r woman, for instance, but can only learn fully--he can only follow to the\r end what is \"fixed\" about them in himself. Occasionally we find certain\r solutions of problems which make strong beliefs for us; perhaps they\r are henceforth called \"convictions.\" Later on--one se","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3752},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-4","text":"232. Woman wishes to be independent, and therefore she begins to\r enlighten men about \"woman as she is\"--THIS is one of the worst\r developments of the general UGLIFYING of Europe. For what must these\r clumsy attempts of feminine scientificality and self-exposure bring\r to light! Woman has so much cause for shame; in woman there is so\r much pedantry, superficiality, schoolmasterliness, petty presumption,\r unbridledness, and indiscretion concealed--study only woman's behaviour\r towards children!--which has really been best restrained and dominated\r hitherto by the FEAR of man. Alas, if ever the \"eternally tedious in\r woman\"--she has plenty of it!--is allowed to venture forth! if she\r begins ra","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3753},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-5","text":"233. It betrays corruption of the instincts--apart from the fact that\r it betrays bad taste--when a woman refers to Madame Roland, or Madame de\r Stael, or Monsieur George Sand, as though something were proved thereby\r in favour of \"woman as she is.\" Among men, these are the three comical\r women as they are--nothing more!--and just the best involuntary\r counter-arguments against feminine emancipation and autonomy.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3754},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-6","text":"234. Stupidity in the kitchen; woman as cook; the terrible\r thoughtlessness with which the feeding of the family and the master of\r the house is managed! Woman does not understand what food means, and she\r insists on being cook! If woman had been a thinking creature, she should\r certainly, as cook for thousands of years, have discovered the most\r important physiological facts, and should likewise have got possession\r of the healing art! Through bad female cooks--through the entire lack\r of reason in the kitchen--the development of mankind has been longest\r retarded and most interfered with: even today matters are very little\r better. A word to High School girls.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3755},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-7","text":"235. There are turns and casts of fancy, there are sentences, little\r handfuls of words, in which a whole culture, a whole society suddenly\r crystallises itself. Among these is the incidental remark of Madame de\r Lambert to her son: \"MON AMI, NE VOUS PERMETTEZ JAMAIS QUE DES FOLIES,\r QUI VOUS FERONT GRAND PLAISIR\"--the motherliest and wisest remark, by\r the way, that was ever addressed to a son.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3756},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-14-8","text":"236. I have no doubt that every noble woman will oppose what Dante and\r Goethe believed about woman--the former when he sang, \"ELLA GUARDAVA\r SUSO, ED IO IN LEI,\" and the latter when he interpreted it, \"the\r eternally feminine draws us ALOFT\"; for THIS is just what she believes\r of the eternally masculine.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3757},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-1","text":"Sombre garb and silence meet: Dress for every dame--discreet.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3758},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-2","text":"Young, a flower-decked cavern home; Old, a dragon thence doth roam.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3759},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-3","text":"Noble title, leg that's fine, Man as well: Oh, were HE mine!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3760},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-4","text":"Speech in brief and sense in mass--Slippery for the jenny-ass!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3761},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-5","text":"237A. Woman has hitherto been treated by men like birds, which, losing\r their way, have come down among them from an elevation: as something\r delicate, fragile, wild, strange, sweet, and animating--but as something\r also which must be cooped up to prevent it flying away.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3762},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-6","text":"238. To be mistaken in the fundamental problem of \"man and woman,\" to\r deny here the profoundest antagonism and the necessity for an eternally\r hostile tension, to dream here perhaps of equal rights, equal\r training, equal claims and obligations: that is a TYPICAL sign of\r shallow-mindedness; and a thinker who has proved himself shallow at\r this dangerous spot--shallow in instinct!--may generally be regarded as\r suspicious, nay more, as betrayed, as discovered; he will probably prove\r too \"short\" for all fundamental questions of life, future as well as\r present, and will be unable to descend into ANY of the depths. On the\r other hand, a man who has depth of spirit as well as of desires, and\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3763},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-15-7","text":"239. The weaker sex has in no previous age been treated with so\r much respect by men as at present--this belongs to the tendency and\r fundamental taste of democracy, in the same way as disrespectfulness to\r old age--what wonder is it that abuse should be immediately made of\r this respect? They want more, they learn to make claims, the tribute\r of respect is at last felt to be well-nigh galling; rivalry for rights,\r indeed actual strife itself, would be preferred: in a word, woman is\r losing modesty. And let us immediately add that she is also losing\r taste. She is unlearning to FEAR man: but the woman who \"unlearns to\r fear\" sacrifices her most womanly instincts. That woman should venture\r f","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3764},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-1","text":"240. I HEARD, once again for the first time, Richard Wagner's overture\r to the Mastersinger: it is a piece of magnificent, gorgeous, heavy,\r latter-day art, which has the pride to presuppose two centuries of music\r as still living, in order that it may be understood:--it is an honour\r to Germans that such a pride did not miscalculate! What flavours\r and forces, what seasons and climes do we not find mingled in it! It\r impresses us at one time as ancient, at another time as foreign, bitter,\r and too modern, it is as arbitrary as it is pompously traditional, it\r is not infrequently roguish, still oftener rough and coarse--it has fire\r and courage, and at the same time the loose, dun-coloured s","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3765},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-2","text":"241. We \"good Europeans,\" we also have hours when we allow ourselves a\r warm-hearted patriotism, a plunge and relapse into old loves and narrow\r views--I have just given an example of it--hours of national excitement,\r of patriotic anguish, and all other sorts of old-fashioned floods of\r sentiment. Duller spirits may perhaps only get done with what confines\r its operations in us to hours and plays itself out in hours--in a\r considerable time: some in half a year, others in half a lifetime,\r according to the speed and strength with which they digest and \"change\r their material.\" Indeed, I could think of sluggish, hesitating races,\r which even in our rapidly moving Europe, would require half a","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3766},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-3","text":"242. Whether we call it \"civilization,\" or \"humanising,\" or \"progress,\"\r which now distinguishes the European, whether we call it simply, without\r praise or blame, by the political formula the DEMOCRATIC movement in\r Europe--behind all the moral and political foregrounds pointed to by\r such formulas, an immense PHYSIOLOGICAL PROCESS goes on, which is ever\r extending the process of the assimilation of Europeans, their\r increasing detachment from the conditions under which, climatically and\r hereditarily, united races originate, their increasing independence of\r every definite milieu, that for centuries would fain inscribe itself\r with equal demands on soul and body,--that is to say, the slow ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3767},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-4","text":"243. I hear with pleasure that our sun is moving rapidly towards the\r constellation Hercules: and I hope that the men on this earth will do\r like the sun. And we foremost, we good Europeans!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3768},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-5","text":"244. There was a time when it was customary to call Germans \"deep\"\r by way of distinction; but now that the most successful type of new\r Germanism is covetous of quite other honours, and perhaps misses\r \"smartness\" in all that has depth, it is almost opportune and patriotic\r to doubt whether we did not formerly deceive ourselves with that\r commendation: in short, whether German depth is not at bottom something\r different and worse--and something from which, thank God, we are on the\r point of successfully ridding ourselves. Let us try, then, to relearn\r with regard to German depth; the only thing necessary for the purpose is\r a little vivisection of the German soul.--The German soul is above ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3769},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-6","text":"245. The \"good old\" time is past, it sang itself out in Mozart--how\r happy are WE that his ROCOCO still speaks to us, that his \"good\r company,\" his tender enthusiasm, his childish delight in the Chinese and\r its flourishes, his courtesy of heart, his longing for the elegant, the\r amorous, the tripping, the tearful, and his belief in the South, can\r still appeal to SOMETHING LEFT in us! Ah, some time or other it will be\r over with it!--but who can doubt that it will be over still sooner with\r the intelligence and taste for Beethoven! For he was only the last echo\r of a break and transition in style, and NOT, like Mozart, the last echo\r of a great European taste which had existed for centuries","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3770},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-7","text":"246. What a torture are books written in German to a reader who has a\r THIRD ear! How indignantly he stands beside the slowly turning swamp\r of sounds without tune and rhythms without dance, which Germans call\r a \"book\"! And even the German who READS books! How lazily, how\r reluctantly, how badly he reads! How many Germans know, and consider it\r obligatory to know, that there is ART in every good sentence--art which\r must be divined, if the sentence is to be understood! If there is a\r misunderstanding about its TEMPO, for instance, the sentence itself\r is misunderstood! That one must not be doubtful about the\r rhythm-determining syllables, that one should feel the breaking of the\r too-rigid ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3771},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-8","text":"247. How little the German style has to do with harmony and with the\r ear, is shown by the fact that precisely our good musicians themselves\r write badly. The German does not read aloud, he does not read for the\r ear, but only with his eyes; he has put his ears away in the drawer for\r the time. In antiquity when a man read--which was seldom enough--he read\r something to himself, and in a loud voice; they were surprised when\r any one read silently, and sought secretly the reason of it. In a\r loud voice: that is to say, with all the swellings, inflections, and\r variations of key and changes of TEMPO, in which the ancient PUBLIC\r world took delight. The laws of the written style were then the s","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3772},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-9","text":"248. There are two kinds of geniuses: one which above all engenders and\r seeks to engender, and another which willingly lets itself be fructified\r and brings forth. And similarly, among the gifted nations, there are\r those on whom the woman's problem of pregnancy has devolved, and the\r secret task of forming, maturing, and perfecting--the Greeks, for\r instance, were a nation of this kind, and so are the French; and others\r which have to fructify and become the cause of new modes of life--like\r the Jews, the Romans, and, in all modesty be it asked: like the\r Germans?--nations tortured and enraptured by unknown fevers and\r irresistibly forced out of themselves, amorous and longing for\r foreign","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3773},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-10","text":"249. Every nation has its own \"Tartuffery,\" and calls that its\r virtue.--One does not know--cannot know, the best that is in one.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3774},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-11","text":"250. What Europe owes to the Jews?--Many things, good and bad, and above\r all one thing of the nature both of the best and the worst: the grand\r style in morality, the fearfulness and majesty of infinite demands, of\r infinite significations, the whole Romanticism and sublimity of moral\r questionableness--and consequently just the most attractive, ensnaring,\r and exquisite element in those iridescences and allurements to life,\r in the aftersheen of which the sky of our European culture, its evening\r sky, now glows--perhaps glows out. For this, we artists among the\r spectators and philosophers, are--grateful to the Jews.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3775},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-12","text":"251. It must be taken into the bargain, if various clouds and\r disturbances--in short, slight attacks of stupidity--pass over the\r spirit of a people that suffers and WANTS to suffer from national\r nervous fever and political ambition: for instance, among present-day\r Germans there is alternately the anti-French folly, the anti-Semitic\r folly, the anti-Polish folly, the Christian-romantic folly, the\r Wagnerian folly, the Teutonic folly, the Prussian folly (just look at\r those poor historians, the Sybels and Treitschkes, and their closely\r bandaged heads), and whatever else these little obscurations of the\r German spirit and conscience may be called. May it be forgiven me that\r I, too, when o","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3776},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-13","text":"252. They are not a philosophical race--the English: Bacon represents an\r ATTACK on the philosophical spirit generally, Hobbes, Hume, and Locke,\r an abasement, and a depreciation of the idea of a \"philosopher\" for more\r than a century. It was AGAINST Hume that Kant uprose and raised himself;\r it was Locke of whom Schelling RIGHTLY said, \"JE MEPRISE LOCKE\"; in the\r struggle against the English mechanical stultification of the world,\r Hegel and Schopenhauer (along with Goethe) were of one accord; the\r two hostile brother-geniuses in philosophy, who pushed in different\r directions towards the opposite poles of German thought, and thereby\r wronged each other as only brothers will do.--What is la","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3777},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-14","text":"253. There are truths which are best recognized by mediocre minds,\r because they are best adapted for them, there are truths which only\r possess charms and seductive power for mediocre spirits:--one is pushed\r to this probably unpleasant conclusion, now that the influence of\r respectable but mediocre Englishmen--I may mention Darwin, John\r Stuart Mill, and Herbert Spencer--begins to gain the ascendancy in the\r middle-class region of European taste. Indeed, who could doubt that it\r is a useful thing for SUCH minds to have the ascendancy for a time? It\r would be an error to consider the highly developed and independently\r soaring minds as specially qualified for determining and collecting many","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3778},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-15","text":"What is called \"modern ideas,\" or \"the ideas of the eighteenth century,\"\r or \"French ideas\"--that, consequently, against which the GERMAN mind\r rose up with profound disgust--is of English origin, there is no doubt\r about it. The French were only the apes and actors of these ideas, their\r best soldiers, and likewise, alas! their first and profoundest VICTIMS;\r for owing to the diabolical Anglomania of \"modern ideas,\" the AME\r FRANCAIS has in the end become so thin and emaciated, that at present\r one recalls its sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, its profound,\r passionate strength, its inventive excellency, almost with disbelief.\r One must, however, maintain this verdict of historical justi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3779},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-16","text":"254. Even at present France is still the seat of the most intellectual\r and refined culture of Europe, it is still the high school of taste; but\r one must know how to find this \"France of taste.\" He who belongs to it\r keeps himself well concealed:--they may be a small number in whom it\r lives and is embodied, besides perhaps being men who do not stand upon\r the strongest legs, in part fatalists, hypochondriacs, invalids, in\r part persons over-indulged, over-refined, such as have the AMBITION to\r conceal themselves.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3780},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-17","text":"They have all something in common: they keep their ears closed in\r presence of the delirious folly and noisy spouting of the democratic\r BOURGEOIS. In fact, a besotted and brutalized France at present sprawls\r in the foreground--it recently celebrated a veritable orgy of bad taste,\r and at the same time of self-admiration, at the funeral of Victor Hugo.\r There is also something else common to them: a predilection to resist\r intellectual Germanizing--and a still greater inability to do so!\r In this France of intellect, which is also a France of pessimism,\r Schopenhauer has perhaps become more at home, and more indigenous than\r he has ever been in Germany; not to speak of Heinrich Heine, who h","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3781},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-18","text":"255. I hold that many precautions should be taken against German music.\r Suppose a person loves the South as I love it--as a great school\r of recovery for the most spiritual and the most sensuous ills, as a\r boundless solar profusion and effulgence which o'erspreads a sovereign\r existence believing in itself--well, such a person will learn to be\r somewhat on his guard against German music, because, in injuring his\r taste anew, it will also injure his health anew. Such a Southerner, a\r Southerner not by origin but by BELIEF, if he should dream of the future\r of music, must also dream of it being freed from the influence of the\r North; and must have in his ears the prelude to a deeper, mightie","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3782},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-19","text":"256. Owing to the morbid estrangement which the nationality-craze has\r induced and still induces among the nations of Europe, owing also to the\r short-sighted and hasty-handed politicians, who with the help of this\r craze, are at present in power, and do not suspect to what extent the\r disintegrating policy they pursue must necessarily be only an interlude\r policy--owing to all this and much else that is altogether unmentionable\r at present, the most unmistakable signs that EUROPE WISHES TO BE ONE,\r are now overlooked, or arbitrarily and falsely misinterpreted. With all\r the more profound and large-minded men of this century, the real general\r tendency of the mysterious labour of their souls","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3783},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-16-20","text":"--Is this our mode?--From German heart came this vexed ululating? From\r German body, this self-lacerating? Is ours this priestly hand-dilation,\r This incense-fuming exaltation? Is ours this faltering, falling,\r shambling, This quite uncertain ding-dong-dangling? This sly\r nun-ogling, Ave-hour-bell ringing, This wholly false enraptured\r heaven-o'erspringing?--Is this our mode?--Think well!--ye still wait for\r admission--For what ye hear is ROME--ROME'S FAITH BY INTUITION!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":3784},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-1","text":"257. EVERY elevation of the type \"man,\" has hitherto been the work of an\r aristocratic society and so it will always be--a society believing in\r a long scale of gradations of rank and differences of worth among human\r beings, and requiring slavery in some form or other. Without the PATHOS\r OF DISTANCE, such as grows out of the incarnated difference of classes,\r out of the constant out-looking and down-looking of the ruling caste on\r subordinates and instruments, and out of their equally constant\r practice of obeying and commanding, of keeping down and keeping at a\r distance--that other more mysterious pathos could never have arisen, the\r longing for an ever new widening of distance within th","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3785},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-2","text":"258. Corruption--as the indication that anarchy threatens to break out\r among the instincts, and that the foundation of the emotions, called\r \"life,\" is convulsed--is something radically different according to\r the organization in which it manifests itself. When, for instance, an\r aristocracy like that of France at the beginning of the Revolution,\r flung away its privileges with sublime disgust and sacrificed itself\r to an excess of its moral sentiments, it was corruption:--it was really\r only the closing act of the corruption which had existed for centuries,\r by virtue of which that aristocracy had abdicated step by step its\r lordly prerogatives and lowered itself to a FUNCTION of royalty (","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3786},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-3","text":"259. To refrain mutually from injury, from violence, from exploitation,\r and put one's will on a par with that of others: this may result in a\r certain rough sense in good conduct among individuals when the necessary\r conditions are given (namely, the actual similarity of the individuals\r in amount of force and degree of worth, and their co-relation within one\r organization). As soon, however, as one wished to take this principle\r more generally, and if possible even as the FUNDAMENTAL PRINCIPLE OF\r SOCIETY, it would immediately disclose what it really is--namely, a Will\r to the DENIAL of life, a principle of dissolution and decay. Here one\r must think profoundly to the very basis and resist","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3787},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-4","text":"260. In a tour through the many finer and coarser moralities which have\r hitherto prevailed or still prevail on the earth, I found certain traits\r recurring regularly together, and connected with one another, until\r finally two primary types revealed themselves to me, and a radical\r distinction was brought to light. There is MASTER-MORALITY and\r SLAVE-MORALITY,--I would at once add, however, that in all higher and\r mixed civilizations, there are also attempts at the reconciliation of\r the two moralities, but one finds still oftener the confusion and\r mutual misunderstanding of them, indeed sometimes their close\r juxtaposition--even in the same man, within one soul. The distinctions\r of moral","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3788},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-5","text":"261. Vanity is one of the things which are perhaps most difficult for\r a noble man to understand: he will be tempted to deny it, where another\r kind of man thinks he sees it self-evidently. The problem for him is\r to represent to his mind beings who seek to arouse a good opinion of\r themselves which they themselves do not possess--and consequently also\r do not \"deserve,\"--and who yet BELIEVE in this good opinion\r afterwards. This seems to him on the one hand such bad taste and so\r self-disrespectful, and on the other hand so grotesquely unreasonable,\r that he would like to consider vanity an exception, and is doubtful\r about it in most cases when it is spoken of. He will say, for\r instance: ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3789},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-6","text":"262. A SPECIES originates, and a type becomes established and strong in\r the long struggle with essentially constant UNFAVOURABLE conditions. On\r the other hand, it is known by the experience of breeders that species\r which receive super-abundant nourishment, and in general a surplus of\r protection and care, immediately tend in the most marked way to develop\r variations, and are fertile in prodigies and monstrosities (also in\r monstrous vices). Now look at an aristocratic commonwealth, say\r an ancient Greek polis, or Venice, as a voluntary or involuntary\r contrivance for the purpose of REARING human beings; there are there men\r beside one another, thrown upon their own resources, who want to","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3790},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-7","text":"263. There is an INSTINCT FOR RANK, which more than anything else is\r already the sign of a HIGH rank; there is a DELIGHT in the NUANCES\r of reverence which leads one to infer noble origin and habits. The\r refinement, goodness, and loftiness of a soul are put to a perilous test\r when something passes by that is of the highest rank, but is not\r yet protected by the awe of authority from obtrusive touches and\r incivilities: something that goes its way like a living touchstone,\r undistinguished, undiscovered, and tentative, perhaps voluntarily veiled\r and disguised. He whose task and practice it is to investigate souls,\r will avail himself of many varieties of this very art to determine the\r ul","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3791},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-8","text":"264. It cannot be effaced from a man's soul what his ancestors have\r preferably and most constantly done: whether they were perhaps diligent\r economizers attached to a desk and a cash-box, modest and citizen-like\r in their desires, modest also in their virtues; or whether they were\r accustomed to commanding from morning till night, fond of rude pleasures\r and probably of still ruder duties and responsibilities; or whether,\r finally, at one time or another, they have sacrificed old privileges of\r birth and possession, in order to live wholly for their faith--for their\r \"God,\"--as men of an inexorable and sensitive conscience, which blushes\r at every compromise. It is quite impossible for a ma","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3792},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-9","text":"265. At the risk of displeasing innocent ears, I submit that egoism\r belongs to the essence of a noble soul, I mean the unalterable belief\r that to a being such as \"we,\" other beings must naturally be in\r subjection, and have to sacrifice themselves. The noble soul accepts the\r fact of his egoism without question, and also without consciousness of\r harshness, constraint, or arbitrariness therein, but rather as something\r that may have its basis in the primary law of things:--if he sought a\r designation for it he would say: \"It is justice itself.\" He acknowledges\r under certain circumstances, which made him hesitate at first, that\r there are other equally privileged ones; as soon as he has se","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3793},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-10","text":"266. \"One can only truly esteem him who does not LOOK OUT FOR\r himself.\"--Goethe to Rath Schlosser.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3794},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-11","text":"267. The Chinese have a proverb which mothers even teach their children:\r \"SIAO-SIN\" (\"MAKE THY HEART SMALL\"). This is the essentially fundamental\r tendency in latter-day civilizations. I have no doubt that an ancient\r Greek, also, would first of all remark the self-dwarfing in us Europeans\r of today--in this respect alone we should immediately be \"distasteful\"\r to him.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3795},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-12","text":"268. What, after all, is ignobleness?--Words are vocal symbols for\r ideas; ideas, however, are more or less definite mental symbols\r for frequently returning and concurring sensations, for groups of\r sensations. It is not sufficient to use the same words in order to\r understand one another: we must also employ the same words for the same\r kind of internal experiences, we must in the end have experiences IN\r COMMON. On this account the people of one nation understand one another\r better than those belonging to different nations, even when they use\r the same language; or rather, when people have lived long together under\r similar conditions (of climate, soil, danger, requirement, toil) there\r ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3796},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-13","text":"269. The more a psychologist--a born, an unavoidable psychologist\r and soul-diviner--turns his attention to the more select cases and\r individuals, the greater is his danger of being suffocated by sympathy:\r he NEEDS sternness and cheerfulness more than any other man. For\r the corruption, the ruination of higher men, of the more unusually\r constituted souls, is in fact, the rule: it is dreadful to have such a\r rule always before one's eyes. The manifold torment of the psychologist\r who has discovered this ruination, who discovers once, and then\r discovers ALMOST repeatedly throughout all history, this universal\r inner \"desperateness\" of higher men, this eternal \"too late!\" in every\r sense--m","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3797},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-14","text":"270. The intellectual haughtiness and loathing of every man who has\r suffered deeply--it almost determines the order of rank HOW deeply men\r can suffer--the chilling certainty, with which he is thoroughly imbued\r and coloured, that by virtue of his suffering he KNOWS MORE than the\r shrewdest and wisest can ever know, that he has been familiar with,\r and \"at home\" in, many distant, dreadful worlds of which \"YOU know\r nothing\"!--this silent intellectual haughtiness of the sufferer, this\r pride of the elect of knowledge, of the \"initiated,\" of the almost\r sacrificed, finds all forms of disguise necessary to protect itself from\r contact with officious and sympathizing hands, and in general from ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3798},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-15","text":"271. That which separates two men most profoundly is a different sense\r and grade of purity. What does it matter about all their honesty and\r reciprocal usefulness, what does it matter about all their mutual\r good-will: the fact still remains--they \"cannot smell each other!\" The\r highest instinct for purity places him who is affected with it in the\r most extraordinary and dangerous isolation, as a saint: for it is just\r holiness--the highest spiritualization of the instinct in question. Any\r kind of cognizance of an indescribable excess in the joy of the bath,\r any kind of ardour or thirst which perpetually impels the soul out\r of night into the morning, and out of gloom, out of \"affliction\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3799},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-16","text":"272. Signs of nobility: never to think of lowering our duties to the\r rank of duties for everybody; to be unwilling to renounce or to share\r our responsibilities; to count our prerogatives, and the exercise of\r them, among our DUTIES.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3800},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-17","text":"273. A man who strives after great things, looks upon every one whom\r he encounters on his way either as a means of advance, or a delay and\r hindrance--or as a temporary resting-place. His peculiar lofty BOUNTY\r to his fellow-men is only possible when he attains his elevation and\r dominates. Impatience, and the consciousness of being always condemned\r to comedy up to that time--for even strife is a comedy, and conceals the\r end, as every means does--spoil all intercourse for him; this kind of\r man is acquainted with solitude, and what is most poisonous in it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3801},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-18","text":"274. THE PROBLEM OF THOSE WHO WAIT.--Happy chances are necessary, and\r many incalculable elements, in order that a higher man in whom the\r solution of a problem is dormant, may yet take action, or \"break forth,\"\r as one might say--at the right moment. On an average it DOES NOT happen;\r and in all corners of the earth there are waiting ones sitting who\r hardly know to what extent they are waiting, and still less that they\r wait in vain. Occasionally, too, the waking call comes too late--the\r chance which gives \"permission\" to take action--when their best youth,\r and strength for action have been used up in sitting still; and how many\r a one, just as he \"sprang up,\" has found with horror that ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3802},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-19","text":"275. He who does not WISH to see the height of a man, looks all the\r more sharply at what is low in him, and in the foreground--and thereby\r betrays himself.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3803},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-20","text":"276. In all kinds of injury and loss the lower and coarser soul is\r better off than the nobler soul: the dangers of the latter must be\r greater, the probability that it will come to grief and perish is in\r fact immense, considering the multiplicity of the conditions of its\r existence.--In a lizard a finger grows again which has been lost; not so\r in man.--","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3804},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-21","text":"277. It is too bad! Always the old story! When a man has finished\r building his house, he finds that he has learnt unawares something\r which he OUGHT absolutely to have known before he--began to build. The\r eternal, fatal \"Too late!\" The melancholia of everything COMPLETED--!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3805},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-22","text":"278.--Wanderer, who art thou? I see thee follow thy path without scorn,\r without love, with unfathomable eyes, wet and sad as a plummet which has\r returned to the light insatiated out of every depth--what did it seek\r down there?--with a bosom that never sighs, with lips that conceal their\r loathing, with a hand which only slowly grasps: who art thou? what\r hast thou done? Rest thee here: this place has hospitality for every\r one--refresh thyself! And whoever thou art, what is it that now pleases\r thee? What will serve to refresh thee? Only name it, whatever I have\r I offer thee! \"To refresh me? To refresh me? Oh, thou prying one,\r what sayest thou! But give me, I pray thee---\" What? what? S","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3806},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-23","text":"279. Men of profound sadness betray themselves when they are happy: they\r have a mode of seizing upon happiness as though they would choke and\r strangle it, out of jealousy--ah, they know only too well that it will\r flee from them!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3807},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-24","text":"280. \"Bad! Bad! What? Does he not--go back?\" Yes! But you misunderstand\r him when you complain about it. He goes back like every one who is about\r to make a great spring.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3808},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-25","text":"281.--\"Will people believe it of me? But I insist that they believe it\r of me: I have always thought very unsatisfactorily of myself and about\r myself, only in very rare cases, only compulsorily, always without\r delight in 'the subject,' ready to digress from 'myself,' and always\r without faith in the result, owing to an unconquerable distrust of the\r POSSIBILITY of self-knowledge, which has led me so far as to feel a\r CONTRADICTIO IN ADJECTO even in the idea of 'direct knowledge' which\r theorists allow themselves:--this matter of fact is almost the most\r certain thing I know about myself. There must be a sort of repugnance\r in me to BELIEVE anything definite about myself.--Is there perhaps\r","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3809},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-26","text":"282.--\"But what has happened to you?\"--\"I do not know,\" he said,\r hesitatingly; \"perhaps the Harpies have flown over my table.\"--It\r sometimes happens nowadays that a gentle, sober, retiring man becomes\r suddenly mad, breaks the plates, upsets the table, shrieks, raves,\r and shocks everybody--and finally withdraws, ashamed, and raging at\r himself--whither? for what purpose? To famish apart? To suffocate with\r his memories?--To him who has the desires of a lofty and dainty soul,\r and only seldom finds his table laid and his food prepared, the danger\r will always be great--nowadays, however, it is extraordinarily so.\r Thrown into the midst of a noisy and plebeian age, with which he does\r not l","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3810},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-27","text":"283. If one wishes to praise at all, it is a delicate and at the\r same time a noble self-control, to praise only where one DOES NOT\r agree--otherwise in fact one would praise oneself, which is contrary\r to good taste:--a self-control, to be sure, which offers excellent\r opportunity and provocation to constant MISUNDERSTANDING. To be able to\r allow oneself this veritable luxury of taste and morality, one must\r not live among intellectual imbeciles, but rather among men whose\r misunderstandings and mistakes amuse by their refinement--or one will\r have to pay dearly for it!--\"He praises me, THEREFORE he acknowledges me\r to be right\"--this asinine method of inference spoils half of the life\r of ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3811},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-28","text":"284. To live in a vast and proud tranquility; always beyond... To have,\r or not to have, one's emotions, one's For and Against, according to\r choice; to lower oneself to them for hours; to SEAT oneself on them as\r upon horses, and often as upon asses:--for one must know how to make\r use of their stupidity as well as of their fire. To conserve one's\r three hundred foregrounds; also one's black spectacles: for there are\r circumstances when nobody must look into our eyes, still less into our\r \"motives.\" And to choose for company that roguish and cheerful vice,\r politeness. And to remain master of one's four virtues, courage,\r insight, sympathy, and solitude. For solitude is a virtue with us, as","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3812},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-29","text":"285. The greatest events and thoughts--the greatest thoughts, however,\r are the greatest events--are longest in being comprehended: the\r generations which are contemporary with them do not EXPERIENCE such\r events--they live past them. Something happens there as in the realm of\r stars. The light of the furthest stars is longest in reaching man; and\r before it has arrived man DENIES--that there are stars there. \"How\r many centuries does a mind require to be understood?\"--that is also a\r standard, one also makes a gradation of rank and an etiquette therewith,\r such as is necessary for mind and for star.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3813},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-30","text":"286. \"Here is the prospect free, the mind exalted.\" [FOOTNOTE: Goethe's\r \"Faust,\" Part II, Act V. The words of Dr. Marianus.]--But there is a\r reverse kind of man, who is also upon a height, and has also a free\r prospect--but looks DOWNWARDS.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3814},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-31","text":"287. What is noble? What does the word \"noble\" still mean for us\r nowadays? How does the noble man betray himself, how is he recognized\r under this heavy overcast sky of the commencing plebeianism, by which\r everything is rendered opaque and leaden?--It is not his actions which\r establish his claim--actions are always ambiguous, always inscrutable;\r neither is it his \"works.\" One finds nowadays among artists and scholars\r plenty of those who betray by their works that a profound longing for\r nobleness impels them; but this very NEED of nobleness is radically\r different from the needs of the noble soul itself, and is in fact the\r eloquent and dangerous sign of the lack thereof. It is not the ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3815},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-32","text":"288. There are men who are unavoidably intellectual, let them turn\r and twist themselves as they will, and hold their hands before their\r treacherous eyes--as though the hand were not a betrayer; it always\r comes out at last that they have something which they hide--namely,\r intellect. One of the subtlest means of deceiving, at least as long as\r possible, and of successfully representing oneself to be stupider\r than one really is--which in everyday life is often as desirable as\r an umbrella,--is called ENTHUSIASM, including what belongs to it, for\r instance, virtue. For as Galiani said, who was obliged to know it: VERTU\r EST ENTHOUSIASME.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3816},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-33","text":"289. In the writings of a recluse one always hears something of the echo\r of the wilderness, something of the murmuring tones and timid vigilance\r of solitude; in his strongest words, even in his cry itself, there\r sounds a new and more dangerous kind of silence, of concealment. He who\r has sat day and night, from year's end to year's end, alone with his\r soul in familiar discord and discourse, he who has become a cave-bear,\r or a treasure-seeker, or a treasure-guardian and dragon in his cave--it\r may be a labyrinth, but can also be a gold-mine--his ideas themselves\r eventually acquire a twilight-colour of their own, and an odour, as much\r of the depth as of the mould, something uncommunicat","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3817},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-34","text":"290. Every deep thinker is more afraid of being understood than of being\r misunderstood. The latter perhaps wounds his vanity; but the former\r wounds his heart, his sympathy, which always says: \"Ah, why would you\r also have as hard a time of it as I have?\"","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3818},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-35","text":"291. Man, a COMPLEX, mendacious, artful, and inscrutable animal, uncanny\r to the other animals by his artifice and sagacity, rather than by his\r strength, has invented the good conscience in order finally to enjoy his\r soul as something SIMPLE; and the whole of morality is a long, audacious\r falsification, by virtue of which generally enjoyment at the sight of\r the soul becomes possible. From this point of view there is perhaps much\r more in the conception of \"art\" than is generally believed.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3819},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-36","text":"292. A philosopher: that is a man who constantly experiences, sees,\r hears, suspects, hopes, and dreams extraordinary things; who is struck\r by his own thoughts as if they came from the outside, from above and\r below, as a species of events and lightning-flashes PECULIAR TO HIM; who\r is perhaps himself a storm pregnant with new lightnings; a portentous\r man, around whom there is always rumbling and mumbling and gaping and\r something uncanny going on. A philosopher: alas, a being who often\r runs away from himself, is often afraid of himself--but whose curiosity\r always makes him \"come to himself\" again.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3820},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-37","text":"293. A man who says: \"I like that, I take it for my own, and mean to\r guard and protect it from every one\"; a man who can conduct a case,\r carry out a resolution, remain true to an opinion, keep hold of a woman,\r punish and overthrow insolence; a man who has his indignation and his\r sword, and to whom the weak, the suffering, the oppressed, and even the\r animals willingly submit and naturally belong; in short, a man who is a\r MASTER by nature--when such a man has sympathy, well! THAT sympathy has\r value! But of what account is the sympathy of those who suffer! Or of\r those even who preach sympathy! There is nowadays, throughout almost the\r whole of Europe, a sickly irritability and sensitive","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3821},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-38","text":"294. THE OLYMPIAN VICE.--Despite the philosopher who, as a genuine\r Englishman, tried to bring laughter into bad repute in all thinking\r minds--\"Laughing is a bad infirmity of human nature, which every\r thinking mind will strive to overcome\" (Hobbes),--I would even\r allow myself to rank philosophers according to the quality of their\r laughing--up to those who are capable of GOLDEN laughter. And supposing\r that Gods also philosophize, which I am strongly inclined to believe,\r owing to many reasons--I have no doubt that they also know how to laugh\r thereby in an overman-like and new fashion--and at the expense of all\r serious things! Gods are fond of ridicule: it seems that they cannot\r refrai","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3822},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-39","text":"295. The genius of the heart, as that great mysterious one possesses\r it, the tempter-god and born rat-catcher of consciences, whose voice can\r descend into the nether-world of every soul, who neither speaks a word\r nor casts a glance in which there may not be some motive or touch\r of allurement, to whose perfection it pertains that he knows how to\r appear,--not as he is, but in a guise which acts as an ADDITIONAL\r constraint on his followers to press ever closer to him, to follow him\r more cordially and thoroughly;--the genius of the heart, which imposes\r silence and attention on everything loud and self-conceited, which\r smoothes rough souls and makes them taste a new longing--to lie placi","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3823},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-17-40","text":"296. Alas! what are you, after all, my written and painted thoughts! Not\r long ago you were so variegated, young and malicious, so full of thorns\r and secret spices, that you made me sneeze and laugh--and now? You\r have already doffed your novelty, and some of you, I fear, are ready\r to become truths, so immortal do they look, so pathetically honest, so\r tedious! And was it ever otherwise? What then do we write and paint,\r we mandarins with Chinese brush, we immortalisers of things which LEND\r themselves to writing, what are we alone capable of painting? Alas, only\r that which is just about to fade and begins to lose its odour! Alas,\r only exhausted and departing storms and belated yellow se","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":3824},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-1","text":"MIDDAY of Life! Oh, season of delight!\r                       My summer's park!\r      Uneaseful joy to look, to lurk, to hark--\r      I peer for friends, am ready day and night,--\r      Where linger ye, my friends? The time is right!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3825},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-2","text":"Is not the glacier's grey today for you\r                          Rose-garlanded?\r      The brooklet seeks you, wind, cloud, with longing thread\r      And thrust themselves yet higher to the blue,\r      To spy for you from farthest eagle's view.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3826},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-3","text":"My table was spread out for you on high--\r                       Who dwelleth so\r      Star-near, so near the grisly pit below?--\r      My realm--what realm hath wider boundary?\r      My honey--who hath sipped its fragrancy?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3827},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-4","text":"Friends, ye are there! Woe me,--yet I am not\r                         He whom ye seek?\r      Ye stare and stop--better your wrath could speak!\r      I am not I? Hand, gait, face, changed? And what\r      I am, to you my friends, now am I not?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3828},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-5","text":"Am I an other? Strange am I to Me?\r                       Yet from Me sprung?\r      A wrestler, by himself too oft self-wrung?\r      Hindering too oft my own self's potency,\r      Wounded and hampered by self-victory?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3829},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-6","text":"I sought where-so the wind blows keenest. There\r                      I learned to dwell\r      Where no man dwells, on lonesome ice-lorn fell,\r      And unlearned Man and God and curse and prayer?\r      Became a ghost haunting the glaciers bare?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3830},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-7","text":"Ye, my old friends! Look! Ye turn pale, filled o'er\r                       With love and fear!\r      Go! Yet not in wrath. Ye could ne'er live here.\r      Here in the farthest realm of ice and scaur,\r      A huntsman must one be, like chamois soar.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3831},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-8","text":"An evil huntsman was I? See how taut\r                     My bow was bent!\r      Strongest was he by whom such bolt were sent--\r      Woe now! That arrow is with peril fraught,\r      Perilous as none.--Have yon safe home ye sought!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3832},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-9","text":"Ye go! Thou didst endure enough, oh, heart;--\r                      Strong was thy hope;\r      Unto new friends thy portals widely ope,\r      Let old ones be. Bid memory depart!\r      Wast thou young then, now--better young thou art!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3833},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-10","text":"What linked us once together, one hope's tie--\r                     (Who now doth con\r      Those lines, now fading, Love once wrote thereon?)--\r      Is like a parchment, which the hand is shy\r      To touch--like crackling leaves, all seared, all dry.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3834},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-11","text":"Oh! Friends no more! They are--what name for those?--\r                            Friends' phantom-flight\r      Knocking at my heart's window-pane at night,\r      Gazing on me, that speaks \"We were\" and goes,--\r      Oh, withered words, once fragrant as the rose!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3835},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-12","text":"Pinings of youth that might not understand!\r                        For which I pined,\r      Which I deemed changed with me, kin of my kind:\r      But they grew old, and thus were doomed and banned:\r      None but new kith are native of my land!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3836},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-13","text":"Midday of life! My second youth's delight!\r                        My summer's park!\r      Unrestful joy to long, to lurk, to hark!\r      I peer for friends!--am ready day and night,\r      For my new friends. Come! Come! The time is right!","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3837},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-14","text":"This song is done,--the sweet sad cry of rue\r                        Sang out its end;\r      A wizard wrought it, he the timely friend,\r      The midday-friend,--no, do not ask me who;\r      At midday 'twas, when one became as two.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3838},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-15","text":"We keep our Feast of Feasts, sure of our bourne,\r                       Our aims self-same:\r      The Guest of Guests, friend Zarathustra, came!\r      The world now laughs, the grisly veil was torn,\r      And Light and Dark were one that wedding-morn.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3839},{"id":"nietzsche-beyond-goo-18-16","text":"End of Project Gutenberg's Beyond Good and Evil, by Friedrich Nietzsche","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — Beyond Good and Evil","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"Beyond Good and Evil","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":3840},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-1","text":"The letter printed below is a translation of Tolstoy's letter written in\r Russian in reply to one from the Editor of Free Hindustan. After having\r passed from hand to hand, this letter at last came into my possession\r through a friend who asked me, as one much interested in Tolstoy's\r writings, whether I thought it worth publishing. I at once replied in\r the affirmative, and told him I should translate it myself into Gujarati\r and induce others' to translate and publish it in various Indian\r vernaculars.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3841},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-2","text":"The letter as received by me was a type-written copy. It was therefore\r referred to the author, who confirmed it as his and kindly granted me\r permission to print it.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3842},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-3","text":"To me, as a humble follower of that great teacher whom I have long\r looked upon as one of my guides, it is a matter of honour to be\r connected with the publication of his letter, such especially as the one\r which is now being given to the world.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3843},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-4","text":"It is a mere statement of fact to say that every Indian, whether he\r owns up to it or not, has national aspirations. But there are as many\r opinions as there are Indian nationalists as to the exact meaning of\r that aspiration, and more especially as to the methods to be used to\r attain the end.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3844},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-5","text":"One of the accepted and 'time-honoured' methods to attain the end\r is that of violence. The assassination of Sir Curzon Wylie was an\r illustration of that method in its worst and most detestable form.\r Tolstoy's life has been devoted to replacing the method of violence for\r removing tyranny or securing reform by the method of non-resistance to\r evil. He would meet hatred expressed in violence by love expressed in\r self-suffering. He admits of no exception to whittle down this great\r and divine law of love. He applies it to all the problems that trouble\r mankind.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3845},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-6","text":"When a man like Tolstoy, one of the clearest thinkers in the western\r world, one of the greatest writers, one who as a soldier has known\r what violence is and what it can do, condemns Japan for having blindly\r followed the law of modern science, falsely so-called, and fears for\r that country 'the greatest calamities', it is for us to pause and\r consider whether, in our impatience of English rule, we do not want to\r replace one evil by another and a worse. India, which is the nursery\r of the great faiths of the world, will cease to be nationalist India,\r whatever else she may become, when she goes through the process of\r civilization in the shape of reproduction on that sacred soil of gun\r fa","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3846},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-7","text":"If we do not want the English in India we must pay the price.\r Tolstoy indicates it. 'Do not resist evil, but also do not yourselves\r participate in evil--in the violent deeds of the administration of the\r law courts, the collection of taxes and, what is more important, of\r the soldiers, and no one in the world will enslave you', passionately\r declares the sage of Yasnaya Polyana. Who can question the truth of\r what he says in the following: 'A commercial company enslaved a\r nation comprising two hundred millions. Tell this to a man free from\r superstition and he will fail to grasp what these words mean. What does\r it mean that thirty thousand people, not athletes, but rather weak and\r ordin","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3847},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-8","text":"One need not accept all that Tolstoy says--some of his facts are not\r accurately stated--to realize the central truth of his indictment of\r the present system, which is to understand and act upon the irresistible\r power of the soul over the body, of love, which is an attribute of the\r soul, over the brute or body force generated by the stirring in us of\r evil passions.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3848},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-3-9","text":"There is no doubt that there is nothing new in what Tolstoy preaches.\r But his presentation of the old truth is refreshingly forceful. His\r logic is unassailable. And above all he endeavours to practise what\r he preaches. He preaches to convince. He is sincere and in earnest. He\r commands attention.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":3849},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-4-1","text":"_All that exists is One. People only call this One by different names._\r THE VEDAS.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3850},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-4-2","text":"_God is love, and he that abideth in love abideth in God, and God\r abideth in him._ I JOHN iv. 16.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3851},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-4-3","text":"_God is one whole; we are the parts._ EXPOSITION OF THE TEACHING OF THE\r VEDAS BY VIVEKANANDA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3852},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-1","text":"Do not seek quiet and rest in those earthly realms where delusions and\r desires are engendered, for if thou dost, thou wilt be dragged through\r the rough wilderness of life, which is far from Me.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3853},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-2","text":"Whenever thou feelest that thy feet are becoming entangled in the\r interlaced roots of life, know that thou has strayed from the path to\r which I beckon thee: for I have placed thee in broad, smooth paths,\r which are strewn with flowers. I have put a light before thee, which\r thou canst follow and thus run without stumbling. KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3854},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-3","text":"I have received your letter and two numbers of your periodical, both of\r which interest me extremely. The oppression of a majority by a minority,\r and the demoralization inevitably resulting from it, is a phenomenon\r that has always occupied me and has done so most particularly of late.\r I will try to explain to you what I think about that subject in general,\r and particularly about the cause from which the dreadful evils of which\r you write in your letter, and in the Hindu periodical you have sent me,\r have arisen and continue to arise.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3855},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-4","text":"The reason for the astonishing fact that a majority of working people\r submit to a handful of idlers who control their labour and their very\r lives is always and everywhere the same--whether the oppressors and\r oppressed are of one race or whether, as in India and elsewhere, the\r oppressors are of a different nation.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3856},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-5","text":"This phenomenon seems particularly strange in India, for there more than\r two hundred million people, highly gifted both physically and mentally,\r find themselves in the power of a small group of people quite alien\r to them in thought, and immeasurably inferior to them in religious\r morality.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3857},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-6","text":"From your letter and the articles in _Free Hindustan_ as well as from\r the very interesting writings of the Hindu Swami Vivekananda and\r others, it appears that, as is the case in our time with the ills of all\r nations, the reason lies in the lack of a reasonable religious teaching\r which by explaining the meaning of life would supply a supreme law for\r the guidance of conduct and would replace the more than dubious precepts\r of pseudo-religion and pseudo-science with the immoral conclusions\r deduced from them and commonly called 'civilization'.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3858},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-7","text":"Your letter, as well as the articles in _Free Hindustan_ and Indian\r political literature generally, shows that most of the leaders of public\r opinion among your people no longer attach any significance to the\r religious teachings that were and are professed by the peoples of India,\r and recognize no possibility of freeing the people from the oppression\r they endure except by adopting the irreligious and profoundly immoral\r social arrangements under which the English and other pseudo-Christian\r nations live to-day.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3859},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-5-8","text":"And yet the chief if not the sole cause of the enslavement of the\r Indian peoples by the English lies in this very absence of a religious\r consciousness and of the guidance for conduct which should flow from\r it--a lack common in our day to all nations East and West, from Japan to\r England and America alike.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":3860},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-6-1","text":"_O ye, who see perplexities over your heads, beneath your feet, and to\r the right and left of you; you will be an eternal enigma unto yourselves\r until ye become humble and joyful as children. Then will ye find Me, and\r having found Me in yourselves, you will rule over worlds, and looking\r out from the great world within to the little world without, you will\r bless everything that is, and find all is well with time and with you._\r KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":3861},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-6-2","text":"To make my thoughts clear to you I must go farther back. We do not,\r cannot, and I venture to say need not, know how men lived millions of\r years ago or even ten thousand years ago, but we do know positively\r that, as far back as we have any knowledge of mankind, it has always\r lived in special groups of families, tribes, and nations in which\r the majority, in the conviction that it must be so, submissively and\r willingly bowed to the rule of one or more persons--that is to a very\r small minority. Despite all varieties of circumstances and personalities\r these relations manifested themselves among the various peoples of\r whose origin we have any knowledge; and the farther back we go the more","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":3862},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-6-3","text":"So it was everywhere. But though this external form of life existed for\r centuries and still exists, very early--thousands of years before\r our time--amid this life based on coercion, one and the same thought\r constantly emerged among different nations, namely, that in every\r individual a spiritual element is manifested that gives life to all that\r exists, and that this spiritual element strives to unite with everything\r of a like nature to itself, and attains this aim through love. This\r thought appeared in most various forms at different times and\r places, with varying completeness and clarity. It found expression in\r Brahmanism, Judaism, Mazdaism (the teachings of Zoroaster), in Buddhism,","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":3863},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-1","text":"_My hand has sowed love everywhere, giving unto all that will receive.\r Blessings are offered unto all My children, but many times in their\r blindness they fail to see them. How few there are who gather the gifts\r which lie in profusion at their feet: how many there are, who, in wilful\r waywardness, turn their eyes away from them and complain with a wail\r that they have not that which I have given them; many of them defiantly\r repudiate not only My gifts, but Me also, Me, the Source of all\r blessings and the Author of their being._ KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3864},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-2","text":"_I tarry awhile from the turmoil and strife of the world. I will\r beautify and quicken thy life with love and with joy, for the light of\r the soul is Love. Where Love is, there is contentment and peace, and\r where there is contentment and peace, there am I, also, in their midst._\r KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3865},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-3","text":"_The aim of the sinless One consists in acting without causing sorrow\r to others, although he could attain to great power by ignoring their\r feelings._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3866},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-4","text":"_The aim of the sinless One lies in not doing evil unto those who have\r done evil unto him._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3867},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-5","text":"_If a man causes suffering even to those who hate him without any\r reason, he will ultimately have grief not to be overcome._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3868},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-6","text":"_The punishment of evil doers consists in making them feel ashamed of\r themselves by doing them a great kindness._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3869},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-7","text":"_Of what use is superior knowledge in the one, if he does not endeavour\r to relieve his neighbour's want as much as his own?_","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3870},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-7-8","text":"_If, in the morning, a man wishes to do evil unto another, in the\r evening the evil will return to him._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":3871},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-8-1","text":"Thus it went on everywhere. The recognition that love represents the\r highest morality was nowhere denied or contradicted, but this truth was\r so interwoven everywhere with all kinds of falsehoods which distorted\r it, that finally nothing of it remained but words. It was taught that\r this highest morality was only applicable to private life--for home\r use, as it were--but that in public life all forms of violence--such as\r imprisonment, executions, and wars--might be used for the protection\r of the majority against a minority of evildoers, though such means were\r diametrically opposed to any vestige of love. And though common sense\r indicated that if some men claim to decide who is to be sub","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3872},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-8-2","text":"For a long time people lived in this obvious contradiction without\r noticing it. But a time arrived when this contradiction became more\r and more evident to thinkers of various nations. And the old and simple\r truth that it is natural for men to help and to love one another, but\r not to torture and to kill one another, became ever clearer, so that\r fewer and fewer people were able to believe the sophistries by which the\r distortion of the truth had been made so plausible.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3873},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-8-3","text":"In former times the chief method of justifying the use of violence and\r thereby infringing the law of love was by claiming a divine right\r for the rulers: the Tsars, Sultans, Rajahs, Shahs, and other heads of\r states. But the longer humanity lived the weaker grew the belief in this\r peculiar, God--given right of the ruler. That belief withered in the\r same way and almost simultaneously in the Christian and the Brahman\r world, as well as in Buddhist and Confucian spheres, and in recent times\r it has so faded away as to prevail no longer against man's reasonable\r understanding and the true religious feeling. People saw more and more\r clearly, and now the majority see quite clearly, the sensele","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":3874},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-9-1","text":"_Children, do you want to know by what your hearts should be guided?\r Throw aside your longings and strivings after that which is null and\r void; get rid of your erroneous thoughts about happiness and wisdom, and\r your empty and insincere desires. Dispense with these and you will know\r Love._ KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3875},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-9-2","text":"_Be not the destroyers of yourselves. Arise to your true Being, and then\r you will have nothing to fear._ KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3876},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-9-3","text":"New justifications have now appeared in place of the antiquated,\r obsolete, religious ones. These new justifications are just as\r inadequate as the old ones, but as they are new their futility cannot\r immediately be recognized by the majority of men. Besides this, those\r who enjoy power propagate these new sophistries and support them so\r skilfully that they seem irrefutable even to many of those who\r suffer from the oppression these theories seek to justify. These new\r justifications are termed 'scientific'. But by the term 'scientific' is\r understood just what was formerly understood by the term 'religious':\r just as formerly everything called 'religious' was held to be\r unquestionable sim","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3877},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-9-4","text":"The third, most important, and unfortunately most widespread\r justification is, at bottom, the age-old religious one just a little\r altered: that in public life the suppression of some for the protection\r of the majority cannot be avoided--so that coercion is unavoidable\r however desirable reliance on love alone might be in human intercourse.\r The only difference in this justification by pseudo-science consists in\r the fact that, to the question why such and such people and not others\r have the right to decide against whom violence may and must be\r used, pseudo-science now gives a different reply to that given by\r religion--which declared that the right to decide was valid because it\r was pr","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3878},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-9-5","text":"Such are the scientific justifications of the principle of coercion.\r They are not merely weak but absolutely invalid, yet they are so much\r needed by those who occupy privileged positions that they believe in\r them as blindly as they formerly believed in the immaculate conception,\r and propagate them just as confidently. And the unfortunate majority of\r men bound to toil is so dazzled by the pomp with which these 'scientific\r truths' are presented, that under this new influence it accepts these\r scientific stupidities for holy truth, just as it formerly accepted\r the pseudo-religious justifications; and it continues to submit to the\r present holders of power who are just as hard-hearted but","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":3879},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-10-1","text":"_Who am I? I am that which thou hast searched for since thy baby eyes\r gazed wonderingly upon the world, whose horizon hides this real life\r from thee. I am that which in thy heart thou hast prayed for, demanded\r as thy birthright, although thou hast not known what it was. I am\r that which has lain in thy soul for hundreds and thousands of years.\r Sometimes I lay in thee grieving because thou didst not recognize me;\r sometimes I raised my head, opened my eyes, and extended my arms calling\r thee either tenderly and quietly, or strenuously, demanding that thou\r shouldst rebel against the iron chains which bound thee to the earth._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":3880},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-1","text":"So matters went on, and still go on, in the Christian world. But we\r might have hope that in the immense Brahman, Buddhist, and Confucian\r worlds this new scientific superstition would not establish itself, and\r that the Chinese, Japanese, and Hindus, once their eyes were opened to\r the religious fraud justifying violence, would advance directly to a\r recognition of the law of love inherent in humanity, and which had\r been so forcibly enunciated by the great Eastern teachers. But what has\r happened is that the scientific superstition replacing the religious one\r has been accepted and secured a stronger and stronger hold in the East.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3881},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-2","text":"In your periodical you set out as the basic principle which should guide\r the actions of your people the maxim that: 'Resistance to aggression is\r not simply justifiable but imperative, nonresistance hurts both Altruism\r and Egotism.'","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3882},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-3","text":"Love is the only way to rescue humanity from all ills, and in it you\r too have the only method of saving your people from enslavement. In very\r ancient times love was proclaimed with special strength and clearness\r among your people to be the religious basis of human life. Love, and\r forcible resistance to evil-doers, involve such a mutual contradiction\r as to destroy utterly the whole sense and meaning of the conception of\r love. And what follows? With a light heart and in the twentieth\r century you, an adherent of a religious people, deny their law, feeling\r convinced of your scientific enlightenment and your right to do so, and\r you repeat (do not take this amiss) the amazing stupidity in","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3883},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-4","text":"You say that the English have enslaved your people and hold them in\r subjection because the latter have not resisted resolutely enough and\r have not met force by force.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3884},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-5","text":"But the case is just the opposite. If the English have enslaved the\r people of India it is just because the latter recognized, and still\r recognize, force as the fundamental principle of the social order. In\r accord with that principle they submitted to their little rajahs, and\r on their behalf struggled against one another, fought the Europeans, the\r English, and are now trying to fight with them again.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3885},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-6","text":"A commercial company enslaved a nation comprising two hundred millions.\r Tell this to a man free from superstition and he will fail to grasp\r what these words mean. What does it mean that thirty thousand men, not\r athletes but rather weak and ordinary people, have subdued two hundred\r million vigorous, clever, capable, and freedom-loving people? Do not the\r figures make it clear that it is not the English who have enslaved the\r Indians, but the Indians who have enslaved themselves?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3886},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-7","text":"When the Indians complain that the English have enslaved them it is as\r if drunkards complained that the spirit-dealers who have settled among\r them have enslaved them. You tell them that they might give up drinking,\r but they reply that they are so accustomed to it that they cannot\r abstain, and that they must have alcohol to keep up their energy. Is it\r not the same thing with the millions of people who submit to thousands'\r or even to hundreds, of others--of their own or other nations?","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3887},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-8","text":"If the people of India are enslaved by violence it is only because they\r themselves live and have lived by violence, and do not recognize the\r eternal law of love inherent in humanity.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3888},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-9","text":"_Pitiful and foolish is the man who seeks what he already has, and does\r not know that he has it. Yes, Pitiful and foolish is he who does not\r know the bliss of love which surrounds him and which I have given him._\r KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3889},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-11-10","text":"As soon as men live entirely in accord with the law of love natural to\r their hearts and now revealed to them, which excludes all resistance\r by violence, and therefore hold aloof from all participation in\r violence--as soon as this happens, not only will hundreds be unable to\r enslave millions, but not even millions will be able to enslave a single\r individual. Do not resist the evil-doer and take no part in doing so,\r either in the violent deeds of the administration, in the law courts,\r the collection of taxes, or above all in soldiering, and no one in the\r world will be able to enslave you.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":3890},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-1","text":"_O ye who sit in bondage and continually seek and pant for freedom, seek\r only for love. Love is peace in itself and peace which gives complete\r satisfaction. I am the key that opens the portal to the rarely\r discovered land where contentment alone is found._ KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3891},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-2","text":"What is now happening to the people of the East as of the West is\r like what happens to every individual when he passes from childhood to\r adolescence and from youth to manhood. He loses what had hitherto guided\r his life and lives without direction, not having found a new standard\r suitable to his age, and so he invents all sorts of occupations, cares,\r distractions, and stupefactions to divert his attention from the misery\r and senselessness of his life. Such a condition may last a long time.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3892},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-3","text":"When an individual passes from one period of life to another a time\r comes when he cannot go on in senseless activity and excitement as\r before, but has to understand that although he has outgrown what before\r used to direct him, this does not mean that he must live without any\r reasonable guidance, but rather that he must formulate for himself an\r understanding of life corresponding to his age, and having elucidated\r it must be guided by it. And in the same way a similar time must come in\r the growth and development of humanity. I believe that such a time has\r now arrived--not in the sense that it has come in the year 1908, but\r that the inherent contradiction of human life has now reached ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3893},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-4","text":"But men can only recognize this truth to its full extent when they\r have completely freed themselves from all religious and scientific\r superstitions and from all the consequent misrepresentations and\r sophistical distortions by which its recognition has been hindered for\r centuries.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3894},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-5","text":"To save a sinking ship it is necessary to throw overboard the ballast,\r which though it may once have been needed would now cause the ship to\r sink. And so it is with the scientific superstition which hides the\r truth of their welfare from mankind. In order that men should embrace\r the truth--not in the vague way they did in childhood, nor in the\r one-sided and perverted way presented to them by their religious and\r scientific teachers, but embrace it as their highest law--the complete\r liberation of this truth from all and every superstition (both\r pseudo-religious and pseudo-scientific) by which it is still obscured\r is essential: not a partial, timid attempt, reckoning with traditions\r sa","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3895},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-12-6","text":"If only people freed themselves from their beliefs in all kinds of\r Ormuzds, Brahmas, Sabbaoths, and their incarnation as Krishnas and\r Christs, from beliefs in Paradises and Hells, in reincarnations and\r resurrections, from belief in the interference of the Gods in the\r external affairs of the universe, and above all, if they freed\r themselves from belief in the infallibility of all the various Vedas,\r Bibles, Gospels, Tripitakas, Korans, and the like, and also freed\r themselves from blind belief in a variety of scientific teachings about\r infinitely small atoms and molecules and in all the infinitely great and\r infinitely remote worlds, their movements and origin, as well as from\r faith in","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":3896},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-13-1","text":"_Children, look at the flowers at your feet; do not trample upon them.\r Look at the love in your midst and do not repudiate it._ KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3897},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-13-2","text":"_There is a higher reason which transcends all human minds. It is far\r and near. It permeates all the worlds and at the same time is infinitely\r higher than they._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3898},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-13-3","text":"_A man who sees that all things are contained in the higher spirit\r cannot treat any being with contempt._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3899},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-13-4","text":"_For him to whom all spiritual beings are equal to the highest there can\r be no room for deception or grief._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3900},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-13-5","text":"_Those who are ignorant and are devoted to the religious rites only, are\r in a deep gloom, but those who are given up to fruitless meditations are\r in a still greater darkness._","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":3901},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-14-1","text":"Yes, in our time all these things must be cleared away in order that\r mankind may escape from self-inflicted calamities that have reached an\r extreme intensity. Whether an Indian seeks liberation from subjection\r to the English, or anyone else struggles with an oppressor either of his\r own nationality or of another--whether it be a Negro defending himself\r against the North Americans; or Persians, Russians, or Turks against\r the Persian, Russian, or Turkish governments, or any man seeking the\r greatest welfare for himself and for everybody else--they do not need\r explanations and justifications of old religious superstitions such as\r have been formulated by your Vivekanandas, Baba Bharatis, ","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3902},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-14-2","text":"_Children, look upwards with your beclouded eyes, and a world full of\r joy and love will disclose itself to you, a rational world made by My\r wisdom, the only real world. Then you will know what love has done\r with you, what love has bestowed upon you, what love demands from you._\r KRISHNA.","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":3903},{"id":"nietzsche-the-gay-sc-15-1","text":"End of the Project Gutenberg EBook of A Letter to a Hindu, by Leo Tolstoy","author":"Friedrich Nietzsche","source":"Nietzsche — The Gay Science","tags":["philosophy","language:english","collection:nietzsche"],"groups":{"work":"The Gay Science","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":3904}]}